//   ,
//     {label:'Business objectives — profit maximisation versus stakeholder theory',concept:'Strategy',related:'Governance, Sustainability, Ethics',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 1.3: Business objectives; AO3 analysis',scene:'A stakeholder map with the business at the centre. Arrows show objectives of each stakeholder group — shareholders (profit), employees (wages and security), customers (quality and price), community (environment), government (tax and employment). Conflicts between objectives shown as tension arrows.',sliders:['Shareholder profit priority (0=Low — social enterprise → 4=High — pure profit maximisation)','Employee welfare priority (0=Cost minimisation only → 4=High wage and wellbeing investment)','Environmental sustainability target (0=No target → 4=Carbon neutral commitment)','Short vs long-term orientation (0=Quarterly results — short term → 4=Long-term vision — 10 year)'],resources:['Profitability index (variable)','Employee retention and satisfaction (variable)','Customer loyalty and NPS score (variable)','Environmental impact score (variable)','Stakeholder conflict level (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that different objectives create real conflicts — maximising short-term profit may reduce employee welfare and damage brand loyalty. Stakeholder theory argues the firm must balance competing interests for long-run success. The simulation models Friedman (shareholder supremacy) versus Freeman (stakeholder theory) debate.',real:'Patagonia mission versus profit — B Corp model, Unilever sustainable living plan balancing growth and sustainability, Enron short-term profit maximisation leading to fraud, John Lewis Partnership — employee ownership and different objective function'},

//     {label:'Business growth — organic internal versus external merger and acquisition',concept:'Strategy',related:'Change, Markets, Risk',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Risk-takers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 1.6: Business growth; AO3 analysis',scene:'A business growth dashboard. Organic growth: reinvested profit, expanding product range, entering new markets. External growth: merger (two equals combining), acquisition (hostile or friendly takeover), strategic alliance, joint venture. Economies of scale and diseconomies shown.',sliders:['Growth strategy type (0=Organic slow and controlled → 4=Aggressive acquisition)','Market share gained (0=Small incremental → 4=Market dominance through merger)','Integration costs post-merger (0=Smooth culture fit → 4=Culture clash — value destruction)','Economies of scale achieved (0=None — same unit costs → 4=Large — significant cost reduction)'],resources:['Revenue growth rate % (variable)','Market share % (variable)','Unit cost change from scale (variable)','Risk level of strategy (variable)','Diseconomies of scale risk (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that external growth through M&A is faster but riskier than organic growth — culture clashes destroy value in many acquisitions. Economies of scale are the main justification but diseconomies (bureaucracy, coordination costs) set a natural limit to optimal firm size. The unit cost curve has a U-shape.',real:'Facebook acquisition of Instagram and WhatsApp, Daimler-Chrysler merger failure from culture clash, Disney acquisitions of Pixar Marvel and Lucasfilm, Tesla organic growth versus GM scale advantages'},

//     {label:'Sources of finance — internal versus external and gearing ratio',concept:'Finance',related:'Risk, Decision-making, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Unit 3.1: Sources of finance; AO4 Calculator required',scene:'A finance structure dashboard. Internal sources: retained profit, sale of assets, working capital management. External short-term: overdraft, trade credit, factoring. External long-term: share issue, debentures, bank loans, grants. Gearing ratio = long-term debt / capital employed calculated.',sliders:['Gearing ratio — debt proportion % (0=Low 10% — conservative → 4=High 80% — highly leveraged)','Retained profit available for reinvestment (0=None — all distributed as dividend → 4=Full retention)','Business risk level (0=Low — high gearing acceptable → 4=High — low gearing safer)','Interest rate environment (0=Low — cheap debt → 4=High — expensive borrowing)'],resources:['Gearing ratio = LT debt / capital employed % (variable)','Interest burden annual kJ (variable)','Debt versus equity cost comparison (variable)','Financial risk level (variable)','Return on equity leverage effect (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the gearing trade-off — high debt (gearing) amplifies returns in good times but amplifies losses in bad times (financial risk). Low-gearing firms are safer but may miss growth opportunities. Internal finance is risk-free but limited. HL Paper 2 requires gearing ratio calculation and interpretation.',real:'WeWork collapse — over-leveraged expansion, Berkshire Hathaway low gearing conservative strategy, UK homebuilders highly geared using land bank loans, Startups — venture capital equity preferred to avoid debt burden'},

//     {label:'Investment appraisal — payback period NPV and ARR',concept:'Decision-making',related:'Finance, Risk, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Unit 3.3: Investment appraisal; AO4 Calculator required',scene:'A capital investment decision dashboard. Students enter initial outlay, annual cash flows and discount rate. Three methods calculated simultaneously: payback period (years to recover investment), ARR (average annual profit as % of initial outlay), NPV (net present value — discounted cash flows). Decision criteria compared.',sliders:['Initial investment outlay (0=Small 100k → 4=Large 10 million)','Annual net cash flows (0=Low — long payback → 4=High — short payback)','Discount rate % (0=Low 3% — NPV relatively high → 4=High 15% — NPV falls sharply)','Project life years (0=Short 3 years → 4=Long 15 years)'],resources:['Payback period years (variable)','ARR = average annual profit / investment times 100 % (variable)','NPV = sum of discounted cash flows minus investment (variable)','Accept or reject decision (variable)','Sensitivity to discount rate change (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that NPV is theoretically superior because it accounts for the time value of money — a pound today is worth more than a pound in the future. Payback is simple and focuses on liquidity risk. ARR ignores timing of cash flows. Comparison of all three on the same investment reveals when they give conflicting advice. Required HL Paper 2 calculation.',real:'HS2 railway NPV and cost-benefit analysis, Solar panel installation payback period for households, NHS hospital investment appraisal, Film production payback period and NPV comparison'},

//     {label:'Cash flow management — forecasting liquidity and working capital',concept:'Finance',related:'Decision-making, Risk, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Unit 3.4: Cash flow; AO4 Calculator required',scene:'A 12-month cash flow forecast table. Monthly inflows and outflows shown. Cumulative cash balance calculated. Negative months highlighted in red — overdraft required. Students adjust timing of payments and receipts and observe effect on cash position. Working capital cycle animated.',sliders:['Revenue collection timing — debtor days (0=Cash on delivery — fast → 4=60-day credit — slow inflow)','Supplier payment timing — creditor days (0=Pay immediately → 4=60-day terms — delay outflow)','Seasonal revenue pattern (0=Steady — even cash → 4=Highly seasonal — cash crisis in off-season)','Stock holding period days (0=Just-in-time zero stock → 4=High safety stock — cash tied up)'],resources:['Net cash flow per month (variable)','Cumulative cash balance each month (variable)','Months in negative cash position (variable)','Working capital = current assets - current liabilities (variable)','Maximum overdraft facility required (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that profitability and liquidity are separate — a profitable business can fail from poor cash flow if customers pay late while suppliers demand immediate payment. The working capital cycle shows how cash is tied up in stock and debtors. Seasonal businesses face predictable cash crises requiring pre-arranged overdraft facilities.',real:'Restaurant business — immediate cash from customers but monthly staff costs, Retailer Christmas season cash flow — buildup then release, Construction company — long payment cycles and cash flow challenges, Uber Eats and food delivery — negative working capital model'},

//     {label:'Profit and profitability — ratios and variance analysis',concept:'Efficiency',related:'Finance, Decision-making, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Unit 3.5 and 3.6: Profitability ratios; AO4 Calculator required',scene:'An income statement and balance sheet displayed. Students calculate gross profit margin, net profit margin, and return on capital employed (ROCE). Variance analysis panel shows actual vs budgeted figures. Favourable and adverse variances highlighted. Possible causes and corrective actions listed.',sliders:['Revenue level (0=Below budget — adverse variance → 4=Above budget — favourable)','Cost of sales efficiency (0=High costs — low gross margin → 4=Low costs — high gross margin)','Overhead control (0=Overhead overrun → 4=Tight overhead control)','Capital employed (0=High — low ROCE → 4=Low capital efficiency — high ROCE)'],resources:['Gross profit margin = GP/revenue times 100 % (variable)','Net profit margin = NP/revenue times 100 % (variable)','ROCE = net profit / capital employed times 100 % (variable)','Revenue variance favourable or adverse (variable)','Cost variance favourable or adverse (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that high revenue does not guarantee profitability if costs are not controlled. Gross margin shows production efficiency; net margin shows overall control. ROCE compares profit to resources deployed — the most comprehensive profitability measure. Variance analysis diagnoses whether problems are from revenue or cost side.',real:'Apple vs Samsung — both profitable but different margin profiles, Amazon low margin high volume versus luxury brand high margin low volume, NHS trust efficiency variance analysis, Small business working capital versus profitability trade-off'},

//     {label:'Marketing mix — 7Ps for service businesses and digital marketing',concept:'Marketing',related:'Customer, Strategy, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.2: Marketing mix extended 7Ps; AO3 analysis',scene:'A 7P marketing mix wheel — Product Price Place Promotion People Process Physical evidence. Students adjust each P for a service business (hotel restaurant or bank) and observe customer satisfaction metrics. Digital marketing extension: SEO social media email and content marketing effectiveness.',sliders:['Price positioning (0=Budget value proposition → 4=Ultra-premium luxury pricing)','Promotion channel (0=Traditional print and TV only → 4=Full digital SEO social media influencer)','Service people quality (0=Poor training — low satisfaction → 4=Excellent service culture — high NPS)','Physical evidence and digital presence (0=Minimal — low trust → 4=Excellent brand experience)'],resources:['Customer satisfaction NPS score (variable)','Conversion rate % (variable)','Customer acquisition cost (variable)','Customer lifetime value (variable)','Brand equity index (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that service businesses require three additional Ps beyond the product 4Ps because services are intangible — People (staff quality), Process (service delivery) and Physical evidence (cues signalling quality). Digital marketing shifts reach and cost per acquisition dramatically versus traditional channels.',real:'Ritz Carlton people training as competitive advantage, Apple Store physical evidence creating premium perception, Airbnb digital marketing — user-generated content and reviews as trust signals, Netflix recommendation algorithm as product personalisation'},

//     {label:'Product life cycle and BCG matrix — portfolio strategy',concept:'Strategy',related:'Marketing, Change, Decision-making',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.4 and 4.5: Product life cycle; BCG matrix; AO3',scene:'A product life cycle S-curve with stages labelled — introduction growth maturity decline. Cash flow and profit shown below. BCG matrix quadrants — star question mark cash cow dog — populated with student-placed products. Extension strategies and Ansoff matrix shown alongside.',sliders:['PLC stage (0=Introduction — low sales high investment → 4=Decline — falling sales)','Market growth rate % (0=Slow — mature market → 4=Rapid — growth market)','Relative market share (0=Low — question mark or dog → 4=High — star or cash cow)','Extension strategy applied (0=None — natural decline → 4=Strong relaunch — extends maturity)'],resources:['Current profitability at PLC stage (variable)','Cash flow position positive or negative (variable)','BCG quadrant classification (variable)','Recommended strategy per BCG (variable)','Brand investment required (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that products move through predictable life cycle stages requiring different strategies and investment levels. The BCG matrix classifies products by market share and growth — stars need investment, cash cows fund the portfolio, question marks need decisions, dogs are candidates for deletion. Together these tools guide portfolio strategy.',real:'iPhone — star that became cash cow, Tesla Model 3 — star in growth market, Kodak film — dog that management held too long, Netflix DVD service — dog successfully managed out while streaming became star'},

//     {label:'Human resources — recruitment selection and training',concept:'Human resource management',related:'Development, Organisational culture, Change',lp:'Caring, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Social skills',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.2: Recruitment and training; AO3 analysis',scene:'A recruitment pipeline showing job analysis role design job description person specification and recruitment method selection. Training types compared — on-the-job induction off-the-job. Internal versus external recruitment costs and benefits. Selection method effectiveness comparison.',sliders:['Recruitment method (0=Word of mouth — low cost low reach → 4=Executive search headhunting — high cost high quality)','Internal vs external hiring (0=Internal — lower cost faster → 4=External — fresh ideas higher cost)','Training investment per employee (0=Minimum induction only → 4=Extensive ongoing professional development)','Selection method rigour (0=CV only → 4=Assessment centre psychometric tests interview)'],resources:['Time to hire days (variable)','Cost per hire (variable)','Quality of hire — performance score (variable)','Employee retention rate % (variable)','Training ROI — productivity improvement (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the recruitment trade-offs — internal hiring is cheaper and lower risk but limits fresh thinking; external hiring brings new capabilities but costs more and has higher failure risk. Training investment reduces turnover and improves performance but takes time to show returns. The best selection methods predict job performance most accurately.',real:'Google structured interview process versus unstructured interviews, Goldman Sachs investment banking training programme cost, Amazon hiring bar — raising minimum quality threshold, NHS nurse recruitment — shift from domestic training to overseas recruitment'},

//     {label:'Organisational change — Lewin model resistance and transformation',concept:'Change',related:'Organisational culture, Strategy, HR',lp:'Open-minded, Principled, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Social skills, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.7: Organisational change; AO3 analysis',scene:'Lewin three-stage change model animated: Unfreeze (creating urgency and challenging status quo), Change (transition and new behaviours), Refreeze (embedding new culture and systems). Resistance to change factors shown — self-interest, misunderstanding, different assessment, low tolerance. Force field analysis diagram.',sliders:['Change urgency and leadership communication (0=No urgency created — resistance persists → 4=Compelling vision — resistance falls)','Employee involvement in design of change (0=Top-down imposed → 4=Co-designed — participation)','Compensation for losers (0=None — resistance intensifies → 4=Full compensation or retraining)','Speed of change (0=Gradual incremental → 4=Rapid disruptive — shock therapy)'],resources:['Employee resistance level (variable)','Change success probability % (variable)','Productivity during transition dip (variable)','Refreeze durability — new habits embedded (variable)','Stakeholder alignment score (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why most organisational change initiatives fail — they skip the unfreeze phase assuming people will simply comply. Involving employees in designing the change dramatically reduces resistance. The productivity dip during transition is unavoidable but its depth and duration depend on change management quality.',real:'Nokia failure to change from mobile phones to smartphones — culture resisted, Toyota lean transformation over 20 years — gradual and participatory, British Airways industrial relations — change imposed leading to conflict, Microsoft cultural change under Satya Nadella — mindset shift from know-it-all to learn-it-all'}]},
//   {icon:'📈',name:'Economics',sub:'39 simulations · Units 1–4',topics:[
//     {label:'Scarcity, choice and the Production Possibility Curve',concept:'Scarcity, Choice, Efficiency',related:'Opportunity cost, Economic growth, Trade-offs',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 Section A — Unit 1: Introduction to Economics; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A Production Possibility Curve drawn live on the screen. Two goods on the axes — guns and butter, or consumer vs capital goods. Points inside on and outside the curve shown. Shifting the curve outward with economic growth. Trade-off arrows show opportunity cost at each point.',sliders:['Resource allocation between Good A and Good B % (0=All resources to A → 4=All resources to B)','State of technology and resources (0=Current — on the PPC → 4=Improved — curve shifts outward)','Unemployment level % (0=Full employment — on curve → 4=High unemployment — inside curve)','Economic growth investment (0=All consumption — no growth → 4=Maximum investment — rapid outward shift)'],resources:['Output of Good A units (variable)','Output of Good B units (variable)','Opportunity cost of one more unit of A (variable)','PPC position — inside on or outside (variable)','Economic growth rate % (variable)'],explain:'Students draw a live PPC by moving the resource allocation slider and observe the opportunity cost — giving up one good to get more of another. Inside the PPC represents inefficiency (unemployment); outside is currently unattainable. Economic growth shifts the PPC outward. This is the foundational diagram of all IB Economics — required for Paper 1 Section A.',real:'USA guns versus butter debate during Cold War, China reallocation from consumer goods to capital investment, COVID-19 shifting healthcare versus economic activity, Space programme opportunity cost in social spending'},

//     {label:'Demand — determinants, shifts and movements',concept:'Change, Intervention',related:'Markets, Consumer behaviour, Scarcity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 Section A — Unit 2.1: Demand; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A live demand curve on a price-quantity diagram. Students move along the curve (price change) and shift the curve (non-price determinants). Five determinants labelled: income, prices of related goods, tastes, expectations, population. The curve shifts left or right with each non-price factor.',sliders:['Price of good P (0=Low → 4=High — movement along curve)','Consumer income level (0=Falling — demand decreases → 4=Rising — normal good demand increases)','Price of substitute good (0=Substitute falls — demand shifts left → 4=Substitute rises — demand shifts right)','Consumer tastes and preferences (0=Good becomes unfashionable → 4=Advertising boom — demand surges)'],resources:['Quantity demanded at current price (variable)','Equilibrium shift direction (left or right)','New equilibrium price P* (variable)','New equilibrium quantity Q* (variable)','Consumer surplus change area (variable)'],explain:'Students distinguish movements along the demand curve (caused by price changes) from shifts of the entire curve (caused by non-price determinants). The five non-price determinants are the core examinable content. Each determinant moves the curve in a predictable direction. Required diagram for IB Economics Paper 1 Section A.',real:'iPhone demand shift from positive reviews and marketing, Petrol demand falls when electric vehicle prices drop, Organic food demand rises with health awareness, House prices and expected future price effects on current demand'},

//     {label:'Supply — determinants, shifts and producer decisions',concept:'Change, Efficiency',related:'Markets, Costs, Production',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 Section A — Unit 2.1: Supply; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A live upward-sloping supply curve. Students move along the curve with price changes and shift the curve using non-price supply determinants. Cost of production, technology, number of firms, taxes and subsidies, price of other goods each shown as a labelled determinant panel.',sliders:['Price of good P (0=Low → 4=High — movement along supply curve)','Cost of inputs and production (0=Falling costs — supply increases → 4=Rising costs — supply decreases)','Technology improvement (0=No change → 4=Major improvement — large right shift)','Government tax or subsidy applied (0=Large tax — supply decreases → 4=Large subsidy — supply increases)'],resources:['Quantity supplied at current price (variable)','Producer surplus area (variable)','Break-even price (variable)','Supply curve shift direction (variable)','New equilibrium after shift (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that supply shifts right when producers can supply more at the same price — falling costs, better technology or subsidies. Supply shifts left when costs rise, firms exit or taxes are imposed. The supply curve represents marginal cost and slopes upward because additional production costs more.',real:'Oil supply shock 2022 from Russia-Ukraine war, Agricultural supply fall from drought and input cost rises, Solar panel supply right shift from technology improvement, COVID-19 supply chain disruption shifting supply left globally'},

//     {label:'Market equilibrium — price mechanism and market clearing',concept:'Efficiency, Change',related:'Markets, Intervention, Scarcity',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 Section A — Unit 2.1: Market equilibrium; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A full supply and demand diagram with intersection shown as equilibrium E*. Students create surpluses by setting price above equilibrium and shortages below. The market automatically adjusts with animated price arrows moving toward equilibrium. Simultaneous shifts of both curves show the four cases.',sliders:['Price set by market or government P (0=Below equilibrium — shortage → 4=Above equilibrium — surplus)','Demand shift direction (0=Large decrease — D shifts left → 4=Large increase — D shifts right)','Supply shift direction (0=Large decrease — S shifts left → 4=Large increase — S shifts right)','Speed of market adjustment (0=Slow — sticky prices → 4=Instant — flexible prices)'],resources:['Surplus or shortage quantity (variable)','New equilibrium price P* after shifts (variable)','New equilibrium quantity Q* after shifts (variable)','Direction of price pressure (variable)','Consumer and producer surplus combined (variable)'],explain:'Students observe the self-correcting price mechanism — surplus creates downward price pressure and shortage creates upward pressure, both driving the market to equilibrium. The four cases of simultaneous D and S shifts reveal when the direction of P* or Q* change is ambiguous. Required diagram for every Paper 1 Section A answer.',real:'Housing market price adjustment after demand surge, Supermarket price adjustment from supply disruption, Airline ticket dynamic pricing responding to demand changes, Agricultural price volatility from weather supply shocks'},

//     {label:'Price elasticity of demand — PED calculation and applications',concept:'Efficiency, Choice',related:'Markets, Consumer behaviour, Intervention',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.2: PED; AO4 Calculator required; Paper 3 HL quantitative',scene:'A demand curve drawn on a price-quantity diagram. PED calculated as % change in Qd divided by % change in P at each point. Elastic demand shown as a flatter curve (PED greater than 1), inelastic as steeper (PED less than 1). Total revenue rectangle updates as price changes — showing the TR test for elasticity.',sliders:['Price change from P1 to P2 % (0=Small 5% change → 4=Large 40% change)','Demand elasticity level (0=Perfectly inelastic PED=0 — vertical curve → 4=Elastic PED=3 — flat curve)','Number of substitutes available (0=No substitutes — inelastic → 4=Many close substitutes — elastic)','Necessity vs luxury (0=Necessity — inelastic → 4=Luxury — elastic)'],resources:['PED = %ΔQd / %ΔP (variable — negative value)','Total revenue P times Q before change (variable)','Total revenue after price change (variable)','Revenue change direction (variable)','Deadweight loss from intervention (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate PED using the midpoint formula and discover the total revenue test: raising price on inelastic goods increases TR (essential drugs); raising price on elastic goods reduces TR (luxury goods). This determines optimal pricing strategy and explains why governments tax inelastic goods like cigarettes and petrol.',real:'Petrol PED approximately -0.1 to -0.3 — very inelastic, Luxury holiday PED approximately -2 — elastic, NHS drug pricing for inelastic demand, Sin taxes on tobacco and alcohol — inelastic demand means revenue raised'},

//     {label:'Price elasticity of supply — PES and market adjustment',concept:'Efficiency, Change',related:'Markets, Production, Time',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.2: PES; AO4 Calculator required',scene:'Supply curves of different slopes drawn side by side — perfectly inelastic vertical, inelastic steep, elastic flat, perfectly elastic horizontal. Students shift demand and observe how price and quantity adjust differently with each supply elasticity. Short-run vs long-run PES comparison.',sliders:['PES value (0=Perfectly inelastic PES=0 — fixed supply → 4=Elastic PES=3 — supply responds easily)','Demand shift magnitude (0=Small demand increase → 4=Large demand increase)','Time horizon (0=Immediate run — very inelastic → 4=Long run — more elastic)','Industry type (0=Agricultural — slow production → 4=Manufacturing — flexible)'],resources:['New equilibrium price change after demand shift (variable — large if PES low)','New equilibrium quantity change (variable — small if PES low)','PES = %ΔQs / %ΔP (variable)','Short vs long run adjustment difference (variable)','Producer surplus change (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that when supply is inelastic (fixed in short run), demand shifts mostly affect price not quantity — explaining why house prices spike suddenly. When supply is elastic, demand shifts mostly increase quantity not price. Time horizon is the main determinant of PES — supply becomes more elastic in the long run as firms respond.',real:'Housing supply PES near zero in short run — explains price surge not quantity surge, Agricultural supply inelastic — explains price volatility from weather shocks, Manufacturing supply more elastic than housing, Oil supply inelastic short run due to capital requirements'},

//     {label:'Income and cross elasticity of demand — YED and XED',concept:'Change, Interdependence',related:'Markets, Consumer behaviour, Trade-offs',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.2: YED and XED; AO4 Calculator required',scene:'Two animated diagrams side by side. Left: Income-demand relationship for normal, inferior and luxury goods — demand curves shifting as income changes. Right: Cross-demand diagram showing how price of one good shifts demand for another — substitutes and complements.',sliders:['Income change % (0=Income falls -20% → 4=Income rises +40%)','YED value (0=Inferior good YED negative → 4=Luxury good YED greater than 1)','Price of related good change % (0=Related price falls -30% → 4=Related price rises +30%)','XED value (0=Strong complements XED negative → 4=Strong substitutes XED positive)'],resources:['YED = %ΔQd / %ΔIncome (variable)','Good classification (normal/inferior/luxury)','XED = %ΔQd good A / %ΔP good B (variable)','Relationship classification (substitutes/complements/independent)','Demand shift quantity (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that YED sign determines good type (positive = normal, negative = inferior) and magnitude determines luxury status (greater than 1 = luxury). XED sign determines relationship (positive = substitutes, negative = complements). Firms use YED to predict how recessions affect their revenue; firms use XED to respond to competitor price changes.',real:'Bus travel YED negative in UK — inferior good, Champagne YED greater than 2 — luxury, Petrol and car demand XED strongly negative — complements, Pepsi and Coca-Cola XED positive — substitutes'},

//     {label:'Consumer and producer surplus — welfare analysis and triangles',concept:'Efficiency, Equity',related:'Markets, Intervention, Economic well-being',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.3: Surplus; AO4 Diagram and Calculator required',scene:'A supply and demand diagram with equilibrium. Consumer surplus shaded as blue triangle above equilibrium price below the demand curve. Producer surplus shaded as gold triangle below equilibrium price above the supply curve. Total welfare = sum of both. Students calculate area of each triangle.',sliders:['Market intervention type (0=No intervention — maximum welfare → 4=Price ceiling below equilibrium)','Price set by government (0=Below equilibrium — ceiling → 4=Above equilibrium — floor)','Tax per unit imposed (0=None → 4=Large tax — deadweight loss triangle appears)','Subsidy per unit given (0=None → 4=Large subsidy — oversupply welfare analysis)'],resources:['Consumer surplus area (variable — shrinks with ceiling or tax)','Producer surplus area (variable — shrinks with floor or tax)','Deadweight welfare loss area (variable — rises with intervention)','Total welfare = CS + PS (variable)','Government revenue from tax (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that free market equilibrium maximises total welfare (CS + PS). Any price control or tax creates deadweight loss — a triangle of welfare destroyed because mutually beneficial transactions no longer occur. The deadweight loss triangle is an assessed calculation skill in HL. Required for Paper 1 evaluation of market intervention.',real:'Rent controls in New York and San Francisco — deadweight loss in housing, Cigarette tax deadweight loss vs government revenue, EU Common Agricultural Policy surplus from price floor, Minimum wage deadweight loss in labour markets'},

//     {label:'Price controls — ceilings and floors with distributional effects',concept:'Intervention, Equity',related:'Markets, Government, Economic well-being',lp:'Principled, Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.3: Price controls; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A supply and demand diagram. Price ceiling line appears below equilibrium — shortage shown as gap between Qs and Qd with parallel arrows. Price floor above equilibrium — surplus shown. Stakeholder analysis panel shows who gains who loses for each intervention. Non-price rationing methods listed.',sliders:['Price ceiling level relative to equilibrium (0=Far below — large shortage → 4=At equilibrium — no effect)','Price floor level relative to equilibrium (0=At equilibrium — no effect → 4=Far above — large surplus)','Intervention type (0=Ceiling — maximum price → 4=Floor — minimum price)','Market type (0=Housing — ceiling common → 4=Agricultural — floor common)'],resources:['Shortage or surplus quantity units (variable)','Consumer gains from lower price (variable)','Consumer loss from reduced quantity (variable)','Producer revenue change (variable)','Non-price rationing required (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that price ceilings help consumers who get the good but hurt those who cannot get it (shortage), while price floors help producers but create surplus. The welfare analysis requires identifying both winners and losers. Non-price rationing (queuing, lottery, discrimination) arises with price ceilings. Required diagram for Unit 2.3.',real:'Energy price cap in UK 2022 — ceiling below equilibrium during energy crisis, EU minimum price for agricultural products — floor above equilibrium, Rent controls in Mumbai and Paris, Minimum alcohol price in Scotland — floor policy'},

//     {label:'Indirect taxes — specific and ad valorem with stakeholder analysis',concept:'Intervention, Efficiency',related:'Markets, Government, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.3: Indirect taxes; AO4 Diagram and Calculator required',scene:'A supply and demand diagram showing tax effect. Supply curve shifts up by the tax amount creating a wedge between price paid by consumer Pc and price received by producer Pp. Tax revenue rectangle shown. Deadweight loss triangle. Tax incidence calculation shows how burden splits between buyers and sellers based on elasticity.',sliders:['Tax per unit amount (0=Zero → 4=Large tax — big wedge)','PED value (0=Perfectly inelastic — consumer bears all tax → 4=Perfectly elastic — producer bears all)','PES value (0=Perfectly inelastic — producer bears all → 4=Perfectly elastic — consumer bears all)','Tax type (0=Specific fixed per unit → 4=Ad valorem percentage of price)'],resources:['Consumer price paid Pc (variable)','Producer price received Pp (variable)','Tax incidence ratio consumer vs producer (variable)','Government tax revenue area (variable)','Deadweight loss area (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that tax incidence (who bears the burden) depends on relative elasticities — not on who formally pays the tax. Inelastic demand means consumers bear most of the tax; inelastic supply means producers bear most. The wedge diagram is an assessed drawing and calculation skill for HL Paper 1 and Paper 3.',real:'UK cigarette tax — consumers bear most due to inelastic demand, UK VAT 20% ad valorem — shared incidence, US soda tax — elastic substitutes shift burden to producers, French carbon tax vehicle fuel incidence analysis'},

//     {label:'Subsidies — production subsidies and stakeholder effects',concept:'Intervention, Efficiency',related:'Markets, Government, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.3: Subsidies; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A supply and demand diagram with a subsidy. Supply curve shifts down by subsidy amount. Consumer price falls Pc. Producer price rises Pp. Government cost rectangle shown as larger than consumer and producer surplus gain — the deadweight loss of subsidy. Over-allocation of resources to this market.',sliders:['Subsidy per unit amount (0=Zero → 4=Large subsidy)','Market type (0=Agriculture — common subsidy recipient → 4=Electric vehicles — new subsidy)','PED value (0=Inelastic — consumer gains less → 4=Elastic — consumer gains most of subsidy)','Externality present (0=No externality — pure efficiency loss → 4=Positive externality — subsidy justified)'],resources:['Consumer surplus gain area (variable)','Producer revenue gain area (variable)','Government subsidy cost total area (variable)','Net welfare change — DWL (variable)','Over-allocation quantity (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that subsidies create over-production relative to the optimal level (without externalities) and that the government subsidy cost always exceeds the combined CS and PS gain — creating a deadweight loss. When positive externalities are present, the subsidy can correct market failure. Required Unit 2.3 diagram.',real:'EU Common Agricultural Policy — 40% of EU budget as farm subsidies, UK electric vehicle subsidy — correcting positive externality, Indian food subsidy programme and budget cost, US corn ethanol subsidy creating overproduction'},

//     {label:'Market failure — externalities and diagrams',concept:'Efficiency, Sustainability',related:'Markets, Government, Economic well-being',lp:'Caring, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.4: Externalities; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'Four panels showing all four externality types. Negative production externality: MSC above MPC — overproduction at Q market, optimal at Q optimal. Positive production externality: MSC below MPC. Negative consumption: MSB below MPB. Positive consumption: MSB above MPB. Deadweight loss shaded.',sliders:['Externality type (0=Negative production MPC below MSC → 4=Positive consumption MSB above MPB)','Magnitude of externality per unit (0=Small divergence → 4=Large divergence)','Government intervention (0=None — market failure persists → 4=Optimal tax or subsidy — corrects failure)','Affected third parties (0=Local neighbourhood → 4=Global — climate externality)'],resources:['Market quantity Qm vs optimal quantity Q optimal (variable)','Market price Pm vs optimal price P optimal (variable)','Deadweight loss area (variable)','External cost or benefit per unit (variable)','Welfare gain from corrective policy (variable)'],explain:'Students draw all four externality diagrams and learn to identify the direction and consequence of divergence between private and social costs/benefits. The deadweight loss is always at the market quantity, not the optimal quantity. Corrective taxes (Pigouvian) and subsidies eliminate the DWL. Required for Paper 1 Section B evaluation.',real:'UK carbon tax correcting negative production externality from fossil fuels, NHS vaccination subsidy correcting positive consumption externality, Cigarette advertising ban correcting negative consumption externality, US honey bee colony protection subsidy — positive production externality'},

//     {label:'Public goods and common access resources',concept:'Efficiency, Sustainability',related:'Markets, Government, Equity',lp:'Principled, Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.4: Public goods and CAR; AO4 required',scene:'A matrix comparing four types of goods by excludability and rivalry. Public goods quadrant shown with lighthouse and national defence examples. Students see the free rider problem animate — nobody pays because nobody can be excluded. CAR tragedy of commons shown as fishing grounds depleted to zero.',sliders:['Excludability of good (0=Non-excludable — pure public good → 4=Fully excludable — private good)','Rivalry in consumption (0=Non-rival — use by one does not reduce for others → 4=Fully rival — pure private)','Number of free riders (0=None — full payment → 4=Maximum free riding — public good underprovided)','Regulation of CAR (0=No regulation — fully open access → 4=Strict quota — sustainable)'],resources:['Type of good classification (variable)','Free rider problem severity (variable)','Private provision possible? (variable)','Government provision justified? (variable)','CAR depletion rate with open access (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that public goods (non-excludable and non-rival) will be underprovided by the market because free riders cannot be excluded — the market fails. Common access resources (rival but non-excludable) face the tragedy of the commons and are overused to depletion without regulation. Both require government intervention.',real:'National defence — classic public good, BBC World Service as near-public good, Atlantic fish stocks as CAR — international governance failure, Street lighting as local public good, Clean air as CAR — air pollution regulation'},

//     {label:'Market structures — perfect competition, monopoly and oligopoly',concept:'Efficiency, Equity',related:'Markets, Change, Interdependence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 Section B — Unit 2.5: Market structures; AO4 Diagram required HL',scene:'Side-by-side profit-maximising diagrams for perfect competition and monopoly. PC firm faces horizontal demand (price taker) — zero long-run profit. Monopoly faces downward demand — maximises profit at MR=MC. Allocative efficiency shown as P=MC for PC; inefficiency P greater than MC for monopoly. Supernormal profit rectangle for monopoly.',sliders:['Market structure (0=Perfect competition — many firms → 4=Pure monopoly — one firm)','Number of firms in market (0=Many — price takers → 4=One — price maker)','Barriers to entry (0=None — free entry → 4=Very high — patents or natural monopoly)','Price set relative to MC (0=P=MC — allocative efficient → 4=P much greater than MC — monopoly markup)'],resources:['Firm profit level (variable — supernormal/normal/loss)','Allocative efficiency P=MC? (variable)','Productive efficiency min ATC? (variable)','Degree of market power (variable)','Consumer surplus compared to PC (variable — smaller under monopoly)'],explain:'Students compare outcomes across market structures and discover the fundamental inefficiency of monopoly: price above MC means consumers willing to pay more than production cost are excluded — allocative inefficiency. Perfect competition maximises allocative efficiency but may not maximise productive efficiency. HL required diagrams for Paper 1 Section B.',real:'Google search monopoly power and antitrust investigation, Pharmaceutical patent monopoly — high prices for essential drugs, UK water company natural monopoly regulation, OPEC oligopoly price coordination'},

//     {label:'Oligopoly — interdependence, game theory and price stability',concept:'Interdependence, Efficiency',related:'Markets, Strategy, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 Section B — Unit 2.5: Oligopoly and game theory; AO4 required HL',scene:'A prisoner dilemma payoff matrix shown as a 2x2 grid. Two firms choose to compete or collude. Payoffs shown in each cell. Dominant strategy identified. Nash equilibrium highlighted. A kinked demand curve shown explaining price rigidity in oligopoly — elastic above current price inelastic below.',sliders:['Payoff from mutual collusion (0=Low profit → 4=High cartel profit)','Payoff from defecting while other colludes (0=Small gain → 4=Large first-mover advantage)','Probability of detection and punishment (0=Never caught → 4=Certain detection — deters cartel)','Number of firms in oligopoly (0=Duopoly 2 → 4=Many — approaches monopolistic competition)'],resources:['Nash equilibrium payoff for each firm (variable)','Cartel equilibrium payoff (variable — higher but unstable)','Dominant strategy identified (variable)','Price stability range in kinked demand (variable)','Welfare loss from collusion vs competition (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the prisoners dilemma — both firms defect even though both would be better off colluding, because each fears defection by the other. The Nash equilibrium (both compete) is worse for firms than the cartel outcome. The kinked demand curve explains why oligopoly prices are sticky — no firm gains from changing price.',real:'OPEC oil cartel — members cheat on quotas despite collective interest in high prices, Airline oligopoly and pricing parallel behaviour, Supermarket price wars in UK — kinked demand model, Amazon and Walmart pricing strategy — watchful mutual awareness'},

//     {label:'Monopolistic competition — differentiation and long-run equilibrium',concept:'Efficiency, Change',related:'Markets, Consumer behaviour, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 Section B — Unit 2.5: Monopolistic competition; AO4 Diagram required HL',scene:'Two diagrams: short-run with supernormal profit (price above ATC) and long-run equilibrium where free entry drives profit to zero (P=ATC tangency point). Product differentiation shown as source of downward-sloping demand despite many competitors.',sliders:['Degree of product differentiation (0=Homogeneous — approaches PC → 4=Highly differentiated — approaches monopoly)','Short vs long run (0=Short run — supernormal profit possible → 4=Long run — normal profit only)','Entry barriers (0=No barriers — free entry erodes profit → 4=Some barriers — profit persists)','Advertising intensity (0=None → 4=Heavy advertising — shift demand right)'],resources:['Short-run supernormal profit area (variable)','Long-run profit (zero — normal profit only)','Excess capacity in long run units (variable — production below minimum ATC)','Allocative efficiency P=MC? (no — slight markup)','Variety and consumer choice (variable — increases with differentiation)'],explain:'Students discover that monopolistic competition offers consumer variety through differentiation but at the cost of excess capacity — firms produce below minimum ATC in long-run equilibrium. The long-run tangency condition means zero economic profit but persistent inefficiency. Free entry is the mechanism driving profit to zero.',real:'Restaurant industry — local monopoly power but free entry, Hairdressers and nail salons — many differentiated competitors, Clothing brands — differentiation gives price setting power, Petrol stations — near homogeneous product but location differentiation'},

//     {label:'Aggregate demand — components and shifts',concept:'Change, Intervention',related:'Macroeconomics, Economic well-being, Interdependence',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.1: AD and components; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'An AD-AS diagram with aggregate demand curve downward sloping. AD components shown as C+I+G+(X-M) with sliders for each. As any component increases the AD curve shifts right — total spending increases at every price level. The Keynesian multiplier calculation shows how an initial spending injection multiplies through the economy.',sliders:['Consumer spending C level (0=Very low — recession → 4=High — confidence boom)','Investment spending I level (0=Near zero — business pessimism → 4=High — investment boom)','Government spending G level (0=Austerity → 4=Maximum stimulus)','Net exports X-M (0=Large deficit → 4=Large surplus)'],resources:['Aggregate demand = C+I+G+(X-M) (variable)','AD shift direction and magnitude (variable)','Keynesian multiplier k = 1/(1-MPC) (variable)','Total spending injection impact on real GDP (variable)','Multiplied GDP change (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that all four components of AD create identical rightward shifts in the AD curve, but with different multiplier effects. The Keynesian multiplier amplifies the initial spending injection — a 100 increase in G multiplied by k=4 gives 400 total increase in GDP. Required for Unit 3 macroeconomic policy analysis.',real:'2009 Obama stimulus — 787 billion dollar AD boost with multiplier effect, UK austerity 2010-2019 — G reduction shifting AD left, China export surplus as source of large (X-M) component, COVID-19 collapse of C component — consumer confidence collapse'},

//     {label:'Aggregate supply — SRAS LRAS and macroeconomic equilibrium',concept:'Change, Efficiency',related:'Macroeconomics, Economic growth, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.1: AS and equilibrium; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'An AD-AS diagram with both SRAS (upward sloping) and LRAS (vertical at potential GDP Yp). Macroeconomic equilibrium where AD intersects SRAS. Students shift AD to create inflationary gap (above Yp) or deflationary gap (below Yp). Keynesian range and classical range of AS shown.',sliders:['AD level — spending in economy (0=Very low — recession — Y far below Yp → 4=Very high — inflationary gap)','SRAS shift — supply shocks (0=Stagflationary shock — SRAS left → 4=Beneficial supply improvement — SRAS right)','LRAS shift — productive capacity (0=No change → 4=Long-run growth — LRAS right)','Time period (0=Short run — SRAS relevant → 4=Long run — LRAS determines output)'],resources:['Real GDP level Y relative to potential Yp (variable)','Output gap type (inflationary/deflationary/none)','Price level index (variable)','Unemployment level (variable — falls when Y rises above Yp)','Long-run equilibrium position (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the two equilibrium positions — short-run (AD intersects SRAS) and long-run (AD intersects LRAS) — explain macroeconomic cycles. Deflationary gap means unemployment; inflationary gap means inflation. Required AD-AS diagram for all Unit 3 macroeconomic policy evaluation questions.',real:'2008 Global Financial Crisis — AD collapsed creating large deflationary gap, Oil shock 1973 — SRAS shifted left creating stagflation, COVID-19 — simultaneous AD and AS collapse, China long-run growth as LRAS shifting right'},

//     {label:'Keynesian multiplier and fiscal policy',concept:'Intervention, Change',related:'Macroeconomics, Economic well-being, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.2: Fiscal policy; HL AO4 Calculator required',scene:'An animated circular flow of income. Government injects spending G. Households receive income, save a fraction (MPS) and spend the rest (MPC). Each round of spending creates income for the next household. The total multiplied effect accumulates. Withdrawals (S, T, M) are the leakages that reduce the multiplier.',sliders:['Marginal propensity to consume MPC (0=Low 0.5 — high saving → 4=High 0.9 — low saving)','Government spending injection G billions (0=Small 10bn → 4=Large 100bn)','Tax rate t % (0=No tax → 4=High 40% tax rate — reduces multiplier)','Marginal propensity to import MPM (0=Closed economy — no imports → 4=Open economy — high import leakage)'],resources:['Keynesian multiplier k = 1/(MPS+MPT+MPM) (variable)','Total change in GDP from G injection (variable)','Change in equilibrium national income (variable)','Tax multiplier (negative — smaller than spending multiplier)','Balanced budget multiplier = 1 (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the multiplier is the reciprocal of total leakages — high MPS, high taxes and high imports all reduce the multiplier. A closed economy with no taxes and no saving has multiplier of infinity (unrealistic). HL students calculate the exact multiplier and apply it to policy scenarios. Required HL Paper 3 calculation.',real:'New Deal 1930s USA — high multiplier in closed economy with low trade, UK austerity low multiplier — economy more open with higher savings, IMF multiplier underestimates in 2010s austerity — led to policy revision, Developing country multipliers — often smaller due to import leakage'},

//     {label:'Unemployment — types measurement and policies',concept:'Economic well-being, Equity',related:'Macroeconomics, Intervention, Sustainability',lp:'Caring, Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.3: Unemployment; AO4 required',scene:'A labour market diagram showing different types of unemployment. Structural unemployment shown as skills mismatch diagram. Cyclical shown as AD falling below potential GDP in AD-AS. Frictional as natural rate. Phillips curve in adjacent panel shows inverse relationship between unemployment and inflation in short run.',sliders:['Type of unemployment (0=Frictional — natural rate → 4=Structural — skills mismatch)','AD level in economy (0=Low — high cyclical unemployment → 4=Full employment level)','Real wage flexibility (0=Rigid — classical unemployment → 4=Flexible — market clears)','Government intervention (0=None → 4=Full retraining and job guarantee)'],resources:['Unemployment rate % (variable)','Natural rate of unemployment NAIRU % (variable)','Cyclical unemployment component % (variable)','Structural unemployment from technology (variable)','Phillips curve trade-off at current inflation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that different types of unemployment require different policies — cyclical (AD stimulus), structural (retraining and education), frictional (job matching services), seasonal. The AD-AS diagram shows cyclical unemployment as a deflationary gap. The Phillips curve shows the short-run trade-off between unemployment and inflation.',real:'2009 UK unemployment reached 8% — cyclical from financial crisis, Welsh coal mining structural unemployment from deindustrialisation, US gig economy frictional unemployment increase, German short-time work scheme (Kurzarbeit) reducing cyclical unemployment'},

//     {label:'Inflation — CPI measurement causes and consequences',concept:'Economic well-being, Change',related:'Macroeconomics, Intervention, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.4: Inflation; HL AO4 Calculator required — weighted CPI',scene:'A CPI basket calculator. Students assign weights to categories — housing food transport etc — and input price changes. Weighted CPI calculates. Demand-pull inflation shown as AD shifting right into inflationary gap in AD-AS diagram. Cost-push shown as SRAS shifting left. Hyperinflation and deflation case studies.',sliders:['Demand-pull pressure — AD shift (0=AD below potential — deflation risk → 4=AD far above — high inflation)','Cost-push pressure — SRAS shift (0=No supply shock → 4=Large oil price shock — stagflation)','Money supply growth % (0=Tight monetary policy → 4=Excessive money printing — hyperinflation)','Wage growth relative to productivity (0=Wages below productivity → 4=Wages far above — wage-price spiral)'],resources:['CPI inflation rate % (variable)','Weighted CPI calculation (variable)','Real vs nominal distinction (variable)','Winners from inflation (debtors) (variable)','Losers from inflation (savers creditors) (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate a weighted CPI using different household spending patterns — discovering that inflation hits low-income households harder if they spend more on food and energy. Demand-pull and cost-push are distinguished in AD-AS diagrams. Redistribution effects of inflation create equity concerns. HL Paper 3 requires weighted CPI calculation.',real:'UK inflation 2022 — peaked at 11% driven by energy cost-push, Zimbabwe hyperinflation 2008 — monetary policy cause, Japan deflationary spiral 1990s-2000s, US 1970s wage-price spiral and stagflation'},

//     {label:'Economic growth — actual and potential output',concept:'Change, Sustainability, Efficiency',related:'Macroeconomics, Economic well-being, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Caring, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.5: Economic growth; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A PPC diagram showing actual GDP inside potential GDP — recessionary gap. LRAS shifts right as potential output grows. AD-AS diagram shows both types of growth. GDP per capita over time graph for different countries. Distribution effects — GDP growth with rising inequality shown by Lorenz curve moving away from equality.',sliders:['Actual GDP level relative to potential % (0=Deep recession — far inside PPC → 4=Boom — on PPC)','Potential GDP growth rate % (0=Zero growth stagnation → 4=Rapid growth 8% per year)','Growth type (0=Unsustainable — environmental costs → 4=Sustainable — green growth)','Distribution of growth benefits (0=Concentrated at top — inequality rises → 4=Widely shared — inequality falls)'],resources:['Real GDP growth rate % (variable)','Actual vs potential GDP gap (variable)','GDP per capita change (variable)','Gini coefficient change from growth (variable)','HDI vs GDP correlation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the distinction between actual growth (closing the output gap) and potential growth (outward shift of LRAS and PPC). Growth can occur with rising or falling inequality depending on who benefits. The sustainability critique argues GDP growth is an inadequate measure of wellbeing when environmental costs are excluded. Core Unit 3 content.',real:'China 10% growth 2000-2010 with rising Gini coefficient inequality, Nordic countries slower growth but falling inequality, Green GDP accounting and environmental cost adjustment, COVID-19 — actual GDP fell while potential output was less affected'},

//     {label:'Monetary policy — interest rates inflation targeting and exchange rates',concept:'Intervention, Change',related:'Macroeconomics, Interdependence, Economic well-being',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.6: Monetary policy; AO4 required',scene:'A transmission mechanism diagram from central bank interest rate decision through to AD. Bank of England or Fed sets rate. Banks borrow at this rate and set mortgage and business loan rates. Lower rates stimulate C and I shifting AD right. Exchange rate channel: lower rates depreciate currency boosting exports.',sliders:['Central bank interest rate % (0=Near zero — maximum stimulus → 4=High 15% — tight monetary policy)','Inflation target % (0=0% — deflation risk → 4=5% — above target — tightening needed)','Transmission mechanism strength (0=Weak — low effectiveness → 4=Strong — rapid pass-through)','Quantitative easing (0=None → 4=Large QE programme — unconventional policy)'],resources:['Consumer spending change from rate cut (variable)','Investment change from rate cut (variable)','Exchange rate change from rate cut (variable)','Inflation rate change 12-18 months later (variable)','GDP growth change (variable)'],explain:'Students trace the monetary policy transmission mechanism and discover that interest rate changes affect AD with a lag of 12-24 months, making it difficult to fine-tune. The exchange rate channel shows how lower rates depreciate the currency boosting exports — an international linkage. QE is explained as an unconventional tool when rates hit zero lower bound.',real:'Bank of England 2022 rate rises from 0.1% to 5.25% — fastest since 1989, Fed QE 2009 — 3 rounds of quantitative easing, Japan zero interest rate policy since 1999, European Central Bank negative interest rates 2014-2022'},

//     {label:'Exchange rates — determination floating fixed and managed',concept:'Interdependence, Change',related:'International economics, Markets, Intervention',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.2: Exchange rates; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A foreign exchange market diagram — supply of pounds and demand for pounds in terms of dollars. Equilibrium exchange rate determined. Students shift supply and demand using determinants: interest rates trade flows speculation inflation. Fixed rate shown as central bank intervention. Managed float intervention.',sliders:['Domestic interest rate change (0=Rate falls — capital outflows — depreciation → 4=Rate rises — capital inflows — appreciation)','Trade balance (0=Large deficit — demand for foreign exchange rises — depreciation → 4=Large surplus — appreciation)','Inflation differential (0=Lower inflation than trading partners — appreciation → 4=Higher inflation — depreciation)','Speculation on currency (0=Selling — depreciation → 4=Buying — appreciation)'],resources:['Exchange rate level (variable — appreciates or depreciates)','Export competitiveness change (variable)','Import price change (variable)','Current account balance change (variable)','Central bank foreign reserve use for fixed rate (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how exchange rates are determined by demand and supply in the forex market and how all determinants connect — higher interest rates attract capital inflows raising demand for the currency appreciating it. Fixed exchange rates require central bank intervention buying or selling reserves. Required diagram for Unit 4.2.',real:'UK pound depreciation after Brexit vote 2016, Swiss franc peg to euro 2011-2015 — abandoned when unsustainable, Turkish lira collapse 2021 — high inflation differential, Chinese yuan managed float and US trade dispute'},

//     {label:'Current account — components deficits and adjustment',concept:'Interdependence, Change',related:'International economics, Markets, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.3: Balance of payments; AO4 required',scene:'A balance of payments decomposed into current account capital account and financial account. Current account shows trade in goods services income and transfers. Deficit shown when spending on imports exceeds export revenue. Automatic adjustment mechanisms — exchange rate depreciation J-curve effect.',sliders:['Trade in goods balance (0=Large deficit → 4=Large surplus)','Trade in services balance (0=Deficit → 4=Surplus — UK financial services)','Primary income (0=Net outflows — interest payments on debt → 4=Net inflows — investment returns)','Exchange rate effect on competitiveness (0=Overvalued — worsening deficit → 4=Depreciated — J-curve improvement)'],resources:['Current account balance GDP % (variable)','J-curve initial worsening then improvement (variable)','Financing requirement for deficit (variable)','Foreign debt accumulation rate (variable)','Marshall-Lerner condition met? (variable — PED exports + PED imports greater than 1)'],explain:'Students discover that a current account deficit must be financed by a capital or financial account surplus — borrowing from abroad. The J-curve shows that exchange rate depreciation initially worsens the current account (due to inelastic trade in short run) before improving it as volumes respond. The Marshall-Lerner condition determines whether depreciation improves the current account.',real:'UK persistent current account deficit — financial services surplus but goods deficit, China large surplus — export-led growth model, USA current account deficit financed by dollar reserve currency status, Greek current account crisis 2010 — unsustainable financing'},

//     {label:'Free trade and comparative advantage — gains from trade',concept:'Interdependence, Efficiency',related:'International economics, Equity, Sustainability',lp:'Open-minded, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.1: Free trade; AO4 Calculator required — comparative advantage',scene:'A two-country two-good comparative advantage table. Students calculate opportunity costs for each country and each good. The country with lower opportunity cost has comparative advantage. Pre-trade and post-trade production and consumption points shown on PPCs for each country. Gains from specialisation quantified.',sliders:['Country A productivity in Good 1 units per worker (0=Low → 4=High)','Country A productivity in Good 2 units per worker (0=Low → 4=High)','Country B productivity in Good 1 (0=Low → 4=High)','Terms of trade ratio (0=Unfavourable — gains go mainly to trading partner → 4=Favourable — most gains captured)'],resources:['Opportunity cost Good 1 in Country A (variable)','Opportunity cost Good 1 in Country B (variable)','Comparative advantage identified (variable)','Gains from trade — consumption above PPC (variable)','Terms of trade and distribution of gains (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate comparative advantage using opportunity cost and discover that trade is mutually beneficial even when one country is absolutely more productive in everything. The terms of trade determine how gains are distributed. HL Paper 3 requires quantitative comparative advantage calculation. Core Unit 4.1 content for all papers.',real:'UK and Portugal wine and cloth example (Ricardo), China comparative advantage in manufacturing shifting to services, India comparative advantage in IT services, US agricultural comparative advantage despite high wages'},

//     {label:'Protectionism — tariffs quotas and non-tariff barriers',concept:'Intervention, Interdependence',related:'International economics, Equity, Efficiency',lp:'Principled, Open-minded, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.1: Protectionism; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A tariff diagram showing domestic supply domestic demand world price and tariff-inclusive price. Consumer surplus falls producer surplus rises government revenue rectangle appears deadweight loss triangles shown. Quota diagram alongside — same welfare effects but revenue goes to importers not government. Stakeholder analysis.',sliders:['Tariff rate per unit (0=Free trade — no tariff → 4=Prohibitive tariff — no imports)','World price relative to domestic price (0=World price above domestic — no imports → 4=World price far below — large import quantity)','Type of protection (0=Tariff — government revenue → 4=Quota — no revenue)','Non-tariff barrier type (0=None → 4=Technical standards blocking imports)'],resources:['Consumer surplus loss from tariff (variable)','Producer surplus gain from protection (variable)','Government tariff revenue (variable)','Deadweight loss area from tariff (variable)','Import quantity before and after tariff (variable)'],explain:'Students draw the tariff diagram and calculate welfare effects on each stakeholder — consumers lose, domestic producers gain, government gains revenue, but net welfare falls by the deadweight loss. Quotas create the same DWL but government gains no revenue (captured by importers). Arguments for protection — infant industry, strategic trade, national security.',real:'US steel tariff 2018 — consumers pay higher prices, domestic steel producers protected, EU Common External Tariff on agricultural imports, China non-tariff barriers — technical standards blocking foreign products, WTO disputes mechanism and trade rules'},

//     {label:'Economic development and the development gap',concept:'Equity, Sustainability',related:'International economics, Economic well-being, Intervention',lp:'Caring, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.4: Development; AO4 required',scene:'A world map coloured by HDI score. Students click any country to see GDP per capita versus HDI plotted. Lorenz curve constructed from income quintile data. Gini coefficient calculated from Lorenz curve. Poverty trap diagram shows how poverty is self-reinforcing without external intervention.',sliders:['GDP per capita USD (0=Very low LDC under 1000 → 4=High income OECD 50000+)','Institutions quality index (0=Corrupt fragile state → 4=Strong transparent institutions)','Education and health investment % of GDP (0=Low — poverty trap → 4=High — human development)','Foreign aid and FDI inflows % of GDP (0=None → 4=Large — financing development)'],resources:['HDI score (variable — may diverge from GDP)','Gini coefficient from Lorenz curve (variable)','Population below poverty line % (variable)','Development gap relative to OECD average (variable)','SDG progress score (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that HDI and GDP per capita diverge significantly — some high-income countries score poorly on health and education, some middle-income countries punch above their GDP weight. The Lorenz curve construction and Gini coefficient calculation is an HL Paper 3 skill. The poverty trap explains why development is not automatic.',real:'Botswana high GDP but health HDI dragged down by HIV/AIDS, Cuba high HDI despite low GDP per capita, India vs China development divergence, Rwanda rapid HDI improvement from institutional reform'},

//     {label:'Lorenz curve and Gini coefficient — inequality measurement',concept:'Equity, Economic well-being',related:'Development, Sustainability, Intervention',lp:'Caring, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 3 — AO4 Calculator required — Lorenz curve construction and Gini',scene:'A Lorenz curve constructed step by step from quintile income share data. X-axis: cumulative % of population. Y-axis: cumulative % of income. Line of perfect equality (45 degree line) shown. Gini coefficient = area between Lorenz curve and equality line divided by total triangle area. Comparison between countries.',sliders:['Bottom quintile income share % (0=Low 2% — high inequality → 4=High 15% — more equal)','Middle quintile income share % (0=Low → 4=High — strong middle class)','Top quintile income share % (0=Moderate 35% → 4=Very high 65% — extreme inequality)','Country comparison (0=Nordic — Gini 0.25 → 4=South Africa — Gini 0.63)'],resources:['Lorenz curve drawn from quintile data (variable)','Gini coefficient calculated (variable — 0 = perfect equality 1 = perfect inequality)','Comparison Gini to OECD average (variable)','Redistribution effect of progressive taxation (variable)','Pre-tax vs post-tax Gini difference (variable)'],explain:'Students construct a Lorenz curve from income quintile data step by step and calculate the Gini coefficient as the ratio of the area between the curve and the equality line to the total triangle. This is a required HL Paper 3 quantitative skill. Different policies shift the Lorenz curve closer to or further from perfect equality.',real:'South Africa Gini 0.63 — most unequal in world, Nordic countries Gini 0.25-0.30 after tax redistribution, UK Gini 0.35 — pre-tax 0.52 showing large redistribution effect, China rising Gini from 0.28 to 0.47 during growth period'},

//     {label:'Minimum wage — floor in labour market and effects',concept:'Intervention, Equity',related:'Markets, Economic well-being, Efficiency',lp:'Principled, Caring, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.3: Minimum wage; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A labour market supply and demand diagram. Wage on vertical axis employment on horizontal. Minimum wage line set above equilibrium creates surplus of labour (unemployment shown as gap between Ls and Ld). Monopsony employer model shown alongside — minimum wage can increase employment when employer has market power.',sliders:['Minimum wage level relative to equilibrium (0=Below equilibrium — no effect → 4=Far above — large unemployment created)','Labour demand elasticity (0=Inelastic — small job loss → 4=Elastic — large job loss)','Employer market power (0=Competitive — minimum wage causes unemployment → 4=Monopsony — minimum wage increases employment)','Living wage level (0=Legal minimum → 4=Full living wage — higher standard)'],resources:['Employment change from minimum wage (variable)','Unemployment created surplus of labour (variable)','Total wage bill change (variable)','Poverty reduction effect (variable)','Income distribution effect (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the controversy around minimum wages — standard competitive model predicts unemployment but the monopsony model shows employment can rise. Empirical evidence is mixed, supporting the view that labour markets are often not perfectly competitive. The diagram shows the distributional benefit (higher wages for employed workers) against the efficiency cost (potential job losses).',real:'UK National Living Wage increases since 2016 — employment effects studied, Seattle minimum wage increase — Card and Krueger style studies, Germany minimum wage introduced 2015 — smaller job losses than predicted, Fast food industry automation response to wage increases'},

//     {label:'Phillips curve — short-run trade-off and long-run neutrality',concept:'Change, Intervention',related:'Macroeconomics, Economic well-being, Equity',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.4: Phillips curve; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'A short-run Phillips curve showing inverse relationship between unemployment and inflation. Students move along the curve as AD changes. Long-run Phillips curve shown as vertical at NAIRU — no long-run trade-off. Supply-side shocks shift the SRPC upward (stagflation). Expectations-augmented version.',sliders:['AD stimulus level (0=Tight — high unemployment low inflation → 4=Loose — low unemployment high inflation)','Supply shock (0=Positive — SRPC shifts down → 4=Negative — SRPC shifts up — stagflation)','NAIRU natural rate % (0=Low — well-functioning labour market → 4=High — structural unemployment)','Inflation expectations (0=Well-anchored — SRPC stable → 4=Unanchored — SRPC shifts up with each stimulus)'],resources:['Unemployment rate % (variable)','Inflation rate % (variable)','SRPC position (variable — shifts with supply shocks)','NAIRU level (variable)','Long-run trade-off (zero — LRPC vertical)'],explain:'Students discover the short-run trade-off between unemployment and inflation and the long-run vertical Phillips curve at NAIRU — there is no permanent trade-off. Policymakers exploiting the SRPC find that inflation expectations rise, shifting the curve upward and requiring more inflation for the same unemployment reduction. The stagflation of the 1970s moved the SRPC up.',real:'UK 1970s stagflation — oil shock shifted SRPC up, 1990s US Goldilocks economy — low unemployment AND low inflation, 2022 global inflation with low unemployment — SRPC shifted right, Fed 2022-2023 tightening to reduce inflation accepting unemployment rise'},

//     {label:'Supply-side policies — long-run growth and competitiveness',concept:'Efficiency, Change',related:'Macroeconomics, Sustainability, Economic well-being',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 3.7: Supply-side policies; AO4 Diagram required',scene:'An AD-AS diagram where LRAS shifts right through supply-side policies. SRAS also shifts right reducing costs. Intervention vs market-based supply-side policies shown: education and infrastructure (interventionist) versus deregulation labour flexibility and privatisation (market-based). Long-run growth path shown.',sliders:['Education and skills investment % of GDP (0=Low — slow human capital → 4=High — rapid skill accumulation)','Labour market flexibility (0=Rigid — high unemployment floor → 4=Flexible — fast wage adjustment)','Deregulation and competition policy (0=High barriers — low competition → 4=Open — competitive markets)','Infrastructure investment (0=Poor roads and broadband → 4=World-class infrastructure)'],resources:['LRAS shift magnitude rightward (variable)','Potential GDP change % (variable)','NAIRU reduction (variable)','Productivity growth rate % per year (variable)','Long-run price level effect (variable — falls with SRAS right shift)'],explain:'Students discover that supply-side policies shift LRAS rightward without creating inflation — unlike demand-side policies that move along SRAS and risk inflation. The trade-off between interventionist supply-side policies (need government spending) and market-based (need deregulation) is the core political economy debate.',real:'UK Thatcher deregulation and privatisation 1980s — market-based supply-side, Singapore education investment — interventionist supply-side, German Hartz labour market reforms 2003 — reduced structural unemployment, Ireland low corporation tax — market-based supply-side attracting FDI'},

//     {label:'Trade liberalisation — free trade areas and the WTO',concept:'Interdependence, Efficiency',related:'International economics, Equity, Sustainability',lp:'Open-minded, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.1: Trade liberalisation; AO4 required',scene:'A world map showing free trade area blocs — EU USMCA ASEAN. Trade creation and trade diversion effects shown in diagrams. WTO dispute settlement animated. Trade liberalisation welfare effects disaggregated by country and stakeholder group.',sliders:['Depth of trade liberalisation (0=No agreements — maximum protection → 4=Full free trade globally)','Trade creation effect (0=Minimal — high barriers within bloc → 4=Large — major efficiency gains)','Trade diversion effect (0=None — no discriminatory effects → 4=Large — third country producers displaced)','Distributional effects (0=All groups gain → 4=Some gain some lose — adjustment costs)'],resources:['Trade creation gains (variable)','Trade diversion losses (variable)','Net welfare effect (variable)','Job gains in export sectors (variable)','Job losses in import-competing industries (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that trade liberalisation creates winners (export industries, consumers of cheaper imports) and losers (import-competing workers) — even when the net effect is positive. Trade diversion occurs when a free trade area diverts trade from efficient non-member producers to less efficient member producers. The political economy of trade explains protectionist pressures.',real:'NAFTA/USMCA — trade creation in North America with trade diversion from Asia, Brexit — UK left EU free trade area, China WTO accession 2001 — large trade creation, US-China trade war — tariff escalation reversing liberalisation'},

//     {label:'Terms of trade and international competitiveness',concept:'Interdependence, Change',related:'International economics, Equity, Development',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.1 and 4.2: Terms of trade; AO4 Calculator required HL',scene:'A terms of trade index chart over time — price of exports divided by price of imports multiplied by 100. Improving terms of trade (export prices rising faster) versus deteriorating. Prebisch-Singer hypothesis shown — commodity exporters face long-run declining terms of trade relative to manufactured goods.',sliders:['Export price index (0=Falling — commodity price collapse → 4=Rising — commodity boom)','Import price index (0=Falling → 4=Rising — oil price spike)','Trade dependency on primary commodities % (0=Diversified economy → 4=Mono-commodity — terms of trade vulnerability)','Exchange rate appreciation (0=None → 4=Large appreciation — reduces export competitiveness)'],resources:['Terms of trade index = Px/Pm times 100 (variable)','Direction of change (improving or deteriorating)','Real income effect of terms of trade change (variable)','Current account impact (variable)','Prebisch-Singer hypothesis evidence (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that a country exports fewer units when terms of trade deteriorate to buy the same quantity of imports — equivalent to a real income loss. The Prebisch-Singer hypothesis argues that primary commodity exporters face secular decline in terms of trade versus manufactured good importers — a key argument for diversification and industrialisation in development.',real:'Zambia copper export terms of trade and economy dependence, Saudi Arabia oil export terms of trade and 2014 price collapse, EU manufactured goods exports — stable terms of trade, IMF commodity price super-cycle and impact on resource exporters'},

//     {label:'Development economics — strategies and aid effectiveness',concept:'Equity, Sustainability',related:'Development, Interdependence, Intervention',lp:'Caring, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.4: Development strategies; AO4 required',scene:'A development strategy comparison dashboard. Import substitution industrialisation versus export-led growth versus aid-based development versus FDI attraction. HDI and GDP per capita trajectories for countries following each strategy shown over 30 years. Sachs versus Easterly debate animated.',sliders:['Development strategy (0=Import substitution — protect infant industry → 4=Export-led growth — open economy)','Aid volume USD per capita (0=Zero → 4=Maximum — dependency risk)','FDI inflow % of GDP (0=None → 4=High — Dutch disease risk for commodity exporters)','Institutional quality (0=Weak — aid diverted → 4=Strong — aid effective)'],resources:['GDP per capita growth rate (variable)','HDI improvement score (variable)','Aid effectiveness index (variable)','Technology transfer from FDI (variable)','Debt sustainability ratio (variable)'],explain:'Students compare development strategies and discover that no single strategy guarantees development — export-led growth worked for East Asian tigers but requires favourable terms of trade; import substitution creates inefficiency without competition; aid effectiveness depends critically on institutional quality. The debate mirrors the Sachs big push versus Easterly decentralised knowledge argument.',real:'South Korea export-led growth 1960s-1990s, Brazil import substitution industrialisation and debt crisis, Rwanda aid-driven development and institutional reform, China FDI-led industrialisation and Dutch disease concerns'},

//     {label:'Marginal and average tax rates — fiscal policy and redistribution',concept:'Equity, Intervention',related:'Macroeconomics, Economic well-being, Development',lp:'Principled, Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 3 — AO4 Calculator required — marginal and average tax rates; Laffer curve',scene:'A tax rate calculator showing progressive tax bands. Students input income and the tool calculates marginal rate (on last pound earned) and average rate (total tax divided by income). Laffer curve shown — tax revenue rises then falls as rate increases. Progressive regressive and proportional tax systems compared.',sliders:['Income level annual (0=Low income 15000 → 4=High income 500000)','Tax system type (0=Regressive flat consumption tax → 4=Steeply progressive income tax)','Top marginal rate % (0=Low 20% → 4=High 80%)','Transfer payments and benefits (0=None → 4=Generous — effective redistribution)'],resources:['Marginal tax rate at given income % (variable)','Average tax rate % = total tax / income (variable)','After-tax income (variable)','Redistributive effect — Gini before and after tax (variable)','Laffer curve optimum rate estimate (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the distinction between marginal rates (affecting work incentives) and average rates (measuring tax burden). Progressive systems have higher marginal rates at higher incomes. The Laffer curve shows that beyond some tax rate revenue falls as incentives to earn or invest are reduced. HL Paper 3 requires calculating marginal and average rates from income data.',real:'UK income tax — 20% basic 40% higher 45% additional rate bands, Sweden marginal rate 57% on top incomes — high redistribution, Reagan tax cuts 1981 — supply-side argument from Laffer curve, CGT versus income tax avoidance through income conversion'},

//     {label:'Debt sustainability — government budget and national debt',concept:'Sustainability, Intervention',related:'Macroeconomics, Equity, Economic well-being',lp:'Principled, Balanced, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 3 — AO4 Calculator required — debt-to-GDP ratio',scene:'A debt dynamics simulation. Budget deficit adds to national debt each year. Interest payments on debt are themselves a cost increasing next year deficit. Debt-to-GDP ratio calculated. When GDP growth rate exceeds interest rate debt becomes sustainable. Debt crisis shown when deficit exceeds GDP growth threshold.',sliders:['Government budget deficit % of GDP (0=Surplus — debt falling → 4=Large deficit 10% — debt rising rapidly)','GDP growth rate % (0=Recession negative → 4=Strong growth 4%)','Interest rate on government debt % (0=Low 1% — cheap borrowing → 4=High 8% — debt spiral risk)','Initial debt level % of GDP (0=Low 20% → 4=Very high 180%)'],resources:['Debt-to-GDP ratio current and trend (variable)','Debt sustainability assessment (variable — r vs g)','Interest payments % of government spending (variable)','Primary balance required for stabilisation % (variable)','Credit rating and borrowing cost impact (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the key debt sustainability condition: when the interest rate r exceeds the GDP growth rate g, debt spirals upward even with a primary budget balance. Debt-to-GDP ratio falls when nominal GDP growth exceeds interest cost. HL Paper 3 requires calculating debt-to-GDP ratios and assessing sustainability.',real:'Japan debt 260% of GDP but low interest rates — sustainable so far, Greece debt crisis 2010 — market panic raised interest rates accelerating unsustainability, UK debt rise from 40% to 100% of GDP 2007-2021, COVID-19 debt surge across all economies'},

//     {label:'Sustainable development — environmental economics and green growth',concept:'Sustainability, Equity',related:'Development, Intervention, Economic well-being',lp:'Caring, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Unit 4.4: Sustainable development; AO4 required',scene:'A triple bottom line dashboard: economic GDP growth, social equity and human development, environmental sustainability. Students adjust policy sliders and observe trade-offs. Environmental Kuznets Curve shown — pollution rises then falls with income. Green GDP versus conventional GDP comparison.',sliders:['Economic growth priority (0=Degrowth — environment first → 4=Maximum GDP — growth first)','Carbon pricing level per tonne (0=Zero — no environmental signal → 4=High 150 per tonne — strong incentive)','Green infrastructure investment % (0=None → 4=Full green new deal)','International environmental cooperation (0=None → 4=Binding global carbon budget)'],resources:['GDP growth rate % (variable)','Gini coefficient and equity measure (variable)','Carbon emissions per capita tonnes (variable)','Environmental Kuznets Curve position (variable)','SDG progress composite score (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the tension in sustainable development — economic growth can improve human welfare but degrades the environment. The Environmental Kuznets Curve suggests pollution peaks at middle income and falls, but this is not automatic without policy. Green GDP accounting subtracts environmental depreciation from conventional GDP.',real:'Costa Rica green GDP accounting and conservation, Bhutan Gross National Happiness alternative to GDP, EU Green New Deal investment programme, Norway sovereign wealth fund from oil wealth investing in renewables'},

//     {label:'Behavioural economics — nudge theory and bounded rationality',concept:'Choice, Efficiency',related:'Markets, Intervention, Economic well-being',lp:'Thinkers, Open-minded, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 — Unit 2.6 HL: Behavioural economics; AO4 required HL',scene:'A series of choice architecture experiments. Default option nudge shown — organ donation opt-in versus opt-out dramatically changes donation rates. Anchoring bias shown — starting price influences final price paid. Loss aversion — framing an outcome as loss versus gain changes decision. Present bias in savings.',sliders:['Choice architecture type (0=No nudge — free choice → 4=Strong nudge — default option heavily influences)','Loss aversion multiplier (0=Standard rational agent → 4=Strong loss aversion — losses feel 2-3 times gains)','Present bias discount rate (0=Future and present weighted equally → 4=Extreme present bias — discounts future heavily)','Information provision (0=No information — uninformed choice → 4=Full transparent information)'],resources:['Decision outcome vs rational prediction (variable)','Nudge effectiveness % change in behaviour (variable)','Welfare improvement from nudge (variable)','Freedom of choice preserved (variable)','Government paternalism concern (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that real human decisions systematically deviate from the rational agent model — loss aversion means losses hurt more than equivalent gains feel good; present bias leads to undersaving; anchoring distorts price judgements. Nudge theory uses these biases to improve outcomes without restricting choice — libertarian paternalism. HL content Unit 2.6.',real:'UK pension auto-enrolment nudge — opt-out raised savings dramatically, Organ donation opt-out UK 2020 — nudge raised donor rates, Menu calorie labelling — nudge reducing unhealthy choice, Payday loan warning labels — anchoring bias correction'}
//   ]},
//   {icon:'∫',name:'Mathematics AA',sub:'30 simulations · Algebra · Functions · Trig · Calculus · Probability',topics:[
//     {label:'Arithmetic sequences \u2014 terms, partial sums and sigma notation',concept:'Patterns',related:'Quantity, Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Number and Algebra \u2014 1.2 Arithmetic sequences',scene:'A number line fills the screen with glowing dots spaced equally. A staircase bar chart shows each term u_n. A sigma notation panel expands the sum live. Students add terms one by one watching S_n grow linearly. A running partial sum counter and a formula derivation panel sit side by side.',sliders:['First term a (0=a=1 \u2192 4=a=100)','Common difference d (0=d=\u22125 \u2014 decreasing \u2192 4=d=10 \u2014 rapidly increasing)','Number of terms n (0=n=3 \u2192 4=n=20)','Display mode (0=Terms only \u2192 4=Sigma notation \u2014 show summation formula)'],resources:['n-th term u_n = a+(n-1)d (variable)','Partial sum S_n = n/2(2a+(n-1)d) (variable)','Last term u_n (variable)','Difference between consecutive terms (constant = d)','Sigma notation \u03a3 expanded (variable)'],explain:'Students build arithmetic sequences term by term and discover that S_n grows quadratically even though each term grows linearly. The formula S_n = n/2(first + last) is derived visually by pairing terms. Sigma notation is decoded through the animation of term-by-term expansion. Maps directly to DP AA Topic 1.2.',real:'Seat rows in a theatre increasing by 3 per row, Stacking logs in a triangular arrangement, Salary increments with fixed annual raise, Simple interest as arithmetic progression'},

//     {label:'Geometric sequences and infinite series \u2014 convergence and Zeno\'s paradox',concept:'Patterns',related:'Function, Change, Quantity',lp:'Inquirers, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Number and Algebra \u2014 1.3\u20131.4 Geometric sequences',scene:'A number line shows a ball bouncing, each bounce exactly r times the previous. Bars chart the terms of the sequence. A running partial sum S_n counter ticks toward the exact limit S_\u221e shown in gold. A fraction breakdown shows each term. A red zone shows the shrinking gap to the limit.',sliders:['Common ratio r (0=r=0.9 \u2014 slow convergence \u2192 4=r=0.1 \u2014 rapid)','First term a (0=a=1 \u2192 4=a=64)','Number of terms n (0=n=3 \u2192 4=n=20)','Divergent mode (0=|r|<1 \u2014 converges \u2192 4=r=1.5 \u2014 explodes)'],resources:['n-th term u_n = ar^(n-1) (variable)','Partial sum S_n (variable)','Infinite sum S_\u221e = a/(1\u2212r) for |r|<1 (variable)','Error S_\u221e \u2212 S_n (variable)','Converges? (yes/no)'],explain:'Zeno\'s paradox: can you traverse infinite steps in finite time? Students discover that an infinite sum of a geometric sequence can be finite when |r|<1. Switching |r|>1 shows divergence dramatically. The partial sums converge physically toward the gold target line. Maps to DP AA Topic 1.3\u20131.4.',real:'Bouncing ball total distance, Repeated drug doses reaching steady-state, Koch snowflake perimeter, Compound decay of medication in bloodstream'},

//     {label:'Compound interest and continuous compounding \u2014 e as a natural limit',concept:'Quantity',related:'Function, Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Financial mathematics \u2014 1.5\u20131.6',scene:'Two side-by-side bars: simple interest grows as a straight line, compound interest curves upward exponentially. A compounding frequency panel shows annual, half-yearly, quarterly, monthly, daily, continuous \u2014 each nudges the curve higher. The formula (1+1/n)^n approaches e=2.718... shown on a counter.',sliders:['Principal amount (0=$1,000 \u2192 4=$100,000)','Annual nominal interest rate % (0=1% \u2192 4=10%)','Compounding frequency n per year (0=Annual n=1 \u2192 4=Daily n=365)','Time horizon years (0=5 years \u2192 4=40 years \u2014 dramatic divergence)'],resources:['Future value A = P(1+r/n)^(nt) (variable)','Simple interest comparison (variable)','Continuous compounding A = Pe^(rt) (variable)','Effective annual rate r_eff (variable)','Total interest earned (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how the frequency of compounding affects final value \u2014 and that daily compounding is virtually identical to continuous compounding. The limit of (1+1/n)^n as n\u2192\u221e equals e=2.718... making e emerge naturally from financial mathematics. Maps to DP AA Topic 1.5\u20131.6.',real:'Bank savings account compounding, Mortgage annual vs daily compounding comparison, Investment app compound growth, Cryptocurrency staking yield calculation'},

//     {label:'Binomial theorem \u2014 Pascal\'s triangle, expansion and combinatorics',concept:'Patterns',related:'Quantity, Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Binomial theorem \u2014 1.9\u20131.10',scene:'A glowing Pascal\'s triangle grows row by row with each coefficient lighting up as n-choose-r. Clicking a row shows the full binomial expansion of (a+b)^n term by term. A Galton board drops marbles through pegs accumulating in a histogram matching row n of the triangle.',sliders:['Power n (0=n=1 \u2014 trivial \u2192 4=n=10 \u2014 complex expansion)','Values of a and b (0=a=b=1 \u2014 pure Pascal \u2192 4=a=2 b=3 \u2014 real coefficients)','Show probability interpretation (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 n coin tosses P(X=r))','Galton board marbles (0=20 \u2192 4=500 \u2014 normal shape emerges)'],resources:['Coefficient C(n,r) (variable)','r-th term = C(n,r)a^(n-r)b^r (variable)','P(X=r) binomial probability (variable)','Row sum = 2^n (variable)','Specific term identified (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that Pascal\'s triangle simultaneously encodes combinatorics, binomial algebra, and probability. The Galton board reveals that the binomial distribution converges to the normal distribution as n grows \u2014 the Central Limit Theorem previewed. The nCr calculator makes the formula concrete. Maps to DP AA Topic 1.9\u20131.10.',real:'Coin flip probability distribution, Genetic inheritance ratios, Pascal\'s triangle in Chinese mathematics (Yang Hui triangle), Galton board and normal distribution'},

//     {label:'Complex numbers \u2014 Argand plane, polar form and arithmetic',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1 AHL: Complex numbers \u2014 AHL 1.12',scene:'An Argand diagram fills the screen. A complex number z appears as a glowing arrow. Its modulus |z| shown as length, argument \u03b8 as a rotating arc. A form-switcher toggles between rectangular a+bi, polar r(cos\u03b8+i sin\u03b8), and Euler re^(i\u03b8). Arithmetic operations animate geometrically.',sliders:['Real part a (0=a=\u22124 \u2192 4=a=+4)','Imaginary part b (0=b=\u22124 \u2192 4=b=+4)','Operation (0=Plot z \u2192 4=Multiply two complex numbers \u2014 rotation visible)','Form display (0=Rectangular \u2192 4=Euler re^(i\u03b8) \u2014 most elegant)'],resources:['Modulus |z| = \u221a(a\u00b2+b\u00b2) (variable)','Argument arg(z) in radians (variable)','Conjugate z* = a\u2212bi (variable)','Product |z\u2082||z\u2081| at angle \u03b8\u2081+\u03b8\u2082 (variable)','Euler form z = re^(i\u03b8) (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that multiplying two complex numbers adds their arguments and multiplies their moduli \u2014 rotation and scaling on the Argand plane. Euler\'s formula e^(i\u03c0)+1=0 emerges naturally when \u03b8=\u03c0. The three equivalent forms of complex numbers are converted live. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 1.12.',real:'AC circuit phasor diagrams in electrical engineering, Quantum wave function phase, Signal processing Fourier transforms, Fractal Julia set iteration on the complex plane'},

//     {label:'De Moivre\'s theorem \u2014 powers, roots and roots of unity (HL)',concept:'Patterns',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1 AHL: De Moivre \u2014 AHL 1.13\u20131.14',scene:'A unit circle on the Argand plane. A complex number z with |z|=1 shown as an arrow. Pressing "raise to power n" rotates the arrow by n times its argument \u2014 animated smoothly. Finding nth roots shows n equally spaced roots appearing around the circle like clock positions.',sliders:['Modulus r (0=r=0.5 \u2014 spirals inward \u2192 4=r=2 \u2014 spirals outward)','Argument \u03b8 as fraction of \u03c0 (0=\u03b8=\u03c0/6 \u2192 4=\u03b8=5\u03c0/6)','Power n (0=n=2 \u2192 4=n=8 \u2014 octagon of roots)','Roots or powers mode (0=Compute z^n \u2192 4=Find n-th roots of z)'],resources:['z^n = r^n e^(in\u03b8) (variable)','Argument of z^n (variable)','n-th roots equally spaced at 2\u03c0/n (variable)','Are roots on unit circle? (yes if |z|=1)','Root spacing angle (variable)'],explain:'Students discover De Moivre\'s theorem: (r e^(i\u03b8))^n = r^n e^(in\u03b8) \u2014 simply raise the modulus to the power and multiply the argument. The nth roots of unity form a perfect regular polygon on the unit circle. This connects complex numbers, trigonometry, and geometry in one elegant result. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 1.13\u20131.14.',real:'Signal processing n-th roots of unity as DFT basis, Regular polygon construction from complex roots, Solving z^n = 1 in engineering, Crystallographic symmetry groups'},

//     {label:'Proof by mathematical induction \u2014 base case and inductive step (HL)',concept:'Patterns',related:'Logic, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1 AHL: Proof \u2014 AHL 1.15',scene:'An animated domino chain fills the screen. Step 1: the first domino falls (base case verified). Step 2: each domino, when it falls, knocks the next (inductive step). Students work through a proof that 1+2+3+...+n = n(n+1)/2 with each step animated. The algebra fills in panel by panel.',sliders:['Statement to prove (0=Sum of first n integers \u2192 4=Divisibility: 3^n\u22121 divisible by 2)','Step shown (0=Base case n=1 only \u2192 4=Full inductive step \u2014 assume P(k) prove P(k+1))','n value for numerical verification (0=n=5 \u2192 4=n=20 \u2014 test formula)','Show LHS = RHS check (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Full algebraic manipulation shown)'],resources:['P(1) verified (yes/no)','P(k) assumed form (variable)','P(k+1) shown to follow (variable)','Algebraic manipulation steps (variable)','Proof complete (yes/no)'],explain:'Students experience the two-step structure of mathematical induction: prove P(1) is true, then show P(k)\u21d2P(k+1). The domino chain makes the logic physical \u2014 you don\'t need to check every n, just the base and the chain. Common errors (forgetting base case, circular reasoning) are flagged. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 1.15.',real:'Establishing formulas for sum of series, Proving divisibility results, Computer science recursive algorithm correctness, Proving inequality chains like 2^n > n\u00b2 for large n'},

//     {label:'Function transformations \u2014 translations, reflections, stretches and composites',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.3\u20132.5',scene:'A parent function f(x) shown in deep indigo. Four transformation sliders reshape it live. Horizontal and vertical translations shift it. Vertical and horizontal stretches scale it. Reflections flip it. A step-by-step mapping notation a\u00b7f(bx+c)+d tracks every transformation applied. A composite g(f(x)) preview panel.',sliders:['Vertical stretch a (0=a=0.2 \u2014 squashed \u2192 4=a=4 \u2014 tall)','Horizontal compression b (0=b=0.25 \u2014 wide \u2192 4=b=3 \u2014 narrow)','Horizontal shift c (0=c=\u22123 \u2014 left \u2192 4=c=+3 \u2014 right)','Vertical shift d (0=d=\u22123 \u2014 down \u2192 4=d=+3 \u2014 up)'],resources:['Mapping notation (variable)','Effect on domain (variable)','Effect on range (variable)','Effect on key points (variable)','Inverse transformation needed to undo (variable)'],explain:'Students apply each transformation in sequence and discover the non-commutative nature of function composition: horizontal transformations work "inside" f and feel counterintuitive. The mapping notation a\u00b7f(bx+c)+d encodes all four transformations in one expression. Directly prepares for every IB Paper 1 transformation question. Maps to DP AA Topic 2.',real:'Sinusoidal model fitting: a sin(bx+c)+d for tidal data, Scaling a probability distribution, Doppler effect as frequency transformation, Image scaling and translation in computer graphics'},

//     {label:'Quadratic functions \u2014 forms, discriminant and completing the square',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.6\u20132.7',scene:'A parabola adjusts with three form-switcher tabs: standard ax\u00b2+bx+c, vertex a(x\u2212h)\u00b2+k, and factored a(x\u2212r)(x\u2212s). Sliders change parameters and the parabola morphs. The discriminant \u0394=b\u00b2\u22124ac pulses: green (two roots), amber (one root), red (no real roots). Completing the square shown step by step.',sliders:['Coefficient a (0=a=\u22122 \u2014 downward \u2192 4=a=3 \u2014 steep upward)','Discriminant control via b (0=b=0 \u2014 perfect square \u2192 4=b large \u2014 two roots)','Coefficient c (0=c=\u22126 \u2192 4=c=6)','Form display (0=Standard \u2192 4=Vertex form \u2014 completing the square)'],resources:['\u0394 = b\u00b2\u22124ac value (variable)','Number of real roots (0, 1, or 2)','Vertex coordinates (h,k) (variable)','Roots (if real) (variable)','Axis of symmetry x = \u2212b/2a (variable)'],explain:'Students switch between three equivalent forms of a quadratic and see the same parabola expressed differently. The discriminant sign predicts root count before any solving. Completing the square animates step-by-step, revealing why the vertex x-coordinate is \u2212b/2a. Essential for every IB quadratic question. Maps to DP AA Topic 2.6\u20132.7.',real:'Projectile height model: h = \u22124.9t\u00b2+ut+h_0, Profit maximisation parabola, Bridge arch parabolic shape, Lens focal point geometry'},

//     {label:'Rational functions and asymptotes \u2014 reciprocal and transformed hyperbola',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.8',scene:'A hyperbola y=(ax+b)/(cx+d) drawn with asymptotes as dashed lines. Sliders change parameters and asymptotes jump to new positions. Axes of symmetry shown. Self-inverse nature of y=1/x demonstrated by overlaying the reflection in y=x. The graph splits across asymptote lines.',sliders:['Numerator parameters a,b (0=a=1 b=0 \u2014 simple 1/x \u2192 4=a=2 b=3 \u2014 shifted)','Denominator parameters c,d (0=c=1 d=0 \u2192 4=c=1 d=\u22122 \u2014 vertical asymptote x=2)','Show asymptotes (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Shown with equations labelled)','Inverse overlay (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Show f\u207b\u00b9(x) \u2014 same function for 1/x)'],resources:['Vertical asymptote x = \u2212d/c (variable)','Horizontal asymptote y = a/c (variable)','x-intercept (variable)','y-intercept (variable)','Self-inverse? f(f(x))=x (yes/no)'],explain:'Students discover that the hyperbola y=1/x is its own inverse \u2014 reflecting it over y=x gives the same curve. Adding parameters shifts the asymptotes to any position. The full rational function (ax+b)/(cx+d) simplifies to a transformed reciprocal, making all such functions members of the same family. Maps to DP AA Topic 2.8.',real:'Ohm\'s law: I = V/R as reciprocal function of resistance, Boyle\'s law: PV = constant, Time to travel vs speed for fixed distance, Lens equation 1/v + 1/u = 1/f'},

//     {label:'Exponential and logarithmic functions \u2014 growth, decay, log scales',concept:'Function',related:'Change, Patterns, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Inquirers, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.9\u20132.11',scene:'A split screen: left shows exponential growth and decay curves (e^x, 2^x, e^(-kx)) updating with sliders. Right shows ln(x) as its mirror over y=x. A half-life animation shows a glowing isotope decaying. Switching to log-scale on the y-axis straightens the exponential into a line. A real data overlay (COVID growth rate) fits to an exponential.',sliders:['Decay constant k (0=k=0.01 \u2014 slow \u2192 4=k=0.7 \u2014 rapid half-life)','Time horizon (0=Short \u2192 4=Long \u2014 dramatic divergence)','Log scale toggle (0=Linear y-axis \u2192 4=Logarithmic y-axis \u2014 becomes straight line)','Base b (0=b=0.5 \u2014 decay \u2192 4=b=3 \u2014 rapid growth)'],resources:['Half-life t\u00bd = ln2/k (variable)','Function value at t (variable)','Doubling time (variable)','Gradient on log-scale = k (constant)','Inverse ln(x) value (variable)'],explain:'Students see exponential decay as radioactive half-life and exponential growth as compound interest simultaneously. The transformative insight: switching to log scale turns a curve into a straight line, explaining why scientists always plot growth data on log-log or semi-log axes. The ln(x) inverse mirrors perfectly. Maps to DP AA Topic 2.9\u20132.11.',real:'Radioactive carbon-14 dating, COVID-19 growth rate on log scale, Richter scale earthquake magnitudes, Population doubling time, Decibel sound intensity'},

//     {label:'Inverse functions and domain restrictions \u2014 reflection and bijectivity',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.2\u20132.3',scene:'A function f(x) and its inverse f\u207b\u00b9(x) drawn simultaneously \u2014 always symmetric over y=x. Dragging a point on f traces the reflected point on f\u207b\u00b9. A domain restriction slider clips f(x) to make it one-to-one, enabling an inverse. The vertical line test and horizontal line test both animate.',sliders:['Function type (0=Linear \u2014 always invertible \u2192 4=Quadratic \u2014 needs restriction)','Domain restriction left boundary (0=\u2212\u221e \u2014 not injective \u2192 4=x\u22650 \u2014 now invertible)','Show y=x mirror line (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 reflection obvious)','Composite f(f\u207b\u00b9(x)) (0=Not shown \u2192 4=Shown = x identity)'],resources:['f\u207b\u00b9(x) equation (variable)','Domain of f\u207b\u00b9 = range of f (variable)','Range of f\u207b\u00b9 = domain of f (variable)','Is f one-to-one? (yes/no)','f(f\u207b\u00b9(x)) = x verified (yes/no)'],explain:'Students discover that a function must be one-to-one (injective) to have an inverse. Dragging a parabola\'s domain restriction to x\u22650 makes it invertible \u2014 its inverse is the square root function. The y=x mirror line makes the geometric relationship between f and f\u207b\u00b9 obvious. Maps to DP AA Topic 2.2\u20132.3.',real:'Celsius/Fahrenheit inverse conversion functions, Logarithm as inverse of exponential, arcsin as inverse of sin on restricted domain, Encryption and decryption as inverse operations'},

//     {label:'Trigonometric functions \u2014 unit circle, radian measure and transformations',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3: Trigonometry \u2014 3.4\u20133.9',scene:'A unit circle with a glowing point moving around it. As the angle increases, sin and cos values trace out the sine and cosine waves in real time on the right panel. A degree-to-radian converter runs alongside. Sliders build a sin(bx+c)+d transforming the wave. A second comparison wave appears.',sliders:['Amplitude a (0=a=0.2 \u2014 barely visible \u2192 4=a=4 \u2014 tall)','Period controller b (0=b=0.25 \u2014 slow wave \u2192 4=b=4 \u2014 rapid oscillation)','Phase shift c (0=c=0 \u2192 4=c=\u03c0 \u2014 half period)','Vertical shift d (0=d=\u22122 \u2192 4=d=+2)'],resources:['Period T = 2\u03c0/b (variable)','Amplitude a (variable)','Range [d\u2212a, d+a] (variable)','Phase shift \u2212c/b (variable)','Angle in radians and degrees (variable)'],explain:'Students watch sine and cosine literally being drawn by a point rotating on the unit circle \u2014 the geometric definition brought to life. All four parameters of the transformed sinusoidal function are adjusted simultaneously. The radian measure emerges naturally as the arc length on the unit circle. Maps to DP AA Topic 3.4\u20133.9.',real:'Sound wave frequency and amplitude (pitch and loudness), Tidal height over 24 hours, Seasonal temperature variation, ECG heart rhythm patterns, Ferris wheel height vs time'},

//     {label:'Trigonometric equations and identities \u2014 Pythagorean and compound angles',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3: Trigonometry \u2014 3.10\u20133.12',scene:'The unit circle shows sin\u00b2\u03b8 + cos\u00b2\u03b8 = 1 as squares on the two legs of a right triangle inside the circle. Sliders rotate \u03b8 and the squares resize but always sum to 1. A double angle panel shows sin(2\u03b8) = 2sin\u03b8cos\u03b8 geometrically. Compound angle identities verified numerically for any A and B.',sliders:['Angle \u03b8 (0=\u03b8=0 \u2192 4=\u03b8=2\u03c0 \u2014 full rotation)','Second angle for compound: A+B (0=A=30\u00b0 B=30\u00b0 \u2192 4=A=60\u00b0 B=45\u00b0)','Identity shown (0=Pythagorean \u2192 4=Compound angle sin(A+B))','Show numerical verification (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 LHS=RHS checked)'],resources:['sin\u00b2\u03b8 + cos\u00b2\u03b8 (always =1)','sin(A+B) = sinAcosB + cosAsinB (verified)','cos(2\u03b8) in three forms (variable)','tan\u03b8 = sin\u03b8/cos\u03b8 (variable)','Double angle sin(2\u03b8) (variable)'],explain:'Students verify the Pythagorean identity by watching sin\u00b2\u03b8 + cos\u00b2\u03b8 = 1 hold true for every angle as the unit circle point rotates. The double angle formula is shown geometrically and numerically. The compound angle identity sin(A+B) is verified for any A,B students choose. Maps to DP AA Topic 3.10\u20133.12.',real:'Constructing sin(75\u00b0) exactly from known angles, Phase addition of AC signals, Beats phenomenon in music from interfering sound waves, GPS trilateration using trigonometric identities'},

//     {label:'Inverse and reciprocal trigonometric functions \u2014 arcsin arccos arctan sec csc cot (HL)',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3 AHL: Trigonometry \u2014 AHL 3.12\u20133.13',scene:'Six graphs tile the screen: sin, cos, tan alongside their inverses arcsin, arccos, arctan. Domain restrictions shown in green (the valid input window for each inverse). Reciprocal trig functions sec=1/cos, csc=1/sin, cot=1/tan plotted with their asymptotes. A mapping shows where each blows up.',sliders:['Input x value (0=x=\u22121 \u2192 4=x=+1 for arcsin/arccos)','Show domain restriction for inverse (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 valid region highlighted)','Reciprocal function (0=sec(x) \u2192 4=cot(x))','Compare to parent trig function (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Overlay \u2014 reciprocal relationship visible)'],resources:['arcsin(x) value in radians (variable)','arccos(x) value (variable)','arctan(x) value (variable)','sec(x) = 1/cos(x) (variable)','Domain of arcsin: [\u22121, 1] (constant)'],explain:'Students discover why arcsin only maps [\u22121,1] to [\u2212\u03c0/2, \u03c0/2] \u2014 the sine function is not one-to-one over its full domain so the inverse must be restricted. Reciprocal functions blow up wherever the parent function equals zero \u2014 the asymptotes of sec(x) appear exactly where cos(x) crosses zero. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 3.12\u20133.13.',real:'Solving for angle in navigation bearing problems, Inverse trig in engineering for angle calculations, sec and csc appearing in integration results, arctan used in computer graphics for atan2 function'},

//     {label:'Vectors \u2014 dot product, projection, angle and 3D applications',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Mathematical modelling, Spatial reasoning',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3: Vectors \u2014 3.14\u20133.16',scene:'Two 3D vectors emerge from the origin on an interactive Argand-style space. Dragging changes their direction. The angle between them shown as a glowing arc. A projection shadow of one vector onto the other animates. The dot product value pulses positive (acute), zero (perpendicular), or negative (obtuse).',sliders:['Vector a direction (0=Pointing right \u2192 4=Pointing left \u2014 angle opens)','Vector b elevation in 3D (0=Flat \u2014 2D \u2192 4=Steep vertical \u2014 3D)','Magnitudes ratio |a|/|b| (0=Equal \u2192 4=a ten times b)','Show projection of a onto b (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Shadow projection animated)'],resources:['Dot product a\u00b7b (variable)','Angle between vectors (variable)','Projection of a onto b (variable)','Are they perpendicular? (yes/no)','Vector components in i, j, k (variable)'],explain:'Students physically drag vectors and feel the dot product respond: it hits zero exactly when vectors are perpendicular. The projection animation makes a\u00b7b = |a||b|cos\u03b8 geometrically obvious. The 3D view adds the k-component and tests understanding of 3D angle calculation. Maps to DP AA Topic 3.14\u20133.16.',real:'Work done by a force along a displacement, Finding the normal to a surface, Robot arm configuration, Computer graphics lighting angle calculation'},

//     {label:'Cross product, vector lines and planes (HL)',concept:'Function',related:'Patterns, Mathematical modelling, Spatial reasoning',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3 AHL: Vectors \u2014 AHL 3.17\u20133.18',scene:'A 3D coordinate system shows two vectors a and b. Their cross product a\xd7b shown as a perpendicular arrow. The parallelogram formed by a and b shaded, its area = |a\xd7b|. A plane built from two vectors shown as a flat panel. The normal vector sticks out perpendicularly. Line-plane and plane-plane intersections animated.',sliders:['Vector a components (0=a=(1,0,0) \u2192 4=a=(2,3,1) \u2014 3D)','Vector b components (0=b=(0,1,0) \u2192 4=b=(1,2,\u22121))','Show plane with normal vector (0=Off \u2192 4=Plane and normal shown)','Intersection type (0=Line-plane \u2192 4=Three planes \u2014 classify solution)'],resources:['Cross product a\xd7b (variable)','|a\xd7b| = parallelogram area (variable)','Normal to plane n = a\xd7b (variable)','Plane equation n\u00b7(r\u2212a)=0 (variable)','Lines skew, parallel, or intersecting (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the cross product gives a vector perpendicular to both inputs \u2014 and its magnitude equals the parallelogram area. This perpendicular is precisely the normal to the plane containing a and b. Line-plane intersection finds where a parametric line pierces a Cartesian plane. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 3.17\u20133.18.',real:'Normal to a wing surface for aerodynamic lift calculation, Volume of parallelepiped using scalar triple product, 3D computer graphics surface normals for rendering, GPS plane intersection for position finding'},

//     {label:'Probability \u2014 Venn diagrams, tree diagrams and conditional probability',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Probability \u2014 4.5\u20134.6',scene:'A two-event Venn diagram with animated populations. Students drag event probabilities. Union, intersection, and complement regions shade interactively. A tree diagram builds alongside for conditional probability. The formula P(A|B) = P(A\u2229B)/P(B) shown live. An independence checker flashes when P(A\u2229B) = P(A)P(B).',sliders:['P(A) (0=0.1 \u2192 4=0.9)','P(B) (0=0.1 \u2192 4=0.9)','P(A\u2229B) \u2014 overlap (0=0 \u2014 mutually exclusive \u2192 4=Min(P(A),P(B)) \u2014 subset)','Events independent? (0=Dependent \u2192 4=Set P(A\u2229B)=P(A)P(B) \u2014 independent)'],resources:['P(A\u222aB) = P(A)+P(B)\u2212P(A\u2229B) (variable)','P(A|B) conditional probability (variable)','P(B|A) conditional probability (variable)','Independent? P(A\u2229B)=P(A)P(B) (yes/no)','P(A\u2019) complement (variable)'],explain:'Students adjust event probabilities and watch the Venn diagram respond \u2014 P(A\u222aB) updates by the addition rule. The conditional probability P(A|B) is shown as the fraction of B occupied by A\u2229B. Setting events independent shows the multiplication rule holds exactly. The tree diagram doubles as a second method for the same calculation. Maps to DP AA Topic 4.5\u20134.6.',real:'Medical test false positive/negative rates, Selecting balls without replacement, Weather forecast: rain given cloudy morning, Two machines failure probability in series vs parallel'},

//     {label:'Bayes\' theorem \u2014 posterior probability and the base rate fallacy',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Probability \u2014 4.6 Bayes\' theorem',scene:'A medical testing scenario. 1000 animated population dots fill the screen. Diseased dots glow red (prevalence set by slider). Test positive dots get a blue ring. True positives, false positives, false negatives, true negatives visible. Bayes\' theorem calculates P(disease|positive) step by step. A confusion matrix updates in the corner.',sliders:['Disease prevalence % (0=0.1% \u2014 rare \u2192 4=20% \u2014 common disease)','Test sensitivity true positive rate % (0=60% \u2014 poor \u2192 4=99% \u2014 excellent)','Test specificity true negative rate % (0=70% \u2014 poor \u2192 4=99% \u2014 excellent)','Population size shown (0=100 dots \u2192 4=10000 dots)'],resources:['P(disease|positive test) (variable)','False positive count (variable)','False negative count (variable)','Positive predictive value (variable)','Negative predictive value (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the most counterintuitive result in probability: even a 99% accurate test gives mostly false positives when the disease is rare. P(disease|positive) depends critically on prevalence \u2014 the base rate fallacy made visceral. Bayes\' theorem calculated live from the tree diagram. Maps to DP AA Topic 4.6.',real:'COVID-19 test false positive rate in low-prevalence areas, Airport security screening and false alarms, DNA court evidence probability misinterpretation, Spam filter Bayesian classification'},

//     {label:'Binomial distribution \u2014 P(X=k), cumulative probabilities and mean/variance',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.7 Binomial distribution',scene:'An animated coin is tossed n times. The binomial distribution B(n,p) histogram glows \u2014 each bar shows P(X=k). As sliders move, the histogram reshapes. P(X=k), P(X\u2264k), P(X>k) each highlighted as requested. The mean \u03bc=np and variance \u03c3\u00b2=np(1\u2212p) update live with annotated arrows on the histogram.',sliders:['Number of trials n (0=n=5 \u2192 4=n=30)','Probability of success p (0=p=0.1 \u2014 rare \u2192 4=p=0.9 \u2014 frequent)','Query: find P(X=k) for k= (0=k=0 \u2192 4=k=n)','Cumulative: P(X\u2264k) shown (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 shaded left tail)'],resources:['P(X=k) = C(n,k)p^k(1\u2212p)^(n-k) (variable)','P(X\u2264k) cumulative (variable)','Mean \u03bc = np (variable)','Variance \u03c3\u00b2 = np(1\u2212p) (variable)','Approach to normal as n increases (visible)'],explain:'Students explore the full binomial distribution interactively \u2014 computing exact probabilities for any k, reading cumulative probabilities for inequalities, and verifying the mean and variance formulas. As n grows and p stays moderate, the histogram bell-curves into a normal distribution. Maps to DP AA Topic 4.7.',real:'Defective items in a production batch: X~B(20,0.05), Drug trial success rate P(X\u22658) out of 10 patients, Quality control acceptance sampling, Genetics: offspring with dominant trait'},

//     {label:'Normal distribution \u2014 z-scores, probabilities and inverse normal',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.9\u20134.10',scene:'A glowing normal bell curve with adjustable mean and standard deviation. Shading appears between any two x-values showing P(a<X<b). A z-score standardisation panel converts X to Z~N(0,1). The 68-95-99.7 rule highlighted. An inverse normal tool: drag a probability slider and the x-value appears.',sliders:['\u03bc (mean) (0=\u03bc=0 \u2192 4=\u03bc=100 \u2014 real measurement scale)','Standard deviation \u03c3 (0=\u03c3=0.5 \u2014 tight \u2192 4=\u03c3=20 \u2014 wide spread)','Query value x (0=x=\u03bc\u22122\u03c3 \u2192 4=x=\u03bc+3\u03c3)','Inverse normal: given probability p, find x (0=p=0.05 \u2019 4=p=0.95)'],resources:['P(X<x) shaded area (variable)','z-score = (x\u2212\u03bc)/\u03c3 (variable)','P(\u03bc\u22121\u03c3<X<\u03bc+1\u03c3) = 68.2% (constant)','Inverse: x such that P(X<x)=p (variable)','Unknown \u03bc or \u03c3 from two conditions (variable)'],explain:'Students shade regions under the normal curve and read off probabilities. The z-score transforms any normal to the standard N(0,1). The inverse normal tool works backwards from a probability to find the threshold value \u2014 exactly as in IB exam questions finding unknown \u03bc or \u03c3. Maps to DP AA Topic 4.9\u20134.10.',real:'IQ score distribution: N(100,15\u00b2), Heights of adult males: N(175,7\u00b2), Exam mark standardisation, Manufacturing tolerances: what % outside 3\u03c3 limits?'},

//     {label:'Continuous random variables \u2014 probability density functions (HL)',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Function',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4 AHL: Statistics \u2014 AHL 4.14',scene:'A piecewise function drawn on screen as a pdf curve. The area under it shaded in coral \u2014 always integrating to 1. Students find P(a<X<b) by adjusting interval sliders and watching the shaded area compute. The mean E(X) and variance Var(X) calculated using integration shown step by step.',sliders:['pdf shape (0=Uniform f(x)=1/3 on [0,3] \u2192 4=Triangular \u2014 piecewise linear)','Query interval a to b (0=a=0 b=1 \u2192 4=a=1 b=3)','Show E(X) = \u222bxf(x)dx (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Integral computed live)','Show Var(X) = E(X\u00b2)\u2212[E(X)]\u00b2 (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Full calculation shown)'],resources:['P(a<X<b) = \u222b_a^b f(x)dx (variable)','Total area \u222b f(x)dx = 1 (always)','E(X) = \u222bxf(x)dx (variable)','E(X\u00b2) (variable)','Var(X) = E(X\u00b2) \u2212 [E(X)]\u00b2 (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that for a continuous random variable, probability equals area \u2014 there is no P(X=a) for a specific value. The pdf must integrate to 1 over its domain. E(X) is found by integrating xf(x) \u2014 the weighted average of all values. Var(X) uses the E(X\u00b2)\u2212[E(X)]\u00b2 shortcut. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 4.14.',real:'Lifetime of a light bulb as exponential pdf, Uniform distribution in random number generation, Bus waiting time as uniform random variable, Rainfall amount as continuous distribution'},

//     {label:'Derivative rules \u2014 power, chain, product and quotient',concept:'Function',related:'Change, Patterns, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 5: Calculus \u2014 5.3\u20135.6',scene:'A function f(x) shown in deep indigo with f\u2032(x) in coral below. A rule-switcher panel highlights which differentiation rule applies to the current function. Composite functions animate the chain rule: inner and outer derivatives appear and multiply. Product rule shows uv\u2032+vu\u2032 with each part highlighted.',sliders:['Function complexity (0=Simple x^n \u2014 power rule \u2192 4=Composite trig e^(sin x) \u2014 chain)','Derivative at specific x (0=x=\u22122 \u2192 4=x=2 \u2014 gradient value)','Show derivative graph below (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 f\u2032(x) plotted)','Rule to apply (0=Power rule \u2192 4=Quotient rule (vu\u2032\u2212uv\u2032)/v\u00b2)'],resources:['f\u2032(x) expression (variable)','Gradient at x = f\u2032(x) (variable)','Chain rule: d/dx[f(g(x))] = f\u2032(g(x))\u00b7g\u2032(x) (variable)','Product rule: (uv)\u2032 = uv\u2032+vu\u2032 (variable)','Quotient rule result (variable)'],explain:'Students apply all four differentiation rules and watch the correct rule highlight automatically based on function structure. The chain rule is demonstrated by identifying inner and outer functions. The product and quotient rules are colour-coded to distinguish the u and v terms. All rules connect back to the tangent line interpretation. Maps to DP AA Topic 5.3\u20135.6.',real:'Rate of change of volume of inflating balloon, Velocity from position function using chain rule, Revenue function differentiated for marginal revenue, Acceleration from composite velocity function'},

//     {label:'Applications of calculus \u2014 turning points, optimisation and related rates',concept:'Function',related:'Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5: Calculus \u2014 5.8\u20135.10',scene:'A factory profit function P(x) plotted. Moving the slider increases production x. The tangent line tracks across the curve. f\u2032(x)=0 critical points shown with a flag. The second derivative test panel classifies each as max, min, or inflection. An optimisation problem (box from sheet) shows the real constraint.',sliders:['Function type (0=Cubic with one local max/min \u2192 4=Quartic with two \u2014 complex)','Show f\u2032(x) graph (0=Off \u2192 4=On)','Show f\u2033(x) sign at critical point (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 max vs min classification)','Related rates scenario (0=Expanding oil spill \u2192 4=Ladder sliding down wall)'],resources:['f\u2032(x) = 0 at x = (variable)','f\u2033(x) sign at critical point (variable)','Local max or min classification (variable)','Optimisation: constraint applied (variable)','Rate of change in related rates problem (variable)'],explain:'Students find turning points by solving f\u2032(x)=0 graphically first, then confirm algebraically. The second derivative test classifies the critical point without plotting. Optimisation shows how calculus finds the exact maximum under real constraints. Related rates demonstrates implicit differentiation in a dynamic context. Maps to DP AA Topic 5.8\u20135.10.',real:'Maximising profit given revenue and cost functions, Minimising packaging material for fixed volume, Fastest time to run to a boat, Ladder sliding: rate at which top descends as base slides out'},

//     {label:'Integration \u2014 Riemann sums, definite integral and area between curves',concept:'Function',related:'Change, Mathematical modelling, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5: Calculus \u2014 5.11\u20135.14',scene:'A coloured region fills under a curve. Left/right/midpoint Riemann rectangles appear and improve as n increases. The exact integral value glows in gold. A second function appears and the region between the two curves shades in coral. Signed area shown below the x-axis in blue. Anti-derivative family of curves shown with a C-slider.',sliders:['Number of rectangles n (0=n=2 \u2014 rough \u2192 4=n=200 \u2014 near-exact)','Method (0=Left endpoints \u2192 4=Midpoint \u2014 most accurate for same n)','Second function (0=Off \u2014 area under one curve \u2192 4=On \u2014 area between two)','C constant in anti-derivative (0=C=\u22123 \u2192 4=C=+3 \u2014 vertical shift)'],resources:['Riemann approximation (variable)','Exact definite integral (variable)','Error percentage (variable)','Area between curves (variable)','Anti-derivative family F(x)+C (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that integration is the limit of summing infinitely thin rectangles. Increasing n from 4 to 200 makes convergence tangible. The area between two curves requires subtracting the lower from the upper integral. The C constant shows that every derivative has infinitely many anti-derivatives. Maps to DP AA Topic 5.11\u20135.14.',real:'Distance from velocity-time graph, Consumer surplus between supply and demand curves, Probability from a density function, Net displacement of an oscillating particle'},

//     {label:'Kinematics \u2014 displacement, velocity, acceleration and particle motion',concept:'Change',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5: Calculus \u2014 5.15',scene:'A particle moves along a number line. Three linked graphs show s(t), v(t)=s\u2032(t), a(t)=v\u2032(t) simultaneously. Shading shows when v>0 (moving right) and v<0 (moving left). Total distance (using |v|) contrasted with displacement. Students predict turning points (v=0) before they appear on the graph.',sliders:['Position function s(t) type (0=Linear \u2014 constant velocity \u2192 4=Cubic \u2014 two direction changes)','Time query t (0=t=0 \u2192 4=t=6 seconds)','Show total distance vs displacement (0=Displacement only \u2192 4=Total distance: \u222b|v|dt)','Initial conditions s(0) and v(0) (0=Both zero \u2192 4=s(0)=5 v(0)=\u22123)'],resources:['Position s(t) at time t (variable)','Velocity v(t) = s\u2032(t) (variable)','Acceleration a(t) = v\u2032(t) (variable)','Total distance \u222b|v|dt (variable)','Displacement s(T)\u2212s(0) (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that displacement and total distance diverge whenever the particle reverses direction (v=0 and changes sign). The three linked graphs make differentiation and integration visible as two directions of the same relationship. Integrating |v| vs v captures the path length correctly. Maps to DP AA Topic 5.15.',real:'Car journey: speedometer gives v, odometer gives \u222b|v|, Oscillating spring position, Ball thrown vertically: height, velocity, acceleration three linked graphs, Satellite orbit kinematics'},

//     {label:'Integration techniques \u2014 substitution and integration by parts (HL)',concept:'Function',related:'Change, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5 AHL: Calculus \u2014 AHL 5.15\u20135.16',scene:'A function \u222b f(g(x))g\u2032(x)dx shown. The substitution u=g(x) is applied step by step with du and dx animated as colour-coded blocks. The integral transforms into \u222b f(u)du. Integration by parts shows \u222buv\u2032dx = uv \u2212 \u222bv u\u2032dx with the LIATE rule for choosing u.',sliders:['Function type (0=Simple: \u222b2x(x\u00b2+1)^5 dx \u2192 4=Needs parts: \u222bx e^x dx)','Substitution variable shown (0=u hidden \u2192 4=u=g(x) animated)','Parts: choose u as (0=u=x (polynomial) \u2014 LIATE \u2192 4=u=ln(x) \u2014 logarithm first)','Check by differentiating result (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 d/dx of answer = integrand)'],resources:['Substitution u = g(x) (variable)','du/dx = g\u2032(x) expressed (variable)','Result after substitution (variable)','Integration by parts result uv\u2212\u222bv u\u2032dx (variable)','Verification by differentiation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that substitution is the chain rule run backwards: identify the inner function g(x) as u, then g\u2032(x)dx becomes du. Integration by parts is the product rule reversed: \u222buv\u2032 = uv \u2212 \u222bv u\u2032. The LIATE rule helps choose u. Both techniques require pattern recognition \u2014 the skill that makes HL calculus elegant. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 5.15\u20135.16.',real:'\u222bx e^x dx: work done by variable force, Volume of revolution integrals, \u222bln(x)dx by parts with u=ln(x) v\u2032=1, Gamma function \u222b x^n e^(-x) dx pattern'},

//     {label:'Volume of revolution \u2014 rotating about x and y axes (HL)',concept:'Function',related:'Change, Mathematical modelling, Spatial reasoning',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5 AHL: Calculus \u2014 AHL 5.17',scene:'A curve f(x) shown between two bounds. A rotation axis (x or y) selected. The 3D solid of revolution forms in real time as the curve sweeps. Cross-section discs or washers appear and stack. The volume formula V = \u03c0\u222b[f(x)]\u00b2dx computed live. A second curve creates the washer method.',sliders:['Function f(x) (0=f(x)=\u221ax \u2014 paraboloid \u2192 4=f(x)=sin(x) \u2014 wave solid)','Rotation axis (0=About x-axis \u2192 4=About y-axis \u2014 different integral)','Bounds a and b (0=Narrow slice \u2192 4=Full region)','Washer method (0=Single curve disc \u2192 4=Region between two curves)'],resources:['Volume V = \u03c0\u222b[f(x)]\u00b2dx (variable)','Cross-section radius at x (variable)','Disc thickness dx (infinitesimal)','Washer volume \u03c0\u222b([f(x)]\u00b2\u2212[g(x)]\u00b2)dx (variable)','3D solid shape name (variable)'],explain:'Students watch a curve sweep around an axis generating a 3D solid whose volume is calculated by stacking infinitely thin discs. Rotating y=\u221ax gives a paraboloid. Rotating y=sin(x) gives a wave-shaped solid. The washer method subtracts the inner hollow. The visual connection between 2D and 3D is the deepest insight. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 5.17.',real:'Volume of a wine barrel (historically motivating calculus), Engineering: volume of a turned component on a lathe, Archimedes\' sphere volume as rotation of semicircle, CT scan cross-sectional reconstruction'},

//     {label:'Differential equations \u2014 Euler\'s method, slope fields and logistic growth (HL)',concept:'Change',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5 AHL: Calculus \u2014 AHL 5.18\u20135.19',scene:'A slope field fills the screen \u2014 tiny gradient arrows pointing in the direction of dy/dx at every grid point. A solution curve emerges from a draggable initial condition. Euler\'s method draws step-by-step approximation in red. The exact analytical solution in indigo. Step size slider controls accuracy.',sliders:['Step size h (0=h=1 \u2014 large steps \u2014 high error \u2192 4=h=0.1 \u2014 small steps \u2014 accurate)','Initial condition y0 (0=y0=0 \u2192 4=y0=100)','DE type (0=Exponential dy/dx=ky \u2192 4=Logistic dP/dt=rP(1\u2212P/K))','Carrying capacity K for logistic (0=K=50 \u2192 4=K=1000)'],resources:['Euler approximation at t (variable)','Exact solution value (variable)','Accumulated error (variable)','Inflection point of logistic at K/2 (variable)','Carrying capacity reached % (variable)'],explain:'Students watch Euler\'s method walk along the slope field arrows, accumulating error. Reducing step size makes the approximation converge. The logistic model shows S-shaped population growth that always decelerates at carrying capacity. The inflection point at K/2 is the fastest-growing moment. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 5.18\u20135.19.',real:'COVID-19 logistic growth modelling, Bacteria culture in a petri dish, Fish population management with harvesting, Medication plasma concentration decaying'},

//     {label:'Maclaurin series \u2014 polynomial approximation of transcendental functions (HL)',concept:'Patterns',related:'Function, Change, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5 AHL: Maclaurin series \u2014 AHL 5.17',scene:'A target function (sin x, cos x, e^x, or ln(1+x)) shown in deep indigo. A polynomial approximation builds term by term in coral. Each new term wraps more tightly around the target. The remainder shown as a shrinking glowing gap. A term-by-term panel shows the formula f(0)+f\u2032(0)x+f\u2033(0)x\u00b2/2!+...',sliders:['Target function (0=e^x \u2014 all terms positive \u2192 4=tan(x) \u2014 converges poorly)','Number of terms n (0=n=1 \u2014 linear only \u2192 4=n=7 \u2014 very accurate near 0)','Evaluation point x (0=x=0 \u2014 trivially exact \u2192 4=x=2 \u2014 far from centre)','Show n-th derivative at x=0 (0=Hidden \u2192 4=f^(n)(0) values displayed)'],resources:['Polynomial P_n(x) (variable)','Exact function value f(x) (variable)','Remainder |f(x)\u2212P_n(x)| (variable)','Radius of convergence (variable)','Series in sigma notation (variable)'],explain:'Students watch a polynomial slowly become sin(x) as more terms are added. The 7-term Maclaurin series matches sine perfectly near zero but diverges far away \u2014 the radius of convergence concept becomes visual. All transcendental functions are secretly infinite polynomials. Maps to DP AA HL AHL 5.17.',real:'Calculator chip computing sin/cos/exp using Maclaurin series, Einstein\'s special relativity \u03b3 expanded for low speeds, Small-angle approximation sin(\u03b8)\u2248\u03b8 in pendulum physics, GPS time dilation correction using Taylor series'}
//   ]},
//   {icon:'📊',name:'Mathematics AI',sub:'28 simulations · Statistics · Finance · Graph Theory · DE · HL',topics:[
//     {label:'Arithmetic and geometric sequences \u2014 financial and real-world applications',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Number and Algebra \u2014 1.2\u20131.4',scene:'A split screen shows arithmetic growth as a staircase (constant step height) and geometric growth as a branching tree (constant multiplication). Real contexts switch between them: arithmetic = salary with fixed raise, geometric = investment with compound multiplier. Sigma notation expands for each.',sliders:['Growth type (0=Arithmetic \u2014 add d each time \u2192 4=Geometric \u2014 multiply by r each time)','Common difference d or ratio r (0=d=2 or r=0.8 decay \u2192 4=d=100 or r=3 rapid growth)','Number of terms n (0=n=5 \u2192 4=n=20)','Real context (0=Pure sequence \u2192 4=Financial context \u2014 salary or investment)'],resources:['n-th term (variable)','Partial sum S_n (variable)','Formula used (arithmetic or geometric)','Total accumulated after n periods (variable)','Difference between arithmetic and geometric growth (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that arithmetic sequences produce linear total growth (S_n quadratic in n) while geometric sequences produce exponential growth \u2014 the fundamental difference between simple and compound interest. Real financial contexts make each formula immediately applicable. Maps to DP AI Topic 1.2\u20131.4.',real:'Salary increments with fixed annual raise, Stadium seating rows with fixed increase, Compound interest investment doubling, Bacterial colony growth rate'},

//     {label:'Financial mathematics \u2014 compound interest, TVM and loan amortisation',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Financial mathematics \u2014 1.7 TVM',scene:'A personal finance dashboard. An animated mortgage balance bar depletes over 25 years. Each monthly payment shown split into interest and principal as a stacked bar chart. Early payments are almost entirely interest. A TVM calculator panel shows FV, PV, i%, n, PMT all linked.',sliders:['Annual nominal interest rate % (0=1% \u2014 near-zero \u2192 4=12% \u2014 high-rate loan)','Loan term years (0=5 years \u2014 high payments short term \u2192 4=30 years \u2014 long low payments)','Principal amount (0=$10,000 \u2192 4=$500,000 \u2014 mortgage scale)','Extra monthly overpayment (0=$0 \u2014 minimum \u2192 4=$500 \u2014 aggressive payoff)'],resources:['Monthly payment required (variable)','Total interest paid lifetime (variable)','Outstanding balance at year 10 (variable)','Years saved by overpayment (variable)','Effective annual interest rate (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the mortgage trap: a $300,000 loan at 5% over 30 years costs $280,000 in interest alone. Overpaying by $300/month cuts 8 years off the loan. The TVM panel links all five financial variables \u2014 change any one and the others update. Maps to DP AI Topic 1.7 TVM.',real:'UK average mortgage cost comparison, Student loan interest vs salary growth, Car finance vs outright purchase, Investment compound growth vs loan cost'},

//     {label:'Annuities and depreciation \u2014 future value, present value and book value',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1: Financial mathematics \u2014 1.7 Annuities and depreciation',scene:'Two side-by-side panels. Left: an annuity \u2014 regular monthly deposits growing as a bar chart with compound interest accumulating. Right: an asset (car) depreciating over time \u2014 book value shown as a declining curve. Straight-line vs reducing-balance depreciation compared. Tax implications shown.',sliders:['Regular payment amount PMT (0=$100/month \u2192 4=$2000/month)','Interest rate on annuity (0=2% \u2192 4=8%)','Number of periods n (0=10 periods \u2192 4=40 periods \u2014 retirement scale)','Depreciation rate % per year (0=5% \u2014 slow \u2192 4=30% \u2014 rapid \u2014 electronics)'],resources:['Future value of annuity FV (variable)','Present value of annuity PV (variable)','Asset book value at year n (variable)','Total deposited vs total value (variable)','Straight-line vs reducing-balance depreciation difference (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that a pension annuity of $500/month at 6% for 30 years accumulates to over $500,000 \u2014 three times what was deposited. Depreciation shows why buying a new car is expensive: 30% reducing-balance depreciation means most value is lost in the first two years. Maps to DP AI Topic 1.7.',real:'Retirement pension fund calculation, Company asset depreciation for tax purposes, Investment annuity comparison, Smartphone resale value depreciation'},

//     {label:'Matrix arithmetic \u2014 multiplication, determinant and inverse (HL)',concept:'Patterns',related:'Mathematical modelling, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1 AHL: Matrices \u2014 AHL 1.14',scene:'Two matrices A and B displayed as number grids. Matrix multiplication animates step by step: each entry of AB highlighted as the dot product of a row and column. The determinant det(A) calculated with the expansion rule shown geometrically as a parallelogram area in 2D. The inverse A\u207b\u00b9 computed.',sliders:['Matrix size (0=2\xd72 \u2014 simple \u2192 4=3\xd73 \u2014 complex determinant)','Matrix entries (0=Simple integers \u2192 4=Decimals \u2014 realistic)','Operation (0=Addition/scalar multiplication \u2192 4=Matrix multiplication AB \u2260 BA demonstrated)','Show det(A) as parallelogram area (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 geometric meaning)'],resources:['Product AB (variable)','det(A) value (variable)','Inverse A\u207b\u00b9 (if det\u22600) (variable)','A\u207b\u00b9A = I verified (yes/no)','Is AB = BA? (usually no)'],explain:'Students discover that matrix multiplication is not commutative \u2014 AB \u2260 BA in general. The determinant measures the scaling factor of the transformation: det(A)=0 means the matrix squashes space flat (no inverse exists). A\u207b\u00b9 always reverses A: A\u207b\u00b9A = I. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 1.14.',real:'Google PageRank matrix power iteration, Cryptography using matrix multiplication, Simultaneous equations via Ax=b and x=A\u207b\u00b9b, Computer graphics transformation matrices'},

//     {label:'Matrix transformations \u2014 rotation, reflection, enlargement and composition (HL)',concept:'Patterns',related:'Mathematical modelling, Spatial reasoning',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 1 AHL: Matrix transformations \u2014 AHL 1.14',scene:'A polygon (letter F or arrow) drawn on a 2D grid. Transformation matrix sliders reshape it. Rotation matrix rotates it. Reflection matrix flips it. Enlargement matrix scales it. Chaining two transformations shows the composite. The unit square image shows column vectors visually. Determinant = scale factor of area.',sliders:['Transformation type (0=Rotation 45\u00b0 \u2192 4=Reflection in y=x then rotation 90\u00b0)','Rotation angle \u03b8 (0=0\u00b0 \u2192 4=360\u00b0 \u2014 full rotation)','Scale factor k for enlargement (0=k=0.5 \u2014 shrink \u2192 4=k=3 \u2014 enlarge)','Composite: T2 then T1 (0=Single transformation \u2192 4=Composite \u2014 order matters)'],resources:['Transformation matrix [cos\u03b8 -sin\u03b8; sin\u03b8 cos\u03b8] (variable)','Image coordinates (variable)','det(A) = area scale factor (variable)','Composite matrix T1T2 (variable)','Fixed points of transformation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that every geometric transformation in 2D corresponds to multiplying by a 2\xd72 matrix. Composing two transformations multiplies their matrices \u2014 and order matters. The determinant reveals how areas scale. Reflection followed by rotation \u2260 rotation followed by reflection. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 1.14.',real:'Computer graphics: game engine vertex transformation, Robotics: joint rotation matrices, Image processing: rotation and scaling, CGI animation: character skeleton transformation'},

//     {label:'Modelling with functions \u2014 fitting linear, quadratic and exponential models',concept:'Models',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.6 Modelling with functions',scene:'A scatter plot of real data appears. Students try fitting three models: linear y=mx+c, quadratic y=ax\u00b2+bx+c, and exponential y=ae^(bx). The R\u00b2 goodness-of-fit updates for each model. Residuals plotted below. The best-fit model declared. A prediction is made beyond the data range with a warning.',sliders:['Data set (0=Linear relationship \u2014 simple \u2192 4=Growth data \u2014 ambiguous model)','Model type (0=Linear \u2192 4=Power y=ax^n \u2014 guess n)','Show residuals (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 residual plot below)','Extrapolation distance (0=Safe interpolation \u2192 4=Far extrapolation \u2014 warning shown)'],resources:['R\u00b2 goodness of fit (variable)','Model equation with fitted parameters (variable)','Prediction at x query (variable)','Residual sum of squares (variable)','Best model by R\u00b2 (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that R\u00b2 alone does not guarantee a good model \u2014 a quadratic can fit noise perfectly but extrapolate badly. The residual plot reveals systematic patterns (curves, not random scatter) that expose a misfit model. Extrapolation warnings reflect real statistical practice. Maps to DP AI Topic 2.6.',real:'Population growth: linear vs exponential model comparison, Car fuel consumption vs speed: quadratic model, Mobile phone adoption: exponential then logistic, Temperature cooling: exponential decay model'},

//     {label:'Sinusoidal model fitting \u2014 tides, temperature and Ferris wheel',concept:'Models',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Function',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.6 Sinusoidal models',scene:'A tidal height chart shows 48 hours of data as dots. A sine curve y=a sin(bx+c)+d overlay adjusts with sliders to fit the data. The period marker shows 12.4 hours (lunar tidal period). A Ferris wheel companion panel shows height vs time sinusoidal alongside. A temperature year panel shows seasonal variation.',sliders:['Amplitude a (0=a=0.5 \u2014 small tidal range \u2192 4=a=6 \u2014 large tidal range)','Period controller b (0=b=0.5 \u2014 slow cycle \u2192 4=b=2 \u2014 short cycle)','Phase shift c (0=c=0 \u2014 starts at midline \u2192 4=c=\u03c0/2 \u2014 starts at peak)','Vertical shift d \u2014 mean height (0=d=1 \u2192 4=d=5)'],resources:['Period T = 2\u03c0/b (variable)','Amplitude a (variable)','Maximum height d+a (variable)','Minimum height d\u2212a (variable)','R\u00b2 fit to tidal data (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that most periodic natural phenomena follow a sinusoidal model. Finding the four parameters from data: amplitude from max-min range, period from peak-to-peak, phase from first peak timing, and vertical shift from the midline. The Ferris wheel makes the geometry of the parameters physical. Maps to DP AI Topic 2.6.',real:'Tidal height prediction for navigation, Seasonal temperature variation modelling, Blood pressure oscillations over a heartbeat, Daylight hours over a year in any city'},

//     {label:'Logistic function \u2014 S-curve modelling and inflection point',concept:'Models',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 2: Functions \u2014 2.6 Modelling with functions',scene:'A glowing S-shaped logistic curve fills the screen. Animated dots populate as population grows. The inflection point glows gold at the steepest section. Parameters L (carrying capacity), k (growth rate), x_0 (midpoint) control the shape. A tangent line touches the inflection point. Real data overlay fits COVID cases.',sliders:['Carrying capacity L (0=L=100 \u2014 small \u2192 4=L=10000 \u2014 large)','Growth rate k (0=k=0.1 \u2014 slow S-curve \u2192 4=k=1.0 \u2014 rapid takeoff)','Midpoint x_0 (0=Early inflection \u2192 4=Late inflection)','Real data overlay (0=Mathematical only \u2192 4=COVID-19 data \u2014 fit logistic)'],resources:['Population at time t (variable)','Inflection point at x_0 (variable)','Maximum growth rate at inflection (variable)','Percentage of carrying capacity (variable)','Residuals from data fit (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the logistic function models any growth that accelerates then decelerates \u2014 from populations to technology adoption. The inflection point (fastest growth) always occurs at exactly L/2. Fitting real epidemic data shows the power of mathematical modelling in context. Maps to DP AI Topic 2.6.',real:'COVID-19 case count logistic curve, Smartphone adoption S-curve 2007\u20132015, Population growth with resource limits, Rumour spread in social networks, New product market penetration'},

//     {label:'Trigonometric applications \u2014 sine rule, cosine rule, bearings and navigation',concept:'Spatial',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3: Geometry \u2014 3.2\u20133.3',scene:'A triangle with three vertices on an animated map. Students input two sides and an angle (or three sides) and the triangle solver finds all unknowns. The ambiguous case of the sine rule shown: two triangles appear when two solutions exist. A bearing navigation problem overlays on a compass rose.',sliders:['Known quantities type (0=Two sides one angle SAS \u2192 4=Three sides SSS \u2014 cosine rule)','Side lengths a, b (0=a=5 b=7 \u2192 4=a=12 b=8)','Included angle or query angle (0=C=30\u00b0 \u2192 4=C=120\u00b0 \u2014 obtuse)','Show ambiguous case SSA (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 two possible triangles shown)'],resources:['Unknown side using cosine rule c\u00b2=a\u00b2+b\u00b2\u22122ab cosC (variable)','Unknown angle using sine rule sinA/a = sinB/b (variable)','Area = \u00bdab sinC (variable)','Ambiguous case: two solutions? (yes/no)','Bearing to destination (variable)'],explain:'Students solve triangles and discover the ambiguous SSA case where two different triangles satisfy the given conditions. The sine rule is applied to the ambiguous case by testing both supplementary angle options. Bearings show how the formulas apply to real navigation. Maps to DP AI Topic 3.2\u20133.3.',real:'Ship navigation: bearing to find position, Surveying land area using triangle formulae, Architecture: roof truss angle calculation, Aviation: cross-wind triangle vector addition'},

//     {label:'3D geometry \u2014 distance, midpoint, volume and surface area of composite solids',concept:'Spatial',related:'Mathematical modelling, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 \u2014 Topic 3: Geometry \u2014 3.1',scene:'A 3D coordinate system with interactive points. Distance between two points computed and visualised as a 3D diagonal. A composite solid (cylinder on top of cone, sphere sliced) shown and dissected. Each component\u2019s volume and surface area calculated, then combined. The full surface area traces each face.',sliders:['Solid type (0=Pure sphere \u2192 4=Hemisphere+cylinder composite \u2014 ice cream cone)','Dimensions r, h (0=r=2 h=3 \u2192 4=r=7 h=15)','3D distance query: two points (0=Simple (1,2,3) to (4,5,6) \u2192 4=General coordinates)','Show working (0=Just answer \u2192 4=Full formula step by step)'],resources:['Volume of composite solid (variable)','Surface area of composite solid (variable)','3D distance between two points (variable)','Midpoint in 3D (variable)','Angle in 3D triangle (variable)'],explain:'Students build composite solids by combining basic shapes and discover that surface area requires careful identification of shared surfaces (cylinder top is NOT part of the surface area when the cone sits on it). 3D distance generalises Pythagoras into three dimensions naturally. Maps to DP AI Topic 3.1.',real:'Designing a storage silo (cylinder+cone): capacity and material cost, Aquarium volume for fish tank design, Satellite antenna dish surface area for signal gain, Capsule drug dosage from hemisphere+cylinder shape'},

//     {label:'Voronoi diagrams \u2014 optimal facility placement and nearest neighbour',concept:'Spatial',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 3: Geometry \u2014 3.6 Voronoi diagrams',scene:'A city map fills the screen. Emergency response stations glow as points. Voronoi cells form around them, each cell the region closest to that station. Adding or dragging a station redraws the diagram instantly. Perpendicular bisectors shown as construction lines. Largest empty circle reveals optimal new station location.',sliders:['Number of stations (0=2 \u2014 one boundary \u2192 4=8 \u2014 complex tessellation)','Placement quality (0=All clustered \u2014 poor coverage \u2192 4=Optimally spread)','Query point (0=Near station \u2014 short response \u2192 4=Far corner \u2014 long response)','Show perpendicular bisector construction (0=Hidden \u2192 4=All shown \u2014 see how cells form)'],resources:['Coverage area per station km\u00b2 (variable)','Maximum response distance km (variable)','Nearest station to query point (variable)','Largest Voronoi cell area (variable)','Optimal new station location (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that Voronoi cells are constructed from perpendicular bisectors and solve the nearest-neighbour problem geometrically. The largest empty circle identifies the optimal location for a new facility. Dragging stations shows how cells reshape instantly. Maps to DP AI Topic 3.6.',real:'Ambulance station placement for fastest response, Supermarket catchment area, Telecommunications tower coverage zones, John Snow 1854 cholera pump Voronoi analysis'},

//     {label:'Graph theory \u2014 minimum spanning tree, Chinese Postman and Travelling Salesman (HL)',concept:'Spatial',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 3 AHL: Graph theory \u2014 AHL 3.4\u20133.5',scene:'An animated town network with roads as weighted edges. Kruskal\'s algorithm runs step by step \u2014 each edge lights green when added to the MST. Chinese Postman highlights repeated edges in red. Travelling Salesman nearest-neighbour route drawn. A lower bound via deleted vertex shown. Upper vs lower bound gap displayed.',sliders:['Number of vertices (0=4 \u2014 simple \u2192 4=10 \u2014 complex)','Algorithm shown (0=Kruskal MST \u2192 4=TSP nearest neighbour upper bound)','Edge weights (0=All equal \u2014 trivial \u2192 4=Highly varied \u2014 interesting problem)','Odd degree vertices highlighted (0=Hidden \u2192 4=Shown \u2014 Chinese Postman repeated edges)'],resources:['MST total weight (variable)','Edges in MST (always n\u22121) (variable)','Chinese Postman total route (variable)','TSP upper bound (nearest neighbour) (variable)','TSP lower bound (deleted vertex) (variable)'],explain:'Students discover Kruskal\'s greedy MST: add cheapest edge that doesn\'t create a cycle. The Chinese Postman requires pairing odd-degree vertices optimally. The Travelling Salesman upper bound (nearest neighbour) and lower bound (deleted vertex) bracket the optimal solution. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 3.4\u20133.5.',real:'Internet cable network minimum cost connection, Royal Mail postal round optimisation, Delivery van route planning, Power grid minimum infrastructure'},

//     {label:'Eulerian trails and graph properties \u2014 degrees, adjacency matrices and PageRank (HL)',concept:'Spatial',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 3 AHL: Graph theory \u2014 AHL 3.4',scene:'A graph with labelled vertices and edges drawn interactively. The degree sequence shown. Eulerian circuit conditions checked (all vertices even degree). An adjacency matrix fills in automatically. Matrix power A^k computed and its entries show number of walks of length k. A PageRank panel runs the iterated matrix multiplication.',sliders:['Graph type (0=Simple path \u2192 4=Complete graph K5)','Euler circuit/trail possible? (0=All even degree \u2014 circuit exists \u2192 4=Two odd degree \u2014 trail only)','Matrix power k for walks (0=k=1 \u2014 direct connections \u2192 4=k=4 \u2014 length-4 walks)','PageRank iterations (0=1 \u2014 initial \u2192 4=20 \u2014 converged)'],resources:['Degree sequence (variable)','Eulerian circuit exists? (yes/no)','Adjacency matrix A (variable)','A^k entry [i,j] = walks of length k (variable)','PageRank vector after n iterations (variable)'],explain:'Students discover Euler\'s theorem: an Eulerian circuit exists if and only if every vertex has even degree. The adjacency matrix encodes the graph in numbers: A^2[i,j] counts the number of 2-step paths from i to j. PageRank iterates A^n until the distribution stabilises. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 3.4.',real:'K\u00f6nigsberg bridge problem \u2014 Euler\'s original problem, Google PageRank web link graph, Social network friend-of-friend connections, Circuit board routing Eulerian path'},

//     {label:'Descriptive statistics \u2014 frequency tables, box plots and measures of spread',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.1\u20134.3',scene:'Raw data points animate into a frequency table. A histogram bars up. A cumulative frequency ogive curves. A box-and-whisker plot forms below showing Q1, median, Q3, and whiskers. Outlier detection shows IQR\xd71.5 fence. Switching datasets shows how skewed vs symmetric distributions look.',sliders:['Dataset (0=Symmetric \u2014 normal-looking \u2192 4=Skewed right \u2014 income data)','Class width for grouped data (0=Narrow \u2014 many bars \u2192 4=Wide \u2014 few bars \u2014 information lost)','Show outlier fence IQR\xd71.5 (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 outliers flagged)','Add or remove a data point (0=Remove outlier \u2192 4=Add extreme outlier \u2014 watch effect on mean)'],resources:['Mean (variable)','Median (variable)','Standard deviation \u03c3 (variable)','IQR = Q3\u2212Q1 (variable)','Outlier count (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the mean is sensitive to outliers but the median is not. Adding a single extreme value pulls the mean toward it while the median barely moves. The box plot compresses all five-number summary statistics into one visual. Skew shown as asymmetry in the box position. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.1\u20134.3.',real:'Income distribution: mean vs median wage debate, Exam score analysis before and after removing outliers, House price distribution: why median is reported, Sports performance statistics: mean vs median'},

//     {label:'Linear regression \u2014 LSRL, Pearson correlation and prediction',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.4 Pearson and LSRL',scene:'A live scatter plot with draggable data points. The LSRL (least squares regression line) adjusts instantly as points move. Residual lines glow red (positive) or blue (negative). The sum of squared residuals shown as animated squares. R\u00b2 counter updates live. A prediction panel and a residual plot below.',sliders:['Underlying correlation strength (0=No correlation \u2014 scattered \u2192 4=Perfect positive)','Number of data points n (0=n=5 \u2014 unreliable \u2192 4=n=50 \u2014 stable)','Outlier added (0=No outlier \u2192 4=Extreme outlier \u2014 LSRL pivots dramatically)','Extrapolation distance (0=Interpolation \u2014 safe \u2192 4=Far extrapolation \u2014 dangerous)'],resources:['Pearson r (variable)','R\u00b2 goodness of fit (variable)','LSRL equation y = mx + c (variable)','Prediction at x query (variable)','Residual sum of squares (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that outliers disproportionately pivot the LSRL. Dragging one point shows R\u00b2 drop dramatically. The residual plot reveals whether linear is appropriate: random scatter = linear is good; curved pattern = non-linear model needed. The mean point (\u0304x, \u0233) always lies on the LSRL. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.4.',real:'Height vs shoe size, GDP per capita vs life expectancy, House price vs floor area, Sports training hours vs performance rating'},

//     {label:'Spearman rank correlation \u2014 non-parametric association for ordinal data',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.4 Spearman\'s rank',scene:'Two judges score 10 artworks. Their scores shown as columns. Each score converts to a rank. Rank differences d calculated and shown. The formula r_s = 1\u22126\u03a3d\u00b2/n(n\u00b2\u22121) computed step by step. A scatter plot of ranks compared to a scatter plot of raw scores. Dragging one score shows r_s update.',sliders:['Judge agreement level (0=Disagree \u2014 r_s near \u22121 \u2192 4=Perfect agreement r_s=+1)','Sample size n (0=n=5 \u2014 few items \u2192 4=n=15 \u2014 more reliable)','Tied ranks presence (0=No ties \u2014 clean \u2192 4=Many ties \u2014 correction needed)','Outlier effect (0=No outlier \u2192 4=Extreme outlier \u2014 Pearson drops, Spearman stable)'],resources:['Spearman r_s value (variable)','Rank differences d table (variable)','Critical value for significance (variable)','Significant association? (yes/no)','Pearson r for comparison (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that Spearman\'s rank is more robust than Pearson\'s when data is ordinal or has outliers. A single extreme value can destroy Pearson r but barely affects r_s. The formula is computed manually \u2014 exactly as required in DP AI exams. Tied ranks require the correction factor. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.4.',real:'Film critics ranking movies: do critics agree?, Wine expert rank agreement, School rank vs employment rank correlation, Employee performance: manager ranking agreement'},

//     {label:'Non-linear regression and model selection \u2014 R\u00b2 comparison (HL)',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4 AHL: Statistics \u2014 AHL 4.12 Non-linear regression',scene:'A scatter plot of real data appears. Five model cards: linear, quadratic, exponential, power (y=ax^n), sinusoidal. Each model curve overlays in a different colour. Their R\u00b2 values shown as a ranked list. Residual plots appear below each. The best model declared with a reason. Overfitting demonstrated with degree-10 polynomial.',sliders:['Dataset scenario (0=Linear relationship \u2192 4=Periodic data \u2014 needs sinusoidal)','Model selected for overlay (0=Linear \u2192 4=Power y=ax^n \u2014 guess exponent)','Show residual plot (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 random pattern means good fit)','Overfitting demonstration (0=Degree 2 polynomial \u2192 4=Degree 10 \u2014 fits all points but wrong)'],resources:['R\u00b2 for each model (variable)','Best model by adjusted R\u00b2 (variable)','Residual pattern: random or curved? (variable)','Prediction accuracy outside data (variable)','Model equation with fitted parameters (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that R\u00b2 alone can mislead: a degree-10 polynomial fits 10 data points perfectly (R\u00b2=1) but is useless for prediction. The residual plot exposes systematic misfit even when R\u00b2 is high. The appropriate model is chosen by understanding the real-world mechanism, not just fitting numbers. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 4.12.',real:'Choosing between exponential and power model for viral spread, Pollution level vs distance: power or exponential?, Temperature cooling curve: exponential decay model selection, Sinusoidal model for tidal data vs polynomial'},

//     {label:'Chi-squared test \u2014 goodness of fit and test for independence',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.11 Chi-squared test',scene:'Sixty animated dice roll simultaneously. Observed frequency bars glow in coral. Expected frequency bars in indigo. The chi-squared statistic \u03c7\u00b2 = \u03a3(O\u2212E)\u00b2/E calculates live. A chi-squared distribution curve shows the critical value. A contingency table panel switches to the independence test: hair colour vs eye colour.',sliders:['Number of rolls (0=30 \u2014 high variation \u2192 4=1000 \u2014 stable frequencies)','Dice bias level (0=Fair \u2014 H0 true \u2192 4=Heavily loaded \u2014 H0 false)','Significance level \u03b1 (0=\u03b1=0.01 \u2014 conservative \u2192 4=\u03b1=0.10 \u2014 liberal)','Test type (0=Goodness of fit: one variable \u2192 4=Independence: 2\xd73 contingency table)'],resources:['\u03c7\u00b2 statistic (variable)','Degrees of freedom (variable)','p-value (variable)','Critical \u03c7\u00b2 value (variable)','Reject H0 of fairness/independence? (yes/no)'],explain:'Students roll a biased die and discover whether the chi-squared test detects the bias. Key insight: with few rolls, bias hides within sampling variation. With 1000 rolls, even small bias is detected. The independence test generalises to any categorical cross-tabulation. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.11.',real:'Gregor Mendel pea plant genetic ratios, Consumer preference survey independence, Quality control defect rate, Political polling demographic cross-tabulation'},

//     {label:'Hypothesis testing framework \u2014 t-test, p-value and Type I/II errors',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.11\u20134.12',scene:'A hypothesis testing dashboard. Two sample datasets appear as dot plots. A t-test compares their means. The null distribution shown as a bell curve with the test statistic marked. The p-value shaded in red. A Type I error zone (false rejection) and Type II error zone (false acceptance) shown. Verdict: reject or fail to reject H0.',sliders:['True difference between means (0=No difference \u2014 H0 true \u2192 4=Large difference \u2014 H0 false)','Sample size n per group (0=n=5 \u2014 low power \u2192 4=n=100 \u2014 high power)','Significance level \u03b1 (0=0.01 \u2014 conservative \u2192 4=0.10 \u2014 liberal)','One-tailed vs two-tailed test (0=Two-tailed \u2192 4=One-tailed \u2014 directional hypothesis)'],resources:['t-statistic (variable)','p-value (variable)','Reject H0? (yes/no)','Type I error probability = \u03b1 (variable)','Type II error \u03b2 (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that a p-value is the probability of the observed result IF H0 is true \u2014 not the probability that H0 is true. Increasing sample size reduces both Type I and Type II errors simultaneously. The two-tailed test is more conservative than one-tailed. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.11\u20134.12.',real:'Clinical drug trial: does the new drug improve outcomes?, A/B test for website conversion rate, Does gender affect salary? (two-sample t-test), Factory: has machine recalibration improved accuracy?'},

//     {label:'Normal distribution in manufacturing \u2014 tolerances and Six Sigma quality control',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.9 Normal distribution',scene:'A production line. Bottles filled with target volume. Normal distribution of fill volumes shown above with tolerance limits as red lines. Bottles outside limits glow red (rejected). The proportion within tolerance calculated. Six Sigma bands (\u00b11\u03c3, \u00b12\u03c3, \u00b13\u03c3) labelled. A control chart tracks the process mean over 50 batches.',sliders:['Process mean \u03bc mL (0=\u03bc=498 \u2014 underfilling \u2192 4=\u03bc=502 \u2014 overfilling)','Process standard deviation \u03c3 (0=\u03c3=0.5 \u2014 tight \u2192 4=\u03c3=3 \u2014 wide variation)','Lower tolerance limit (0=495 mL \u2014 permissive \u2192 4=499 mL \u2014 strict)','Upper tolerance limit (0=505 mL \u2014 permissive \u2192 4=501 mL \u2014 strict)'],resources:['Proportion within tolerance % (variable)','Daily rejects at 10000 units/day (variable)','P(X<lower limit) (variable)','Sigma level achieved (variable)','Process capability index C_pk (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that a process centred perfectly on target still produces rejects if variation is large. Reducing \u03c3 from 3 to 0.5 drops the reject rate from 5% to near zero. This is why Six Sigma manufacturing (no more than 3.4 defects per million) revolutionised industry. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.9.',real:'Coca-Cola bottle filling tolerances, Microchip gate width variation in semiconductor manufacturing, Medical dosage pill weight control, Car engine piston diameter \u00b10.01mm tolerance'},

//     {label:'Binomial and Poisson distributions \u2014 P(X=k), cumulative and context',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Statistics \u2014 4.7\u20134.8',scene:'A hospital emergency room scene. Patients arrive randomly. Left panel: binomial B(n,p) histogram for fixed n trials. Right panel: Poisson P(\u03bb) histogram for continuous arrivals. As n increases and p decreases with np=\u03bb constant, the binomial histogram morphs to match the Poisson. P(X=k) bars highlighted on request.',sliders:['Distribution type (0=Binomial B(n,p) \u2192 4=Poisson P(\u03bb) \u2014 large n small p limit)','Parameters n and p or \u03bb (0=B(10,0.3) \u2192 4=P(8) hospital scenario)','Query k for P(X=k) (0=k=0 \u2014 no arrivals \u2192 4=k=15 \u2014 busy)','Show P(X\u2264k) cumulative (0=Off \u2192 4=Shaded cumulative tail)'],resources:['P(X=k) exact formula (variable)','P(X\u2264k) cumulative (variable)','Mean E(X) (variable)','Variance Var(X) (variable)','Binomial approaches Poisson shown (yes/no)'],explain:'Students discover that the Poisson distribution is the limit of the binomial when n is large and p is small (rare events). The single parameter \u03bb = np is both the mean and variance \u2014 a unique property. The hospital context makes rare-but-real events tangible. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.7\u20134.8.',real:'Hospital A&E patient arrival rate per hour, Call centre incoming calls per minute, Radioactive decay counts per minute, Road accidents per km on a motorway'},

//     {label:'Expected value and decision trees \u2014 optimal choice under uncertainty',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4: Probability \u2014 4.7 Expected value',scene:'An animated decision tree. A company decides whether to launch a product. Rectangles are decision nodes, circles are chance nodes. Branches show outcomes with probabilities and payoffs. Expected monetary value (EMV) calculated at each chance node. The rollback method traces back to the optimal first decision.',sliders:['Probability of market success (0=p=0.1 \u2014 unlikely \u2192 4=p=0.9 \u2014 likely)','Payoff if success $K (0=$50K \u2014 small \u2192 4=$2M \u2014 large potential)','Cost to launch $K (0=$10K \u2014 cheap \u2192 4=$500K \u2014 expensive commitment)','Add second decision node (0=Single decision \u2192 4=Sequential decisions \u2014 pilot study first)'],resources:['EMV of launch decision (variable)','EMV of do not launch (variable)','Optimal decision (variable)','Breakeven probability p* (variable)','Value of perfect information (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that rational decision-making maximises expected value. The breakeven probability shows exactly when launching is worthwhile. Sequential decisions (pilot study first) introduce the value of information: knowing the outcome would be worth the conditional probability cost. Maps to DP AI Topic 4.7.',real:'Insurance premium calculation and expected loss, Pharmaceutical go/no-go clinical trial decision, Casino expected value of roulette wheel, Startup investment expected return vs risk'},

//     {label:'Markov chains and transition matrices \u2014 steady state and long-run equilibrium (HL)',concept:'Patterns',related:'Mathematical modelling, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 1 AHL: Matrices \u2014 AHL 1.14 Transition matrices',scene:'Three animated brands of coffee. Each month customers switch or stay based on probability arrows. A state vector animates each month. After many months market shares stabilise \u2014 the steady state emerges. Matrix powers T^n shown converging. A steady-state equation \u03c0T=\u03c0 solved analytically in a panel.',sliders:['Brand loyalty probability (0=Low 50% \u2014 lots of switching \u2192 4=High 90% \u2014 sticky brand)','Initial market share (0=Equal thirds \u2192 4=One brand dominates 90/5/5)','Number of months simulated n (0=n=1 \u2192 4=n=20 \u2014 approaching steady state)','Show T^n matrix powers (0=Hidden \u2192 4=T^1 T^5 T^20 all shown converging)'],resources:['Market share after n months (variable)','Steady state \u03c0 prediction (variable)','Months to reach 99% of steady state (variable)','Dominant eigenvalue = 1 (always)','Second eigenvalue: controls convergence rate (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that no matter the initial market share, the Markov chain always converges to the same steady state determined entirely by the transition probabilities. Repeated matrix multiplication T^n drives all rows to the steady state vector. The second eigenvalue controls how fast convergence happens. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 1.14.',real:'Google PageRank as Markov chain over web links, Brand switching consumer loyalty, Weather Markov chain: sunny/cloudy/rainy, Genetic drift allele frequency models'},

//     {label:'Differentiation in context \u2014 gradient, tangent, optimisation and related rates',concept:'Change',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5: Calculus \u2014 5.1\u20135.5',scene:'A profit function P(x) plotted for a business. The gradient function P\u2032(x) shown below. A tangent line drags across the curve. At P\u2032(x)=0 a flag marks the maximum profit point. An optimisation problem panel shows the box-volume or can-surface-area problem with constraint. A real spreadsheet overlay fits a trend and differentiates it.',sliders:['Function context (0=Quadratic profit function \u2192 4=Cubic \u2014 two local extrema)','Show marginal cost/revenue (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 derivatives as economic quantities)','Optimisation problem type (0=Maximum area given perimeter \u2192 4=Minimum surface area for fixed volume)','Constraint value (0=Perimeter=20 \u2192 4=Volume=500 cm\u00b3)'],resources:['f\u2032(x) at current x (variable)','Critical points where f\u2032(x)=0 (variable)','Maximum or minimum value (variable)','Tangent line equation y=mx+c (variable)','Optimisation answer (variable)'],explain:'Students apply differentiation directly to real business and science contexts. The marginal concept (marginal cost = rate of change of cost) makes derivatives immediately relevant to economics students. The optimisation problem shows calculus as a problem-solving tool for real engineering constraints. Maps to DP AI Topic 5.1\u20135.5.',real:'Maximising profit given revenue and cost functions, Minimising tin can surface area for fixed volume, Fastest path to a point: run and swim, Optimal dimensions of a cardboard box'},

//     {label:'Trapezoidal rule and integration in context \u2014 numerical area estimation',concept:'Change',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5: Calculus \u2014 5.8 Trapezoidal rule',scene:'A velocity-time graph of a car journey plotted as discrete data points. Trapezoids fill between consecutive points and the x-axis. The area (= distance) accumulates as a running total. Increasing the number of data points improves accuracy. An exact integral overlay shows the error. Real running data from a GPS tracker used.',sliders:['Number of trapezoids n (0=n=2 \u2014 rough \u2192 4=n=20 \u2014 accurate)','Function shape (0=Linear \u2014 trapezoid is exact \u2192 4=Curved \u2014 trapezoid overestimates)','Show exact integral for comparison (0=Off \u2192 4=On \u2014 error visible)','Real data mode (0=Mathematical function \u2192 4=GPS speed data \u2014 fit trapezoid)'],resources:['Trapezoidal area estimate (variable)','Exact definite integral (variable)','Error percentage (variable)','Does curve concave up or down affect over/underestimate? (variable)','Accumulated distance from velocity data (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the trapezoidal rule is exact for linear functions but overestimates for concave-up curves (because the top of each trapezoid lies above the curve). More trapezoids reduces error. Real GPS speed data makes the connection between velocity-time area and actual distance travelled completely concrete. Maps to DP AI Topic 5.8.',real:'GPS distance from speed measurements, Fuel consumption from flow rate data, Medical: drug concentration area under curve (AUC), Estimating work done from variable force data'},

//     {label:'Differential equations in context \u2014 Euler\'s method, Newton\'s cooling and logistic growth (HL)',concept:'Change',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5 AHL: Calculus \u2014 AHL 5.18',scene:'A slope field fills the screen. Three DE scenarios switchable: Newton\'s cooling (dT/dt = -k(T-T_env)), logistic growth (dP/dt = rP(1-P/K)), and exponential decay. Euler\'s method steps shown in red against exact solution in indigo. A real coffee cooling dataset overlays on Newton\'s law.',sliders:['DE scenario (0=Exponential decay \u2192 4=Logistic growth dP/dt=rP(1\u2212P/K))','Step size h (0=h=1 \u2014 large \u2014 high error \u2192 4=h=0.05 \u2014 small \u2014 accurate)','Initial condition (0=T(0)=90\u00b0C for cooling \u2192 4=P(0)=10 for logistic)','Environmental temperature T_env (0=0\u00b0C \u2014 fridge \u2192 4=25\u00b0C \u2014 room)'],resources:['Euler approximation at time t (variable)','Exact analytical solution (variable)','Accumulated error (variable)','Half-life or doubling time (variable)','Carrying capacity approached % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how Euler\'s method walks along slope arrows to approximate a continuous solution. Newton\'s cooling fits a real coffee temperature dataset making the model tangible and testable. The logistic DE reveals why population growth always slows. Step size and accuracy form the key trade-off. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 5.18.',real:'Coffee cooling experiment: match temperature data to Newton\'s law, COVID logistic model fitting to wave data, Drug plasma concentration exponential decay, Radioactive isotope decay to stable state'},

//     {label:'Coupled differential equations \u2014 predator-prey model and phase portraits (HL)',concept:'Change',related:'Function, Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 5 AHL: Calculus \u2014 AHL 5.18\u20135.19',scene:'An animated meadow. Rabbit and fox population icons change each time step. Two linked graphs show rabbit and fox populations over time \u2014 oscillating with a phase lag. A phase portrait (rabbits on x-axis, foxes on y-axis) draws an orbit. Students adjust parameters and see stable oscillations, extinction spirals, or explosion.',sliders:['Rabbit birth rate \u03b1 (0=\u03b1=0.2 \u2014 slow reproduction \u2192 4=\u03b1=1.5 \u2014 rapid)','Predation rate \u03b2 (0=\u03b2=0.01 \u2014 rare encounters \u2192 4=\u03b2=0.1 \u2014 frequent)','Fox death rate \u03b3 (0=\u03b3=0.1 \u2014 low mortality \u2192 4=\u03b3=0.8 \u2014 high)','Initial populations (0=10 rabbits 2 foxes \u2192 4=200 rabbits 20 foxes)'],resources:['Rabbit population at time t (variable)','Fox population at time t (variable)','Oscillation period years (variable)','Phase portrait orbit type (stable/spiral/extinction)','Equilibrium point (R*, F*) (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the Lotka-Volterra model produces perpetual oscillations: foxes grow when rabbits are plentiful, overhunt them, then starve and decline, allowing rabbits to recover. The phase portrait orbit shows the coupled system is conservative. Changing parameters creates spiral in to equilibrium or spiral out to extinction. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 5.18\u20135.19.',real:'Lynx and snowshoe hare 10-year cycle data, Fishery stock and harvesting pressure, COVID susceptible-infected-recovered SIR model, Chemical reaction oscillator (Belousov-Zhabotinsky)'},

//     {label:'Sampling methods and data collection \u2014 random, systematic, stratified and quota (HL)',concept:'Quantity',related:'Mathematical modelling, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 \u2014 Topic 4 AHL: Statistics \u2014 AHL 4.12 Sampling',scene:'A population of 500 animated dots categorised by colour (gender, age, department). Four sampling method panels operate simultaneously: simple random (computer selects), systematic (every kth person), stratified (proportional from each group), quota (fixed number from each group). Bias and representativeness compared.',sliders:['Population size N (0=50 \u2014 small \u2192 4=1000 \u2014 large)','Sample size n (0=n=10 \u2014 small % \u2192 4=n=200 \u2014 large %)','Stratification variable (0=Two groups 50/50 \u2192 4=Four groups unequal sizes)','Systematic interval k = N/n (0=Every 5th \u2192 4=Every 50th)'],resources:['Sample selected under each method (variable)','Sampling fraction n/N (variable)','Representativeness of sample (variable)','Potential bias in each method (variable)','Standard error of sample mean (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that simple random sampling gives each individual an equal chance of selection, while stratified sampling ensures every subgroup is represented proportionally. Systematic sampling introduces periodicity bias if the population has regular structure. Quota sampling (interviewer chooses) risks selection bias. Maps to DP AI HL AHL 4.12.',real:'Opinion polling before an election, Medical trial participant selection, Market research consumer sampling, School satisfaction survey by year group'}
//   ]},
//   {icon:'💻',name:'Computer Science',sub:'10 simulations · SL & HL',topics:[
//     {label:'Algorithm efficiency — Big O and searching/sorting',concept:'Efficiency',related:'Logic, Systems, Processing',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',scene:'An array of numbered boxes being sorted. Comparison flashes glow between boxes. Operations counter ticks rapidly or slowly depending on algorithm choice.',sliders:['Array size n (0=10 → 4=10,000)','Algorithm choice (0=Bubble sort O(n²) → 4=Merge sort O(n log n))','Data pre-sortedness (0=Already sorted → 4=Reverse sorted — worst case)','Memory constraint (0=Unlimited → 4=O(1) space only)','Problem type (0=Searching → 4=Sorting)'],resources:['Operations count (variable)','Time complexity class (variable)','Space used (variable)','Worst-case scenario (variable)','Algorithm correctness (100)'],explain:"Students see Big O notation made concrete — bubble sort on 10,000 items performs catastrophically worse than merge sort.",real:'Google search indexing, Spotify music matching, DNA sequence alignment, GPS shortest path computation, Fraud detection'},
//     {label:'Artificial intelligence & machine learning ethics',concept:'Ethics in computing',related:'Bias, Decision-making, Systems',lp:'Principled, Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',scene:'An AI decision engine — animated as a black box with data flowing in and decisions flowing out. Bias meter measures fairness across demographic groups.',sliders:['Training data diversity (0=Homogeneous → 4=Fully representative)','Model transparency (0=Black box → 4=Fully explainable)','Accuracy optimisation (0=Fairness priority → 4=Accuracy only)','Human oversight (0=None → 4=Human in the loop always)','Consent & privacy (0=None → 4=Informed consent always)'],resources:['Model accuracy % (80)','Fairness across groups (45)','Public trust (50)','Transparency score (30)','Harm prevention (40)'],explain:'Students discover the accuracy-fairness trade-off: optimising for accuracy often increases bias against minority groups. Connects to DP CS ethics and HL Paper 3.',real:'Amazon hiring algorithm gender bias, COMPAS recidivism racial bias, Facial recognition misidentification, ChatGPT bias and hallucination'}
//   ,
//     {label:'Object-oriented programming — classes, inheritance and polymorphism',concept:'Systems',related:'Logic, Abstraction, Models',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 2: Computer Organisation; Option D: OOP',scene:'An animated class hierarchy diagram. Parent and child classes shown as connected boxes. When a method is called, the inheritance chain lights up showing which class handles it. Polymorphism demonstrated as the same method call produces different outputs.',sliders:['Number of inheritance levels (0=No inheritance — flat → 4=Deep 4-level hierarchy)','Method override level (0=No overriding → 4=Full polymorphic override)','Encapsulation strictness (0=All public → 4=All private — getters/setters required)','Coupling between classes (0=Loosely coupled → 4=Tightly coupled — fragile)'],resources:['Code reusability score (variable)','Maintainability index (variable)','Coupling metric (variable — lower is better)','Cohesion score (variable — higher is better)','Bug introduction risk (variable)'],explain:"Students discover how inheritance enables code reuse but deep hierarchies create fragility, why encapsulation protects data integrity, and how polymorphism allows flexible extensible design.",real:'Java Android app class hierarchy, Python Django web framework inheritance, Game character class hierarchies, Uber driver/rider/trip OOP design'},
//     {label:'Cybersecurity — encryption, threats and system vulnerabilities',concept:'Systems',related:'Ethics, Privacy, Interaction',lp:'Principled, Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 5: Abstract data structures; Option C: Web science',scene:'An animated network map showing client, server, and attacker nodes. Data packets travel as glowing capsules. Encryption padlock appears when SSL/TLS activates. SQL injection arrow shows database breach. Firewall wall rises and falls.',sliders:['Encryption strength (0=Plaintext → 4=AES-256 end-to-end)','Password policy (0=No requirements → 4=MFA + long random)','Software patch currency (0=Never updated → 4=Auto-patched immediately)','User security training (0=None → 4=Regular phishing simulations)'],resources:['Breach probability % (variable — lower is better)','System usability score (variable)','Recovery time if breached hours (variable)','Regulatory compliance score (variable)','User friction level (variable)'],explain:"Students discover the security-usability trade-off — maximum security creates user friction that leads to workarounds, often introducing vulnerabilities. The human factor is the weakest link.",real:'Equifax 2017 breach from unpatched Apache, WannaCry NHS ransomware, Signal vs WhatsApp encryption comparison, GDPR compliance requirements'},
//     {label:'Computational thinking — decomposition, abstraction and algorithms',concept:'Systems',related:'Logic, Abstraction, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 1: System fundamentals; Topic 4: Computational thinking',scene:'An animated problem-solving studio. A complex real-world problem — route planning traffic control or sorting a library — appears. Students decompose it into sub-problems. Abstraction panel removes unnecessary detail. Algorithm steps appear as a flowchart that executes step by step with tracing.',sliders:['Problem complexity (0=Simple one-step → 4=Complex multi-layered decomposition)','Level of abstraction (0=Concrete all detail → 4=Abstract — only essential features kept)','Algorithm efficiency (0=Brute force O(n2) → 4=Optimised O(n log n))','Visualisation mode (0=Pseudocode → 4=Animated execution trace)'],resources:['Decomposition levels needed (variable)','Abstraction quality — irrelevant details removed (variable)','Algorithm steps count (variable)','Pattern identified and generalised (variable)','Solution correctness verified (variable)'],explain:'Students practise the four pillars of computational thinking — decomposition, pattern recognition, abstraction and algorithm design — on a realistic problem. They discover that algorithmic thinking is not about coding but about structuring a problem so it can be solved systematically by any agent, human or machine. Core IB CS Topic 4 skill.',real:'Google Maps route algorithm — decomposition of city network into graph, Netflix recommendation — abstraction of user preference patterns, ATM transaction — decomposed into authentication balance check dispensing logging, Genome sequencing algorithm — divide and conquer decomposition'},

//     {label:'Data structures — arrays stacks queues linked lists and trees',concept:'Systems',related:'Logic, Abstraction, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 5: Abstract data structures',scene:'An interactive data structure zoo. Students select a structure and perform operations — push/pop a stack, enqueue/dequeue a queue, insert into a linked list, traverse a binary tree. Each operation animated step by step showing pointer updates. Time complexity shown for each operation.',sliders:['Data structure type (0=Array — random access O(1) → 4=Binary search tree — O(log n) search)','Operation performed (0=Access/Read → 4=Insert/Delete)','Data size n (0=Small 10 elements → 4=Large 1000 elements)','Implementation shown (0=Abstract — user view → 4=Memory — pointer view)'],resources:['Time complexity for operation (O(1) O(n) O(log n))','Space complexity (variable)','Operations per second relative (variable)','Best structure for this use case (variable)','Memory layout diagram (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why choosing the right data structure is the most important algorithm design decision — a stack is perfect for undo operations but terrible for searching; a hash table gives O(1) lookup but no ordering. The animation makes pointer manipulation and memory layout concrete. Core IB CS Topic 5 abstract data structures.',real:'Browser back button uses a stack, Printer queue uses a queue, File system directory uses a tree, Database index uses B-tree for fast lookup, Undo-redo in Photoshop uses two stacks'},

//     {label:'Networks — protocols OSI model client-server and packet switching',concept:'Systems',related:'Communication, Logic, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 3: Networks',scene:'An animated network diagram. Data packet created at source — layered through OSI model gaining headers at each layer. Packet travels through routers choosing paths. At destination layers stripped off in reverse. TCP handshake animated. HTTP request-response cycle shown. DNS lookup visualised.',sliders:['Network type (0=LAN single building → 4=WAN global internet)','Protocol layer shown (0=Physical bits → 4=Application HTTP SMTP)','Packet loss simulation (0=No loss — reliable → 4=High loss — TCP retransmission visible)','Encryption (0=Plaintext HTTP → 4=Encrypted HTTPS — TLS handshake shown)'],resources:['Latency ms for packet journey (variable)','Bandwidth utilisation % (variable)','OSI layer currently shown (1-7)','Packets retransmitted from loss (variable)','TCP vs UDP comparison (variable)'],explain:'Students trace a data packet through the full OSI model, discovering that each layer adds a header with control information — encapsulation. Routers operate at Layer 3 (Network) reading IP addresses; switches at Layer 2. The TCP three-way handshake ensures reliability. Packet switching means packets take different routes — the internet is resilient because of this. Core IB CS Topic 3.',real:'Netflix streaming — UDP for speed (some loss acceptable), WhatsApp messages — TCP for reliability, Zoom video — proprietary protocol balancing speed and reliability, DNS lookup chain — root TLD authoritative servers'},

//     {label:'Databases — SQL relational model normalisation and queries',concept:'Systems',related:'Logic, Abstraction, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 1 and Option D: Databases',scene:'An interactive relational database with three linked tables — Customers Orders Products. Students write SQL queries visually using a builder. JOIN shown as animated table merging. Normalisation wizard checks for 1NF 2NF 3NF violations and suggests fixes. ER diagram updates as schema changes.',sliders:['Query complexity (0=Simple SELECT WHERE → 4=Multi-table JOIN with aggregation)','Normalisation level (0=Unnormalised — data redundancy → 4=Third normal form — no redundancy)','Data volume (0=10 rows — fast → 4=Million rows — index needed)','Index presence (0=No index — full table scan → 4=Indexed — fast lookup)'],resources:['Query result rows returned (variable)','Query execution time ms (variable — index matters)','Data redundancy removed by normalisation % (variable)','Join type used (INNER LEFT RIGHT) (variable)','Primary and foreign key relationships (variable)'],explain:'Students write SQL queries and immediately see results, discovering that JOINs combine tables by matching foreign keys to primary keys. Normalisation removes redundancy — storing the same data in multiple places creates inconsistency when one copy is updated. An index is a sorted lookup structure that makes SELECT queries dramatically faster.',real:'Amazon product database — millions of rows indexed by category, Hospital patient records relational database, Spotify music recommendation database with millions of relationships, Google BigQuery — SQL on petabyte-scale datasets'},

//     {label:'System development lifecycle — analysis design testing and evaluation',concept:'Systems',related:'Logic, Abstraction, Communication',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 1: System fundamentals and SDLC',scene:'An animated SDLC Gantt chart. Waterfall and Agile shown side by side. Requirements analysis feeds into design feeds into implementation feeds into testing feeds into deployment and maintenance. Each phase has activities and deliverables. Agile shows sprints cycling through all phases repeatedly.',sliders:['Methodology type (0=Waterfall — linear sequential → 4=Agile scrum — iterative sprints)','Requirements clarity (0=Vague — scope creep risk → 4=Clear — waterfall works well)','Project size and team (0=Small 2-person → 4=Large 50-person distributed team)','Testing rigour (0=Manual only → 4=Automated unit integration and acceptance testing)'],resources:['Project delivery time estimate (variable)','Scope change risk (variable)','User satisfaction at delivery (variable)','Bug rate at launch (variable)','Maintenance cost over 5 years (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that Waterfall works when requirements are fixed and clear (building a bridge) but fails when requirements change — a common software reality. Agile delivers working software in 2-week sprints getting constant user feedback. Testing is most expensive when left to the end. The SDLC phases are the same; the sequence and iteration differ.',real:'NASA shuttle software — waterfall with strict verification, Spotify development — continuous deployment agile, NHS COVID-19 app development — agile iterations, Facebook famous move fast and break things — agile extreme'},

//     {label:'Social and ethical impacts of computing — AI bias privacy and automation',concept:'Ethics',related:'Responsibility, Change, Interaction',lp:'Principled, Caring, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Topic 4.3: Social and ethical issues',scene:'Three case study panels rotate: AI hiring algorithm showing demographic bias from training data, facial recognition accuracy rates by skin tone, automation displacing routine jobs. Students set algorithm training parameters and observe which groups are disadvantaged. Privacy dashboard shows data collected by a typical smartphone.',sliders:['Training data diversity (0=Homogeneous — high bias → 4=Representative — low bias)','Algorithm transparency (0=Black box — opaque → 4=Explainable AI — full audit)','Automation level in industry (0=No automation → 4=Full automation — job displacement)','Privacy regulation strength (0=No regulation — maximum data collection → 4=GDPR-level — strict consent)'],resources:['Algorithmic bias index across demographics (variable)','False positive rate by demographic group (variable)','Jobs displaced by automation estimate (variable)','Privacy data points collected per user (variable)','Public trust in technology (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that AI algorithms trained on biased historical data perpetuate and amplify discrimination — a hiring algorithm trained on past employees inherits historical biases. Facial recognition has documented accuracy gaps by skin tone. Automation creates productivity gains but concentrates winners in capital owners. These are core IB CS social and ethical issues.',real:'Amazon hiring algorithm scrapped 2018 — biased against women, COMPAS recidivism algorithm racial bias, US facial recognition in policing — NIST accuracy study, UK taxi driver displacement from Uber — gig economy job quality'}]},
//   {icon:'⚗️',name:'Chemistry',sub:'56 simulations · Structure 1–3 · Reactivity 1–3',topics:[
//     {label:'Kinetic molecular theory — states of matter',concept:'Structure',related:'Energy, Transformation, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.1.2: States of matter and particle model',scene:'Three animated panels side by side — solid, liquid, gas. Particles shown as coloured spheres. In the solid panel particles vibrate in fixed positions; liquid particles flow and slide; gas particles move rapidly in all directions bouncing off walls. Temperature slider speeds up all motion.',sliders:['Temperature K (0=Cold 50K — near absolute zero → 4=Hot 1000K — high speed particles)','Pressure atm (0=Very low — gas expands → 4=High — gas compressed)','Substance type (0=Noble gas — monatomic → 4=Large polar molecule)','Phase at current conditions (0=Solid → 4=Gas)'],resources:['Average particle speed m/s (variable)','Inter-particle spacing relative (variable)','State of matter (solid/liquid/gas)','Frequency of wall collisions (variable)','Kinetic energy average J (variable)'],explain:'Students observe how temperature affects particle motion across all three states and discover that melting and boiling occur when kinetic energy overcomes inter-particle forces. The transition from liquid to gas is dramatic — particle spacing increases 1000-fold. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.1.2.',real:'Liquid nitrogen demonstrations — state change at 77K, Steam engine efficiency and gas expansion, Plasma screen — fourth state of matter at extreme temperature, Aerosol can explosion warning — gas pressure rises with temperature'},

//     {label:'Maxwell-Boltzmann energy distribution',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Change, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — R2.2.4: Collision theory and activation energy',scene:'An animated Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution curve — the y-axis shows fraction of molecules and x-axis kinetic energy. The curve shifts and flattens as temperature rises. A vertical activation energy threshold line shown in red. The shaded area to the right of Ea represents molecules with enough energy to react.',sliders:['Temperature K (0=Low 250K → 4=High 750K — curve flattens and shifts right)','Activation energy Ea kJ/mol (0=Low 20 kJ/mol — most molecules react → 4=High 150 kJ/mol — very few react)','Catalyst present (0=No catalyst → 4=Catalyst — Ea line moves left)','Gas molar mass g/mol (0=Light H2 2 → 4=Heavy Xe 131 — narrower curve)'],resources:['Fraction of molecules above Ea (variable)','Most probable speed m/s (variable)','Mean speed m/s (variable)','Rate of reaction relative (variable)','Effect of catalyst on shaded area (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that doubling temperature does not double the rate — it dramatically increases the fraction of molecules above Ea because of the exponential tail of the distribution. The catalyst effect is visible as the Ea line shifts left, enormously increasing the shaded area without changing the distribution curve. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.2.4.',real:'Haber process temperature compromise — too high and Ea is easy but equilibrium shifts wrong, Enzyme catalysts in biology — same principle, Food refrigeration slowing reactions by reducing molecules above Ea, Explosives — very low Ea allows rapid chain reaction'},

//     {label:'Atomic emission spectra and photon energy',concept:'Structure',related:'Energy, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.3.1: Line spectra and photon energy E=hf',scene:'An animated electromagnetic spectrum shown as a colour band. Discharge tubes for different elements glow. A spectroscope prism splits the light into discrete coloured lines. Students can click each line to calculate E = hf using the wavelength. Hydrogen Balmer series shown in detail.',sliders:['Element selected (0=Hydrogen simplest → 4=Neon — complex spectrum)','Wavelength of selected line nm (0=UV 200nm → 4=Near-IR 800nm)','Energy level transition (0=High energy — UV Lyman series → 4=Low energy — IR Paschen series)','Photon energy scale (0=Single photon → 4=1 mole of photons — molar energy)'],resources:['Photon frequency Hz (variable — c/lambda)','Photon energy J (E=hf)','Energy in kJ/mol (variable)','Spectral colour of emission line (variable)','Series name (Lyman/Balmer/Paschen)'],explain:'Students apply E = hf to calculate photon energies for visible emission lines and discover that each element has a unique spectral fingerprint. The Balmer series for hydrogen gives 4 visible lines whose energies exactly match the differences between specific energy levels — direct evidence for quantised energy. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.3.1.',real:'Sodium street lamp characteristic yellow-orange doublet, Neon advertising signs, Stellar spectroscopy identifying elements in distant stars, Laser technology — stimulated emission of specific photon wavelengths'},

//     {label:'Hydrogen emission spectrum — Bohr model and energy levels',concept:'Structure',related:'Energy, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.3.2: Bohr model and hydrogen energy levels',scene:'A clickable Bohr model of hydrogen — concentric rings showing n=1 to n=6. When the student clicks a transition arrow, an electron jumps and a photon of the correct colour appears. Energy level diagram on the right shows En = -13.6/n2 eV. Balmer series transitions highlighted in visible light.',sliders:['Initial energy level ni (0=n=2 → 4=n=6)','Final energy level nf (0=n=1 ground state → 4=n=5)','Observation frame (0=Emission — electron drops → 4=Absorption — electron rises)','Energy scale (0=eV → 4=kJ/mol)'],resources:['Energy of transition eV (variable — En = -13.6/n2)','Wavelength of photon nm (variable)','Series of transition (Lyman/Balmer/Paschen)','Visible or UV or IR (variable)','Frequency Hz (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the discrete lines in the hydrogen spectrum arise directly from quantised energy levels — only specific photon energies are emitted, corresponding to exact differences between energy levels. En = -13.6/n2 eV predicts all emission lines exactly. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.3.2.',real:'Hubble Space Telescope uses hydrogen spectral lines to measure star composition and redshift, Helium discovered in the Sun via spectroscopy before found on Earth, Laser pointer — stimulated emission, Franck-Hertz experiment demonstrating discrete energy levels'},

//     {label:'Electron configuration builder',concept:'Structure',related:'Patterns, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.3.5: Electron configurations and orbital notation',scene:'An interactive orbital energy diagram. Sublevels shown as horizontal lines in increasing energy — 1s 2s 2p 3s 3p 4s 3d etc. Students drag electrons (shown as arrows up or down for spin) into sublevels following Aufbau principle Hund rule and Pauli exclusion. Chromium and Copper exceptions flagged.',sliders:['Atomic number Z (0=H Z=1 → 4=Kr Z=36)','Notation type (0=Orbital box diagram → 4=Condensed noble gas notation)','Ion formed (0=Neutral atom → 4=Maximum oxidation state ion)','HL: Exceptions displayed (0=Hide exceptions → 4=Show Cr and Cu with explanation)'],resources:['Electron configuration written (variable)','Number of unpaired electrons (variable)','Magnetic properties (paramagnetic/diamagnetic)','Period and group (variable)','Oxidation state range possible (variable)'],explain:'Students build electron configurations step by step, discovering that Hund\'s rule fills degenerate orbitals singly before pairing and that Cr [Ar]3d54s1 and Cu [Ar]3d104s1 are exceptions due to extra stability of half-filled and filled d-sublevels. The link from configuration to periodic table position becomes concrete. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.3.5.',real:'MRI machine — unpaired electrons in contrast agents, Oxygen paramagnetism demonstration (liquid O2 in a magnetic field), Transition metal colour from d-d electron transitions, Periodic table structure explained by electron configuration filling order'},

//     {label:'Ionisation energy trends across the periodic table',concept:'Structure',related:'Patterns, Evidence, Periodicity',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.3.6: First IE trends; S1.3.7 (HL): Successive IEs',scene:'A graph of first ionisation energies plotted across periods 1-3 as a bar chart. Discontinuities at Be/B and N/O highlighted in red. Students click any element to show its successive IE graph as a bar chart — the dramatic jump indicates group number.',sliders:['Period displayed (0=Period 1-2 → 4=Period 1-3 with transition metals)','IE type (0=First IE only → 4=Successive IEs for one element)','Element selected for successive IE (0=Na → 4=Al)','Scale (0=kJ/mol → 4=eV)'],resources:['First IE of selected element kJ/mol (variable)','Anomaly explanation (variable — Be/B and N/O)','Group number from successive IE jump (variable)','Number of core vs valence electrons (variable)','Effective nuclear charge Zeff trend (variable)'],explain:'Students predict the group of a mystery element by finding the dramatic jump in successive ionisation energies, and explain the two anomalies in first IE across Period 2: Be to B drops because 2p is higher energy than 2s; N to O drops because O has paired electrons in one 2p orbital with increased repulsion. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.3.6-7.',real:'Mass spectrometer measures successive IEs directly, Neon signs — Ne requires very high energy to ionise (noble gas), Aluminium smelting electrolysis removes 3 electrons matching IE pattern, Sodium-potassium pump — biological use of ion differences'},

//     {label:'Ideal gas law — PVT sandbox',concept:'Structure',related:'Systems, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.5.3-4: Ideal gas law PV=nRT',scene:'An animated container with gas particle dots. Four sliders control P V T and n. When any slider changes, particles animate to reflect new density and speed. A calculation panel shows PV=nRT step by step. Boyle Charles and Gay-Lussac law graphs draw automatically.',sliders:['Pressure P atm (0=0.1 atm very low → 4=10 atm high)','Volume V litres (0=0.5L small → 4=20L large)','Temperature T K (0=200K cold → 4=600K hot)','Amount of gas n mol (0=0.1 mol → 4=2.0 mol)'],resources:['PV/nRT ratio (should equal 1 for ideal gas)','Particle density n/V mol/L (variable)','Average speed m/s (variable with T)','Calculated missing variable (variable)','Predicted vs actual pressure comparison (variable)'],explain:'Students fix two variables and change a third, predicting the result using PV=nRT before the simulation reveals it. The ratio PV/nRT equals 1 for ideal gas confirms the law. Boyle Charles and Gay-Lussac emerge as special cases. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.5.3-4 and builds quantitative gas law calculation skill.',real:'Hot air balloon — heating air reduces density at constant pressure, Scuba diving — Boyle law and pressure-volume at depth, Car tyre pressure changes with temperature, Autoclave sterilisation — high T and P to kill pathogens'},

//     {label:'Real gas vs ideal gas deviation',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Patterns, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.5.2: Real gas behaviour and van der Waals equation',scene:'A compressibility factor graph Z=PV/nRT vs P for several real gases. At low P all gases converge toward ideal Z=1. At high P hydrogen and helium show Z above 1 (repulsive forces dominate) while CO2 dips below 1 (attractive forces dominate) before rising. Temperature slider shows convergence to ideal at high T.',sliders:['Gas chosen (0=Helium — least ideal deviation → 4=CO2 — large molecule strong IMF)','Pressure range atm (0=Low 1-10 atm → 4=High 1-300 atm)','Temperature K (0=Cold 200K — big deviation → 4=Hot 1000K — approaches ideal)','Parameter shown (0=Compressibility Z → 4=van der Waals a and b values)'],resources:['Compressibility factor Z at current P and T (variable)','Deviation from ideal % (variable)','van der Waals a coefficient measure of attraction (variable by gas)','van der Waals b coefficient measure of volume (variable by gas)','Boyle temperature where Z=1 across range (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that real gases deviate from ideal behaviour because the ideal gas model assumes no intermolecular forces and zero particle volume — both incorrect at high pressure. CO2 liquefies where Z drops sharply. High temperature restores near-ideal behaviour because kinetic energy overwhelms IMF. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.5.2.',real:'Liquefaction of gases — industrial production of liquid nitrogen and oxygen, Supercritical CO2 in coffee decaffeination, Compressed natural gas storage in vehicles, Deep-sea diving gas mixture deviations at extreme pressure'},

//     {label:'Mole concept and Avogadro constant calculator',concept:'Structure',related:'Quantity, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.4.1-3: Mole concept and Avogadro constant',scene:'An animated laboratory balance with a sample. Students enter any two of four quantities — mass in grams moles number of particles Mr. The third quantity calculates instantly. A visual counter attempts to display 6.02 times 10 to the 23 as animated grain dots — impossible to complete, illustrating the scale of Avogadro.',sliders:['Mass of sample g (0=0.1g → 4=100g)','Molar mass Mr g/mol (0=H2 Mr=2 → 4=CaCO3 Mr=100)','Number of moles n (0=0.001 mol → 4=5 mol)','Visualisation scale (0=Individual atoms → 4=Molar quantities)'],resources:['Moles n = mass/Mr (variable)','Number of particles = n times NA (variable)','Mass required for 1 mol g (= Mr)','Avogadro constant 6.022 times 10^23 (fixed)','Volume at STP for gaseous sample litres (variable)'],explain:'Students convert fluently between mass moles particles and volume using the molar calculation triangle. The Avogadro visualisation makes 6.02 times 10^23 tangible by showing that a mole of sand grains would cover Earth to 1km depth. The mole bridges the macroscopic laboratory world with the atomic scale. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.4.1-3.',real:'Drug dosage calculated in moles per kilogram, Atmospheric CO2 measured in ppm then converted to moles per litre, Industrial chemistry — tonne-scale reactions still planned in moles, Electroplating — moles of electrons (Faraday) deposit moles of metal'},

//     {label:'Empirical and molecular formula solver',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Quantity, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.4.4: Empirical and molecular formula from percentage composition',scene:'A percentage composition input panel — students enter % by mass for each element. The solver shows the full worked calculation step by step: divide by Mr, find ratio, convert to smallest whole number ratio. Then enter molar mass to scale up to molecular formula. Full audit trail visible.',sliders:['Number of elements in compound (0=2 binary → 4=4 elements CHNO)','Percentage composition precision (0=Rough to nearest 5% → 4=Exact to 0.1%)','Molecular mass M given (0=Empirical formula only → 4=Full molecular formula derived)','Combustion analysis mode (0=Direct % input → 4=Combustion products masses input)'],resources:['Empirical formula derived (variable)','Mole ratio of elements (variable)','Molecular formula if M given (variable)','Atom economy of formula derivation N/A (educational display)','Degree of unsaturation for organic (HL) (variable)'],explain:'Students follow the algorithm for empirical formula derivation — divide each % by atomic mass find simplest ratio multiply to whole numbers — and discover why the ratio must be whole numbers (atoms cannot be fractional). Combustion analysis mode shows how CHO compounds are analysed. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.4.4.',real:'Determination of water of crystallisation in hydrated salts, Sugar molecular formula C12H22O11 vs empirical CH2O, Protein amino acid sequencing mass spectrometry, Mars Curiosity rover organic compound identification by combustion analysis'},

//     {label:'Molar concentration and dilution calculator',concept:'Structure',related:'Quantity, Systems, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S1.4.5: Concentration and dilution C1V1=C2V2',scene:'Two animated beakers. The left shows a concentrated solution with many coloured solute dots and bright colour intensity. A pipette transfers volume to the right beaker with water added. Colour fades as dilution occurs. C1V1=C2V2 displayed with substitution highlighted in real time.',sliders:['Initial concentration C1 mol/L (0=Very dilute 0.01 → 4=Concentrated 10.0)','Initial volume V1 mL (0=1mL → 4=100mL)','Volume of solvent added mL (0=0 — no dilution → 4=900mL — 10-fold dilution)','Solute type (0=Strong acid → 4=Salt)'],resources:['Final concentration C2 = C1V1/V2 mol/L (variable)','Total final volume V2 mL (variable)','Dilution factor (variable)','Moles of solute conserved mol (variable — same before and after)','pH change for acid dilution (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that dilution conserves moles of solute — C1V1 = C2V2 follows directly from moles = C times V being constant. The colour visualisation makes the dilution tangible. For acids they observe pH change is not proportional to concentration change because of the logarithmic scale. Models IB DP Chemistry S1.4.5.',real:'Hospital IV drip preparation — precise dilution of stock solutions, Wine dilution to reach target alcohol content, Swimming pool chlorine concentration management, Serial dilution in microbiology for bacterial colony counting'},

//     {label:'VSEPR molecular geometry builder',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Patterns, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.2.4: VSEPR theory and molecular geometry',scene:'A 3D animated central atom. Students select the number of bonding pairs and lone pairs using sliders. The geometry updates instantly in 3D — linear trigonal planar tetrahedral trigonal bipyramidal octahedral and all lone-pair distortions. Bond angles displayed and compared to ideal.',sliders:['Number of bonding pairs (0=2 → 4=6)','Number of lone pairs on central atom (0=0 → 4=3)','Electronegativity difference (0=Non-polar → 4=Highly polar)','HL: Multiple bonds included (0=Single bonds only → 4=Double and triple bonds)'],resources:['Molecular geometry name (variable)','Bond angle degrees (variable — reduced by lone pairs)','Hybridisation of central atom (variable)','Polarity of molecule (polar/non-polar)','Example molecule for this geometry (variable)'],explain:'Students build any molecular geometry by selecting bonding and lone pairs, discovering that lone pairs occupy more space than bonding pairs and reduce bond angles. Water has tetrahedral electron geometry but bent molecular geometry — a distinction students often miss. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.4 VSEPR in full.',real:'Drug receptor binding — 3D shape of active site determines specificity, Thalidomide — chirality and mirror image molecules with different effects, Carbon dioxide linear vs water bent explains why CO2 is non-polar and H2O is polar, Ammonia shape allows hydrogen bonding'},

//     {label:'Lewis structure constructor',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.2.1: Lewis structures and octet rule',scene:'A blank molecular construction space. Students select atoms and bond types. Electrons shown as dots or dashes. The octet counter for each atom glows green when satisfied and red when violated. Formal charge calculated for each atom. Expanded octet species like PCl5 and SF6 for HL.',sliders:['Molecule type (0=Simple diatomic → 4=Polyatomic with lone pairs)','Bond type (0=Single only → 4=Triple bond)','Formal charge display (0=Hidden → 4=Shown for each atom)','HL: Expanded octet allowed (0=Octet rule strict → 4=Expanded octet for P S Cl)'],resources:['Total valence electrons counted (variable)','Electrons used in structure (variable)','Formal charge per atom (variable)','Resonance structures available (variable)','VSEPR geometry predicted from Lewis (variable)'],explain:'Students draw Lewis structures using the systematic approach — count valence electrons place single bonds satisfy octets place lone pairs — and discover that formal charge guides which resonance structure is dominant. HL students explore expanded octets in period 3 elements. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.1.',real:'Drug molecule Lewis structures for pharmacology, CO2 Lewis structure explains its non-polarity despite polar bonds, Ozone resonance explains equal O-O bond lengths, N2 triple bond explains its chemical inertness in atmosphere'},

//     {label:'Bond polarity and molecular dipole',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.2.5-6: Electronegativity and molecular polarity',scene:'A molecular model builder. Students drag atoms onto a central atom. Electronegativity values load from the data booklet automatically. Bond dipole vector arrows appear on each bond pointing toward more electronegative atom. The net molecular dipole shown as a large arrow. Symmetrical molecules show cancelling vectors.',sliders:['Central atom (0=Carbon → 4=Chlorine)','Surrounding atoms (0=Hydrogen — low EN → 4=Fluorine — highest EN)','Molecular geometry (0=Linear → 4=Tetrahedral)','Symmetry (0=Asymmetric — polar → 4=Symmetric — non-polar despite polar bonds)'],resources:['Electronegativity difference for each bond (variable)','Bond dipole moment D (variable)','Net molecular dipole moment D (variable — zero if symmetric)','Polar or non-polar classification (variable)','Intermolecular force type expected (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that bond polarity is necessary but not sufficient for molecular polarity — CO2 has two polar bonds but is non-polar because they cancel. H2O has the same bonds but is polar because the geometry is bent. This explains the dramatic difference in boiling points and solubility. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.5-6.',real:'Water as universal solvent due to polarity, HCl gas vs water polarity explains different properties, Microwave oven — polar water molecules rotate in electromagnetic field generating heat, Non-stick Teflon surface — non-polar PTFE resists polar substances'},

//     {label:'Intermolecular forces comparator',concept:'Structure',related:'Energy, Patterns, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.2.8-9: London dispersion dipole-dipole and hydrogen bonding',scene:'Three side-by-side animated panels for London dipole-dipole and hydrogen bonding. Induced dipoles flicker on noble gas atoms. Partial charges shown on polar molecules attracting. Hydrogen bonds shown as dotted lines between H and electronegative atoms. Boiling point vs molar mass graph for noble gases alkanes and alcohols.',sliders:['IMF type displayed (0=London only → 4=All three types)','Molar mass of molecule g/mol (0=Small 30 → 4=Large 200 — London forces increase)','Presence of H bonded to N O F (0=No H bond → 4=Strong H bond present)','Temperature relative to boiling point (0=Well below Tb — liquid → 4=Well above — gas)'],resources:['Relative IMF strength kJ/mol (variable)','Boiling point trend C (variable)','Solubility in water (variable — like dissolves like)','Viscosity relative (variable — increases with IMF)','Surface tension relative (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why water boils at 100C while H2S at -60C despite similar molar mass — hydrogen bonding adds enormously to intermolecular forces. The London force trend explains why hexane boils higher than methane. The like dissolves like principle emerges from polarity matching. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.8-9.',real:'Geckos walking on glass using London forces from millions of tiny hairs, Water strider walking on water due to surface tension from hydrogen bonding, Ethanol miscible with water — both hydrogen bond, Grease stain removed by non-polar solvent not water'},

//     {label:'Carbon allotropes — structure and properties',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.2.7: Allotropes of carbon',scene:'Four rotating 3D structures — diamond tetrahedral network graphite layered hexagonal graphene single sheet fullerene C60 sphere. Click each to see bonding highlighted — covalent bonds in diamond graphite graphene sp2 pi system in graphite and graphene. Electrical conductivity demonstration.',sliders:['Allotrope selected (0=Diamond → 4=Fullerene C60)','Property shown (0=Hardness and melting point → 4=Electrical conductivity)','Bonding highlighted (0=Sigma bonds only → 4=All bonds including pi)','Scale (0=Single unit cell → 4=Macroscopic sample)'],resources:['Hybridisation of carbon (variable — sp3 or sp2)','Electrical conductivity (variable — insulator to conductor)','Melting point relative C (variable)','Hardness Mohs scale (variable)','Density g/cm3 (variable)'],explain:'Students connect carbon allotrope structure to properties — diamond is hard and non-conducting because all electrons are localised in sigma bonds; graphite conducts because delocalised pi electrons move between layers. Graphene conducts better than copper. Fullerene C60 has pharmaceutical potential. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.7.',real:'Diamond drill bits cutting through rock, Graphite pencil — layers slide apart leaving mark, Graphene Nobel Prize 2010 — thinnest strongest conductor, Fullerene C60 drug delivery carrier, Carbon nanotube tensile strength 100 times steel'},

//     {label:'Resonance structure visualiser',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S2.2.11: Resonance structures and delocalisation',scene:'A central molecule display for ozone NO2 minus benzene or sulfate. Click arrows cycle through resonance contributors. An animated electron density overlay shows where electrons actually spend time — spread equally across equivalent positions. Bond length data shown confirming intermediate character.',sliders:['Molecule (0=Ozone O3 → 4=Benzene C6H6)','Display mode (0=Individual contributors → 4=Delocalised hybrid)','Evidence shown (0=Structural formulas → 4=Bond length and enthalpy data)','Formal charge displayed (0=Hidden → 4=Shown)'],resources:['Number of resonance contributors (variable)','Actual bond order intermediate (variable)','Bond length pm — intermediate value (variable)','Resonance stabilisation energy kJ/mol (variable — benzene 150 kJ/mol)','Delocalisation description (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that resonance structures are not isomers switching back and forth — the molecule exists as a single hybrid with intermediate bond order. Benzene evidence: all C-C bonds 140pm between single 154pm and double 134pm; three dibromobenzene isomers not six; combustion enthalpy 150 kJ/mol less negative than expected. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.11 HL.',real:'Benzene in petrol and as industrial solvent, Aspirin contains carboxylate resonance stabilisation, Ozone layer — ozone O3 resonance explains its reactivity, Nitrate ion fertiliser NO3 minus three equivalent bonds'},

//     {label:'Benzene — evidence for delocalisation model',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Form, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S2.2.12: Evidence for benzene delocalisation',scene:'Four pieces of evidence presented sequentially: a bond length diagram showing all C-C equal at 140pm, a combustion enthalpy level diagram showing 150 kJ/mol stabilisation, a 3D electron density map showing ring current, and a substitution vs addition reaction outcome. Students weigh evidence and choose the model.',sliders:['Evidence type displayed (0=Bond length uniformity → 4=Reaction type with bromine)','Kekule model comparison (0=Show Kekule prediction → 4=Show actual result)','Stabilisation energy emphasis (0=Enthalpy diagram → 4=Molecular orbital picture)','Historical timeline (0=Kekule 1865 model → 4=Modern delocalised model)'],resources:['Kekule predicted bond lengths pm (alternating 134 154)','Actual bond length pm (140 all equal)','Predicted hydrogenation enthalpy kJ/mol (Kekule — 360)','Actual hydrogenation enthalpy kJ/mol (208 — stabilised)','Reaction type — substitution not addition (confirmed)'],explain:'Students build the scientific argument for the delocalised model of benzene by examining four independent pieces of evidence: uniform bond lengths, anomalous stability, and substitution rather than addition reactions with bromine. No single piece of evidence is conclusive alone — the convergence of all four makes the delocalised model compelling. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.12 HL.',real:'Pharmaceutical chemistry — aromatic ring stability in drug design, Benzene in petrol — carcinogen due to metabolic epoxide intermediate, Dyes and pigments — chromophore from conjugated pi systems, OLED screens — organic semiconductor delocalised electrons'},

//     {label:'sp sp2 sp3 hybridisation visualiser',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S2.2.16: Hybridisation and molecular shape',scene:'Animated atomic orbitals mixing into hybrid orbitals. For sp3 four sp3 hybrid lobes point to tetrahedral corners. For sp2 three sp2 hybrids in a plane with one unhybridised p orbital above and below. For sp two sp hybrids linear with two p orbitals perpendicular. Sigma and pi bonds overlaid on organic molecules.',sliders:['Hybridisation type (0=sp3 tetrahedral → 4=sp linear)','Molecule example (0=Methane sp3 → 4=Ethyne sp)','Bond type shown (0=Sigma bonds only → 4=Both sigma and pi)','3D rotation (0=Fixed view → 4=Full 3D rotation)'],resources:['Bond angle degrees (variable — 109.5 sp3 120 sp2 180 sp)','Number of sigma bonds (variable)','Number of pi bonds (variable)','Geometry (variable — tetrahedral trigonal planar linear)','Unhybridised p orbitals available for pi (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that hybridisation explains molecular geometry mechanistically — sp3 gives tetrahedral bond angles of 109.5 exactly, sp2 gives 120 for trigonal planar. The unhybridised p orbital in sp2 forms pi bonds by sideways overlap, explaining why alkenes undergo addition. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.16 HL.',real:'Ethylene in fruit ripening — sp2 double bond, Acetylene in welding torch — sp triple bond hottest flame, Diamond sp3 hardness, Retinal molecule in eye — conjugated pi system absorbs visible light'},

//     {label:'Ionic lattice and properties',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.1.3: Ionic bonding and lattice structure',scene:'A 3D NaCl lattice that rotates. Students can select different ionic compounds to compare — NaCl MgO CaF2. Ion size shown as sphere radius. Charge shown as colour intensity. Lattice enthalpy display updates when ion charge or radius changes. Dissolution in water animation shows ion hydration.',sliders:['Cation charge (0=+1 Na+ → 4=+3 Al3+)','Anion charge (0=-1 Cl- → 4=-2 O2-)','Ion radius ratio (0=Similar sizes → 4=Very different sizes)','Temperature effect on dissolution (0=Cold — slow dissolving → 4=Hot — rapid)'],resources:['Lattice enthalpy kJ/mol (variable — higher with smaller and more charged ions)','Melting point relative C (variable)','Solubility in water (variable)','Electrical conductivity solid vs liquid vs solution (variable)','Hardness and brittleness relative (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the lattice enthalpy pattern — MgO has a much higher melting point than NaCl because Mg2+ and O2- have double charges giving four times stronger electrostatic attraction and smaller ionic radii further increasing attraction. This explains why ionic compounds vary enormously in properties. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.1.3.',real:'Table salt NaCl dissolving in water — hydration shells visible, Magnesium oxide MgO in refractory bricks — high melting point, Calcium fluoride CaF2 fluorite mineral, Lithium battery — Li+ small size and charge gives high energy density'},

//     {label:'Metallic bonding and conductivity',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Energy, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.3.1: Metallic bonding model',scene:'An animated metal lattice of positive ions immersed in a sea of delocalised electrons shown as blue clouds. When a voltage is applied electrons flow collectively in one direction as a current. A hammer blow animation shows layers sliding past each other — malleability explained as ions moving in the electron sea without breaking bonds.',sliders:['Metal type (0=Sodium — 1 valence electron weak metallic bond → 4=Tungsten — many electrons strong bond)','Applied voltage (0=None → 4=High — maximum electron flow)','Temperature (0=Cold — high conductivity → 4=Hot — increased ion vibration reduces conductivity)','Alloy addition (0=Pure metal → 4=Alloy — different size atoms disrupt layers)'],resources:['Electrical conductivity relative (variable)','Melting point relative C (variable)','Malleability and ductility (variable)','Tensile strength relative (variable)','Effect of temperature on conductivity (variable)'],explain:'Students explain all metallic properties from one model — delocalised electron sea conducts electricity and heat, allows ion layers to slide (malleability), holds ions together (strength). Alloys are stronger because different-sized atoms disrupt regular layer sliding. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.3.1.',real:'Copper wiring — best conductor after silver, Shape memory alloys in spectacle frames, Steel alloy stronger than pure iron, Titanium lightweight and strong for aircraft and medical implants'},

//     {label:'Bonding triangle — van Arkel-Ketelaar diagram',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S2.4.1-2: Bonding triangle and bond character',scene:'An interactive triangular diagram with ionic at the top left metallic at the bottom left and covalent at the bottom right. Students enter two elements and the electronegativity difference and average electronegativity calculate. The compound plots on the triangle. Students see which type of bonding is predicted.',sliders:['Electronegativity of element A (0=Very low 0.7 Cs → 4=Very high 4.0 F)','Electronegativity of element B (0=Very low 0.9 K → 4=Very high 3.5 O)','Electronegativity difference (0=0 pure covalent or metallic → 4=3.3 ionic)','Average electronegativity (0=Low metallic → 4=High covalent)'],resources:['Electronegativity difference (variable — high = ionic)','Average electronegativity (variable — low = metallic)','Predicted bonding character (ionic/covalent/metallic)','Percentage ionic character % (variable)','Compound plotted position (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that bonding type is not binary — it exists on a continuum. NaCl plots near the ionic apex but still has partial covalent character. Compounds near the covalent apex can be network or molecular. The diagram explains why some bonds are intermediate and predictions from electronegativity alone are insufficient. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.4.1-2.',real:'HF most polar covalent bond not ionic despite large EN difference, Silicon carbide SiC — network covalent ceramic used in cutting tools, Aluminium trichloride — intermediate character explains dimers, Intermetallic compounds plotting in the metallic corner'},

//     {label:'Chromatography Rf calculator',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Patterns, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'SL/HL Practical — S2.2.10: Chromatography and separation',scene:'A paper chromatography animation. A mixture spot is placed at the bottom. Solvent rises up the paper. Different coloured component spots travel different distances as the solvent front rises. A ruler overlay allows measurement of spot distance and solvent front distance. Rf calculation panel.',sliders:['Number of components in mixture (0=2 → 4=5)','Solvent polarity (0=Non-polar hexane → 4=Polar water or ethanol)','Stationary phase polarity (0=Non-polar reversed phase → 4=Polar paper)','Temperature of development C (0=Cold 4 → 4=Hot 40)'],resources:['Rf value for each spot = distance spot/distance solvent (variable)','Separation quality — spot resolution (variable)','Identity compared to reference spots (variable)','Polarity of each component relative (variable)','Optimal solvent identified (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate Rf = distance of spot divided by distance of solvent front for each component, discovering that more polar compounds travel less far on polar stationary phases. Changing solvent polarity shifts all Rf values. Rf is constant for a compound under the same conditions — used for identification. Models IB DP Chemistry S2.2.10 practical skill.',real:'Drug testing in sport — urine sample chromatography, Food dye separation in sweets, Amino acid separation — ninhydrin staining, Forensic science ink analysis in questioned documents'},

//     {label:'Periodic table trends — interactive property explorer',concept:'Structure',related:'Patterns, Evidence, Periodicity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — S3.1.3: Periodic table trends',scene:'An interactive periodic table that colour-codes by any chosen property. Students select atomic radius first IE electron affinity or electronegativity. A heat map colours the table from low (blue) to high (red). Clicking any element shows cross-section graphs for its period and group. Anomalies highlighted.',sliders:['Property displayed (0=Atomic radius → 4=Electronegativity)','Period cross-section (0=Period 1 → 4=Period 4 with d-block)','Group cross-section (0=Group 1 alkali metals → 4=Group 17 halogens)','Scale (0=Absolute values → 4=Relative to neighbour)'],resources:['Selected element property value (variable)','Trend explanation across period (variable)','Trend explanation down group (variable)','Anomaly highlighted and explained (variable)','Predicted value for unknown element (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the quantitative trends: atomic radius decreases across a period as Zeff increases and increases down a group as new shells add. First IE follows opposite trend to radius. Electronegativity peaks at fluorine. Anomalies at Be/B and N/O in IE explained by orbital and electron pairing effects. Models IB DP Chemistry S3.1.3.',real:'Mendeleev predicted properties of undiscovered elements using trends, Fluorine most electronegative — strongest oxidising agent, Caesium most reactive metal — lowest IE, Polonium discovery by Curie — periodic table predicted its properties'},

//     {label:'Transition metal properties and d-orbital filling',concept:'Structure',related:'Patterns, Form, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 — S3.1.8: Transition element properties',scene:'An interactive d-block section of the periodic table. Click any transition metal to see its electron configuration and d-orbital filling. Variable oxidation states shown as a colour wheel — each oxidation state of Mn from +2 to +7 shown with corresponding colour of aqueous ion. Catalytic applications displayed.',sliders:['Element selected (0=Sc — one d electron → 4=Zn — full d10)','Oxidation state shown (0=+2 most stable → 4=Highest available)','Ion colour display (0=Single ion → 4=All oxidation state colours for Mn)','Catalytic activity (0=Not catalytically active → 4=Active catalyst — Fe in Haber)'],resources:['Electron configuration with d electrons (variable)','Oxidation states available (variable)','Colour of aqueous ion (variable)','Catalytic function if applicable (variable)','Magnetic properties — unpaired d electrons (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why transition metals show variable oxidation states (similar energy of 3d and 4s electrons), coloured ions (d-d electronic transitions absorbing visible light), catalytic activity (variable oxidation states allow catalytic cycles) and paramagnetism (unpaired d electrons). Models IB DP Chemistry S3.1.8 HL.',real:'Iron catalyst in Haber process — variable oxidation state allows catalytic cycle, Haemoglobin iron centre — Fe2+ binds O2, Permanganate MnO4- as titrant using intense purple colour, Vanadium pentoxide catalyst in contact process for H2SO4'},

//     {label:'Mass spectrometry simulator',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Patterns, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S3.2.8: Mass spectrometry and fragmentation',scene:'An animated mass spectrometer: ionisation chamber electron beam, acceleration through electric field, magnetic deflection by mass to charge ratio, detector. A simulated mass spectrum appears with M+ molecular ion peak and characteristic fragment peaks. Students interpret the pattern to identify the compound.',sliders:['Compound selected (0=Simple alkane C4H10 → 4=Complex aromatic)','Fragmentation displayed (0=M+ peak only → 4=Full fragmentation pattern)','Isotope peaks shown (0=12C only → 4=M+1 and M+2 peaks for Cl and Br)','Unknown mode (0=Known compound → 4=Unknown — student identifies)'],resources:['Molecular ion M+ m/z (variable = Mr)','Base peak m/z (variable — most stable carbocation)','Fragment assignments (variable)','Isotope pattern for halogens (variable)','Molecular formula deduced (variable)'],explain:'Students interpret mass spectra by identifying the M+ peak as the molecular mass and significant fragments as stable carbocations lost from the parent. The M+2 peak of double intensity for chlorine compounds reveals two isotopes 35Cl and 37Cl in 3:1 ratio. Fragmentation follows predictable bond breaking patterns. Models IB DP Chemistry S3.2.8 HL.',real:'Airport security scanners — mass spectrometry for explosives detection, Drug metabolite identification in blood samples, Doping control in sport — mass spec identifies banned substances, Space probe mass spectrometers analysing planetary atmospheres'},

//     {label:'IR spectroscopy — functional group identification',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Form, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S3.2.9: IR spectroscopy and functional groups',scene:'An animated IR spectrum display with wavenumber axis from 4000 to 400 cm-1. A functional group identification panel on the right matches absorption bands to the data booklet table. Students drag absorption regions to match — broad 2500-3300 for O-H acid, 3300-3500 for O-H alcohol, 1700 for C=O carbonyl. A greenhouse gas module shows IR activity of CO2 and CH4.',sliders:['Molecule selected (0=Alkane C-H only → 4=Carboxylic acid all functional groups)','Wavenumber region examined (0=Low 400-1500 fingerprint → 4=High 2500-4000 functional)','Greenhouse gas mode (0=Off → 4=On — show IR activity of CO2 and CH4)','Comparison mode (0=Single spectrum → 4=Before and after reaction)'],resources:['Absorption band wavenumber cm-1 (variable)','Functional group identified (variable)','Bond responsible for absorption (variable)','Greenhouse gas warming potential relative (variable)','Functional group lost or gained in reaction (variable)'],explain:'Students use the data booklet IR table to identify functional groups from absorption positions, discovering that the fingerprint region below 1500 cm-1 is complex but the region above 2500 cm-1 contains diagnostic peaks. The greenhouse gas extension shows why CO2 and CH4 absorb IR radiation from Earth while N2 and O2 do not — explaining the greenhouse effect chemically. Models IB DP Chemistry S3.2.9 HL.',real:'Police breathalyser — IR absorption measures blood alcohol, Quality control in food industry for fat and moisture content, Medical diagnosis by IR of exhaled breath analysis, Climate science — CO2 and CH4 IR absorption explains warming'},

//     {label:'1H NMR spectrum interpreter',concept:'Structure',related:'Evidence, Form, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S3.2.10-11: NMR spectroscopy and proton environments',scene:'An NMR spectrum display with chemical shift axis 0-10 ppm. Multiple signals shown with integration traces proportional to number of protons. Splitting patterns shown — singlet doublet triplet quartet. Students click each signal to assign it to a proton environment on the structural formula.',sliders:['Molecule complexity (0=Ethanol simple 3 signals → 4=Complex 6+ signals)','Display mode (0=Spectrum only → 4=Structure alongside for assignment)','Splitting pattern emphasis (0=Chemical shift only → 4=Full coupling pattern)','Integration shown (0=Hidden → 4=Visible — ratio of protons)'],resources:['Chemical shift ppm for each signal (variable)','Integration ratio (variable — proportional to H count)','Splitting pattern n+1 rule (variable)','Proton environment assignment (variable)','Structural fragment identified (variable)'],explain:'Students interpret NMR spectra by applying three rules: chemical shift reveals electron density around proton, integration shows relative number of protons, splitting pattern n+1 shows number of adjacent protons. Ethanol gives three signals matching CH3 CH2 and OH. The systematic approach builds from simple spectra to complex unknowns. Models IB DP Chemistry S3.2.10-11 HL.',real:'MRI scanning — medical NMR of hydrogen atoms in water in body tissue, Drug purity testing — NMR confirms correct structure, Metabolomics — identifying metabolites in blood by NMR, Food adulteration detection — olive oil contamination by NMR'},

//     {label:'Organic structural formula converter',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — S3.2.1: Organic structural formulas and IUPAC nomenclature',scene:'A structural formula input panel. Students type an IUPAC name and four formula representations appear side by side — molecular formula empirical formula displayed formula and skeletal formula. A functional group identifier labels any groups present. Works for all IB DP Chemistry organic compounds up to C8.',sliders:['Carbon chain length (0=C1 methane → 4=C8 octane)','Functional group (0=Alkane → 4=Carboxylic acid)','Branching (0=Straight chain → 4=Highly branched)','Formula type displayed (0=Molecular only → 4=All four types)'],resources:['Molecular formula CxHyOz (variable)','Structural displayed formula (variable)','Skeletal formula (variable)','IUPAC name confirmed (variable)','Degree of unsaturation (variable)'],explain:'Students convert fluently between IUPAC name and structural representations, discovering that skeletal formulas encode the same information more efficiently. The degree of unsaturation formula (2C+2+N-H-X)/2 predicts rings and double bonds before drawing begins. Models IB DP Chemistry S3.2.1.',real:'Pharmaceutical databases store drugs as IUPAC names and SMILES codes, Fossil fuel components — octane rating linked to carbon chain branching, Flavour molecules — isoamyl acetate banana flavour structural formula, Polymer repeat units derived from monomer structure'},

//     {label:'Stereoisomer 3D model viewer — cis-trans and enantiomers',concept:'Structure',related:'Form, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — S3.2.7: Stereoisomerism — cis-trans and optical isomers',scene:'A 3D molecular model with interactive rotation. For alkenes shows cis and trans isomers as separate non-interconvertible structures with different properties. For chiral centres shows enantiomers as non-superimposable mirror images. Plane polarised light rotates differently for each enantiomer shown with polarimeter animation.',sliders:['Isomer type (0=Cis-trans E/Z alkenes → 4=Optical enantiomers chiral centre)','Molecule complexity (0=But-2-ene simple → 4=Amino acid with multiple chiral centres)','Property comparison (0=Melting points → 4=Optical rotation direction)','Superimposition test (0=Attempted overlay → 4=Non-superimposable mirror confirmed)'],resources:['Cis or trans designation (variable)','R or S configuration (variable)','Optical rotation +/- degrees (variable)','Boiling point difference cis vs trans (variable)','Biological activity difference (variable)'],explain:'Students see directly why cis and trans isomers have different properties — cis-but-2-ene is more polar and boils higher. They rotate enantiomers to confirm non-superimposability and discover that enantiomers are chemically identical in achiral environments but interact differently with biological receptors. Models IB DP Chemistry S3.2.7 HL.',real:'Thalidomide tragedy — one enantiomer therapeutic other teratogenic, Cis-platin vs trans-platin — only cis isomer is anti-cancer drug, Limonene — R enantiomer smells of oranges S enantiomer smells of lemons, Amino acids in proteins all L-configuration'},

//     {label:'Enthalpy profile sketch tool',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Change, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R1.1.3: Enthalpy profile diagrams',scene:'An interactive energy profile builder. Students sketch by dragging — reactant energy level activation energy hump transition state and product energy level. Delta H calculated automatically as product minus reactant. A catalyst pathway adds a lower hump. Quiz mode hides labels and asks students to identify each feature.',sliders:['Reaction type (0=Exothermic — products lower → 4=Endothermic — products higher)','Activation energy Ea kJ/mol (0=Low 20 — fast reaction → 4=High 200 — very slow)','Catalyst effect (0=No catalyst → 4=Catalyst — Ea reduced significantly)','Multi-step mechanism (0=One-step → 4=Three-step — two intermediates visible)'],resources:['Delta H value kJ/mol (variable)','Activation energy Ea kJ/mol (variable)','Catalysed Ea kJ/mol (variable — lower)','Intermediate energy levels (variable)','Rate prediction relative (variable — Arrhenius)'],explain:'Students draw enthalpy profiles for both exothermic and endothermic reactions, discovering that activation energy is always positive regardless of delta H — even exothermic reactions require energy input to start. The catalyst lowers Ea without changing delta H or the energy of reactants/products. The transition state is at the peak — highest energy species. Models IB DP Chemistry R1.1.3.',real:'Combustion of wood — large negative delta H but needs ignition energy, Protein denaturation — endothermic process, Enzyme catalysis — active site provides alternative lower-Ea pathway, Catalytic converter in cars — lowers Ea for CO and NOx reactions'},

//     {label:'Calorimetry virtual experiment',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Evidence, Measurement',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'SL/HL Practical — R1.1.4: Calorimetry and Q=mcΔT',scene:'A virtual calorimeter setup — fuel burner beneath a copper calorimeter containing water. Students select fuel type record initial temperature burn a measured mass and record final temperature. Q=mcΔT calculated step by step. Systematic errors identified — heat loss to surroundings incomplete combustion.',sliders:['Fuel type (0=Methanol Mr=32 → 4=Octanol Mr=130)','Mass of water in calorimeter g (0=100g → 4=500g)','Mass of fuel burned g (0=0.1g → 4=2.0g)','Insulation quality (0=None — large heat loss → 4=Perfect — no heat loss)'],resources:['Temperature rise delta T degrees C (variable)','Heat released Q = mcΔT joules (variable)','Experimental delta Hc kJ/mol (variable)','Data booklet delta Hc kJ/mol (variable)','Percentage error % (variable — always negative due to heat loss)'],explain:'Students discover that experimental calorimetry always underestimates the true enthalpy of combustion because heat is lost to the surroundings and combustion is rarely complete. The systematic error is always in the same direction — experimental values are always less negative than data booklet values. Uncertainty analysis skills built. Models IB DP Chemistry R1.1.4 practical.',real:'Bomb calorimeter for accurate food energy content measurement, Calorie content of food measured in food science, Power station efficiency — heat lost to cooling towers, Hot pack and cold pack chemistry — dissolving salts calorimetry'},

//     {label:'Bond enthalpy calculator',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R1.2.1: Bond enthalpy calculations and Hess law',scene:'An animated reaction equation. Reactant molecules split into atoms with bonds breaking — shown as energy absorbed going up. Product molecules form with bonds forming — shown as energy released going down. Bond enthalpy values from the data booklet substituted automatically. Net delta H calculated step by step.',sliders:['Reaction selected (0=H2 + Cl2 → 2HCl simple → 4=Complex organic combustion)','Bond type emphasis (0=Show all bonds → 4=Highlight bonds broken vs formed)','Step display (0=Overall only → 4=Every bond step by step)','Comparison with Hess law (0=Bond enthalpy only → 4=Compare with Hess cycle value)'],resources:['Sum of bonds broken kJ/mol (endothermic — positive)','Sum of bonds formed kJ/mol (exothermic — negative)','Net delta H = broken minus formed kJ/mol (variable)','Difference from Hess law value kJ/mol (variable — bond enthalpies are averages)','Most significant bond type energy contribution (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that bond enthalpy calculations use average values and are therefore approximate — the actual bond enthalpy of a C-H bond varies slightly in different molecules. The calculation gives a value systematically different from the precise Hess law value. This limitation explains why Hess law is preferred when formation enthalpies are available. Models IB DP Chemistry R1.2.1.',real:'N2 triple bond 945 kJ/mol explains chemical inertness of nitrogen gas, HF bond strongest H-X bond explains HF safety hazards, C=O double bond in CO2 stability — difficult to break in reduction, Ozone O=O-O weaker than O2 O=O explains ozone instability'},

//     {label:'Hess law cycle builder',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R1.2.2: Hess law and enthalpy cycles',scene:'A Hess law diagram builder. Students drag enthalpy arrows upward (endothermic) or downward (exothermic) to construct multi-step thermochemical cycles. Arrow direction and magnitude checked automatically. Target delta H calculates when cycle is complete. Born-Haber cycle template available for HL.',sliders:['Cycle type (0=Simple two-step cycle → 4=Full Born-Haber ionic)','Known enthalpy values provided (0=All given → 4=One unknown — solve)','Scale of diagram kJ/mol (0=Small energies → 4=Large lattice enthalpies)','Verification mode (0=Build only → 4=Verify sum around cycle equals zero)'],resources:['Sum of all enthalpies around cycle kJ/mol (should equal zero)','Unknown delta H calculated kJ/mol (variable)','Formation enthalpy of product kJ/mol (variable)','Combustion enthalpy used kJ/mol (variable)','Accuracy of Hess law verification (variable)'],explain:'Students discover Hess law as a consequence of enthalpy being a state function — the total enthalpy change is path-independent. Building the cycle forces attention to direction of arrows (reverse reaction flips sign) and stoichiometric multipliers. The sum around any complete cycle must equal zero — a powerful self-check. Models IB DP Chemistry R1.2.2.',real:'Industrial process design — using Hess law to find unmeasurable reaction enthalpy, Standard formation enthalpies defined using Hess law, Carbon monoxide toxicity explained by enthalpy comparison, Rocket fuel oxidation enthalpy calculated by Hess cycles'},

//     {label:'Born-Haber cycle — ionic compound formation',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Form, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 — R1.2.5: Born-Haber cycle and lattice enthalpy',scene:'A complete Born-Haber energy ladder for NaCl or MgO. Each step labelled and placed at correct energy level — atomisation IE electron affinity and lattice enthalpy. Students drag numerical values from a data set onto the appropriate step. The unknown lattice enthalpy calculates when all others are placed correctly.',sliders:['Ionic compound (0=NaCl simple → 4=MgO high lattice enthalpy)','Step revealed (0=All steps shown → 4=One step hidden — solve for it)','Comparison cycle (0=Single compound → 4=Two compounds — compare lattice enthalpies)','HL: Theoretical vs experimental lattice enthalpy (0=Theoretical only → 4=Both — percent ionic character)'],resources:['Atomisation enthalpy kJ/mol (variable)','First IE kJ/mol (variable)','Electron affinity kJ/mol (variable)','Lattice enthalpy calculated kJ/mol (variable)','Percentage difference theoretical vs experimental (variable — covalent character indicator)'],explain:'Students build the complete Born-Haber cycle for ionic compounds, discovering that lattice enthalpy cannot be measured directly but is calculated as the only unknown in the cycle. The difference between theoretical (purely ionic model) and experimental lattice enthalpy indicates covalent character — largest for compounds with polarising cations like Li+ and anions like I-. Models IB DP Chemistry R1.2.5 HL.',real:'NaCl lattice enthalpy 787 kJ/mol vs AgCl 905 kJ/mol — Ag+ polarises Cl- giving covalent character, MgO lattice enthalpy 3791 kJ/mol explains high melting point, Lithium fluoride vs caesium iodide comparison, Industrial electrochemistry energy requirements predicted from Born-Haber data'},

//     {label:'Entropy and Gibbs energy — spontaneity calculator',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Change, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 1 — R1.4.1-3: Entropy delta S and Gibbs energy delta G = delta H - T delta S',scene:'An interactive Gibbs energy calculator. Students input delta H and delta S values. Delta G calculates as delta H minus T times delta S at adjustable temperature T. A graph plots delta G vs T showing where the reaction becomes spontaneous. All four combinations of sign for delta H and delta S mapped.',sliders:['Enthalpy change delta H kJ/mol (0=Highly exothermic -500 → 4=Highly endothermic +500)','Entropy change delta S J/mol/K (0=Large decrease -300 → 4=Large increase +300)','Temperature T K (0=Cold 200K → 4=Hot 1000K)','System type (0=Closed system → 4=Open system with surroundings entropy)'],resources:['Gibbs energy delta G kJ/mol (variable — negative means spontaneous)','Spontaneous or non-spontaneous (variable)','Temperature at which spontaneous delta G = 0 K (variable)','Entropy of surroundings delta S surr (variable)','Total entropy change delta S total (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the four cases: always spontaneous when delta H negative and delta S positive; never spontaneous when delta H positive and delta S negative; temperature-dependent in the mixed cases. The crossover temperature where delta G = 0 equals delta H / delta S. This explains why endothermic reactions like dissolving ammonium chloride are spontaneous — driven by entropy increase. Models IB DP Chemistry R1.4.1-3 HL.',real:'Ice melting — endothermic but spontaneous above 0C due to entropy increase, Nitrogen fixation non-spontaneous at room temperature but driven at high T in Haber process, Diamond to graphite spontaneous but immeasurably slow (kinetics not thermodynamics), Biological ATP hydrolysis — coupled reactions driving non-spontaneous processes'},

//     {label:'Stoichiometry and limiting reagent solver',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Quantity, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R2.1.2-4: Stoichiometry and limiting reagent',scene:'An animated reaction vessel. Students enter a balanced equation and initial masses or volumes of each reactant. The solver identifies the limiting reagent by converting all to moles and comparing mole ratios. Theoretical yield calculated. Experimental yield input gives percent yield. Bar chart shows moles of each species.',sliders:['Reaction type (0=Simple 1:1 → 4=Complex non-1:1 stoichiometry)','Reactant 1 mass g (0=Small → 4=Large excess)','Reactant 2 mass g (0=Small — limiting → 4=Large excess)','State of reactants (0=Solid masses → 4=Gas volumes at STP)'],resources:['Moles of each reactant (variable)','Limiting reagent identified (variable)','Theoretical yield g (variable)','Excess reactant remaining g (variable)','Percent yield if experimental given % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the limiting reagent is identified by dividing available moles by stoichiometric coefficient and finding the smallest value — not simply the smaller mass or volume. Percent yield = (experimental/theoretical) times 100 is always less than 100% due to incomplete reaction side reactions or product loss. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.1.2-4.',real:'Industrial Haber process — NH3 yield from given N2 and H2 quantities, Pharmaceutical tablet manufacture — exact stoichiometry of active ingredient, Breathalyser calculation — moles of ethanol from breath volume, Rocket fuel oxidiser ratio optimisation'},

//     {label:'Atom economy calculator',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Quantity, Sustainability, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R2.1.5: Atom economy and green chemistry',scene:'An animated reaction equation. Desired product highlighted in green; unwanted byproducts shown in grey. Atom economy bar chart shows the fraction of atoms in reactants that end up in desired product. Addition reactions show 100%; condensation reactions show the small molecule lost. Green chemistry principles panel.',sliders:['Reaction type (0=Addition — 100% atom economy → 4=Condensation — small molecule lost)','Molar mass of desired product g/mol (variable)','Molar masses of byproducts g/mol (variable)','Industrial relevance (0=Laboratory route → 4=Industrial optimised green route)'],resources:['Atom economy % = Mr desired/sum of all reactants Mr times 100 (variable)','Mass of byproduct per tonne of product kg (variable)','Waste generated relative (variable)','Green chemistry rating (variable)','Economic impact of waste disposal (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that percent yield measures how much product you actually get while atom economy measures how much of the reactant mass ends up in the desired product. A reaction can have 100% yield but terrible atom economy if most atoms become byproduct waste. Addition polymerisation has perfect atom economy; condensation polymerisation loses water. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.1.5.',real:'Aspirin synthesis — traditionally poor atom economy improved by green chemistry, Paracetamol alternative synthesis routes compared by atom economy, Polymer production — addition vs condensation polymerisation trade-offs, Pharmaceutical industry target 95%+ atom economy for cost and waste reasons'},

//     {label:'Reaction rate — concentration experiment',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'SL/HL Practical — R2.2.3: Reaction rate and concentration',scene:'A virtual iodine clock reaction. Students set sodium thiosulfate concentration and measure time until the solution suddenly turns blue-black when iodine exceeds thiosulfate. Multiple runs at different concentrations plotted automatically. Rate vs concentration graph determines order.',sliders:['Sodium thiosulfate concentration mol/L (0=Very dilute 0.01 → 4=Concentrated 0.5)','Temperature C (0=Cold 5 → 4=Hot 50 — combined experiment)','Reactant 2 concentration held constant (0=0.01 mol/L → 4=0.1 mol/L)','Number of runs (0=3 data points → 4=8 data points — better statistics)'],resources:['Time to colour change seconds (variable — shorter at higher concentration)','Rate = 1/time arbitrary units (variable)','Rate vs concentration log-log slope (variable — gives order)','Rate constant k at this temperature (variable)','Order with respect to reactant (variable)'],explain:'Students plot rate vs concentration on log-log axes and find the slope equals the order with respect to that reactant. A slope of 1 means first order — doubling concentration doubles rate. A slope of 2 means second order — doubling concentration quadruples rate. The iodine clock gives a sharp endpoint making timing reliable. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.2.3.',real:'Drug metabolism — first order elimination half-life, Radioactive decay — first order kinetics, Ozone depletion — rate depends on concentration of O3 and Cl, Bread rising — yeast fermentation rate and sugar concentration'},

//     {label:'Reaction rate — temperature experiment',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Energy, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'SL/HL Practical — R2.2.3: Reaction rate and temperature',scene:'A virtual reaction rate vs temperature experiment using Na2S2O3 and HCl. Rate measured at six temperatures. Maxwell-Boltzmann curves at each temperature overlaid on a graph showing the fraction of molecules above Ea increasing exponentially with temperature.',sliders:['Temperature range C (0=5C — slow → 4=55C — fast)','Activation energy Ea kJ/mol (0=Low 30 — less sensitive to T → 4=High 100 — very sensitive)','Catalyst present (0=No catalyst → 4=Catalyst — lower Ea)','Number of data points (0=3 → 4=8 — better Arrhenius plot)'],resources:['Rate at each temperature (variable)','Rate ratio T+10 to T (variable — approximately doubles per 10C)','Ln k vs 1/T slope = -Ea/R (variable — for HL)','Activation energy from graph kJ/mol (variable)','Temperature coefficient Q10 (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that reaction rate approximately doubles for every 10C temperature rise — a rough rule traceable to the exponential Arrhenius equation. The Maxwell-Boltzmann overlay explains mechanistically why: a small temperature rise dramatically increases the fraction of molecules above Ea in the tail of the distribution. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.2.3.',real:'Food refrigeration — slowing bacterial growth and food spoilage, Body temperature fever — 40C dramatically speeds bacterial growth, Activated sludge wastewater treatment — temperature optimised for bacteria, Industrial chemistry reaction vessels heated to increase rate'},

//     {label:'Rate equation and reaction order grapher',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R2.2.9-10: Rate equation and reaction order from data',scene:'A dual graph display. Left shows concentration vs time data points with fitted curve. Right shows three linearisation plots — concentration vs time (zero order linear), ln concentration vs time (first order linear), 1/concentration vs time (second order linear). Students identify which gives a straight line to determine order.',sliders:['Reaction order (0=Zero order — straight line conc vs t → 4=Second order — straight line 1/c vs t)','Initial concentration mol/L (0=Low → 4=High)','Rate constant k (0=Small — slow → 4=Large — fast)','Noise level in data (0=Perfect data → 4=Experimental scatter)'],resources:['Zero order plot linearity R2 (variable)','First order plot linearity R2 (variable)','Second order plot linearity R2 (variable)','Rate constant k from gradient (variable)','Half life t1/2 from k for first order (variable)'],explain:'Students determine reaction order by identifying which linearisation plot gives the best straight line — the graphical method used in HL chemistry. First order gives ln[A] vs t with slope -k and constant half-life. The rate constant k has units that depend on order — mol/L/s for zero, /s for first, L/mol/s for second. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.2.9-10 HL.',real:'Drug elimination kinetics — typically first order with half-life on the label, Carbon-14 dating uses first order radioactive decay, Enzyme-catalysed reactions — often zero order at high substrate concentration, Antibiotics — first order clearance determines dosing interval'},

//     {label:'Arrhenius equation — graphical analysis',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R2.2.12-13: Arrhenius equation and Ea from graph',scene:'A plot of ln k vs 1/T using six to eight experimental rate constant measurements at different temperatures. A best-fit line drawn through the points. Slope equals -Ea/R and y-intercept equals ln A. Students extract the activation energy from the slope and Arrhenius pre-exponential factor A from the intercept.',sliders:['Temperature range K (0=Narrow 290-310K → 4=Wide 250-500K — better precision)','True activation energy kJ/mol (0=Low 30 → 4=High 150)','Data scatter (0=Perfect → 4=Experimental noise added)','Catalyst comparison (0=Single dataset → 4=Catalysed and uncatalysed datasets)'],resources:['Slope = -Ea/R (variable)','Ea calculated from slope kJ/mol (variable)','Arrhenius factor A = e to power intercept (variable)','R2 of linear fit (variable)','Catalysed Ea from second dataset kJ/mol (variable — lower)'],explain:'Students apply linear regression to the Arrhenius plot and extract activation energy without needing to know the collision frequency factor A. The method directly connects to the Maxwell-Boltzmann physical interpretation — steeper slopes mean higher Ea means more sensitive to temperature. Catalysts give shallower slopes confirming lower Ea. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.2.12-13 HL.',real:'Industrial kinetics — companies measure Ea to optimise reaction temperature, Shelf life prediction — Arrhenius used to extrapolate storage stability testing, Protein folding and enzyme denaturation kinetics, Corrosion rates of metals measured as a function of temperature'},

//     {label:'Reaction mechanism step analyser',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R2.2.6-7: Reaction mechanisms and rate-determining step',scene:'An energy profile diagram for a multi-step mechanism. Each step shown as a valley (intermediate) or peak (transition state). Students identify the rate-determining step as the highest energy barrier. Consistency check verifies that the sum of elementary steps gives the overall equation. Intermediate vs transition state labelled.',sliders:['Number of elementary steps (0=One step → 4=Three steps with two intermediates)','Rate-determining step position (0=First step slowest → 4=Last step slowest)','Intermediate stability (0=Very unstable — high energy valley → 4=Stable — deep valley)','Mechanism type (0=SN1 two-step → 4=Complex multi-step)'],resources:['Rate-determining step identified (variable)','Rate law predicted from RDS (variable)','Intermediate species name (variable)','Transition state at RDS (variable)','Overall equation consistency check (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the rate law is determined by the slow step — the rate-determining step — not the overall stoichiometry. A two-step mechanism where step 1 is slow gives a rate law containing only the reactants of step 1 even if step 2 involves more species. Intermediates appear in valleys; transition states at peaks. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.2.6-7 HL.',real:'SN1 reaction of tertiary halogenoalkane — first step ionisation is RDS, Catalytic converter mechanism — platinum surface intermediate, Ozone depletion mechanism — Cl radical as intermediate not consumed, Acid catalysis — protonation intermediate lowers RDS activation energy'},

//     {label:'Le Chatelier principle — equilibrium stress simulator',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Systems, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R2.3.4: Le Chatelier principle',scene:'An animated equilibrium system showing the N2 + 3H2 reversible 2NH3 reaction or other choices. Concentration bars for each species shown at equilibrium. Student applies a stress — add N2, increase pressure, decrease temperature, add catalyst. Bars animate shifting to new equilibrium. The system always minimises the effect of the change.',sliders:['Equilibrium system (0=Haber N2+3H2 = 2NH3 → 4=N2O4 = 2NO2 coloured)','Stress applied (0=Concentration change → 4=Temperature change)','Magnitude of stress (0=Small → 4=Large — dramatic shift)','Catalyst added (0=No → 4=Yes — reaches equilibrium faster same position)'],resources:['Equilibrium position before stress (variable)','Equilibrium position after shift (variable)','Direction of shift (forward/reverse)','New equilibrium constant same or different (variable — only T changes K)','Time to reach new equilibrium (variable — catalyst reduces this)'],explain:'Students apply each type of stress and observe the system shifting to counteract the change — Le Chatelier principle. The crucial distinction: a catalyst reaches equilibrium faster but does not change the equilibrium position or constant K. Temperature is the only factor that changes K. Concentration and pressure changes shift position but not K. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.3.4.',real:'Haber process operating conditions — compromise between K and rate, Carbonated drinks releasing CO2 when opened — pressure decrease, Hemoglobin oxygen binding — high altitude shifts equilibrium, Industrial SO3 production contact process pressure optimisation'},

//     {label:'Equilibrium constant Kc — calculator and ICE table',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R2.3.2-3: Equilibrium constant Kc and ICE table',scene:'An ICE table (Initial Change Equilibrium) builder. Students enter initial concentrations and the equilibrium constant. The solver fills in the change row algebraically and calculates equilibrium concentrations. For HL students enter equilibrium concentrations and calculate Kc. Q vs K comparison predicts direction of shift.',sliders:['Reaction stoichiometry (0=1:1 simple → 4=Complex 1:3 stoichiometry)','Initial concentrations mol/L (0=Equimolar → 4=Large excess of one reactant)','Kc value (0=Very small Kc<0.001 — reactant favoured → 4=Very large Kc>1000 — product favoured)','Temperature C (0=Cold — Kc changes → 4=Hot — different Kc)'],resources:['Kc calculated from equilibrium concentrations (variable)','Reaction quotient Q at initial conditions (variable)','Q vs K comparison direction (variable)','Equilibrium concentrations mol/L (variable)','Percent conversion of limiting reactant % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that Kc depends only on temperature — not on initial concentrations or pressure for solutions. The ICE table provides a systematic method for calculating unknown equilibrium concentrations. Q compared to K immediately predicts which way a reaction will shift to reach equilibrium. Models IB DP Chemistry R2.3.2-3.',real:'Blood carbonic acid equilibrium — CO2 dissolved H2CO3 HCO3- H+ at specific K, Haber process K varies enormously with temperature explaining operating conditions, Solubility equilibrium Ksp for sparingly soluble salts, Protein denaturation equilibrium in cooking'},

//     {label:'pH and strong acid/base calculator',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Quantity',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R3.1.4-5: pH calculations for strong acids and bases',scene:'A pH calculator with a visual logarithmic pH strip showing colour from dark red (pH 0) through orange yellow green to dark blue (pH 14). Students input strong acid concentration and pH calculates instantly. The logarithmic scale is visualised — pH 3 is 10 times more acidic than pH 4 shown as expanding scale.',sliders:['Strong acid concentration mol/L (0=Very dilute 0.000001 → 4=Concentrated 1.0)','Acid type (0=Strong monoprotic HCl → 4=Strong diprotic H2SO4)','Strong base added mol/L (0=None → 4=Equimolar — neutralisation)','Temperature effect on Kw (0=25C standard → 4=60C — Kw changes)'],resources:['H+ concentration mol/L (variable)','OH- concentration mol/L (variable — Kw/H+)','pH = -log H+ (variable)','pOH = 14 - pH (variable)','Kw at given temperature (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the relationship pH = -log[H+] and that pH is a compressed logarithmic scale — small pH changes represent large concentration changes. At 25C Kw = 10^-14 fixes the relationship between [H+] and [OH-] and pH + pOH = 14. At other temperatures pKw changes so neutrality is not exactly pH 7. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.1.4-5.',real:'Stomach acid pH 1.5 — HCl concentration about 0.03 mol/L, Blood pH 7.35-7.45 — small change is life-threatening, Swimming pool pH 7.2-7.8 controlled carefully, Industrial wastewater pH regulation before discharge'},

//     {label:'Weak acid Ka and pH solver',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R3.1.10-11: Weak acid Ka and partial dissociation',scene:'An animated weak acid dissociation. A beaker shows HA molecules mostly intact with few H+ and A- ions — unlike strong acid where all dissociate. Ka expression shown. ICE table builds to solve for H+ concentration. pH calculated. Percent dissociation shown decreasing as concentration increases.',sliders:['Weak acid Ka (0=Very weak Ka=10^-10 → 4=Moderate Ka=10^-3)','Concentration of weak acid mol/L (0=Dilute 0.001 → 4=Concentrated 1.0)','Approximation check (0=Full quadratic → 4=Approximation — valid when 5% check passes)','Conjugate base concentration added (0=None → 4=Buffer conditions)'],resources:['H+ concentration mol/L (variable — from ICE table)','pH = -log H+ (variable)','Percent dissociation % (variable — increases with dilution)','pKa = -log Ka (variable)','Valid approximation? 5% check (variable)'],explain:'Students solve weak acid pH using an ICE table and discover that percent dissociation increases with dilution — more dilute solutions are proportionally more dissociated even though absolute [H+] is lower. The approximation [H+] equals sqrt(Ka times C) works when percent dissociation is below 5%. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.1.10-11 HL.',real:'Ethanoic acid in vinegar — 4-8% but only 1% dissociated, Carbonic acid in blood pH regulation — Ka controls CO2 equilibrium, Aspirin stomach irritation from acidic functional group, Industrial fermentation pH control by weak acid product'},

//     {label:'pH curve virtual titration',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'SL/HL Practical — R3.1.8: pH curves and titration',scene:'A virtual burette dripping titrant into a conical flask. A pH probe reads continuously. The pH curve plots live with each addition. Students can choose any combination of strong and weak acid and base. Equivalence point marked. Buffer zone highlighted for weak acid/strong base. Indicator choice panel with transition ranges.',sliders:['Acid type (0=Strong acid HCl → 4=Weak acid CH3COOH)','Base type (0=Strong base NaOH → 4=Weak base NH3)','Volume of titrant added mL (0=0mL before start → 4=Beyond equivalence)','Indicator chosen (0=Phenolphthalein pH 8-10 → 4=Methyl orange pH 3-5)'],resources:['Current pH (variable — updates with each addition)','Volume at equivalence point mL (variable)','pH at equivalence point (variable — depends on acid/base types)','Buffer zone identified (variable — for weak acid)','Indicator correct choice? (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that strong acid/strong base titrations give pH 7 at equivalence while weak acid/strong base give pH above 7 (conjugate base is basic) and strong acid/weak base give pH below 7. The choice of indicator must match the equivalence point pH — phenolphthalein for weak acid/strong base, methyl orange for strong acid/weak base. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.1.8.',real:'Blood type testing using colour indicators, Industrial neutralisation of acid waste before disposal, Pharmaceutical dosage — tablet neutralisation capacity, Winemaking pH control using tartaric acid and potassium hydroxide'},

//     {label:'Buffer solution designer',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Systems, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R3.1.16-17: Buffer solutions and Henderson-Hasselbalch',scene:'An animated buffer designer. Students select a weak acid and enter concentrations of acid and conjugate base. Henderson-Hasselbalch equation calculates pH. Then students add small amounts of strong acid or base and observe the tiny pH change compared to an unbuffered solution of the same pH. The two are shown side by side.',sliders:['Weak acid Ka (0=Ka=10^-10 very weak → 4=Ka=10^-3 moderate)','Acid to conjugate base ratio (0=10:1 acid excess — low pH → 4=1:10 base excess — high pH)','Amount of strong acid or base added mol (0=None → 4=Large amount — buffer breaks down)','Buffer capacity concentration mol/L (0=Dilute — low capacity → 4=Concentrated — high capacity)'],resources:['Buffer pH from Henderson-Hasselbalch = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]) (variable)','pH after acid addition (variable — small change)','pH of unbuffered solution after same acid addition (variable — large change)','Buffer capacity range pH units (variable — approximately 1 unit either side of pKa)','Fraction of buffer remaining (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that a buffer works best when pH equals pKa (equimolar acid/base ratio) and that buffering capacity depends on concentration — a dilute buffer resists small changes while a concentrated one resists larger amounts. The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation predicts exactly how pH changes with the ratio. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.1.16-17 HL.',real:'Blood buffer system: carbonic acid/bicarbonate maintains pH 7.4 with pKa 6.1 plus respiratory compensation, Shampoo buffered to near pH 5.5 to protect hair, Seawater carbonate buffer system and ocean acidification, Biological cell cytoplasm buffered by phosphate system'},

//     {label:'Oxidation state assignment tool',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Evidence, Change, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R3.2.1: Oxidation states and redox identification',scene:'A molecular or ionic formula input panel. The algorithm assigns oxidation states step by step — showing which rules apply in sequence: sum of oxidation states equals charge, oxygen is -2, hydrogen is +1, fluorine is -1. Each atom labelled with its oxidation state. Students identify which element is oxidised and which reduced in a reaction.',sliders:['Species entered (0=Simple NaCl → 4=Complex permanganate MnO4-)','Reaction displayed (0=Single species → 4=Full redox equation with change shown)','Step-by-step mode (0=Answer only → 4=Rule applied at each step)','Identification quiz (0=Told answer → 4=Student identifies OA and RA)'],resources:['Oxidation state of each atom (variable)','Oxidising agent identified (species reduced) (variable)','Reducing agent identified (species oxidised) (variable)','Change in oxidation state for each element (variable)','Is this reaction a redox reaction? (variable)'],explain:'Students apply oxidation state rules systematically and discover that in any redox reaction, the total increase in oxidation state (oxidation) equals the total decrease (reduction) — electron conservation. Identifying the oxidising and reducing agents requires recognising which species contains the element that changes. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.2.1.',real:'Rusting — iron oxidised from Fe(0) to Fe(+3), Bleach oxidising power — Cl from +1 to -1, Photosynthesis — C from +4 in CO2 to 0 in glucose, Breathalyser reaction — ethanol oxidised by dichromate which is reduced from +6 to +3'},

//     {label:'Half-equation balancer and cell builder',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Evidence, Change, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — R3.2.2: Balancing half-equations and overall redox',scene:'A two-panel display showing two unbalanced half-reactions. A guided step process walks through: balance the main element, add H2O to balance O, add H+ to balance H, add electrons to balance charge. The two balanced half-equations are then combined eliminating electrons. Overall equation automatically checked.',sliders:['Half-reaction 1 (0=Simple Fe2+/Fe3+ → 4=Complex MnO4-/Mn2+)','Half-reaction 2 (0=Simple halide oxidation → 4=Complex organic)','Medium (0=Acidic H+ solution → 4=Alkaline OH- solution)','Stoichiometric multiplier needed (0=1:1 → 4=5:2 — electrons must cancel)'],resources:['Balanced half-equation 1 (variable)','Balanced half-equation 2 (variable)','Electrons transferred in each (variable)','Multiplier to cancel electrons (variable)','Overall balanced redox equation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the systematic method for balancing any redox equation and find that the number of electrons lost equals those gained — conservation of charge. The multiplier needed to cancel electrons gives the stoichiometric ratio in the overall equation. This method avoids guesswork in balancing complex redox reactions. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.2.2.',real:'Titration of KMnO4 with iron (II) — MnO4- gains 5e- Fe2+ loses 1e- so 5:1 ratio, Electroplating calculations — moles of electrons deposited per mole of metal, Fuel cell half-equations for hydrogen and oxygen, Photosynthesis light-driven electron transfer — two half-reactions'},

//     {label:'Voltaic cell virtual lab',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Evidence, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'SL/HL Practical — R3.2.6: Voltaic cells and standard electrode potentials',scene:'Two half-cells — beakers with metal electrodes and electrolyte solutions — connected by a salt bridge (KNO3 soaked paper) and external wire with voltmeter. Students pick any two half-cells from a data booklet list. Electron flow animates through external circuit from anode to cathode. Ion flow shown in the salt bridge.',sliders:['Anode half-cell (0=Zn/Zn2+ — most negative E0 → 4=Cu/Cu2+ — more positive)','Cathode half-cell (0=Zn/Zn2+ less positive → 4=Ag/Ag+ — most positive)','Electrolyte concentration mol/L (0=Very dilute — Nernst deviation → 4=Standard 1.0 mol/L)','Salt bridge material (0=KNO3 → 4=KCl — may affect Ag cell)'],resources:['Cell potential Ecell = E cathode - E anode V (variable)','Anode electrode reaction (variable — oxidation)','Cathode electrode reaction (variable — reduction)','Spontaneous? Ecell positive = yes (variable)','Mass change at each electrode g (variable — anode dissolves cathode gains)'],explain:'Students predict cell potential from any two half-cell E0 values and confirm by virtual measurement, discovering that Ecell = E cathode minus E anode and that spontaneous cells have positive Ecell. The salt bridge maintains electrical neutrality — without it the reaction quickly stops. Changing concentration from standard conditions shifts Ecell (Nernst). Models IB DP Chemistry R3.2.6.',real:'Car battery — lead-acid voltaic cell, Zinc-carbon dry cell AA battery, Copper refining using electrolytic cell, Corrosion as an unwanted voltaic cell — iron and copper in salt water'},

//     {label:'Standard electrode potential and Gibbs energy',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Energy, Evidence, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R3.2.12-13: Standard electrode potential and delta G = -nFE',scene:'A data booklet E0 table displayed interactively. Students select two half-reactions. Ecell calculates automatically. Spontaneity assessed. Then delta G = -nFE converts to Gibbs energy. Students see how electrochemistry and thermodynamics connect — positive Ecell equals negative delta G equals spontaneous.',sliders:['Half-reaction 1 E0 V (0=Very negative -3V Li/Li+ → 4=Very positive +1.5V Cl2/Cl-)','Half-reaction 2 E0 V (0=Negative → 4=Positive)','Number of moles of electrons n (0=n=1 → 4=n=4)','Temperature K for Nernst equation (0=250K → 4=400K)'],resources:['Ecell = E cathode - E anode V (variable)','Spontaneous? positive Ecell (variable)','delta G = -nFE kJ/mol (variable)','delta G negative = spontaneous confirmed (variable)','Equilibrium constant K from delta G = -RT ln K (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the three-way connection between Ecell, delta G, and K: positive Ecell means negative delta G means K greater than 1 means spontaneous and product-favoured at equilibrium. The formula delta G = -nFE quantifies how much electrical work a cell can do in theory. This unifies electrochemistry and chemical thermodynamics. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.2.12-13 HL.',real:'Lithium battery — Li/Li+ has most negative E0 giving maximum cell voltage, Fuel cell theoretical voltage and efficiency calculation, Electroplating gold from solution — non-spontaneous requires external voltage, Hydrogen evolution overpotential in industrial electrolysis'},

//     {label:'Electrolysis product predictor',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R3.2.8-15: Electrolysis and competing reactions',scene:'An animated electrolytic cell with inert carbon electrodes and selectable electrolyte. For molten salts: straightforward cation to cathode anion to anode. For aqueous solutions: competing reactions shown at each electrode with logic for predicting the actual product. Concentration and electrode material sliders change outcomes.',sliders:['Electrolyte type (0=Molten NaCl simple → 4=Dilute CuSO4 aqueous complex)','Cathode material (0=Inert carbon → 4=Copper — dissolves in copper refining)','Anode material (0=Inert graphite → 4=Active copper anode)','Concentration of electrolyte mol/L (0=Dilute — water oxidised at anode → 4=Concentrated — halide oxidised)'],resources:['Cathode product (variable — metal or hydrogen)','Anode product (variable — O2 or halogen)','Logic for electrode product selection (variable)','Faraday calculation — mass deposited g (variable)','Energy required joules (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the rules for predicting electrolysis products: at the cathode the cation with the least negative E0 is preferentially discharged; at the anode concentration determines whether water or halide is oxidised. Concentrated NaCl gives Cl2; dilute gives O2. The Faraday calculation links charge passed to mass deposited. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.2.8-15 HL.',real:'Chlor-alkali industry — electrolysis of brine gives Cl2 NaOH and H2, Aluminium smelting Hall-Heroult process — molten cryolite electrolysis, Electroplating chrome on car parts, Copper refining — impure anode dissolves pure copper deposits at cathode'},

//     {label:'Radical chain reaction — halogenation mechanism',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — R3.3.2-3: Radical substitution and chain mechanism',scene:'An animated mechanism display. Three stages labelled: initiation (Cl-Cl homolytic cleavage by UV light shown with fish-hook curly arrows creating two Cl radicals), propagation (two steps: Cl abstracts H from CH4 creating HCl and CH3 radical; CH3 attacks Cl-Cl creating CH3Cl and new Cl), termination (any two radicals combine).',sliders:['Halogen (0=Cl2 — most reactive → 4=I2 — too slow endothermic)','Alkane complexity (0=Methane — one H type → 4=Propane — primary secondary tertiary H)','UV intensity (0=No UV — no initiation → 4=High UV — rapid initiation)','Chain length before termination (0=Short 5 cycles → 4=Long 10000 cycles)'],resources:['Ratio of products CH3Cl to CH2Cl2 to CHCl3 to CCl4 (variable)','Chain length before termination (variable)','Energy change at each propagation step kJ (variable)','Regioselectivity for branched alkanes (variable)','Rate of initiation relative (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that radical chain reactions produce mixtures because propagation continues until termination, and more propagation cycles mean more substituted products. For branched alkanes tertiary radicals are more stable and form faster giving higher proportion of tertiary substitution. Iodine does not work because the first propagation step is endothermic. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.3.2-3.',real:'Ozone depletion mechanism — Cl radical chain initiated by UV in stratosphere, Combustion of hydrocarbons — radical chain mechanism, Polyethylene production — radical addition chain polymerisation, Antioxidants in food — terminate radical chains stopping oxidation'},

//     {label:'Nucleophilic substitution — SN1 vs SN2 mechanism',concept:'Reactivity',related:'Change, Evidence, Form',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — R3.4.2 and R3.4.9: SN1 and SN2 mechanisms and stereochemistry',scene:'Two reaction pathways shown side by side. Left: SN2 — backside attack with simultaneous bond formation and breaking — the Walden inversion animation showing umbrella-flip. Right: SN1 — ionisation to flat carbocation intermediate then nucleophile attacks both faces giving racemic mixture. Energy profiles for both shown.',sliders:['Substrate type (0=Primary — SN2 only → 4=Tertiary — SN1 only)','Nucleophile strength (0=Weak — SN1 favoured → 4=Strong concentrated — SN2 favoured)','Solvent polarity (0=Non-polar — SN2 → 4=Polar protic — SN1)','HL: Stereochemistry shown (0=No stereochemistry → 4=Full inversion or racemisation)'],resources:['Mechanism type (SN1 or SN2 or mixed)','Rate law first or second order (variable)','Stereochemical outcome (inversion/racemisation)','Stability of carbocation intermediate for SN1 (variable)','Relative rate of reaction (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that tertiary substrates undergo SN1 because the stable tertiary carbocation intermediate forms readily; primary substrates undergo SN2 because the less hindered back face allows nucleophile approach. The stereochemical consequence is definitive: SN2 gives complete inversion (Walden inversion) while SN1 gives racemisation through the flat achiral carbocation. Models IB DP Chemistry R3.4.2/R3.4.9 HL.',real:'Thalidomide racemisation in body — SN1-like mechanism converts therapeutic enantiomer to toxic form, Enzyme-catalysed reactions — enzymes use SN2-like backside attack with precise stereochemistry, Drug synthesis — choosing SN1 or SN2 conditions to control stereochemical outcome, Nerve agent mechanism — irreversible SN2 at phosphorus centre'}
//   ]},
//   {icon:'🧬',name:'Biology',sub:'33 simulations · Themes A–D',topics:[
//     {label:'Cell structure and compartmentalisation — organelles and function',concept:'Systems',related:'Form and function, Unity, Interaction',lp:'Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 1: Cell biology',scene:'A eukaryotic cell cross-section with all labelled organelles visible. Students adjust slider to toggle between prokaryotic and eukaryotic. Endosymbiosis timeline shows chloroplast and mitochondria origin.',sliders:['Cell type (0=Prokaryotic → 4=Complex eukaryotic)','Metabolic activity level (0=Dormant → 4=Maximum activity — mitochondria glow)','Scale magnification (0=Light microscope resolution → 4=Electron microscope resolution)','Membrane permeability (0=Impermeable → 4=Freely permeable)'],resources:['Organelle identification score (variable)','Surface area to volume ratio (variable)','ATP production rate (variable)','Number of compartments visible (variable)','Endosymbiosis stage (variable)'],explain:'Students identify organelles and their functions, then discover why compartmentalisation allows specialised chemical environments impossible in an undivided cell.',real:'Antibiotic targeting of prokaryotic ribosomes, Mitochondrial disease and maternal inheritance, Chloroplast genome and plant evolution, Organelle dysfunction in lysosomal storage diseases'},
//     {label:'Enzyme kinetics — substrate concentration and inhibition',concept:'Systems',related:'Function, Regulation, Interaction',lp:'Inquirers, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 2: Molecular biology',scene:'An enzyme-substrate animation showing active site docking. Reaction rate vs substrate concentration curve builds. Competitive and non-competitive inhibitor molecules visible. Km and Vmax marked.',sliders:['Substrate concentration mM (0=Low → 4=Saturating — Vmax approached)','Competitive inhibitor concentration (0=None → 4=High — raised apparent Km)','Non-competitive inhibitor (0=None → 4=High — reduced Vmax)','Temperature °C (0=0°C — inactive → 4=45°C — denaturing)'],resources:['Reaction rate μmol/min (variable)','Apparent Km (variable — raised by competitive inhibitor)','Vmax (variable — reduced by non-competitive inhibitor)','Enzyme efficiency % (variable)','Substrate turnover rate (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the Michaelis-Menten curve shape and how different inhibitor types affect Km vs Vmax differently — the basis of drug mechanism identification.',real:'Statins competitively inhibiting HMG-CoA reductase, ACE inhibitors for blood pressure, Penicillin irreversibly inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis, Poison antidotes and enzyme protection'},
//     {label:'Mitosis — cell cycle, checkpoints and cancer',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Unity and diversity, Regulation, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 1: Cell biology',scene:'Animated cell cycle showing G1, S, G2, M phases with duration proportional. Chromosome movement in mitosis animated through prophase to telophase. Checkpoint sensors glow green or red.',sliders:['Growth factor signalling (0=None — cell stays in G1 → 4=Strong — rapid progression)','DNA damage level (0=None → 4=Severe — G2 checkpoint arrests)','p53 tumour suppressor function (0=Mutated — no arrest → 4=Normal function)','Telomere length (0=Short — senescence → 4=Long — continued division)'],resources:['Cell cycle duration hours (variable)','Checkpoint 1 passed (G1/S — variable)','Checkpoint 2 passed (G2/M — variable)','Chromosome segregation accuracy % (variable)','Cancer risk index (variable — rises when checkpoints fail)'],explain:'Students discover how checkpoints prevent damaged cells from dividing and why mutations in p53 and checkpoint genes lead to uncontrolled cancer cell proliferation.',real:'Cancer chemotherapy targeting rapidly dividing cells, p53 tumour suppressor mutations in 50% of human cancers, Warburg effect — cancer cells preferring glycolysis, Stem cell therapy for tissue regeneration'},
//     {label:'Meiosis and genetic variation — crossing over and independent assortment',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Diversity, Change, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 3: Genetics',scene:'Meiosis I and II animated with homologous chromosomes pairing. Crossing-over events shown as glowing exchange points. Independent assortment of non-homologous chromosomes animated. Gamete diversity counter.',sliders:['Number of chromosome pairs (0=1 pair → 4=5 pairs — human-like complexity)','Crossover frequency per chromosome (0=None — no variation → 4=Multiple crossovers)','Crossing over position (0=Near centromere — less effective → 4=Far from centromere)','Non-disjunction risk (0=Normal → 4=High — trisomy risk)'],resources:['Number of unique gametes possible (2^n × crossovers)','Genetic variation generated index (variable)','Recombination frequency % (variable — map distance)','Non-disjunction events (variable — Down syndrome risk)','Allele reassortment score (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate the extraordinary number of unique gametes produced by independent assortment alone (2^23 for humans), then see how crossing-over multiplies this further.',real:'Down syndrome trisomy 21 from non-disjunction, Genetic mapping using recombination frequency, Evolution of genetic diversity in sexual vs asexual reproduction, Identical vs fraternal twins genetic differences'},
//     {label:'Photosynthesis — light reactions, Calvin cycle and limiting factors',concept:'Systems',related:'Energy transfer, Function, Interaction',lp:'Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 2: Molecular biology',scene:'A detailed leaf cell cross-section — chloroplast with thylakoid membranes glowing. Light reactions shown in thylakoid. Calvin cycle as rotating enzyme wheel in stroma. Photosynthesis rate graph updates with each slider change.',sliders:['Light intensity W/m² (0=Dark — zero → 4=Saturating 1000 W/m²)','CO₂ concentration % (0=0% → 4=0.4% current atmosphere)','Temperature °C (0=0°C — enzyme inactive → 4=45°C — denaturation)','Chlorophyll concentration (0=None — variegated → 4=Maximum)'],resources:['Net photosynthesis rate μmol CO₂/m²/s (variable)','Cellular respiration rate (variable)','Net gas exchange (positive = net photosynthesis)','ATP and NADPH production (variable)','Light compensation point (reached yes/no)'],explain:'Students discover the three limiting factors of photosynthesis and find the compensation point by adjusting each variable independently.',real:'C4 plants adapted to high temperature and light, LED grow-light wavelength selection for vertical farming, Ocean phytoplankton and global carbon fixation, Shade-tolerance adaptations in forest understorey plants'},
//     {label:'Cellular respiration — glycolysis, Krebs cycle and ATP yield',concept:'Systems',related:'Energy transfer, Function, Interaction',lp:'Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 2: Molecular biology',scene:'Energy accounting simulation — a glucose molecule enters at the top. Glycolysis in cytoplasm yields 2 ATP. Krebs cycle in mitochondrial matrix produces reduced carriers. ETC on inner mitochondrial membrane generates bulk ATP.',sliders:['Oxygen availability (0=Anaerobic — glycolysis only → 4=Aerobic — full oxidation)','Glucose concentration (0=Low — minimal ATP → 4=High — maximum rate)','Temperature °C (0=Cold — slow enzymes → 4=Optimal 37°C)','Inhibitor type (0=None → 4=Cyanide — blocks ETC completely)'],resources:['ATP produced per glucose (2 anaerobic, ~36-38 aerobic)','Metabolic pathway active (glycolysis/Krebs/ETC)','Lactate produced (anaerobic only)','NADH and FADH₂ produced (variable)','Oxygen consumed μmol/min (variable)'],explain:'Students trace carbon and energy through cellular respiration, discovering why aerobic respiration produces ~18x more ATP than anaerobic.',real:'Lactic acid build-up in sprinting muscles, Yeast fermentation for bread and brewing, Cyanide poisoning blocking cytochrome oxidase, Exercise physiology VO2 max and aerobic capacity'},
//     {label:'Mendelian genetics — monohybrid and dihybrid crosses',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Patterns, Evidence, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 3: Genetics',scene:'A Punnett square that fills in as genotype sliders change. Offspring phenotype ratios displayed as animated pie chart. Parents gamete production shown. Chi-squared goodness of fit to Mendelian ratio calculated.',sliders:['Parent 1 genotype (0=Homozygous dominant AA → 4=Homozygous recessive aa)','Parent 2 genotype (0=Homozygous dominant → 4=Homozygous recessive)','Number of gene loci (0=Monohybrid 1 locus → 4=Dihybrid 2 loci)','Inheritance pattern (0=Complete dominance → 4=Codominance or incomplete)'],resources:['Dominant phenotype frequency % (variable)','Recessive phenotype frequency % (variable)','Genotype ratio (variable)','Chi-squared value vs expected (variable)','Expected offspring per cross (variable)'],explain:'Students predict phenotype ratios using Punnett squares, then perform chi-squared analysis to test whether observed ratios match expected Mendelian ratios.',real:'Human ABO blood type inheritance codominance, Cystic fibrosis carrier frequency calculation, Dog coat colour inheritance, Plant breeding programmes for crop improvement'},
//     {label:'Membrane transport — diffusion, osmosis and active transport',concept:'Systems',related:'Form and function, Interaction, Regulation',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 1: Cell biology',scene:'A cell membrane cross-section with phospholipid bilayer visible. Concentration gradient arrows show solute movement. Aquaporin channels animate during osmosis. ATP-driven sodium-potassium pump cycles visually.',sliders:['External solute concentration mol/m³ (0=Hypotonic → 4=Hypertonic)','Membrane permeability (0=Impermeable → 4=Freely permeable — all channels open)','ATP availability (0=None — no active transport → 4=Abundant — max pump rate)','Temperature °C (0=Cold — slow diffusion → 4=Warm — fast diffusion)'],resources:['Net flux direction (variable — in/out)','Water potential difference (variable)','Cell volume change % (variable — swells or shrinks)','Rate of diffusion molecules/s (variable)','ATP consumed by pumps/s (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that osmosis is water moving down its own concentration gradient and that active transport requires ATP to move solutes against concentration gradients.',real:'Plant wilting when underwatered (loss of turgor), Kidney tubule reabsorption of glucose against gradient, Dialysis machine mimicking kidney filtration, Sports drink osmolarity and hydration'},
//     {label:'Ecosystem energy flow and trophic levels',concept:'Interaction',related:'Systems, Interdependence, Change',lp:'Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 4: Ecology',scene:'A food web with 4 trophic levels animated as energy flows with visible 10% loss at each level. Pyramid of biomass builds as energy flows. Decomposer and detritivore pathways shown.',sliders:['Primary productivity kJ/m²/year (0=Low — desert → 4=High — tropical forest)','Efficiency of energy transfer % (0=5% — low efficiency → 4=20% — high efficiency)','Number of trophic levels (0=2 → 4=5)','Human consumption level (0=Plant-based diet → 4=All meat diet)'],resources:['Energy at producer level kJ/m² (variable)','Energy at primary consumer level kJ/m² (variable)','Energy at apex predator level kJ/m² (variable)','Land area required per person ha (variable)','Carbon sequestration capacity (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate how energy loss at each trophic level limits the number of organisms that can be supported, and why plant-based diets require less land.',real:'Beef vs plant protein land and water use comparison, Amazon rainforest highest biodiversity and primary productivity, Ocean food web and fisheries yield calculation, Biofuel energy efficiency vs fossil fuels'},
//     {label:'Population genetics and Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Change, Patterns, Unity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Evolution; HL Topic 10',scene:'A gene pool pond with allele frequency bubbles in contrasting colours. Selection arrows deflect frequencies. Gene flow arrows enter from outside. Genetic drift shown as random swirls that intensify in small populations.',sliders:['Selection pressure (0=Neutral — HWE maintained → 4=Strong directional selection)','Population size Ne (0=Small 10 — drift dominant → 4=Large 10000 — drift negligible)','Mutation rate (0=None → 4=High — new alleles constantly entering)','Gene flow rate (0=Isolated → 4=Panmictic — open)'],resources:['Dominant allele frequency p (variable)','Recessive allele frequency q (variable — p+q=1 always)','Heterozygote frequency 2pq (variable)','Deviation from HWE expected (variable)','Evolutionary change per generation (variable)'],explain:'Students manipulate the five HWE conditions and observe how each violation causes allele frequency shifts away from equilibrium predictions.',real:'Sickle cell heterozygote advantage in malaria regions, Cheetah severe genetic bottleneck and disease susceptibility, Finnish disease heritage from founder effect, Peppered moth industrial melanism as selection evidence'},
//     {label:'Nervous system — action potential and synaptic transmission',concept:'Systems',related:'Form and function, Regulation, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'An animated neuron with resting potential shown as charge distribution. Stimulus triggers depolarisation wave travelling along axon. At synapse, vesicle fusion and neurotransmitter binding animated.',sliders:['Stimulus strength mV (0=Below threshold — no AP → 4=Strong — maximum AP)','Myelin sheath present (0=Unmyelinated — slow → 4=Fully myelinated — fast saltatory)','Neurotransmitter type (0=Inhibitory GABA → 4=Excitatory glutamate)','Refractory period duration (0=Short — high frequency possible → 4=Long)'],resources:['Action potential triggered (yes/no — all-or-nothing)','Conduction velocity m/s (variable)','Synaptic delay ms (variable)','Post-synaptic potential mV (variable)','Relative refractory period ms (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the all-or-nothing nature of action potentials, why myelination speeds conduction, and how excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmitters sum at the synapse.',real:'Multiple sclerosis demyelination and conduction failure, Local anaesthetic blocking sodium channels, SSRIs blocking serotonin reuptake in depression treatment, Pain gate control theory'},
//     {label:'Homeostasis — blood glucose regulation and thermoregulation',concept:'Systems',related:'Regulation, Function, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'Two linked simulations: left shows blood glucose level with insulin and glucagon response curves; right shows core temperature with hypothalamus thermostat control. Negative feedback arrows animate.',sliders:['Carbohydrate meal size g (0=None → 4=Large high-GI meal)','Exercise intensity (0=Rest → 4=Maximum — glucose consumed rapidly)','Pancreatic β-cell function (0=None — Type 1 diabetes → 4=Normal insulin secretion)','Ambient temperature °C (0=Cold -10°C → 4=Hot 40°C)'],resources:['Blood glucose level mmol/L (4-7 target range)','Insulin secretion rate μU/min (variable)','Glucagon secretion rate (variable)','Core temperature °C (36.1–37.8 normal range)','Glycogen stores in liver (variable)'],explain:'Students manage both blood glucose and temperature homeostasis simultaneously, discovering that diabetes (β-cell failure) causes blood glucose to escape the set-point range.',real:'Type 1 vs Type 2 diabetes pathophysiology, Insulin pump closed-loop artificial pancreas, Hypoglycaemia in endurance athletes, Heat stroke hypothalamus failure mechanism'},
//     {label:'DNA structure and semi-conservative replication',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Unity, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 2: Molecular biology',scene:'A DNA double helix unwinding as helicase runs ahead. DNA polymerase III building new strand. Leading strand continuous; lagging strand shown with Okazaki fragments. Meselson-Stahl density gradient result animated.',sliders:['Replication speed DNA pol speed bp/s (0=Slow → 4=Fast — 1000 bp/s)','Error rate and proofreading (0=No proofreading — high errors → 4=Full proofreading)','Number of replication rounds (0=1 → 4=4 — all generations tracked)','Isotope label type (0=¹⁴N light → 4=¹⁵N heavy — Meselson-Stahl)'],resources:['New DNA copies produced (variable — doubles each round)','Error rate per base pair (variable)','Fraction of original strand remaining (variable)','Replication fork speed (variable)','Density centrifuge band pattern (variable)'],explain:'Students verify semi-conservative replication by following the Meselson-Stahl experimental result, seeing that each daughter molecule contains one old and one new strand.',real:'PCR amplification cycles mimicking DNA replication, Cancer mutations from replication errors, DNA damage repair mechanisms and genome stability, Antibiotic rifampin blocking bacterial RNA polymerase'},
//     {label:'Transcription and translation — protein synthesis',concept:'Systems',related:'Unity, Function, Information flow',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 2: Molecular biology',scene:'RNA polymerase traversing a DNA template strand producing mRNA. mRNA then attaches to ribosome. tRNAs bring amino acids matched to codons. Polypeptide chain grows and folds.',sliders:['Transcription start signal (promoter strength) (0=Weak → 4=Strong — high gene expression)','mRNA codon chosen (0=Start AUG → 4=Stop codon — UAA/UAG/UGA)','Mutation type (0=None → 4=Frameshift — all downstream amino acids change)','Post-translational modification (0=None → 4=Glycosylation, phosphorylation)'],resources:['Protein production rate per minute (variable)','Amino acids incorporated correctly (variable)','Effect of mutation on protein function (variable)','mRNA lifetime before degradation (variable)','Ribosome attachment frequency (variable)'],explain:'Students trace the information flow from gene to protein, discover how frameshift mutations disrupt the entire reading frame downstream, and see how gene expression is controlled at the promoter.',real:'mRNA COVID-19 vaccine — synthetic mRNA and spike protein production, CRISPR gene editing correcting mutations, Antibiotic tetracycline blocking bacterial ribosome 30S subunit, Sickle cell disease single amino acid substitution'},
//     {label:'Population ecology — logistic growth and carrying capacity',concept:'Interaction',related:'Change, Systems, Patterns',lp:'Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 4: Ecology',scene:'A population growth graph showing sigmoid S-curve. J-curve exponential growth shown alongside for comparison. Carrying capacity K shown as horizontal asymptote. Population crashes shown when K is exceeded.',sliders:['Intrinsic growth rate r (0=Low r-strategist → 4=High r-strategist — rapid exponential)','Carrying capacity K (0=Low — limited resources → 4=High — abundant resources)','Initial population N₀ (0=Very small → 4=Near K already)','Density-dependent factor strength (0=None → 4=Strong — sharp crash above K)'],resources:['Population at time t (variable — follows logistic equation)','Growth rate dN/dt (variable — maximum at N=K/2)','Distance below K (variable)','Overshoot beyond K if occurs (variable)','Oscillation amplitude (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that maximum growth rate occurs at N = K/2 (logistic equation dN/dt = rN(1-N/K)) and that populations crash when resources are exhausted above K.',real:'Easter Island human population collapse, Deer overpopulation without predators, Pest management intervention at population threshold, Invasive species population explosion without natural predators'},
//     {label:'Gas exchange systems — surface area and Ficks law',concept:'Form and function',related:'Systems, Interaction, Energy',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology; SL Topic 2',scene:'Alveoli and capillary interface animation showing oxygen and CO₂ gradient arrows. Fish gill counter-current system shown adjacent. Surface area visualised as folded membranes. Diffusion rate meter.',sliders:['Alveolar surface area m² (0=Collapsed — 10m² → 4=Normal — 70m²)','Diffusion membrane thickness μm (0=Thin — 0.1μm → 4=Thick — emphysema)','Concentration gradient for O₂ (0=Low — anaemia → 4=High — pure O₂ breathing)','Ventilation-perfusion ratio (0=Mismatch → 4=Perfect match)'],resources:['O₂ diffusion rate ml/min (Fick\'s law: rate = DA·ΔC/l)','CO₂ removal rate ml/min (variable)','Blood O₂ saturation % (variable)','Respiratory quotient RQ (variable)','Partial pressure O₂ in alveoli kPa (variable)'],explain:'Students apply Fick\'s Law of Diffusion (rate ∝ surface area × concentration gradient / thickness) and discover why emphysema, which destroys alveolar surface area, causes breathlessness.',real:'Emphysema alveolar destruction from smoking, High-altitude adaptation and haemoglobin affinity, SCUBA diving gas exchange at pressure, Lung surfactant and premature baby respiratory distress'},
//     {label:'Nutrient cycling — nitrogen and carbon biogeochemical cycles',concept:'Interaction',related:'Systems, Change, Global impact',lp:'Caring, Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 4: Ecology',scene:'An animated landscape showing the nitrogen cycle: atmospheric N₂ fixation by Rhizobium, nitrification, denitrification, and crop uptake. Carbon cycle alongside shows photosynthesis, respiration, decomposition, and fossil fuel emissions.',sliders:['Artificial fertiliser application kg/ha (0=None → 4=Excessive — eutrophication risk)','Nitrogen fixation by legumes (0=None → 4=Maximum — crop rotation with legumes)','Denitrification conditions (0=Well-aerated → 4=Waterlogged — high denitrification)','Fossil fuel carbon emissions Gt/year (0=Zero → 4=Current levels ~37 Gt/year)'],resources:['Soil nitrate concentration mg/kg (variable)','Atmospheric N₂O (variable — potent greenhouse gas)','Nitrogen runoff to waterways (variable — eutrophication risk)','Carbon cycle balance (variable — sink or source)','Crop yield productivity (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how human interference with the nitrogen cycle through synthetic fertilisers causes eutrophication, and how the carbon cycle is disrupted by fossil fuel combustion.',real:'Dead zones in Gulf of Mexico from agricultural nitrate runoff, Haber-Bosch doubling food production at environmental cost, Wetland drainage releasing stored carbon, Cow methane emissions and enteric fermentation'},
//     {label:'Hormonal system — endocrine signalling and feedback',concept:'Systems',related:'Regulation, Function, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'A stress response pathway — hypothalamus detects stressor, signals pituitary, which signals adrenal cortex to release cortisol. Cortisol feeds back to hypothalamus. Anabolic vs catabolic effects shown.',sliders:['Perceived stress level (0=No stress → 4=Extreme chronic stress)','Cortisol feedback sensitivity (0=Insensitive — Cushing\'s syndrome → 4=Highly sensitive — normal)','Hormone type (0=Peptide — cell surface receptor → 4=Steroid — nuclear receptor)','Diabetes insipidus simulation (ADH) (0=Normal ADH → 4=No ADH — massive water loss)'],resources:['Cortisol blood level μg/dL (variable)','Blood glucose level mmol/L (variable)','Immune function index (variable — cortisol suppresses immunity)','HPA axis feedback loop status (variable)','Hormone receptor binding % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the HPA axis negative feedback loop and why chronic stress (prolonged cortisol elevation) suppresses immune function and disrupts glucose regulation.',real:'Cushing\'s syndrome from cortisol excess, Addison\'s disease cortisol deficiency, Steroid hormone sports doping mechanism, Melatonin and circadian rhythm jet lag'},
//     {label:'Natural selection — directional, stabilising and disruptive selection',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Change, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Evolution and biodiversity',scene:'A population phenotype distribution curve that shifts over generations. Directional selection shifts the peak. Stabilising narrows the bell curve. Disruptive creates two peaks. Fitness landscape colour-coded.',sliders:['Selection type (0=Neutral drift → 4=Strong directional selection)','Selection pressure strength (0=Weak → 4=Intense — strong environmental pressure)','Number of generations (0=5 → 4=50 — clear pattern emerges)','Heritability of trait (0=Low — mostly environment → 4=High — mostly genetic)'],resources:['Population mean phenotype shift (variable)','Phenotype variance change (variable — narrows in stabilising)','Allele frequency change per generation (variable)','Fixation time for favoured allele (variable)','Extinction probability for disadvantaged (variable)'],explain:'Students observe all three modes of natural selection and discover how selection pressure strength determines how rapidly allele frequencies shift over generations.',real:'Peppered moth colour change during industrial revolution, Galápagos finch beak size variation, Antibiotic resistance selection in hospitals, Dog breed artificial selection extremes'},
//     {label:'Classification and phylogenetics — cladistics',concept:'Unity and diversity',related:'Patterns, Evidence, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Evolution and biodiversity',scene:'An interactive cladogram builder. Students add taxa and choose shared derived characters. The cladogram shape changes to reflect parsimony. Morphological and molecular data comparison shown.',sliders:['Data type used (0=Morphology only → 4=Molecular DNA — more accurate)','Number of taxa compared (0=3 → 4=8 taxa)','Rate of evolution clock (0=Slow — ancient divergence → 4=Fast — recent)','Convergent evolution present (0=None → 4=Strong convergence — misleads morphology)'],resources:['Number of shared derived characters (variable)','Most parsimonious tree score (variable)','Bootstrap support % (variable — confidence in clade)','Divergence time estimate mya (variable)','Molecular clock consistency (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how cladistics uses shared derived characters rather than overall similarity, and why molecular data often contradicts morphological classification.',real:'Whale reclassification as artiodactyls from DNA, Bat echolocation convergent evolution with dolphins, Human-chimpanzee 98.7% DNA similarity, SARS-CoV-2 phylogenetics and variant tracking'},
//     {label:'Circulatory system — cardiac cycle and blood pressure',concept:'Systems',related:'Form and function, Energy, Regulation',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'The Wiggers diagram — simultaneous plots of atrial and ventricular pressure, aortic pressure, and ECG. Valve opening and closing marked. Heart rate, stroke volume, and cardiac output calculated.',sliders:['Heart rate beats/min (0=Resting 60 → 4=Maximum exercise 200)','Stroke volume mL (0=Low 50mL — hypovolaemia → 4=High 120mL — trained athlete)','Systemic vascular resistance (0=Low — exercise → 4=High — hypertension)','Preload (venous return) (0=Low — dehydration → 4=High — lying supine)'],resources:['Cardiac output L/min (CO = HR × SV)','Systolic blood pressure mmHg (variable)','Diastolic blood pressure mmHg (variable)','Pulse pressure mmHg (variable)','Mean arterial pressure mmHg (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate cardiac output and observe how heart rate, stroke volume, and vascular resistance combine to determine blood pressure.',real:'Exercise training increasing stroke volume, Hypertension and cardiovascular disease risk, Cardiac arrest defibrillation restoring rhythm, Blood pressure measurement clinical significance'},
//     {label:'Immunity — innate and adaptive immune responses',concept:'Interaction',related:'Systems, Regulation, Diversity',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'An infection timeline: pathogen enters, innate response (neutrophils, inflammation) activates within hours, adaptive response (B cells, T cells) builds over days, memory cells formed. Antibody titre curve visible.',sliders:['Pathogen dose initial (0=Low → 4=High — overwhelming)','Prior vaccination status (0=None → 4=Fully vaccinated with memory cells)','Innate immune response speed (0=Slow — immunocompromised → 4=Fast — healthy)','Antibiotic administered (0=None → 4=Appropriate antibiotic)'],resources:['Pathogen load (variable — rises then falls)','Innate response activation time hours (variable)','Antibody titre units/mL (variable — primary vs secondary)','Memory cell formation (variable)','Time to clearance days (variable)'],explain:'Students observe the primary immune response\'s slow antibody production compared to the rapid secondary response from memory cells, explaining why vaccines work.',real:'COVID-19 primary infection vs vaccinated response, Autoimmune diseases from self-recognition failure, HIV evading immune recognition, Organ transplant rejection and immunosuppression'},
//     {label:'Epigenetics and gene expression regulation',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Change, Information, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Open-minded, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 7: Nucleic acids (AHL)',scene:'DNA wrapped around histones shown as beads on a string. Methylation and acetylation marks shown on histones. Chromatin state (open = active, closed = silenced) changes as modifications are added. Identical twin divergence animated.',sliders:['DNA methylation level % (0=None — gene active → 4=Fully methylated — gene silenced)','Histone acetylation (0=Deacetylated — chromatin closed → 4=Acetylated — open)','Environmental trigger (0=Normal → 4=Strong — diet/stress/toxin exposure)','Number of cell divisions with mark inherited (0=0 → 4=4 generations)'],resources:['Gene expression level (variable — 0 to maximum)','Chromatin accessibility (variable)','Epigenetic inheritance probability % (variable)','Phenotype affected (variable)','Reversibility of mark (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how the same DNA sequence can produce different phenotypes through epigenetic modification, and how some modifications are inherited across cell divisions.',real:'Identical twin epigenetic divergence with age, Famine during Dutch Hunger Winter — metabolic disease in offspring, PTSD and stress epigenetic marks, Cancer epigenetic silencing of tumour suppressors'},
//     {label:'Digestion — enzyme specificity and absorption',concept:'Form and function',related:'Systems, Interaction, Energy',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'A journey through the digestive tract following a mixed meal. Mechanical digestion shown in mouth and stomach. Specific enzymes appear at each location with their optimal pH shown. Villus absorption animation in small intestine.',sliders:['Meal composition (0=Simple sugars only → 4=Complex mixed meal — fat, protein, carbs)','Gastric acid production (0=Achlorhydria — no acid → 4=Normal — pepsin activated)','Surface area of small intestine (0=Reduced — coeliac damage → 4=Normal villi)','Enzyme function (0=All inhibited → 4=All enzymes optimal)'],resources:['Starch digestion completion % (variable)','Protein digestion completion % (variable)','Lipid emulsification and digestion (variable)','Absorption rate across villi (variable)','Time for full digestion hours (variable)'],explain:'Students trace each macronutrient through its specific digestive enzymes and discover why pH changes at each organ activate or deactivate specific enzymes.',real:'Lactose intolerance — lactase enzyme deficiency, Coeliac disease destroying villi and reducing absorption, Pancreatic enzyme supplement need in cystic fibrosis, Proton pump inhibitor reducing gastric acid'},
//     {label:'Viruses — structure, replication cycle and immune evasion',concept:'Unity and diversity',related:'Systems, Change, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 1: Cell biology extended',scene:'An animated virus particle (bacteriophage or enveloped animal virus). Attachment to host cell receptor shown. Lytic cycle: injection, replication, assembly, lysis animated. Lysogenic cycle: viral DNA integration shown.',sliders:['Cycle type (0=Lysogenic — dormant → 4=Lytic — active replication)','Viral mutation rate (0=Low → 4=Very high — RNA virus like influenza)','Host cell receptor match (0=No match — no infection → 4=Perfect fit)','Antiviral drug effect (0=None → 4=Full inhibition of replication)'],resources:['Viral copies per cell (burst size) (variable)','Time to cell lysis hours (variable)','Antigenic variation rate (variable)','Drug resistance emergence risk (variable)','Progeny viruses released (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why lytic viruses rapidly kill cells while lysogenic viruses can remain dormant for years, and why high mutation rates in RNA viruses (like influenza) challenge vaccine production.',real:'HIV latent reservoir in memory T cells, Influenza seasonal mutation and vaccine update, SARS-CoV-2 spike protein mutation and immune escape, Bacteriophage therapy as antibiotic alternative'},
//     {label:'Animal behaviour — innate and learned behaviour',concept:'Interaction',related:'Systems, Change, Communication',lp:'Open-minded, Thinkers, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 7 AHL: Physiology of behaviour',scene:'Side-by-side comparisons: a fixed action pattern in a bird (stickleback aggression) and a habituation experiment. Pavlovian conditioning bells and food. Operant conditioning Skinner box. Hawk-dove game theory matrix.',sliders:['Fixed action pattern trigger strength (0=No trigger → 4=Maximum releaser stimulus)','Habituation stimulus repetitions (0=Novel → 4=After 20 repetitions — habituated)','Reward schedule type (0=No reward → 4=Variable ratio — most persistent)','Social group size for cooperation (0=Solitary → 4=Large group — altruism possible)'],resources:['Innate behaviour frequency (variable)','Habituation degree — reduced response % (variable)','Learning acquisition rate (variable)','Evolutionarily stable strategy (variable — hawk vs dove)','Kin selection coefficient r (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how fixed action patterns cannot be stopped once triggered, how habituation reduces response to irrelevant stimuli, and why cooperation evolves through kin selection.',real:'Greylag goose egg retrieval FAP — irreversible once started, Pavlov dog salivation conditioning, Skinner variable reward schedule and gambling addiction, Honeybee waggle dance kin selection cooperation'},
//     {label:'Speciation — allopatric and sympatric mechanisms',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Change, Diversity, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Evolution and biodiversity',scene:'A geographic barrier (mountain range, ocean) appears between two populations of the same species. Allele frequencies diverge over generations through different selection pressures. Reproductive isolation test at various time points.',sliders:['Geographic barrier permeability (0=Complete barrier → 4=Permeable — gene flow continues)','Time since barrier formation generations (0=Recent → 4=Long — many generations)','Selection pressure difference between populations (0=Same environment → 4=Very different environments)','Speciation type (0=Allopatric — geography → 4=Sympatric — polyploidy or niche)'],resources:['Genetic divergence between populations (variable — Fst statistic)','Reproductive isolation level % (variable)','New species formed (boolean — after threshold)','Hybrid viability (variable — decreases over time)','Gene flow between populations (variable)'],explain:'Students observe how allopatric speciation requires geographic separation while sympatric speciation can occur through polyploidy in plants or divergent resource use without geographic isolation.',real:'Darwin\'s Galápagos finch beak divergence, Hawaiian honeycreeper radiation from single ancestor, Polyploid wheat species from hybridisation, Apple maggot fly sympatric speciation by host shift'},
//     {label:'Muscle contraction — sliding filament model',concept:'Form and function',related:'Systems, Energy, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'A sarcomere cross-section with myosin heads and actin filaments. Power stroke animation shows cross-bridge cycle. ATP binding causes head detachment. Z-disc to Z-disc distance changes with contraction.',sliders:['Calcium ion concentration (0=None — tropomyosin blocking → 4=High — all binding sites exposed)','ATP availability (0=None — rigor mortis → 4=Abundant — rapid cross-bridge cycling)','Load on muscle N (0=No load — isometric → 4=Heavy load — slow contraction)','Stimulation frequency Hz (0=Single twitch → 4=Tetanus — fused)'],resources:['Sarcomere length μm (variable — shortens on contraction)','Force generated N (variable — increases to tetanus)','ATP consumed per minute (variable)','Cross-bridge cycling rate (variable)','Fatigue time to onset s (variable)'],explain:'Students trace the cross-bridge cycle (attachment, power stroke, ATP binding causes detachment, re-cocking) and discover that rigor mortis occurs when ATP is depleted and myosin cannot detach.',real:'Rigor mortis ATP depletion post-mortem, Malignant hyperthermia anaesthetic reaction, Botulinum toxin blocking acetylcholine for medical cosmetic use, Statin myopathy from coenzyme Q10 depletion'},
//     {label:'Stem cells and differentiation',concept:'Unity and diversity',related:'Change, Information, Function',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 1 HL: Cell biology extension',scene:'A totipotency spectrum from zygote to differentiated cell. Each step shows gene expression changes (active genes glowing). Reprogramming arrows show Yamanaka factors reverting a cell to pluripotency.',sliders:['Differentiation state (0=Totipotent zygote → 4=Fully differentiated neuron)','Yamanaka factors applied (0=None → 4=All 4 — Oct4, Sox2, Klf4, c-Myc)','Tissue environment signal (0=No inductive signal → 4=Strong differentiation signal)','Epigenetic barrier to reprogramming (0=Low — early development → 4=High — adult somatic cell)'],resources:['Potency level (totipotent/pluripotent/multipotent/unipotent)','Genes expressed vs silenced ratio (variable)','Reprogramming efficiency % (variable — ~0.01% for iPSC)','Tumour formation risk (variable — c-Myc raises risk)','Time to differentiation days (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why differentiation is progressive and largely irreversible under normal conditions, and why reprogramming to induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) requires overcoming epigenetic barriers.',real:'Shinya Yamanaka iPSC Nobel Prize 2012, Human embryonic stem cell ethical debate, Bone marrow transplant for leukaemia — haematopoietic stem cells, Salamander limb regeneration from dedifferentiation'},
//     {label:'Ecological succession — from bare rock to climax community',concept:'Interaction',related:'Change, Systems, Diversity',lp:'Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 4: Ecology',scene:'A barren volcanic rock landscape. Pioneer lichens appear first. Mosses follow. Grasses colonise. Shrubs replace grasses. Finally climax forest establishes. Time slider moves through succession stages.',sliders:['Type of succession (0=Primary — bare rock → 4=Secondary — forest after disturbance)','Disturbance frequency (0=Stable — climax maintained → 4=Frequent fire — subclimax)','Climate conditions (0=Dry — slow succession → 4=Wet/warm — rapid succession)','Grazing pressure (0=None → 4=Heavy overgrazing — prevents climax)'],resources:['Biodiversity index (variable — rises then stabilises)','Primary productivity (variable — rises then stabilises)','Soil depth cm (variable — increases)','Biomass g/m² (variable)','Succession stage (pioneer/intermediate/climax)'],explain:'Students discover how pioneer species modify the environment making it suitable for later species, and why disturbance (fire, grazing) maintains subclimax communities.',real:'Krakatau island recolonisation after 1883 eruption, Yellowstone forest recovery after 1988 fire, Coral reef recovery succession after bleaching, Sand dune succession from marram grass pioneers'},
//     {label:'Kidney and osmoregulation — nephron function',concept:'Systems',related:'Form and function, Regulation, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 6: Human physiology',scene:'An animated nephron cross-section — glomerulus filtration shown, proximal convoluted tubule reabsorption, loop of Henle counter-current multiplier building gradient, distal tubule and collecting duct ADH control.',sliders:['ADH antidiuretic hormone level (0=None — diabetes insipidus → 4=Maximum — maximally concentrated urine)','Blood pressure and filtration rate (0=Low — minimal filtration → 4=High — rapid filtration)','Aldosterone level (0=None → 4=High — maximum Na⁺ and water retention)','Kidney disease severity (0=Healthy → 4=Renal failure — dialysis needed)'],resources:['Urine concentration mOsm/L (variable — 50 to 1200 range)','Urine output mL/hour (variable)','Filtered water reabsorbed % (variable — up to 99%)','Blood plasma osmolarity mOsm/L (variable — should be ~300)','GFR glomerular filtration rate mL/min (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how the counter-current multiplier in the loop of Henle creates the medullary gradient, and how ADH controls the permeability of the collecting duct to concentrate urine.',real:'Diabetes insipidus from ADH deficiency producing 20 litres urine/day, Kidney dialysis mimicking filtration and reabsorption, Camel kidney extreme water conservation, Sports drink electrolyte replacement and kidney regulation'},
//     {label:'Antibiotic resistance — evolution in a clinical setting',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Change, Interaction, Evidence',lp:'Principled, Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 5: Evolution and biodiversity',scene:'A hospital ward showing antibiotic treatment of a bacterial infection. Initial sensitive population treated. Rare resistant mutant survives and multiplies. Horizontal gene transfer plasmid passes resistance to other species.',sliders:['Antibiotic dose completeness (0=Patient stops early → 4=Full course completed)','Antibiotic type (0=Narrow spectrum → 4=Broad spectrum — kills gut microbiome too)','Horizontal gene transfer rate (0=None → 4=High — plasmid transfer between species)','Initial resistance allele frequency (0=Very rare → 4=Already present at detectable level)'],resources:['Sensitive bacteria population (variable — decreases)','Resistant bacteria population (variable — increases if antibiotic used)','Time to resistance fixation days (variable)','New antibiotic needed (boolean)','Patient recovery outcome (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that antibiotic resistance is an example of natural selection in real time — resistant variants have higher fitness in the antibiotic environment and rapidly fix in the population.',real:'MRSA methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus hospital outbreaks, WHO critical priority antibiotic-resistant pathogens list, Antibiotic overuse in livestock farming, Phage therapy as antibiotic alternative research'},
//     {label:'Human evolution — fossil record and comparative evidence',concept:'Continuity and change',related:'Evidence, Change, Patterns',lp:'Open-minded, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Evolution and biodiversity',scene:'A hominin timeline from 7 million years ago to present. Skull silhouettes change progressively — increasing cranial capacity, reducing prognathism. Molecular clock and fossil record compared side-by-side.',sliders:['Time period mya (0=Ardipithecus 7mya → 4=H. sapiens 0.3mya)','Evidence type (0=Fossil morphology only → 4=DNA molecular clock)','Migration hypothesis (0=African multiregional → 4=Recent Out of Africa single origin)','Interbreeding with other hominins (0=None → 4=Significant Neanderthal admixture)'],resources:['Cranial capacity cc (variable — increases over time)','Tool complexity index (variable)','DNA similarity to chimpanzee % (variable)','Neanderthal DNA in modern humans % (variable — 1-4% in non-Africans)','Estimated divergence date from common ancestor (variable)'],explain:'Students trace the hominin lineage using both fossil morphological data and molecular clock evidence, and discover that modern non-African humans carry 1-4% Neanderthal DNA from interbreeding.',real:'Denisovan DNA in Melanesian and Tibetan populations, FOXP2 language gene in Neanderthals, Homo floresiensis "Hobbit" island isolation dwarfism, Ancient DNA sequencing from 40,000-year-old bones'}
