//     {label:'Newtons laws — force, mass and acceleration',concept:'Motion',related:'Forces, Dynamics, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 2: Mechanics',scene:'An Atwood machine with two masses over a pulley, or a block on a frictionless surface. Real-time force diagram shows applied force, normal force, friction, and weight. Velocity-time graph builds alongside.',sliders:['Net applied force N (0=Zero → 4=Maximum 20N)','Mass of object kg (0=Very light 0.5kg → 4=Heavy 5.0kg)','Surface friction coefficient (0=Frictionless → 4=High friction 0.8)','Incline angle degrees (0=Horizontal → 4=Steep 45°)'],resources:['Acceleration m/s² (variable)','Net force N (variable)','Friction force N (variable)','Displacement after 5s m (variable)','Final velocity m/s (variable)'],explain:'Students verify F=ma by adjusting mass and force independently, observing the linear relationship. Predict acceleration before simulation runs.',real:'Car crash safety (crumple zones extend impact time), Rocket propulsion (exhaust thrust), Elevator acceleration feeling, Sports biomechanics'},
