//     {label:'Work, energy and power — conservation along a ramp',concept:'Energy transfer',related:'Forces, Transformation, Conservation',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 2: Mechanics',scene:'A ball rolling down a ramp with variable height and friction. Energy bar charts (KE + PE + heat) update in real time. Power output meter at the base. Students compare energy with and without friction.',sliders:['Ramp height m (0=Low 0.5m → 4=High 3.0m)','Mass kg (0=Light 0.2kg → 4=Heavy 2.0kg)','Friction coefficient (0=Frictionless → 4=High friction 0.4)','Ramp length m (0=Short → 4=Long — same height, more friction)'],resources:['Gravitational PE at top J (variable)','KE at bottom J (variable)','Heat generated by friction J (variable)','Speed at base m/s (variable)','Power at base W (variable)'],explain:'Students verify the work-energy theorem and conservation of energy, quantifying exactly how much PE converts to KE versus thermal energy with friction.',real:'Rollercoaster design height vs speed, Hydroelectric dam power generation, Bicycle braking heat, Sports — ski slope speed calculation'},
//     {label:'Gravitational fields and orbital mechanics',concept:'Fields',related:'Motion, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 10: Fields',scene:'A planet with visible gravitational field lines. A satellite in elliptical orbit with velocity and force vectors. Orbital parameters (altitude, speed, period) display. Escape velocity marker shown.',sliders:['Orbital radius from centre km (0=Low orbit → 4=High orbit)','Satellite mass kg (0=Small → 4=Large — same orbit)','Planet mass (0=Small — Moon-like → 4=Large — Jupiter-like)','Initial orbital speed m/s (0=Below circular → 4=Above escape velocity)'],resources:['Orbital speed m/s (variable)','Orbital period hours (variable)','Gravitational field strength N/kg (variable)','Escape velocity m/s (variable)','Total orbital energy J (variable)'],explain:'Students discover Kepler\'s laws empirically — T² ∝ r³ — and find escape velocity conditions. The inverse square relationship of gravitational field strength becomes tangible.',real:'International Space Station orbit, GPS satellite constellation design, Geostationary communication satellites, Voyager escape trajectory'},
//     {label:'Torque and rotational equilibrium',concept:'Motion',related:'Forces, Balance, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 2 HL: Rotational dynamics',scene:'A see-saw or lever system with multiple force vectors. Torque magnitude and direction shown for each force. The beam pivots until students find equilibrium. Animated rotation when out of balance.',sliders:['Force 1 magnitude N (0=0N → 4=100N)','Distance 1 from pivot m (0=0m → 4=3m)','Force 2 magnitude N (0=0N → 4=100N)','Distance 2 from pivot m (0=0m → 4=3m)'],resources:['Torque 1 N·m (variable)','Torque 2 N·m (variable)','Net torque N·m (variable)','System status (rotating/equilibrium)','Angular acceleration rad/s² (variable)'],explain:'Students find that equilibrium requires equal and opposite torques, not equal forces. HL students calculate angular acceleration for unbalanced systems.',real:'Crane counterweight design, Wrench mechanical advantage, Human musculoskeletal lever systems, Bicycle gear ratios'},
//     {label:'Special relativity — time dilation',concept:'Motion',related:'Patterns, Change, Space and time',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 1: Kinematics (SR)',scene:'Twin paradox animation — one twin boards a rocket at adjustable fraction of speed of light. Two clocks side-by-side show proper time vs coordinate time diverging.',sliders:['Relative velocity as fraction of c (0=0.01c slow → 4=0.99c near light speed)','Journey distance light years (0=1 LY short → 4=100 LY long)','Observer frame (0=Earth frame → 4=Rocket frame)','Number of journeys (0=1 → 4=10 round trips)'],resources:['Lorentz factor γ (variable — rises steeply near c)','Proper time on rocket years (variable)','Coordinate time on Earth years (variable)','Time dilation difference years (variable)','Age difference on return years (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate time dilation using t = t₀γ and discover that the faster the journey, the more time passes on Earth relative to the traveller.',real:'GPS satellite clock correction (SR + GR), Muon atmospheric decay observed at sea level, Particle accelerator high-energy physics, Sci-fi faster-than-light travel implications'},
//     {label:'Special relativity — length contraction and mass-energy',concept:'Motion',related:'Patterns, Transformation, Energy',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 1 (SR) HL extension',scene:'A ruler moving at relativistic speed appears contracted along direction of motion. Side view shows length vs velocity curve. E=mc² calculator panel shows rest energy and relativistic energy.',sliders:['Velocity as fraction of c (0=0.1c → 4=0.999c)','Proper length of ruler m (0=1m → 4=10m)','Rest mass kg (0=1kg → 4=1000kg)','Frame of reference (0=Rest frame → 4=Moving frame)'],resources:['Contracted length m (variable — decreases)','Lorentz factor γ (variable)','Rest energy mc² Joules (variable)','Relativistic KE J (variable)','Total energy E=γmc² J (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that length contraction accompanies time dilation, and that E=mc² represents an enormous rest energy — a 1kg mass contains ~9×10¹⁶ J.',real:'Nuclear fission energy release calculation, Particle accelerator kinematics, GPS relativistic correction, Antimatter annihilation energy'},
//     {label:'Angular momentum and rotational dynamics',concept:'Motion',related:'Energy, Conservation, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 2 HL: Rotational dynamics',scene:'A figure skater pulls arms in — angular velocity visibly increases as moment of inertia decreases. Conservation of angular momentum meter shows L = Iω = constant.',sliders:['Initial angular velocity rad/s (0=Slow → 4=Fast)','Initial moment of inertia kg·m² (0=Small — arms in → 4=Large — arms out)','Final moment of inertia kg·m² (0=Arms fully in → 4=Arms fully out)','External torque applied (0=None → 4=Strong braking torque)'],resources:['Angular momentum L = Iω (conserved)','Final angular velocity rad/s (variable)','Rotational KE J (variable)','Angular impulse N·m·s (variable)','Angular deceleration rad/s² (variable)'],explain:'Students apply conservation of angular momentum L = Iω to discover that reducing moment of inertia increases angular velocity proportionally.',real:'Figure skater spin-up, Neutron star formation and pulsar rotation, Helicopter rotor torque and tail rotor, Gymnast tuck position for faster rotation'},
//     {label:'Damped and forced oscillations — resonance',concept:'Motion',related:'Energy, Systems, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 4 HL: Wave phenomena',scene:'A driven spring-mass system with adjustable damping. Amplitude vs driving frequency graph draws in real time. Resonance peak appears at natural frequency. Under/over/critically damped curves shown.',sliders:['Damping coefficient b kg/s (0=Undamped → 4=Overdamped)','Driving frequency Hz (0=Much below resonance → 4=Much above resonance)','Natural frequency ω₀ rad/s (0=Low → 4=High)','Driving force amplitude N (0=Small → 4=Large)'],resources:['Amplitude at resonance m (variable — peak at ω=ω₀)','Q factor (variable)','Phase lag radians (variable)','Energy dissipated per cycle J (variable)','Resonant frequency Hz (variable)'],explain:'Students find the resonant frequency and observe how damping broadens the resonance peak and reduces its height. Heavy damping prevents resonance entirely.',real:'Tacoma Narrows Bridge resonance collapse 1940, MRI machine RF resonance, Musical instrument resonance, Building seismic dampers design'},
//     {label:'Ideal gas law and kinetic theory',concept:'Thermal physics',related:'Systems, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 3: Thermal physics',scene:'A container of animated gas molecules. Pressure gauges, volume indicators, and temperature thermometer visible. When volume decreases, collision frequency visibly increases.',sliders:['Pressure Pa (0=Low 50kPa → 4=High 400kPa)','Volume m³ (0=Small 1L → 4=Large 10L)','Temperature K (0=Cold 200K → 4=Hot 600K)','Number of moles n (0=0.1 mol → 4=1.0 mol)'],resources:['PV/nRT ratio (should equal 1.0 for ideal gas)','Average molecular speed m/s (variable)','Internal energy U J (variable)','Root mean square speed m/s (variable)','Collision frequency with wall (variable)'],explain:'Students verify pV = nRT by fixing two variables and changing the third, predicting the result before seeing it. Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution shown alongside.',real:'Weather balloon expansion as altitude rises, Car tyre pressure temperature dependence, Scuba diving gas laws and decompression, Aerosol can warnings about heat'},
//     {label:'Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution — molecular speeds',concept:'Thermal physics',related:'Patterns, Energy, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 3: Thermal physics',scene:'Animated Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution curve. The peak shifts right and flattens as temperature rises. A threshold velocity line shows what fraction of molecules have enough energy to react.',sliders:['Temperature K (0=Low 200K → 4=High 1200K)','Molar mass g/mol (0=Light H₂ 2g/mol → 4=Heavy Xe 131g/mol)','Activation energy threshold (0=Low → 4=High)','Gas pressure atm (0=Low → 4=High)'],resources:['Most probable speed vp m/s (variable)','Mean speed v̄ m/s (variable)','RMS speed vrms m/s (variable)','Fraction above threshold % (variable)','Average kinetic energy J (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how temperature affects the shape of the distribution — higher T shifts the curve right and increases the fraction of molecules above any given energy threshold.',real:'Haber Process temperature choice and Maxwell-Boltzmann, Atmospheric escape of gases from planets, Enzyme reaction temperature dependence, Combustion engine cylinder temperature'},
//     {label:'Thermal energy transfer — conduction, convection and radiation',concept:'Energy transfer',related:'Systems, Transformation, Environment',lp:'Thinkers, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 3: Thermal physics',scene:'Three-panel animation: left shows conduction through a metal rod with heat gradient, centre shows convection cells in a fluid, right shows blackbody radiation spectrum glowing from a hot object.',sliders:['Temperature difference ΔT K (0=Small 10K → 4=Large 200K)','Material thermal conductivity W/m·K (0=Insulator 0.1 → 4=Metal conductor 400)','Thickness of material m (0=Thin 0.01m → 4=Thick 0.2m)','Surface area m² (0=Small → 4=Large)'],resources:['Conduction heat flux W/m² (variable)','Radiation power emitted W (variable)','Stefan-Boltzmann emission W (variable)','Temperature of equilibrium K (variable)','Heat transfer rate W (variable)'],explain:'Students compare all three heat transfer modes and discover the inverse relationship between insulation thickness and heat flux for conduction, and the T⁴ relationship for radiation.',real:'Building insulation and energy efficiency, Thermos flask design, Earth energy balance and greenhouse effect, Solar panel thermal design'},
//     {label:'Specific heat capacity and latent heat — phase changes',concept:'Thermal physics',related:'Energy, Transformation, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 3: Thermal physics',scene:'A heating curve animation — temperature vs heat added graph with a flat region at melting/boiling point. Multiple materials shown side-by-side for comparison. Particle arrangement changes at phase boundaries.',sliders:['Material type (0=Ice/water → 4=Metal of choice)','Mass kg (0=Small 0.1kg → 4=Large 2.0kg)','Heat power added W (0=Low → 4=High)','Initial temperature K (0=Cold 200K → 4=Warm 350K)'],resources:['Current temperature K (variable)','Phase state (solid/liquid/gas)','Energy added total J (variable)','Time to reach boiling s (variable)','Specific heat capacity J/kg·K (fixed by material)'],explain:'Students identify the flat regions where latent heat is absorbed without temperature change, and measure specific heat capacity from the slope of the temperature-heat graph.',real:'Thermal mass in buildings reducing temperature swings, Cooking pasta and energy efficiency, Refrigerator evaporator coil phase change, Body temperature regulation and sweat evaporation'},
//     {label:'Blackbody radiation and Wiens law',concept:'Energy transfer',related:'Patterns, Transformation, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 11: Electromagnetic induction (advanced)',scene:'A glowing sphere whose colour shifts from dark red through orange to white-hot as temperature rises. The emission spectrum displayed alongside shifts peak wavelength leftward with increasing temperature.',sliders:['Surface temperature K (0=Warm 1000K → 4=Very hot 10000K)','Surface emissivity ε (0=0.1 reflective → 4=1.0 perfect blackbody)','Surface area m² (0=Small → 4=Large)','Distance from observer m (0=Close → 4=Far)'],resources:['Peak wavelength λmax nm (variable — shifts left with T)','Total power emitted W (P=εσAT⁴)','Intensity at observer W/m² (variable)','Colour of emission (variable — red to blue)','Stefan-Boltzmann power ratio vs reference (variable)'],explain:'Students verify Wien\'s displacement law λmax·T = 2.90×10⁻³ m·K and Stefan-Boltzmann law P = εσAT⁴ through experimental manipulation.',real:'Stellar temperature classification by colour, Incandescent vs LED lamp efficiency, Infrared thermal camera imaging, Earth\'s energy balance and climate'},
//     {label:'Entropy and the second law of thermodynamics',concept:'Thermal physics',related:'Change, Systems, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 3 HL: Thermodynamics',scene:'Gas molecules in a divided container. When divider removed, they diffuse spontaneously into the vacuum. Students observe the probability of spontaneous re-compression is astronomically small.',sliders:['Number of gas molecules (0=10 → 4=1000)','Initial energy J (0=Low → 4=High)','System boundary (0=Isolated → 4=Open)','Compression speed (0=Quasi-static → 4=Rapid)'],resources:['Entropy change ΔS J/K (variable — positive for spontaneous)','Probability of reverse process (variable — essentially zero)','Gibbs free energy ΔG J (variable)','Available work extractable J (variable)','Disorder measure (variable)'],explain:'Students see directly why entropy increases in isolated systems and why heat naturally flows from hot to cold — the statistical mechanics basis of the second law.',real:'Refrigerator requires work to move heat cold-to-hot, Heat death of the universe concept, Carnot engine maximum efficiency, Information entropy and data compression'},
//     {label:'Carnot cycle and heat engine efficiency',concept:'Thermal physics',related:'Energy, Systems, Efficiency',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 3 HL: Thermodynamics',scene:'A pV diagram of the Carnot cycle with isothermal and adiabatic stages highlighted. Work output shown as enclosed area. Hot and cold reservoir temperatures drive the efficiency calculation.',sliders:['Hot reservoir temperature TH K (0=Low 400K → 4=High 1200K)','Cold reservoir temperature TC K (0=Cold 200K → 4=Warm 600K)','Number of cycles per second (0=1 → 4=10)','Engine type comparison (0=Carnot ideal → 4=Real steam engine)'],resources:['Carnot efficiency η = 1 - TC/TH (variable)','Work output per cycle J (variable)','Heat absorbed from hot source J (variable)','Heat rejected to cold sink J (variable)','Real engine efficiency % (variable — below Carnot)'],explain:'Students discover why the Carnot efficiency is always less than 100% and depends only on reservoir temperatures. No real engine can exceed this theoretical maximum.',real:'Coal and nuclear power station thermodynamic efficiency, Combined cycle gas turbine power plants, Car engine Carnot limit and waste heat, Geothermal power plant efficiency'},
