//     {label:'Capacitors — charge, discharge and RC circuits',concept:'Fields',related:'Energy, Systems, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism',scene:'An RC circuit with a capacitor charging from a battery and discharging through a resistor. Voltage across capacitor and current graphs build in real time showing exponential curves.',sliders:['Capacitance C μF (0=Small 10μF → 4=Large 10000μF)','Resistance R kΩ (0=Small 1kΩ → 4=Large 100kΩ)','Initial voltage V (0=Low 3V → 4=High 12V)','Process type (0=Charging from dead → 4=Discharging from full)'],resources:['Time constant τ = RC seconds (variable)','Voltage at time t V (V = V₀e^(-t/τ))','Current at time t mA (variable)','Energy stored in capacitor J (½CV²)','Charge on plates μC (variable)'],explain:'Students measure the time constant τ = RC and verify the exponential charge/discharge equations. Predict voltage after a given time before simulation reveals.',real:'Camera flash capacitor rapid discharge, Defibrillator cardiac shock timing, Computer power supply smoothing, Touch screen capacitive sensing'},
//     {label:'DC circuits — Kirchhoffs laws and resistor networks',concept:'Fields',related:'Systems, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism',scene:'A circuit board with adjustable series and parallel resistor combinations. Current arrows animate through the circuit. Voltmeter and ammeter readings update. Power dissipation shown as heat glow on resistors.',sliders:['Resistor 1 Ω (0=10Ω → 4=1000Ω)','Resistor 2 Ω (0=10Ω → 4=1000Ω)','Circuit configuration (0=Series → 4=Parallel)','EMF of battery V (0=1.5V → 4=12V)'],resources:['Total resistance Ω (variable)','Total current from battery A (variable)','Current through R1 A (variable)','Current through R2 A (variable)','Power dissipated in R1 W (variable)'],explain:'Students apply Kirchhoff\'s junction and loop rules to predict current and voltage in complex resistor networks before simulation verifies.',real:'House wiring parallel circuit design, Christmas tree light series circuit failure, Car electrical system design, Variable resistor dimmer switch'},
//     {label:'Electromagnetic induction and Faradays law',concept:'Fields',related:'Energy, Transformation, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 11: Electromagnetic induction',scene:'A coil moving into and out of a magnetic field. EMF induced shown on a galvanometer. The faster the movement, the larger the deflection. Stationary coil shows zero EMF.',sliders:['Number of coil turns N (0=10 → 4=500)','Magnetic flux density B Tesla (0=0.1T → 4=2.0T)','Coil area m² (0=Small 0.01m² → 4=Large 0.1m²)','Rate of flux change — speed (0=Stationary → 4=Very fast)'],resources:['Induced EMF = -NΔΦ/Δt V (variable)','Magnetic flux Φ = BA·cosθ Wb (variable)','Direction of induced current (Lenz\'s Law)','Peak EMF for AC generation V (variable)','Energy generated per cycle J (variable)'],explain:'Students verify Faraday\'s law ε = -NΔΦ/Δt by changing each variable independently. Lenz\'s law direction is checked against simulation.',real:'Electric guitar pickup coil, Wireless phone charging induction, Credit card magnetic strip reading, Regenerative braking in electric vehicles'},
//     {label:'Magnetic force on moving charges and conductors',concept:'Fields',related:'Forces, Energy, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism',scene:'An animated charged particle entering a magnetic field region. The circular curved path shown. Radius of curvature updates with velocity and field. Fleming\'s left-hand rule visualised with animated hand.',sliders:['Particle charge q C (0=Proton charge +e → 4=Alpha particle 2e)','Particle velocity m/s (0=Slow → 4=Very fast)','Magnetic field strength B Tesla (0=Weak 0.1T → 4=Strong 2.0T)','Particle mass (0=Proton → 4=Alpha particle)'],resources:['Radius of circular orbit r = mv/qB m (variable)','Cyclotron frequency Hz (variable — charge/mass ratio)','Force on particle F = qvB N (variable)','Direction of force (right-hand rule)','Pitch of helical path m (variable at angle)'],explain:'Students verify r = mv/qB and discover that heavier particles curve less for the same charge-to-mass ratio. Connects to mass spectrometer operation.',real:'Mass spectrometer separating isotopes, Cyclotron particle accelerator, Aurora borealis electron spiral in Earth\'s field, CRT television electron beam deflection'},
//     {label:'Transformer — turns ratio, voltage and power',concept:'Fields',related:'Energy, Transformation, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 11: Electromagnetic induction',scene:'A step-up or step-down transformer with primary and secondary coils. Voltage and current meters on each side. Laminated iron core shown. Power conservation verified numerically. Heat loss for non-ideal transformer.',sliders:['Primary turns Np (0=100 → 4=10000)','Secondary turns Ns (0=100 → 4=10000)','Primary input voltage Vp V (0=12V → 4=240V)','Transformer efficiency % (0=70% real → 4=100% ideal)'],resources:['Secondary voltage Vs = Vp×(Ns/Np) V (variable)','Turns ratio Ns/Np (variable)','Secondary current A (variable — Ip/Is = Ns/Np for ideal)','Power input W (variable)','Power output W (variable — reduced by efficiency)'],explain:'Students verify Vs/Vp = Ns/Np for voltage and see how current transforms inversely. The national grid rationale (step up to reduce I²R losses) becomes clear.',real:'Phone charger step-down transformer, National Grid step-up 400kV transmission, Microwave oven high-voltage step-up, Welding machine high-current step-down'},
//     {label:'AC circuits with resistance, inductance and capacitance',concept:'Fields',related:'Energy, Patterns, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 11 HL: AC theory',scene:'Phasor diagrams for R, L, C components in an AC circuit. Phase relationships between voltage and current animated. Impedance triangle drawn. Resonance frequency shown when XL = XC.',sliders:['Frequency of AC supply Hz (0=Low 10Hz → 4=High 10000Hz)','Resistance R Ω (0=Small 10Ω → 4=Large 10kΩ)','Inductance L H (0=Small 0.1H → 4=Large 10H)','Capacitance C μF (0=Small 10μF → 4=Large 10000μF)'],resources:['Inductive reactance XL = 2πfL Ω (variable)','Capacitive reactance XC = 1/(2πfC) Ω (variable)','Total impedance Z = √(R²+(XL-XC)²) Ω (variable)','Phase angle φ = arctan((XL-XC)/R) (variable)','Current amplitude A (variable)'],explain:'Students find the resonant frequency where XL = XC and Z = R (minimum), and observe phase differences between voltage and current for reactive components.',real:'Radio tuner circuit LC resonance, Power factor correction in industrial motors, Signal filter design, MRI machine RF coil impedance matching'},
//     {label:'Hall effect and charge carrier determination',concept:'Fields',related:'Forces, Evidence, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 5 HL: Electromagnetism',scene:'A current-carrying semiconductor strip in a perpendicular magnetic field. Charge carriers deflect sideways. Hall voltage measured across the width. Sign of voltage reveals whether carriers are positive or negative.',sliders:['Current through sample A (0=Small 10mA → 4=Large 1A)','Magnetic field perpendicular B T (0=Weak 0.1T → 4=Strong 2.0T)','Carrier type (0=Negative electrons n-type → 4=Positive holes p-type)','Sample thickness m (0=Thin → 4=Thick)'],resources:['Hall voltage VH = IB/(nqd) V (variable)','Carrier concentration n /m³ (variable)','Direction of Hall voltage (variable — reveals carrier sign)','Hall coefficient RH = 1/nq (variable)','Carrier drift velocity m/s (variable)'],explain:'Students determine charge carrier type from the sign of the Hall voltage, and calculate carrier concentration from Hall coefficient measurements.',real:'Semiconductor device doping type determination, Current sensor in motor controllers, Magnetic field measurement in MRI machines, Touch screen position sensing'},
//     {label:'Radioactive decay and half-life',concept:'Nuclear physics',related:'Change, Patterns, Evidence',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 12: Nuclear physics',scene:'A jar of coloured balls representing radioactive nuclei. Each round, a fraction decays (changes colour). Decay curve builds on graph: N = N₀e^(-λt). Half-life marked on the curve.',sliders:['Initial number of nuclei N₀ (0=Small 100 → 4=Large 10000)','Decay constant λ per second (0=Slow 0.01 → 4=Fast 0.5)','Time elapsed seconds (0=Short → 4=Long — many half-lives)','Parent or daughter tracking (0=Parent decay → 4=Daughter growth)'],resources:['Number remaining N = N₀e^(-λt) (variable)','Number decayed (variable)','Half-life t½ = ln2/λ s (variable)','Activity A = λN decays/s (variable)','Fraction remaining % (variable)'],explain:'Students verify N = N₀e^(-λt) and measure half-life from the graph by finding when N = N₀/2. Predict remaining nuclei at any time before simulation calculates.',real:'Carbon-14 dating of archaeological samples, Medical isotope technetium-99m choice of half-life, Nuclear power station fuel depletion, Radon gas in homes building risk'},
//     {label:'Nuclear binding energy and mass defect',concept:'Nuclear physics',related:'Energy, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 12: Nuclear physics',scene:'A binding energy per nucleon vs mass number graph (Bethe-Weizsäcker curve). Selected nucleus highlighted. Mass defect calculated. Students predict binding energy per nucleon for chosen isotopes.',sliders:['Proton number Z (0=H 1 → 4=U 92)','Neutron number N (0=0 → 4=150)','Process type (0=Fusion of light nuclei → 4=Fission of heavy nuclei)','Comparison isotope (0=H-2 deuterium → 4=Fe-56 most stable)'],resources:['Mass defect Δm kg (variable)','Binding energy MeV (E = Δmc²)','Binding energy per nucleon MeV/A (variable)','Energy released in reaction MeV (variable)','Stability indicator (variable)'],explain:'Students read the binding energy per nucleon curve and discover why Fe-56 is the most stable nucleus, why fusion of light nuclei releases energy, and why fission of heavy nuclei releases energy.',real:'Nuclear fission energy in power stations, Hydrogen fusion in stars and the Sun, Nuclear weapon energy release comparison, Isobar stability and beta decay prediction'},
//     {label:'Fission and fusion — energy calculations',concept:'Nuclear physics',related:'Energy, Evidence, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 & 2 — Topic 12: Nuclear physics',scene:'Left panel: U-235 nucleus absorbing a neutron, fissioning into Ba and Kr plus neutrons and gamma rays. Right panel: D + T fusion producing He-4 plus neutron. Energy release calculated.',sliders:['Fission: U-235 enrichment % (0=Natural 0.7% → 4=Weapons grade 90%)','Neutron multiplication factor k (0=Subcritical <1 → 4=Supercritical >1)','Fusion: plasma temperature keV (0=Below ignition → 4=Above ignition threshold)','Confinement type (0=Magnetic tokamak → 4=Inertial laser)'],resources:['Energy per fission reaction MeV (variable)','Energy per fusion reaction MeV (variable)','Chain reaction status (subcritical/critical/supercritical)','Neutrons per fission (variable)','Plasma energy gain Q (variable — must exceed 1 for net energy)'],explain:'Students calculate Q-values from mass defects and compare energy release per kilogram for fission vs fusion vs chemical reactions.',real:'Nuclear fission power station design, ITER tokamak fusion reactor construction, Hydrogen bomb energy release, Radioisotope thermoelectric generator (RTG) for spacecraft'},
//     {label:'Photoelectric effect and photon energy',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Evidence, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 12: Nuclear physics; Quantum',scene:'A metal surface illuminated by light of adjustable frequency. Photoelectrons emitted only above threshold frequency. Stopping potential graph shows linear relationship with frequency. Einstein photoelectric equation illustrated.',sliders:['Photon frequency Hz (0=Below threshold — no emission → 4=High UV — high energy emission)','Light intensity W/m² (0=Dim → 4=Bright — more electrons, same energy)','Metal work function eV (0=Low — caesium 2.1eV → 4=High — platinum 5.7eV)','Applied stopping voltage V (0=Zero → 4=Sufficient to stop all electrons)'],resources:['Photon energy E = hf eV (variable)','Maximum kinetic energy of electron eV (KE = hf - φ)','Threshold frequency Hz (variable — φ/h)','Stopping potential V (variable — KE/e)','Photocurrent A (variable — proportional to intensity)'],explain:'Students verify Einstein\'s photoelectric equation KE = hf - φ and discover that intensity increases the number but not the energy of emitted electrons.',real:'Solar cell photovoltaic energy conversion, Night vision camera photomultiplier, Photosynthesis light-energy absorption, Burglar alarm light-sensor photodiode'},
//     {label:'de Broglie wavelength and wave-particle duality',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Evidence, Patterns, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 12: Nuclear and quantum physics',scene:'Electron diffraction rings compared side-by-side with X-ray diffraction from the same crystal. As electron energy increases, de Broglie wavelength decreases and rings shrink. Diffraction confirmation of wave nature.',sliders:['Electron kinetic energy eV (0=Low 100eV → 4=High 100keV)','Particle type (0=Electron → 4=Alpha particle — much shorter λ)','Crystal spacing d nm (0=Small 0.1nm → 4=Large 1.0nm)','Diffraction order n (0=First → 4=Fourth order)'],resources:['de Broglie wavelength λ = h/p m (variable — decreases with energy)','Momentum p = mv kg·m/s (variable)','Diffraction angle for 1st maximum (variable — nλ = 2d·sinθ)','Ratio λ/d (determines visibility of diffraction pattern)','Resolution achievable m (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate de Broglie wavelengths and verify that electrons produce identical diffraction patterns to X-rays when λ matches crystal spacing.',real:'Electron microscope atomic resolution imaging, Neutron diffraction for protein structure, Low-energy electron diffraction (LEED) surface analysis, Electron diffraction in electron microscope calibration'},
//     {label:'Bohr model and atomic emission spectra',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Evidence, Patterns, Energy',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Topic 12: Nuclear and quantum physics',scene:'Hydrogen atom with electron energy levels shown as horizontal lines. Electrons make transitions between levels as photons are absorbed or emitted. Spectral lines appear in the correct visible spectrum colours.',sliders:['Electron initial level n_i (0=n=1 ground state → 4=n=5 excited state)','Electron final level n_f (0=Drops to n=1 → 4=Drops to n=2)','Atomic species (0=Hydrogen — simple → 4=Helium — more complex)','Observation type (0=Emission spectrum → 4=Absorption spectrum)'],resources:['Photon energy emitted/absorbed eV (variable — E = hf)','Wavelength of photon nm (variable)','Series type (Lyman/Balmer/Paschen)','Frequency Hz (variable)','Colour of spectral line (variable)'],explain:'Students predict spectral lines using En = -13.6/n² eV for hydrogen and verify by comparing to the simulation spectrum. Explains why only certain wavelengths are absorbed/emitted.',real:'Spectroscopy identification of elements in distant stars, Neon and sodium street lamp colours, Laser wavelength selection from energy levels, Stellar hydrogen Balmer absorption lines'},
//     {label:'Quantum tunnelling and Heisenberg uncertainty',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Evidence, Change, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 12 HL: Quantum and nuclear extension',scene:'A particle wavefunction approaching a potential energy barrier. The wavefunction decays exponentially within the barrier and emerges on the other side. Transmission probability shown vs barrier width and height.',sliders:['Barrier height relative to particle energy (0=Below barrier — classical pass → 4=Much above — classical forbidden)','Barrier width nm (0=Very thin → 4=Thick — exponential decrease in tunnelling)','Particle mass (0=Electron — high tunnelling → 4=Proton — low tunnelling)','Particle energy relative to barrier (0=Low → 4=Just below barrier height)'],resources:['Transmission probability T (variable — exponential with width)','Reflection probability R = 1-T (variable)','Decay constant κ inside barrier (variable)','Uncertainty in position Δx m (variable)','Momentum uncertainty Δp from ΔxΔp≥ℏ/2 (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that quantum tunnelling allows particles to pass through barriers forbidden to them classically, with probability decreasing exponentially with barrier thickness.',real:'Scanning tunnelling microscope atom imaging, Nuclear alpha decay tunnelling through Coulomb barrier, Tunnel diode electronics, Fusion in stars at temperatures too low classically'},
//     {label:'Pair production and annihilation',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Energy, Evidence, Transformation',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 12 HL: Particle and nuclear physics',scene:'A high-energy gamma-ray photon creating an electron-positron pair near a heavy nucleus. Energy conservation verified. Then pair annihilation produces two gamma rays. Momentum arrows ensure conservation.',sliders:['Gamma-ray photon energy MeV (0=Just above threshold 1.022MeV → 4=Very high energy 10MeV)','Excess energy above threshold MeV (0=Zero → 4=Large — both particles very energetic)','Pair separation distance (0=Created close → 4=Travel far apart)','Proximity of heavy nucleus for momentum (required for conservation)'],resources:['Threshold photon energy MeV (1.022 MeV = 2×0.511)','KE of electron MeV (variable — half of excess)','KE of positron MeV (variable — half of excess)','Annihilation photon energy MeV (2×0.511 minimum)','Momentum conservation verified (boolean)'],explain:'Students verify that E_photon ≥ 2m_e·c² = 1.022 MeV for pair production to occur, and that annihilation produces two 0.511 MeV photons traveling in opposite directions.',real:'PET scan positron emission tomography medical imaging, Gamma-ray burst pair production in extreme astrophysical environments, Particle detector pair production events, Antimatter production at CERN'},
//     {label:'Quark model and the Standard Model',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Systems, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 12 HL: Particle physics',scene:'An interactive quark composition builder. Students drag up, down, and strange quarks to build baryons (proton, neutron) and mesons. Charge and strangeness conservation checked after assembly.',sliders:['Quark combination (0=uud proton → 4=udd neutron and others)','Baryon vs meson (0=Baryon 3 quarks → 4=Meson quark-antiquark)','Quark flavour (0=up/down only → 4=Including strange quark)','Interaction type (0=Strong → 4=Weak — quark flavour change)'],resources:['Total electric charge (must be integer)','Baryon number B (variable)','Strangeness S (variable)','Is this particle real? (boolean)','Decay products if unstable (variable)'],explain:'Students construct valid hadrons and verify conservation laws. Discover that protons (uud) have charge +1 and neutrons (udd) have charge 0 from quark content.',real:'CERN LHC quark-gluon plasma research, Proton structure deep inelastic scattering, Neutrino detection in ice at IceCube observatory, Higgs boson discovery 2012'},
//     {label:'X-ray and Compton scattering',concept:'Nuclear and quantum',related:'Evidence, Energy, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Topic 12 HL: Quantum physics extension',scene:'An X-ray photon scattering off a loosely-bound electron. The scattered photon direction and wavelength change shown. Wavelength shift Δλ plotted against scattering angle θ.',sliders:['Scattering angle θ degrees (0=Forward — zero shift → 4=Backscatter 180° — maximum shift)','Initial photon energy keV (0=Low 10keV → 4=High 200keV)','Target material (0=Graphite light atoms → 4=Heavy atoms — less electron momentum)','Photon polarisation (0=Unpolarised → 4=Polarised)'],resources:['Wavelength shift Δλ = λc(1-cosθ) pm (variable)','Compton wavelength λc = h/(mec) = 2.43pm (constant)','Scattered photon energy keV (variable — reduced)','Electron recoil energy keV (variable)','Scattering cross-section (variable)'],explain:'Students verify Δλ = (h/m_ec)(1-cosθ) and observe that X-ray scattering shows both wave behaviour (diffraction) and particle behaviour (energy shift) — wave-particle duality.',real:'Medical X-ray imaging energy selection, Gamma-ray telescope Compton scattering detection, X-ray Compton spectrometer soil analysis, Astrophysical Compton scattering in active galactic nuclei'}
