//   {icon:'🌱',name:'ESS',sub:'30 simulations · Topics 1–8 + HL',topics:[
//     {label:'Systems diagrams — storages, flows and feedback loops',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Flows, Feedback, Equilibrium',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 1.2: Systems; Tool 4: Systems and Models (1.2.3, 1.2.8, 1.2.10)',scene:'An interactive systems diagram builder. Storages appear as labelled boxes; flows as animated arrows. Positive feedback loops glow red; negative feedback glow blue. The Daisyworld model shows temperature self-regulation through albedo change as daisy populations shift.',sliders:['System input disturbance (0=Minimal → 4=Maximum — large perturbation)','Negative feedback strength (0=None — runaway → 4=Strong homeostatic correction)','Positive feedback intensity (0=Stable → 4=Runaway cascade activated)','System complexity (0=2 storages — simple → 4=8 storages — complex web)'],resources:['System equilibrium index (75)','Feedback loop balance (50)','Flow rate between storages (variable)','Storage deviation from baseline (0)','Resilience to perturbation (70)'],explain:'Students build and manipulate systems diagrams for any ESS topic — ecosystems, soil, carbon cycle, hydrological cycle, urban systems — adjusting inputs and observing how storages change and feedback loops respond. Models the Daisyworld negative feedback system and Gaia hypothesis directly. Addresses IB ESS Tools 4 skills: construct and interpret systems diagrams.',real:'Daisyworld temperature self-regulation model, Gaia hypothesis Earth as integrated system, Arctic ice-albedo positive feedback loop, Nutrient cycle storage and flow in tropical rainforest'},

//     {label:'Population growth models — J-curve, S-curve and boom-and-bust',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Biodiversity, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 2.1.12: Population growth curves; Topic 8.1.4: UN three-scenario projections',scene:'An animated habitat with a growing species population. Exponential J-curve first — population shoots upward. Then logistic S-curve emerges as carrying capacity K is approached. Boom-and-bust oscillations appear when K is exceeded. Predator-prey counter-cycle animated alongside the main population graph.',sliders:['Intrinsic growth rate r (0=Very low — stable → 4=Very high — rapid exponential)','Carrying capacity K of environment (0=Low resource scarce → 4=High abundant resources)','Density-dependent limiting factor strength (0=None — no brake on growth → 4=Strong — sharp S-curve)','Predator population pressure (0=None → 4=High — drives boom-bust cycle)'],resources:['Population size N (variable — follows logistic equation)','Growth rate dN/dt (maximum at N=K/2)','Overshoot above K (0 — rises when limit exceeded)','Recovery time after crash years (variable)','Carrying capacity gap remaining (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why the J-curve becomes an S-curve when density-dependent limiting factors activate at high population densities, and experience the boom-and-bust cycle when populations overshoot K. Directly models IB ESS 2.1.12 and the three UN population projection scenarios used in 8.1.4.',real:'Easter Island human population overshoot and collapse, Reindeer introduction to St Matthew Island — boom then crash, Lynx-hare 10-year oscillation, UN low-medium-high scenario projections to 2100'},

//     {label:'Predator-prey models and food web stability',concept:'Interaction',related:'Biodiversity, Systems, Balance',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 2.1.9: Predator-prey models; Topic 2.2.8: Food webs from given data',scene:'An animated grassland ecosystem. Prey (rabbits) multiply in foreground; predators (foxes) chase them. Population counters oscillate in opposite phase. Food web arrows glow showing energy transfer direction. Remove the apex predator and watch the trophic cascade unfold.',sliders:['Prey birth rate (0=Very low — prey declines → 4=High — prey boom)','Predation efficiency (0=Poor — predators starve → 4=Highly efficient — prey crash)','Habitat carrying capacity (0=Low → 4=High — supports larger populations)','Trophic levels in food web (0=Producer-consumer only → 4=Five-level food web)'],resources:['Prey population (variable — oscillates)','Predator population (variable — lags prey)','Food web stability index (65)','Energy loss per trophic level % (90)','Apex predator extinction risk (low — variable)'],explain:'Students observe the classic predator-prey oscillation where prey peaks before predators, and discover that removing the apex predator causes prey explosion and vegetation collapse — the trophic cascade. Directly addresses IB ESS 2.1.9 predator-prey models and 2.2.8 constructing food webs.',real:'Yellowstone wolf reintroduction 1995 and elk trophic cascade, Lynx-snowshoe hare Canadian boreal cycle, Grand Banks cod collapse from overfishing, Sea otter-urchin-kelp cascade in Pacific'},

//     {label:'Energy flow and pyramids — numbers, biomass and energy',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Flows, Biodiversity, Energy',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 2.2.9: Pyramids; Topic 2.2.15: Efficiency of energy transfer calculations',scene:'An animated energy flow diagram. Gross primary productivity at the producer level. Energy arrows flow upward shrinking by approximately 90% at each trophic level. Three parallel pyramid displays show numbers, biomass, and energy side by side. Students can invert numbers pyramid by choosing parasites.',sliders:['Gross Primary Productivity GPP kJ/m2/year (0=Low desert 200 → 4=High rainforest 9000)','Energy transfer efficiency % per trophic level (0=5% very low → 4=20% high)','Number of trophic levels (0=2 → 4=5)','Net to Gross productivity ratio NPP/GPP (0=Low — high respiration → 4=High — efficient producers)'],resources:['NPP kJ/m2/year (GPP minus respiration)','Energy at herbivore level kJ (variable)','Energy at primary carnivore level kJ (variable)','Energy at apex level kJ (variable)','Number of apex consumers supported (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate energy availability at each trophic level using the 10% rule and discover why food chains rarely exceed 4 to 5 links. They build all three pyramid types from the same ecosystem data and explain why pyramids of energy cannot be inverted unlike pyramids of numbers.',real:'Tropical rainforest vs Arctic tundra GPP comparison, Agricultural ecosystem energy efficiency — plant-based diets need less land, Open ocean productivity paradox — low biomass but high turnover, Decomposer pathway energy compared to grazing pathway'},

//     {label:'Biogeochemical cycles — carbon and nitrogen systems diagrams',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Flows, Change, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Caring, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 2.3.4: Carbon cycle diagram; Topic 2.3.17: Nitrogen cycle diagram',scene:'A split-screen diagram. Left: carbon cycle with atmosphere, ocean, soil, biota and fossil fuel stores. Right: nitrogen cycle with fixation, nitrification, denitrification pathways. Animated flow arrows. Human interference sliders shift arrow thicknesses to show anthropogenic disruption.',sliders:['Fossil fuel combustion rate Gt C/year (0=Zero carbon economy → 4=Current 10+ Gt C/year)','Deforestation and land use change (0=Active reforestation → 4=Maximum deforestation rate)','Nitrogen fixation from fertiliser application (0=None → 4=Haber-Bosch maximum synthetic fertiliser)','Denitrification conditions — soil waterlogging (0=Well-aerated → 4=Waterlogged — N2O release)'],resources:['Atmospheric CO2 ppm (280 pre-industrial baseline — rises)','Ocean carbon sink uptake Gt/year (variable — declining with acidification)','Soil nitrate concentration mg/kg (variable)','N2O atmospheric concentration ppb (variable — potent GHG)','Eutrophication risk index (variable)'],explain:'Students manipulate human interference with both cycles simultaneously, discovering the interconnections — burning fossil fuels disrupts carbon; synthetic fertilisers disrupt nitrogen; both create atmospheric greenhouse gases. Directly builds the systems diagram skill required in IB ESS Topics 2.3.4 and 2.3.17.',real:'Great Acceleration post-1950 simultaneous disruption of C and N cycles, Haber-Bosch process nitrogen fixation feeds 50% of world population, Dead zones in Gulf of Mexico from agricultural runoff, Amazon deforestation converting carbon sink to source'},

//     {label:'Hydrological cycle — systems diagram and water footprint',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Flows, Sustainability, Human impact',lp:'Thinkers, Caring, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 4.1.4: Hydrological cycle diagram; Topic 4.2.11: Water footprint modelling',scene:'A cross-section landscape showing ocean, atmosphere, mountains, rivers and underground aquifer. Animated water molecules cycle through evaporation, transpiration, condensation, precipitation, runoff and infiltration. Water footprint calculator panel shows virtual water per food product.',sliders:['Land cover type (0=Dense forest — high evapotranspiration → 4=Concrete urban — rapid runoff)','Human water extraction from aquifers (0=None → 4=Severe overextraction — aquifer depletion)','Precipitation intensity mm/year (0=Drought conditions → 4=Heavy monsoon rainfall)','Diet composition (0=Fully plant-based → 4=High meat and dairy — large water footprint)'],resources:['Surface freshwater availability (80)','Groundwater aquifer level (75)','Annual water footprint litres/person/year (variable)','Flood risk from rapid runoff (variable)','Evapotranspiration rate mm/year (variable)'],explain:'Students trace water through the full hydrological cycle and calculate water footprints, discovering that 80% of water use is virtual — embedded in food production. Manipulating land cover reveals how deforestation converts infiltration to runoff, increasing flood risk while reducing groundwater recharge.',real:'Cape Town Day Zero 2018 groundwater depletion, Aral Sea death from irrigation diversion, Virtual water in food — 15500 litres per kg beef, Ogallala Aquifer US High Plains overextraction'},

//     {label:'Demographic transition model — age-sex pyramids and population momentum',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Development, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 8.1.7: Age-sex pyramids; Topic 8.1.8: DTM five stages; Topic 8.1.12: Gapminder',scene:'A live demographic transition model showing all five stages. As development sliders change, the age-sex pyramid morphs from wide-base pyramid in Stage 1 to column shape in Stage 4 to inverted pyramid in Stage 5. Birth rate and death rate curves trace the DTM shape in real time.',sliders:['Economic development index HDI (0=Pre-industrial 0.2 → 4=Post-industrial 0.95)','Infant mortality rate per 1000 births (0=Very low 3 — Stage 4/5 → 4=Very high 150 — Stage 1)','Female education and empowerment index (0=None → 4=Full gender equality and education)','Urbanisation rate urban to rural ratio (0=90% rural → 4=90% urban)'],resources:['Birth rate per 1000 population (variable — high Stage 1 falls Stage 3)','Death rate per 1000 population (variable — falls Stage 2 stays low)','Natural population increase % (variable — peaks Stage 2)','Dependency ratio % (variable)','Population momentum decades of growth remaining (variable)'],explain:'Students observe all five DTM stages and discover why countries in Stage 2 have the highest population growth despite falling birth rates — death rates fell first creating a gap. Age-sex pyramid morphs in real time. Directly models IB ESS 8.1.8 and connects to Gapminder database visualisation skill in 8.1.12.',real:'Niger Stage 2 high growth rate, India completing Stage 3 transition, Japan Stage 5 ageing and population decline, Bangladesh demographic dividend enabling economic growth'},

//     {label:'Maximum sustainable yield — fisheries management and harvesting risk',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Sustainability, Biodiversity, Change',lp:'Caring, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 2.2.26: MSY modelling; Topics 4.3.6-4.3.13: Yield-effort graph and harvesting risk',scene:'An animated ocean fishing scenario. A yield-effort graph builds in real time — yield rises then falls as effort increases beyond MSY. Fish population counter declines toward collapse at maximum effort. The MSY point flashes on the parabolic curve. Quota policy effects shown.',sliders:['Fishing effort intensity (0=Very low — well below MSY → 4=Maximum effort — stock collapse)','Quota enforcement effectiveness (0=No quota open access → 4=Strict science-based quota)','Environmental variability affecting MSY (0=Stable — easy to predict → 4=High variability — MSY shifts unpredictably)','Spawning habitat quality (0=Degraded → 4=Pristine and protected)'],resources:['Fish stock biomass tonnes (variable — declines above MSY)','Annual sustainable yield tonnes (variable — peaks at MSY)','Probability of stock collapse % (variable)','Economic return per vessel (variable)','Recovery time if fishing stopped years (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the counterintuitive result: harvesting at maximum effort produces less long-term yield than harvesting at MSY. The yield-effort graph shows why MSY occurs at half the carrying capacity. Environmental variability reveals why harvesting at exactly MSY is risky — small errors cause collapse. Models IB ESS Topics 2.2.26 and 4.3.6-4.3.13.',real:'Grand Banks cod collapse 1992 — catastrophic overfishing beyond MSY, North Sea herring recovery after moratorium, Pacific bluefin tuna IUCN Red List status, MSC certification and sustainable seafood labelling'},

//     {label:'Climate models — IPCC scenarios, tipping points and feedback cascades',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Feedback, Sustainability',lp:'Caring, Thinkers, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 6.2.7, 6.2.11-6.2.14: Climate models, scenarios, tipping points; Topic 6.3.8: IPCC five scenarios',scene:'An Earth cross-section climate model. Students adjust emissions using five IPCC SSP scenario sliders. Temperature anomaly graph builds showing 1.5C and 2C threshold lines. Tipping cascade animation triggers when multiple thresholds are crossed — permafrost, ice sheet, Amazon each shown separately.',sliders:['Emissions scenario (0=SSP1 deep cuts now → 4=SSP5 continued fossil fuel growth)','Carbon capture and negative emissions deployment (0=None → 4=Full-scale industrial CCS)','Permafrost methane release rate (0=Controlled → 4=Runaway positive feedback)','Deforestation rate (0=Active reforestation → 4=Maximum — Amazon tips to savanna)'],resources:['Global mean temperature anomaly C (0 baseline — rises)','Atmospheric CO2 ppm (420 current — variable)','Sea level rise cm by 2100 (variable)','Tipping points crossed count (0 — rises)','Probability of tipping cascade % (variable)'],explain:'Students manipulate the five IPCC emissions scenarios and observe how each produces a different temperature pathway. Critical thresholds at 1.5C and 2C trigger qualitatively different impacts. Tipping point cascades show non-linear interactions between permafrost, ice sheets and Amazon dieback. Directly models IB ESS Topics 6.2.11-6.2.14 and 6.3.8.',real:'IPCC AR6 five SSP scenarios and temperature pathways, Greenland ice sheet irreversibility above 1.5C, Amazon rainforest dieback tipping point 20-25% deforested, West Antarctic Ice Sheet marine ice cliff instability'},

//     {label:'Planetary boundaries, doughnut economics and circular economy',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Sustainability, Equity, Global governance',lp:'Caring, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 1.3.19-1.3.21: Planetary boundaries, doughnut economics, circular economy; HL.b.17: Ecological economics',scene:'An interactive doughnut economics diagram. The inner circle shows 12 social foundation categories; the outer ring shows 9 planetary boundaries. Student decisions push indicators inside or outside the safe and just space. Circular economy butterfly diagram shown alongside.',sliders:['Material consumption and GDP growth rate (0=Degrowth → 4=Maximum growth — overshoots limits)','Redistribution to meet social foundation needs (0=None → 4=Full — all social floors met)','Circular economy adoption rate (0=Linear take-make-dispose → 4=Full circular zero waste)','International cooperation on planetary boundaries (0=None → 4=Full binding global governance)'],resources:['Planetary boundaries exceeded count (0 to 9 — rises with overshoot)','Social foundations met count (0 to 12 — rises with redistribution)','Safe and just space score (variable)','Material footprint per capita (variable)','SDG achievement rate % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the tension between meeting all 12 social foundation needs while staying within 9 planetary boundaries — the central challenge of sustainable development. The circular economy slider reveals how material flows can be decoupled from economic activity. Directly models IB ESS Topics 1.3.19-1.3.21 and HL ecological economics.',real:'Kate Raworth Doughnut Economics Amsterdam city-level application, Stockholm Resilience Centre planetary boundaries 2023 update — 6 of 9 already exceeded, UN SDG 2023 progress — only 15% on track, Netherlands formally adopting doughnut economics framework'},

//     {label:'Ecological footprint, biocapacity and Earth Overshoot Day',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Change, Human impact, Systems',lp:'Principled, Caring, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Self-management',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 1.3.13: Ecological and carbon footprint calculators; Topic 1.3.2: Strong and weak sustainability',scene:'A world map with countries coloured by ecological footprint size relative to biocapacity. An Earth Overshoot Day calendar marker advances when footprint exceeds biocapacity. Individual lifestyle choice panel shows footprint components — food, transport, housing, goods.',sliders:['Diet type (0=Fully plant-based local → 4=High meat and imported food)','Transport mode (0=Walking and cycling → 4=Frequent long-haul flights and private car)','Housing energy (0=Zero-carbon passive house → 4=Large fossil-fuel heated home)','Consumer goods and shopping (0=Minimal repair and reuse → 4=Maximum consumption)'],resources:['Personal ecological footprint global hectares/year (variable)','Number of Earths needed if everyone lived this way (variable)','Earth Overshoot Day month and day (variable — earlier with higher footprint)','Carbon footprint % of total (variable)','Biocapacity reserve or deficit (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate their own ecological footprint and observe that if everyone lived like a high-income country resident, 3 to 5 Earths would be needed. The strong versus weak sustainability comparison is built in: weak sustainability assumes technology substitution compensates for natural capital loss. Directly addresses IB ESS Topic 1.3.13.',real:'Earth Overshoot Day 2024 — August 1st globally, Qatar 9 Earths vs India 0.8 Earths per capita comparison, Global Footprint Network country data, Finland national footprint reduction strategy'},

//     {label:'Eutrophication — positive feedback model and aquatic system collapse',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Feedback, Biodiversity, Human impact',lp:'Thinkers, Caring, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 4.4.6: Eutrophication systems model with positive feedback loops',scene:'A lake cross-section animation. Nutrient inputs flow in from surrounding farmland. Algal bloom grows visibly on the surface. Positive feedback shown as a cascade: algae shades underwater plants which die releasing nutrients which grow more algae which reduces oxygen which kills fish which release more nutrients.',sliders:['Agricultural nutrient runoff kg N/ha/year (0=None → 4=Heavy excess fertiliser application)','Phosphorus loading from sewage (0=Advanced tertiary treatment → 4=Untreated direct discharge)','Water body flushing rate (0=Rapid flow-through stream → 4=Stagnant enclosed lake)','Riparian buffer strip width m (0=None → 4=50m effective filtration)'],resources:['Dissolved oxygen mg/L (8 healthy target — falls)','Algal bloom biomass mg chlorophyll/L (variable — rises)','Aquatic biodiversity index (80 — falls)','Biological Oxygen Demand BOD mg/L (variable — rises)','Hypoxic zone area % of lake (0 — rises)'],explain:'Students trigger the eutrophication positive feedback cascade and discover why it is so difficult to reverse — once internal phosphorus loading from anoxic sediments begins, the system becomes trapped in a new degraded state. The buffering effect of riparian strips becomes viscerally clear. Models IB ESS Topic 4.4.6.',real:'Lake Erie harmful algal bloom 2011 — largest on record, Baltic Sea dead zones from agricultural runoff, China Lake Taihu cyanobacterial bloom and drinking water crisis, Thames River eutrophication and recovery after EU Urban Wastewater Directive'},

//     {label:'Tragedy of the commons — governance, cooperation and global commons',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Systems, Equity, Human impact',lp:'Principled, Caring, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 3.2.7: Tragedy of the commons; Topic 6.3.14: Tragedy applied to climate change',scene:'An animated shared commons — a pasture with individual herder characters each making rational decisions to add animals. The commons degrades as total herd exceeds carrying capacity. Individual rational decisions produce collective irrational outcome. Governance mechanisms added via slider.',sliders:['Number of herders sharing the commons (0=2 cooperative → 4=20 uncoordinated)','Individual herder self-interest (0=Fully cooperative voluntary restraint → 4=Fully self-interested maximum animals)','Governance mechanism strength (0=None open access → 4=Strong binding quotas enforced)','Commons resilience and recovery rate (0=Fragile slow recovery → 4=Resilient fast recovery)'],resources:['Commons carrying capacity utilised % (variable — above 100 means degradation)','Collective yield from commons (variable — peaks then crashes)','Individual herder short-term yield (variable — temporarily above collective optimum)','Governance compliance rate % (variable)','Commons recovery time after intervention years (variable)'],explain:'Students experience the Hardin tragedy of the commons: individual rational self-interest produces collective irrational outcomes when shared resources lack governance. The solution — governance mechanisms, property rights, or community norms — emerges from the simulation. Applied directly to climate change as a global commons problem in IB ESS Topic 6.3.14 and Ostrom\'s critique of Hardin.',real:'Hardin 1968 Science paper and subsequent critique by Elinor Ostrom, Ostrom Nobel Prize 2009 for governing commons without privatisation, High seas fishing governance vacuum and pirate fishing, Global atmosphere as a commons — free-rider problem in climate negotiations'},

//     {label:'Simpson\'s Diversity Index — quantitative biodiversity assessment',concept:'Biodiversity',related:'Patterns, Evidence, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 3.1.8: Simpson\'s reciprocal diversity index; Tool 2: Mathematical and quantitative skills',scene:'Two ecosystems shown side by side — a monoculture pine plantation and a mixed old-growth forest. Students select species counts and individual numbers. A calculation panel shows the formula D = sum of n(n-1) divided by N(N-1) building step by step. Reciprocal index 1/D updates as data is entered.',sliders:['Number of species — species richness (0=1 monoculture → 4=20 species high richness)','Evenness of abundance distribution (0=One species dominates 99 percent → 4=Perfectly even distribution)','Sample size n total individuals surveyed (0=Small 20 → 4=Large 500)','Habitat disturbance level (0=Undisturbed — high diversity → 4=Heavy disturbance — pioneer species dominate)'],resources:['Simpson Diversity Index D (variable — approaches 1 for high diversity)','Reciprocal index 1/D (variable — higher means more diverse)','Species richness count (variable)','Evenness index (variable)','Comparison to reference ecosystem score (variable)'],explain:'Students calculate Simpson\'s reciprocal diversity index 1/D by entering species abundance data and discover that a diverse ecosystem with many rare species can score lower than one with moderate richness but high evenness. The formula becomes meaningful when students see why squaring proportions penalises dominant species.',real:'Amazon primary forest vs palm oil plantation diversity comparison, Coral reef species diversity before and after bleaching event, UK farmland bird decline measured by diversity index, Rewilding Knepp Estate diversity recovery monitoring data'},

//     {label:'Urban systems metabolism — circular economy and sustainability modelling',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Sustainability, Human impact',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 8.2.3: Urban systems flow diagram; Topic 8.2.12: Circular economy and doughnut economics in urban context; HL.b.17',scene:'An animated urban metabolism diagram showing material and energy inputs flowing into a city — food, water, fuel, construction materials — and waste outputs flowing out — sewage, solid waste, CO2, waste heat. A circular economy overlay shows closed loops that keep materials in use within the city.',sliders:['Urban metabolism linearity (0=Fully circular all materials recovered → 4=Fully linear all to landfill)','Renewable energy grid share % (0=All fossil fuel → 4=100% renewable electricity)','Urban form compactness (0=Dense mixed-use walkable → 4=Low-density car-dependent sprawl)','Green infrastructure coverage % (0=No green space → 4=30% urban green and blue)'],resources:['Urban carbon emissions per capita tonnes/year (variable)','Material recovery and recycling rate % (variable)','Urban heat island intensity C above rural (variable)','Water recycling and reuse rate % (variable)','Resident liveability and wellbeing score (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how urban form and metabolism determine sustainability outcomes. Dense compact cities with circular material flows and renewable energy dramatically outperform sprawling linear-metabolism cities. Directly models IB ESS Topic 8.2.3 urban systems flow diagrams and 8.2.12 circular and doughnut economics applied to cities.',real:'Singapore closed-loop urban water system NEWater, Copenhagen carbon neutral 2025 target, Curitiba Brazil urban systems innovation, Amsterdam doughnut city strategy 2020'}
//   ,
//     {label:'Environmental value systems — technocentrism, ecocentrism and anthropocentrism',concept:'Perspectives',related:'Values, Ethics, Sustainability',lp:'Open-minded, Principled, Reflective',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 1.1.7-1.1.8: Environmental value systems as models',scene:'An animated spectrum from left (ecocentrism) to right (technocentrism) with anthropocentrism in the centre. A policy scenario appears each round — deforestation for development, nuclear power, rewilding — and student selects their EVS stance. A world map shows how different EVS positions have shaped real environmental policies.',sliders:['EVS position on spectrum (0=Deep ecocentrism — nature has intrinsic value → 4=Technocentrism — technology solves all problems)','Weighting of economic development vs conservation (0=Conservation absolute priority → 4=Development absolute priority)','Trust in technological solutions (0=Technology distrust → 4=Full techno-optimism)','Intergenerational responsibility horizon (0=Future generations equally weighted → 4=Present generation only)'],resources:['Biodiversity protection outcome (variable)','Economic development rate (variable)','Sustainability of policy chosen (variable)','Social justice achieved (variable)','Long-term environmental health (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how their own EVS shapes environmental decision-making and explore how the same ecological data produces different policy conclusions when filtered through technocentric versus ecocentric value systems. The model inputs are values; outputs are policies — directly mirroring IB ESS 1.1.7-1.1.8.',real:'Deep ecology movement Naess vs Brundtland anthropocentric sustainability, Bjorn Lomborg technocentric Copenhagen Consensus vs IPCC ecocentric approach, Wangari Maathai ecocentric Green Belt Movement, Shell versus Greenpeace Brent Spar dispute — contrasting EVS'},

//     {label:'Gaia hypothesis and Earth as an integrated self-regulating system',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Equilibrium, Feedback, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 1.2.5: Gaia hypothesis as a model; Topic 1.2.8: Daisyworld negative feedback',scene:'An animated Earth cross-section showing biosphere, atmosphere, hydrosphere and lithosphere as interconnected components. The Daisyworld model runs simultaneously — black and white daisy populations shift as solar luminosity changes, regulating planetary temperature through albedo feedback.',sliders:['Solar luminosity relative to current (0=70% early Sun — weak → 4=130% future Sun — intense)','Black daisy population proportion (0=All white daisies — high albedo reflects → 4=All black — low albedo absorbs)','Atmospheric composition CO2 and O2 levels (0=Pre-biotic anoxic → 4=Current biotic atmosphere)','Human disruption to biotic regulation (0=None — Gaia intact → 4=Severe — biotic regulation breaking down)'],resources:['Global mean temperature C (variable — regulated by Daisyworld mechanism)','Atmospheric oxygen % (variable)','Biosphere regulatory capacity (80)','Carbon sequestration by biota (variable)','System resilience to perturbation (variable)'],explain:'Students run the Daisyworld simulation and discover that black and white daisy populations self-regulate planetary temperature through albedo — a negative feedback loop operating without any conscious purpose. This models the Gaia hypothesis concept that the biosphere maintains conditions suitable for life. Covers IB ESS 1.2.5 and 1.2.8.',real:'Lovelock and Margulis Gaia hypothesis 1972, Venus and Mars comparison — no biotic regulation, Antarctic ice cores showing CO2-temperature correlation over 800000 years, Great Oxygenation Event 2.4 billion years ago as biosphere transforming atmosphere'},

//     {label:'Models — definition, types, simplification and predictive limitations',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Evidence, Change, Methods',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 1.2.13-1.2.14: Definition of a model; simplification and loss of accuracy',scene:'A model complexity workshop. Five model types shown side by side — physical model, diagram, equation, verbal description, computer simulation. Each is applied to the same ecological system. Complexity slider increases model detail and accuracy but also uncertainty and parameter sensitivity.',sliders:['Model complexity and detail (0=Simple 2-variable diagram → 4=Complex multi-variable computer simulation)','Spatial scale of model (0=Local single site → 4=Global Earth system model)','Temporal scale of model (0=Days — short prediction → 4=Centuries — long-range projection)','Validation data quality (0=No validation data — pure theory → 4=Extensive historical hindcast validation)'],resources:['Prediction accuracy for known outcomes % (variable)','Model uncertainty range % (variable — rises with complexity and timescale)','Number of parameters requiring estimation (variable)','Computational cost relative (variable)','Communication clarity for non-specialists (variable — decreases with complexity)'],explain:'Students discover the fundamental trade-off in modelling: simple models are transparent but inaccurate; complex models are more realistic but have more parameters that must be estimated, amplifying uncertainty. This directly addresses IB ESS 1.2.13-1.2.14 and the limitations of climate and population growth predictive models.',real:'IPCC climate model ensemble — 40 models with uncertainty range, World3 model used for Limits to Growth 1972 predictions, Population projection uncertainty — UN low vs high scenario divergence, Simple exponential growth model vs complex age-structured population model'},

//     {label:'Sustainability frameworks — SDGs, strong and weak sustainability models',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Systems, Equity, Change',lp:'Caring, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 1.3.2: Strong and weak sustainability; 1.3.17-1.3.18: SDG model and frameworks',scene:'A split-screen comparison: left shows the Three Pillars model with overlapping economy, society and environment circles; right shows the nested model with environment containing society containing economy. The SDG wheel of 17 goals visualised with trade-offs highlighted when one goal conflicts with another.',sliders:['Capital substitutability assumption (0=Strong sustainability — natural capital irreplaceable → 4=Weak sustainability — technology can fully substitute)','SDG priority focus (0=Environmental SDGs 13-15 → 4=Economic SDGs 8-9 — decent work and growth)','Intergenerational equity weight (0=Future generations equally weighted → 4=Present generation only)','Global governance for SDG coordination (0=No coordination — fragmented → 4=Strong binding global framework)'],resources:['Natural capital maintained (variable — declines under weak sustainability)','Social development index (variable)','SDG synergies achieved (variable)','SDG conflicts and trade-offs (variable — rises when goals prioritised separately)','Framework legitimacy and adoption rate (variable)'],explain:'Students compare the Three Pillars and nested sustainability models, discovering that the model chosen fundamentally shapes policy — the Three Pillars implies equal weighting while the nested model establishes hierarchy. Strong versus weak sustainability debate emerges from the capital substitutability slider. Directly models IB ESS 1.3.2 and 1.3.17-1.3.18.',real:'Brundtland Commission 1987 weak sustainability definition, Herman Daly strong sustainability and natural capital, SDG Synergies project mapping 17 goals — found both synergies and conflicts, Amsterdam and Copenhagen as SDG voluntary local review leaders'},

//     {label:'Lincoln index — capture-mark-release-recapture population estimation',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Biodiversity, Evidence, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 2.1.17: Lincoln index to estimate population size',scene:'An animated lake with fish. Round 1: a net captures a sample of fish which are tagged (marked with a red dot) and released. Round 2: a second sample is caught. The proportion of marked fish in the second sample is used to calculate the estimated total population N. Sampling error visualised.',sliders:['True population size N in habitat (0=Small 50 → 4=Large 2000 individuals)','First sample size M marked and released (0=Small 5 → 4=Large 100)','Second sample size n recaptured (0=Small 10 → 4=Large 150)','Population movement and mixing quality (0=Poor mixing — estimate unreliable → 4=Good mixing — estimate valid)'],resources:['Marked individuals in second sample R (variable)','Lincoln Index estimate N = Mn/R (variable)','Percentage error from true population (variable)','95% confidence interval width (variable)','Assumptions met? (variable — yes/no)'],explain:'Students apply the Lincoln index formula N = Mn/R to estimate population size without counting every individual, discovering how sample sizes affect estimate accuracy and the four key assumptions (no births/deaths/immigration, marks persist, random mixing) determine validity. Directly practises IB ESS 2.1.17 quantitative skill.',real:'Mark-recapture used for Great White Shark population estimate, Butterfly survey in UK hedgerow habitats, Wildlife corridor effectiveness monitoring using marked individuals, Illegal wildlife trade estimation from mark-recapture of known populations'},

//     {label:'Biome prediction — climate graphs, tricellular circulation and biome distribution',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Patterns, Biodiversity',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 2.4.5: Tricellular atmospheric circulation; 2.4.9: Predicting biomes from climate data',scene:'A rotating animated globe showing atmospheric circulation cells — Hadley, Ferrel and Polar. Wind patterns and precipitation bands shown. On the right, a climate graph builder — students adjust mean monthly temperature and precipitation to predict which biome would develop. Actual biome world map updates.',sliders:['Latitude of location degrees (0=Equatorial 0 degrees → 4=Polar 90 degrees)','Continentality — distance from ocean km (0=Coastal — oceanic climate → 4=Continental interior — extreme seasons)','Annual precipitation mm (0=Hyper-arid under 25mm → 4=Humid over 2000mm)','Temperature seasonality (0=Isothermal no seasons → 4=Extreme seasonal range over 40C)'],resources:['Predicted biome type (variable — updates with climate data)','Koppen climate classification (variable)','Actual measured annual rainfall mm (variable)','Growing season length months (variable)','Net primary productivity relative (variable)'],explain:'Students use the tricellular model to predict precipitation zones and then match temperature-precipitation combinations to the correct biome — directly practising IB ESS Tools 4 skill of predicting biome characteristics from climate data. The Hadley Cell explains tropical rainforests and deserts at 30 degrees from a single animated model.',real:'Sahara Desert at 30N due to Hadley Cell subsidence, Amazon at equator due to ITCZ convergence and uplift, Mediterranean climate at 30-40 latitude — seasonal precipitation, Boreal taiga at high northern latitudes — continental climate'},

//     {label:'Rewilding — secondary data modelling and restoration assessment',concept:'Biodiversity',related:'Change, Sustainability, Interaction',lp:'Caring, Inquirers, Open-minded',atl:'Research, Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 3.2: Rewilding project success assessment using secondary data',scene:'An animated landscape rewilding timeline. A degraded agricultural landscape progressively transforms as keystone species are reintroduced. Secondary data graphs populate: vegetation cover, species richness, predator-prey balance, ecosystem services value. Students set rewilding parameters and observe 50-year trajectories.',sliders:['Keystone species reintroduced (0=None — passive rewilding only → 4=Full trophic rewilding — apex predators and megafauna)','Area of rewilded landscape km2 (0=Small 10km2 → 4=Large 10000km2 — wildlife corridor)','Connectivity to other wild areas (0=Isolated fragment → 4=Fully connected wildlife corridor)','Human intervention intensity (0=Completely passive — nature led → 4=Active intensive management)'],resources:['Species richness change % from baseline (variable)','Carbon sequestration tonnes/year (variable)','Trophic cascade strength index (variable)','Ecosystem services value change % (variable)','Public support and social acceptance % (variable)'],explain:'Students assess rewilding project success using secondary data — species counts, vegetation surveys, predator-prey ratios — exactly as required in IB ESS Topic 3.2. The simulation shows how different rewilding strategies produce measurably different ecological outcomes over 50-year timescales.',real:'Knepp Estate UK rewilding — secondary data showing beaver, turtle dove, purple emperor butterfly return, Yellowstone Greater Ecosystem wolf recovery assessment data, Pleistocene Park Siberia — megafauna rewilding permafrost protection, European Rewilding Network restoration monitoring databases'},

//     {label:'Biotic index and BOD — measuring water quality as a modelling tool',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Evidence, Biodiversity, Human impact',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 4.5: Biotic index and BOD protocols as modelling tools',scene:'An animated river cross-section from clean source to polluted urban section to recovering downstream zone. Indicator species population counters shown — mayfly nymphs, freshwater shrimp, bloodworms. BOD meter reads oxygen demand. Biotic index score builds from species data.',sliders:['Upstream organic pollution load BOD mg/L (0=Clean 1mg/L → 4=Heavily polluted 20mg/L)','Industrial effluent temperature discharge C above ambient (0=None → 4=+10C — thermal pollution)','Sewage treatment quality upstream (0=None — raw discharge → 4=Tertiary treatment — high quality)','Distance downstream from pollution source km (0=At source → 4=10km downstream — self-purification)'],resources:['Dissolved oxygen mg/L (8 healthy → falls near source)','BOD mg/L (variable — rises at source falls downstream)','Biotic index score (variable — low = poor quality)','Saprobes and pollution-tolerant species % (variable — high near source)','Mayfly and sensitive indicator species % (variable — absent at source)'],explain:'Students apply the biotic index by observing which indicator organisms are present at each point along the river. They discover that BOD and biotic index are complementary models — one chemical, one biological — each with different strengths. The self-purification curve downstream models natural remediation. Directly addresses IB ESS Topic 4.5.',real:'River Thames biological recovery from 1960s dead river to salmon return, EU Water Framework Directive using biotic indices for status classification, India Ganga Yamuna biotic index data — heavily polluted urban sections, New Zealand SHMAK stream health monitoring using indicator species'},

//     {label:'Soil system — flow diagram, horizons and land-use impacts',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Flows, Biodiversity, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Caring, Inquirers',atl:'Research, Thinking',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 5.1.8: Systems flow diagram of soil; 5.1.10: Soil profiles linked to biomes',scene:'An animated soil profile cross-section showing O, A, B, C and R horizons. Organic material enters at the top from leaf litter. Decomposers break it down. Nutrients leach or get taken up by plants. The profile morphs when biome type changes — tropical oxisol versus temperate spodosol versus arid aridisol.',sliders:['Biome type (0=Tropical humid — deep weathered oxisol → 4=Arctic — thin permafrost cryosol)','Land use intensity (0=Old-growth forest — full soil ecosystem → 4=Intensive tillage — degraded)','Organic matter input kg/ha/year (0=None — bare soil → 4=Maximum leaf litter and root biomass)','Erosion and compaction level (0=None → 4=Severe — topsoil lost)'],resources:['Topsoil organic matter % (variable)','Soil biological activity index (variable)','Nutrient leaching rate kg/ha/year (variable)','Water infiltration rate mm/hour (variable)','Carbon storage in soil tonnes/ha (variable)'],explain:'Students build the soil system flow diagram by adjusting inputs and observing how organic matter, nutrient cycling and water infiltration respond. The soil profile morphs between biome types showing how parent material and climate interact with biota to produce different soil orders. Directly models IB ESS 5.1.8 and 5.1.10.',real:'Amazon rainforest nutrient poor oxisol — nutrients in biota not soil, explaining fragility after deforestation, Dust Bowl 1930s USA — topsoil loss after deep plowing broke soil structure, Regenerative agriculture soil carbon sequestration — reversing compaction, UK peat soil carbon store — drainage for farming releasing centuries of stored carbon'},

//     {label:'Land-use systems — comparative modelling of agriculture and sustainability',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Human impact, Biodiversity, Systems',lp:'Principled, Caring, Balanced',atl:'Research, Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 5.2: Contrasting land-use systems comparative modelling',scene:'Side-by-side animated comparison of four land-use systems: intensive monoculture, organic mixed farming, agro-forestry and shifting cultivation. Output meters show food yield, biodiversity index, soil health, water quality and carbon balance simultaneously.',sliders:['Intensification level (0=Low input traditional → 4=Intensive industrial — maximum yield)','Biodiversity in system (0=Monoculture — one species → 4=Polyculture — high diversity)','Synthetic input use fertiliser and pesticide (0=Zero — organic → 4=Maximum chemical input)','Scale of operation ha (0=Smallholder 1ha → 4=Industrial 50000ha)'],resources:['Food yield tonnes/ha/year (variable)','Biodiversity index on farm (variable)','Soil health and organic matter % (variable)','Water quality downstream (variable)','Net carbon balance kg CO2/ha/year (variable)'],explain:'Students compare land-use systems across five sustainability dimensions simultaneously, discovering the fundamental trade-off — intensive monoculture maximises yield but collapses biodiversity, soil health and water quality; diverse low-input systems provide multiple ecosystem services but lower food yield. Models IB ESS Topic 5.2 comparative land-use study.',real:'Green Revolution wheat yield vs Punjab soil degradation, Borneo oil palm biodiversity comparison with primary forest, Cuba low-input agriculture after Soviet collapse, Agroforestry in Sahel — trees and crops together restoring degraded land'},

//     {label:'Atmospheric system — tricellular model and Milankovitch cycles',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Patterns, Systems',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 6.1.2: Tricellular model; 6.1.7: Milankovitch cycles over geological time',scene:'A dual simulation: left shows the animated tricellular atmospheric circulation model with Hadley Ferrel and Polar cells, ITCZ, jet streams and surface wind patterns. Right shows Milankovitch cycle graphs — eccentricity obliquity and precession — with ice age timing overlay and proxy data.',sliders:['Time period in Earth history (0=Modern interglacial → 4=Last glacial maximum 20000 years ago)','Milankovitch cycle phase (0=Low eccentricity circular orbit → 4=High eccentricity elliptical — greater seasonal contrast)','Obliquity axial tilt degrees (0=Low 22 degrees — mild seasons → 4=High 24.5 degrees — extreme seasons)','Northern hemisphere land ice extent (0=Modern ice extent → 4=Maximum glacial ice — lowered sea level 120m)'],resources:['Global mean temperature relative to modern C (variable)','Sea level relative to modern m (variable — lower in glacials)','Northern hemisphere insolation W/m2 (variable)','Atmospheric CO2 ppm from ice cores (variable)','ITCZ position and precipitation belt latitude (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that orbital forcing explains the 100000-year ice age cycle and the asymmetry between slow glacial buildup and rapid deglaciation — a positive feedback amplification of a small orbital signal. The tricellular model explains why ice ages shift precipitation belts equatorward. Models IB ESS 6.1.2 and 6.1.7.',real:'Vostok ice core record showing four glacial cycles perfectly matching Milankovitch predictions, Sahara Green Period 11000-5000 years ago during ITCZ shift, Heinrich events rapid ice sheet collapse, Younger Dryas rapid climate reversal showing non-linear climate system'},

//     {label:'Albedo, greenhouse effect and climate system — simulation experiment',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Energy, Feedback, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 6.1.8: Investigate albedo or GHG impact on temperature of a closed system',scene:'A sealed experimental chamber animation — a mini-Earth inside a glass box. Short-wave solar radiation enters; long-wave infrared radiation tries to escape but is absorbed by GHG molecules. Albedo slider changes surface reflectivity. Temperature equilibrium reached after each adjustment.',sliders:['Greenhouse gas concentration in chamber (0=Pre-industrial 280 ppm CO2 → 4=Double pre-industrial 560 ppm)','Surface albedo of model Earth (0=Low albedo 0.1 — dark ocean absorbs → 4=High albedo 0.8 — ice reflects)','Solar irradiance input W/m2 (0=70% current — young Sun → 4=110% current — future Sun)','Water vapour feedback (0=No water vapour → 4=Full positive feedback — water vapour amplifies warming)'],resources:['Equilibrium temperature C inside chamber (variable)','Energy imbalance W/m2 (variable — zero at equilibrium)','Outgoing longwave radiation W/m2 (variable)','Absorbed shortwave radiation W/m2 (variable)','Climate sensitivity degrees per CO2 doubling (variable)'],explain:'Students replicate the conceptual design of IB ESS Topic 6.1.8 using a virtual closed system, adjusting albedo and GHG concentration to reach temperature equilibrium. They discover climate sensitivity — how much warming results from doubling CO2 — and see the water vapour positive feedback amplifying initial warming.',real:'Tyndall 1859 laboratory experiment proving CO2 absorbs infrared radiation, Hansen 1988 Senate testimony climate model predictions vs actual observed warming, Arctic amplification — albedo feedback doubling warming rate at poles, Venus greenhouse effect — runaway to 465C surface temperature'},

//     {label:'Ice cores, proxy data and historical climate reconstruction',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Evidence, Change, Patterns',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 6.2.3: 800000 years of ice core data; 6.2.4: Climate graphs; 6.2.10: Direct and indirect measurement',scene:'An animated ice core extraction showing annual layers of compressed snow. Each layer encases bubbles of ancient atmosphere. CO2 and CH4 concentrations from bubbles plotted alongside temperature from oxygen isotope ratios. The past 800000 years build across the screen showing four glacial-interglacial cycles.',sliders:['Time window displayed years before present (0=Recent 1000 years → 4=Full 800000 year record)','Proxy data type analysed (0=Ice core oxygen isotopes — temperature → 4=Tree rings — local precipitation)','Modern instrumental record overlay (0=Excluded → 4=Overlaid — showing dramatic recent anomaly)','CO2 concentration emphasis (0=Temperature only → 4=CO2-temperature correlation highlighted)'],resources:['Maximum CO2 in past 800000 years ppm (298 — compare to today 420)','Temperature anomaly at last glacial maximum C (variable — about minus 6C)','Current CO2 rate of increase ppm per decade (variable — unprecedented in record)','Correlation coefficient CO2 and temperature (variable — very high)','Time lag between CO2 and temperature peaks years (variable — about 800 years)'],explain:'Students discover that current CO2 levels (420 ppm) are 50% above the maximum in 800000 years of ice core data, and that the rate of increase is unprecedented. The time-lag between CO2 and temperature peaks reveals CO2 as an amplifier not initiator in natural cycles — but as the initiator in modern anthropogenic warming. Models IB ESS 6.2.3 and 6.2.10.',real:'Vostok ice core 420000 year record, EPICA Dome C extending record to 800000 years, Keeling Curve direct CO2 measurement since 1958, Mann hockey stick reconstruction controversy and subsequent validation by multiple proxy datasets'},

//     {label:'Environmental Impact Assessment — predictive modelling and decision-making',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Human impact, Sustainability, Evidence',lp:'Principled, Thinkers, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topics 7.1.14-7.1.15: EIA baseline studies to predict and evaluate impacts',scene:'An animated EIA process for a proposed development — a dam, mine or wind farm. Baseline data collection shown as sampling grid. Impact matrix completed as students select development type and mitigation measures. Residual impact scores shown for each environmental receptor.',sliders:['Development type impact magnitude (0=Minor low-impact — small tourism facility → 4=Major — large hydroelectric dam)','Baseline survey quality and duration (0=No baseline data — impacts unknown → 4=Three-year comprehensive baseline)','Mitigation measures applied (0=None — maximum impact → 4=Best available mitigation technology)','Stakeholder and community consultation (0=None → 4=Full participatory consultation — indigenous rights respected)'],resources:['Predicted biodiversity impact score (variable)','Water quality change (variable)','Greenhouse gas emissions change (variable)','Socioeconomic benefit to community (variable)','EIA quality and credibility score (variable)'],explain:'Students design an Environmental Impact Assessment process, discovering that EIA quality depends critically on baseline data — you cannot measure change without knowing the starting point. Mitigation hierarchy: avoid, reduce, restore, offset. Models IB ESS 7.1.14-7.1.15 predictive modelling skill used in real development decision-making.',real:'Three Gorges Dam China EIA — what was predicted vs what happened, Great Barrier Reef Adani Carmichael Mine EIA controversy, UK High Speed 2 HS2 environmental statement, Belo Monte Dam Brazil — indigenous communities excluded from EIA consultation'},

//     {label:'Dependency ratio, population momentum and slow or zero growth economics',concept:'Systems and models',related:'Change, Development, Sustainability',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 — Topic 8.1.10: Dependency ratio and population momentum; HL.b.16: Slow/no/zero growth economic model',scene:'An animated age-sex pyramid with dependency ratio bars highlighted — young dependants under 15, workers 15-64, elderly over 65. As the pyramid shape changes between DTM stages, dependency ratio recalculates. The population momentum animation shows why growth continues 20-70 years after fertility falls to replacement level.',sliders:['Age structure of population (0=Very young — Stage 2 pyramid → 4=Very old — Stage 5 inverted)','Total Fertility Rate TFR (0=Below replacement 1.3 — rapid ageing → 4=Very high 6.0 — young population)','GDP growth model (0=Degrowth actively pursued → 4=Maximum growth — GDP the sole measure)','Pension and social care system design (0=Pay-as-you-go — dependency ratio critical → 4=Fully funded — resilient to demographics)'],resources:['Youth dependency ratio % (variable — high in Stage 2)','Old age dependency ratio % (variable — high in Stage 5)','Total dependency ratio % (variable)','Population growth momentum years remaining (variable)','GDP growth rate under chosen model % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why population momentum means growth continues for 50-70 years even after fertility falls to replacement level — the large cohort of young people in Stage 2 countries will produce children even with smaller family sizes. The HL degrowth model explores whether economic wellbeing requires GDP growth. Covers IB ESS 8.1.10 and HL.b.16.',real:'India demographic dividend — large working-age population driving growth, Japan ageing crisis — dependency ratio above 50%, Bangladesh fertility decline and population momentum, Kate Raworth degrowth and doughnut economics — wellbeing without GDP growth'}]},
//   {icon:'🌐',name:'Global Politics',sub:'25 simulations · Core · R+J · D+S · P+C · HL',topics:[
//     {label:'UN Security Council veto debate',concept:'Power',related:'Sovereignty, Multilateralism, Governance',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 \u2014 Core: Power, sovereignty and international relations',scene:'A Security Council chamber. P5 flags visible. A draft resolution is proposed. Students role-play France, US, Russia, China, UK. Each state has a veto chip. A global crisis meter rises if no resolution passes.',sliders:['P5 national interest alignment (0=Strong divergence \u2014 veto likely \u2192 4=Strong alignment \u2014 unanimous passage)','Pressure from non-permanent members (0=None \u2192 4=Coalition of 10 \u2014 coordinated pressure)','Public international opinion (0=Indifferent \u2192 4=Strong moral pressure on P5)','Geopolitical alliance strength (0=Fractured \u2192 4=Bloc solidarity)'],resources:['Resolution passed or vetoed (variable)','UN legitimacy (70)','State bilateral relations (65)','Civil society pressure (50)','Crisis escalation index (40)'],explain:'Students experience how the P5 veto creates structural inequality in global governance and why states use it as a tool of national interest. Directly models the sovereignty-multilateralism tension at the heart of IB Global Politics.',real:'Russia veto on Syria resolutions 2011-2023, China-US veto dynamic on North Korea, France veto debates on Iraq 2003, UK veto on Zimbabwe sanctions'},
//     {label:'NATO Article 5 collective security activation debate',concept:'Interdependence',related:'Security, Alliances, Sovereignty',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 \u2014 Core: Power and sovereignty; Peace and Conflict thematic study',scene:'An animated NATO summit. A member state has been attacked. Students debate whether Article 5 is triggered. Legal advisors, defence ministers, and heads of state speak in turn. Alliance commitment meter visible.',sliders:['Attack attribution clarity (0=Ambiguous \u2192 4=Clear state-sponsored attack)','Military capacity of attacked member (0=Small \u2014 NATO-dependent \u2192 4=Large \u2014 can respond independently)','Economic cost of Article 5 (0=Low \u2192 4=Very high \u2014 recession risk)','Alliance solidarity (0=Fractured \u2192 4=United \u2014 unanimous commitment)'],resources:['Article 5 invoked (yes/no)','Alliance cohesion (75)','Deterrence credibility (65)','Bilateral relations maintained (70)','Public support in member states (55)'],explain:'Students discover that Article 5 does not mandate a specific military response \u2014 only that each member takes the action it deems necessary. This ambiguity creates strategic space for debate about the meaning of collective security.',real:'NATO Article 5 invoked after 9/11, Baltic states anxiety about hybrid warfare threshold, Montenegro accession debate, Ukraine Article 5 debate 2022'},
//     {label:'WTO trade dispute arbitration',concept:'Interdependence',related:'International law, Trade, Development',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 1 \u2014 Core: Interdependence; Development and Sustainability thematic study',scene:'A WTO dispute settlement chamber. Two states have filed competing claims over subsidies, tariffs, or intellectual property. Legal teams present evidence. A three-person panel deliberates and rules.',sliders:['Complainant legal case strength (0=Weak precedent \u2192 4=Strong \u2014 clear WTO rule violation)','Respondent economic power (0=Small developing state \u2192 4=Large G7 member)','Political pressure on panel (0=None \u2014 purely legal \u2192 4=High \u2014 diplomatic pressure visible)','Willingness to comply (0=Defiance likely \u2192 4=Full compliance expected)'],resources:['Panel ruling direction (variable)','Rule of law credibility (70)','Trade relationship preserved (65)','Bilateral diplomatic damage (40)','Development impact (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how WTO dispute settlement can function as international law with real enforcement \u2014 but also how large economies can absorb non-compliance costs that small states cannot. Models interdependence through legal inequality.',real:'US-EU Airbus-Boeing subsidy dispute, US-China intellectual property WTO cases, India pharmaceutical patent disputes, Ecuador banana trade dispute'},
//     {label:'G20 global financial regulation negotiation',concept:'Interdependence',related:'Development, Power, Governance',lp:'Thinkers, Balanced, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 \u2014 Core: Interdependence; Development and Sustainability thematic study',scene:'A G20 finance ministers summit. Basel banking standards are under renegotiation after a global financial crisis. Students represent major economies each with different financial sector interests.',sliders:['Capital requirement stringency (0=Weak \u2014 banks lobby for minimal \u2192 4=Strong \u2014 Basel IV full)','Tax haven crackdown (0=None \u2014 offshore finance protected \u2192 4=Full \u2014 OECD global minimum tax)','Developing world representation (0=G7 dominates \u2192 4=Equal voice \u2014 G20 consensus)','Coordination vs national interest (0=Beggar-thy-neighbour \u2192 4=Full coordination)'],resources:['Global financial stability (variable)','Developing world growth access (variable)','Banking sector profitability (variable)','Public debt sustainability (variable)','Tax revenue for public services (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that global financial regulation requires genuine coordination \u2014 if one major state defects to low regulation it creates a race to the bottom. Models why the G20 emerged after the 2008 crisis and why the OECD global minimum tax represents a historic breakthrough.',real:'Basel III and IV negotiations, OECD global minimum corporate tax 15% 2021, 2008 financial crisis G20 coordination, Panama Papers and tax haven crackdown'},
//     {label:'Soft power vs hard power foreign policy competition',concept:'Power',related:'Diplomacy, Influence, Foreign policy',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 \u2014 Core: Power and sovereignty',scene:'Two state teams compete to influence a fictional swing state. Team A uses cultural diplomacy, foreign aid, education partnerships, and media. Team B uses sanctions threats, military presence, and economic coercion.',sliders:['Soft power investment quality (0=Token gestures \u2192 4=Deep cultural and educational ties)','Hard power coercive credibility (0=Bluffing \u2014 no capability \u2192 4=Credible \u2014 demonstrated power)','Target state vulnerability (0=Stable \u2014 resistant \u2192 4=Fragile \u2014 highly susceptible)','International legitimacy (0=Hard power seen as bullying \u2192 4=Soft power seen as authentic)'],resources:['Target state alignment shift (variable)','International reputation (65)','Alliance network expansion (60)','Domestic political cost (45)','Long-term influence durability (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that soft power operates slowly but durably while hard power is quick but generates resentment. Smart power combines both. Maps directly to IB Global Politics core concept of power and models real geopolitical competition.',real:'China Belt and Road vs Western development aid, US cultural diplomacy through Hollywood, Russia hard power in post-Soviet sphere, Qatar World Cup soft power strategy'},
//     {label:'Sovereignty vs humanitarian intervention UN debate',concept:'Sovereignty',related:'Human rights, R2P, International law',lp:'Principled, Thinkers, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 1 \u2014 Core: Sovereignty; Rights and Justice thematic study',scene:'A UN General Assembly debate. A state is committing documented atrocities. Three actor groups present cases: the intervening coalition (citing R2P), the target state (citing sovereignty), and the Global South bloc (citing selective intervention).',sliders:['Severity of humanitarian crisis (0=Disputed allegations \u2192 4=Documented mass atrocities)','Intervening coalition legitimacy (0=Self-interested \u2014 oil present \u2192 4=Multilateral \u2014 diverse coalition)','Security Council support (0=Veto blocking \u2192 4=Unanimous authorisation)','Target state sovereignty claim (0=Failed state \u2192 4=Functioning democracy)'],resources:['Intervention authorised (yes/no)','Civilian protection outcome (variable)','Sovereignty norm eroded (variable)','Precedent created (yes/no)','Global South trust in system (variable)'],explain:'Students experience the core tension between sovereignty (Article 2(7) UN Charter) and the Responsibility to Protect norm. The simulation reveals that who intervenes and why matters as much as what is happening \u2014 directly modelling the selectivity critique.',real:'Libya 2011 NATO intervention, Syria non-intervention despite chemical weapons, Kosovo 1999 NATO action, Rwanda failure to act 1994'},
//     {label:'Responsibility to Protect R2P activation debate',concept:'Justice',related:'Sovereignty, Human rights, International law',lp:'Principled, Caring, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Rights and Justice thematic study; R2P three pillars',scene:'An emergency Security Council session. Early warning reports from a fictional state show mass atrocity risk. Three pillars of R2P displayed: state responsibility, international assistance, and international response.',sliders:['Early warning evidence quality (0=Disputed \u2192 4=Verified \u2014 multiple independent sources)','Host state consent (0=Hostile \u2014 refuses help \u2192 4=Consenting \u2014 invites support)','Available coalition capacity (0=No states willing \u2192 4=Large willing coalition)','China-Russia SC position (0=Veto threat \u2014 R2P blocked \u2192 4=Abstention \u2014 R2P activated)'],resources:['R2P activated (yes/no)','Civilian lives protected (variable)','Sovereignty norm costs (variable)','UN credibility (variable)','Future deterrence effect (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that R2P has three pillars and Pillar 3 is the most contested \u2014 requiring SC authorisation that the P5 veto can block. Models why R2P remains a norm rather than a legal obligation. Connects directly to the R&J thematic study.',real:'Libya 2011 \u2014 first explicit R2P authorisation, Darfur \u2014 R2P invoked but not enforced, Myanmar Rohingya \u2014 R2P failure, Kosovo \u2014 intervention before R2P existed'},
//     {label:'Mock ICC war crimes prosecution',concept:'Justice',related:'International law, Accountability, Sovereignty',lp:'Principled, Thinkers, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Rights and Justice thematic study; ICC jurisdiction and complementarity',scene:'An International Criminal Court chamber. Students play prosecutor, defence counsel, judges, witnesses, and state representatives. An indicted leader is charged with crimes against humanity. Evidence presented, witnesses cross-examined.',sliders:['Evidence strength (0=Circumstantial \u2014 weak \u2192 4=Direct \u2014 documented orders)','Defendant state cooperation (0=Non-cooperative \u2014 ignores warrant \u2192 4=Fully cooperative)','Political interference from P5 (0=None \u2192 4=Diplomatic pressure on ICC)','Defence sovereignty argument (0=Weak \u2014 clearly ICC jurisdiction \u2192 4=Strong \u2014 genuine dispute)'],resources:['Verdict (variable)','ICC credibility (65)','Future deterrence of atrocities (variable)','Defendant state relations (variable)','Victim community justice satisfaction (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the ICC can only prosecute when states are unable or unwilling \u2014 the complementarity principle. The simulation reveals that the ICC indicts leaders from weaker states while powerful states (US, China, Russia, India) are non-members. Directly models the selectivity critique.',real:'Omar al-Bashir ICC warrant Sudan, Hague trial of Slobodan Milosevic, Rodrigo Duterte ICC withdrawal Philippines, US sanctions against ICC prosecutors 2020'},
//     {label:'Refugee resettlement burden-sharing negotiation',concept:'Justice',related:'Human rights, Development, Borders',lp:'Caring, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Rights and Justice thematic study; refugee law and protection',scene:'A UNHCR ministerial conference. Students role-play UNHCR, major receiving states, reluctant border states, and origin country representatives. A burden-sharing formula is negotiated.',sliders:['Host state political willingness (0=Hostile \u2014 zero-quota \u2192 4=Welcoming \u2014 above-quota volunteer)','Economic integration capacity (0=High unemployment \u2192 4=Labour shortage \u2014 high absorption)','International burden-sharing fund (0=No fund \u2192 4=Large fully-funded programme)','Origin state cooperation (0=None \u2014 statelessness risk \u2192 4=Full cooperation)'],resources:['Refugees resettled annually (variable)','Refugee wellbeing (55)','Host community cohesion (60)','Legal status protection (variable)','Return prospects (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the 1951 Refugee Convention framework and why burden-sharing remains voluntary and politically contested. The simulation reveals how refugee flows are both humanitarian and political. Directly addresses the R&J thematic study.',real:'Syrian refugee EU burden-sharing crisis 2015-2016, Australia offshore processing, Turkey-EU refugee deal, UNHCR resettlement backlog globally'},
//     {label:'Climate change COP negotiation developed vs developing states',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Development, Justice, Interdependence',lp:'Caring, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Development and Sustainability thematic study; climate governance',scene:'A COP conference plenary. States grouped as G7, BRICS, AOSIS small island developing, and LDC least developed. Emissions targets, finance commitments, and technology transfer on the table. Loss and damage fund debate visible.',sliders:['Developed state ambition (0=Token \u2014 below 1.5C pathway \u2192 4=Transformative \u2014 Paris-aligned)','Climate finance pledged (0=Far below $100bn \u2192 4=Above $100bn with loss and damage fund)','Developing state growth rights (0=No restrictions \u2014 historical justice \u2192 4=Universal caps)','Small island state influence (0=Marginalised \u2192 4=Agenda-setting \u2014 moral authority)'],resources:['Temperature pathway C by 2100 (variable)','Finance to developing world (variable)','Trust between blocs (55)','Agreement legally binding (yes/no)','Loss and damage compensation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the structural inequity at the heart of climate negotiations \u2014 states that contributed least face the worst consequences. Models the CBDR-RC principle and reveals why COPs are as much about justice as science. Directly models the D&S thematic study.',real:'Paris Agreement 2015 NDC structure, COP28 Dubai loss and damage fund, AOSIS Maldives underwater cabinet, China peak emissions pledge'},
//     {label:'IMF structural adjustment conditionality debate',concept:'Development',related:'Sovereignty, Economic justice, Power',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Development and Sustainability thematic study; Bretton Woods institutions',scene:'A negotiation room. A debtor state in financial crisis faces IMF conditions. Students play IMF economists, government negotiators, civil society protesters, domestic business leaders, and creditor state representatives.',sliders:['IMF conditionality severity (0=Soft \u2014 flexible \u2192 4=Hard structural adjustment \u2014 privatise and cut)','Debtor state political stability (0=Fragile \u2014 protests overwhelming \u2192 4=Stable \u2014 political capital)','Alternative financing available (0=None \u2014 IMF only \u2192 4=China development bank \u2014 leverage)','Civil society resistance (0=Weak \u2192 4=Mass strikes \u2014 political pressure)'],resources:['Loan disbursed (yes/no)','Debt sustainability ratio (variable)','Public services maintained (variable)','Economic growth forecast (variable)','Social inequality Gini (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the core critique of IMF structural adjustment \u2014 conditionality requires austerity that falls hardest on the poorest while protecting creditors. Models the asymmetric power between IMF and debtor states. Key D&S thematic study content.',real:'Greece austerity 2010-2018, Argentina IMF debt restructuring, Ecuador oil-for-IMF deal, Zambia debt default 2020'},
//     {label:'Nuclear deterrence crisis simulation',concept:'Peace',related:'Security, Power, International law',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Peace and Conflict thematic study; nuclear deterrence and disarmament',scene:'A crisis management simulation. Two nuclear-armed rival states are in escalating tension. Students play heads of state, defence ministers, intelligence advisors, and UN mediators. Decision trees show escalation pathways. A nuclear threshold meter rises.',sliders:['Crisis provocation severity (0=Diplomatic incident \u2014 low \u2192 4=Territorial incursion with casualties)','Communication channel quality (0=Cut off \u2014 dangerous \u2192 4=Direct hotline \u2014 de-escalation possible)','Domestic political pressure (0=Population wants de-escalation \u2192 4=Nationalist pressure \u2014 hardline)','Third-party mediator effectiveness (0=Rejected \u2192 4=Accepted \u2014 credible mediator)'],resources:['Nuclear use probability % (variable)','Diplomatic resolution reached (yes/no)','Civilian casualties avoided (variable)','International norms upheld (variable)','Escalation ladder position (variable)'],explain:'Students discover deterrence theory (MAD) and its paradox: the threat of annihilation prevents annihilation. The simulation reveals how communication failures and misperception drive nuclear crises more than rational calculation. Directly models the P&C thematic study.',real:'Cuban Missile Crisis 1962 hotline established after, India-Pakistan Kargil crisis 1999, North Korea missile tests and US response, Ukraine nuclear discussion after Crimea'},
//     {label:'Peace negotiation role-play ceasefire and PIN model',concept:'Peace',related:'Conflict resolution, Justice, Sovereignty',lp:'Principled, Communicators, Open-minded',atl:'Communication, Social skills, Thinking',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Peace and Conflict thematic study; conflict resolution and mediation',scene:'A mediation room with a facilitator and two conflict parties. A fictional intrastate conflict has lasted 5 years. Students play government negotiators, rebel faction representatives, international mediators, and civil society observers.',sliders:['Ceasefire terms overlap (0=Maximalist positions \u2014 no overlap \u2192 4=Bridging formula \u2014 both can accept)','Spoiler groups present (0=No spoilers \u2192 4=Active hardliners on both sides)','Mediator credibility (0=Partial \u2014 seen as biased \u2192 4=Impartial \u2014 trusted by both)','Power balance (0=Asymmetric \u2014 strong side unwilling \u2192 4=Military stalemate \u2014 both need deal)'],resources:['Ceasefire agreement reached (yes/no)','Civilian protection during ceasefire (variable)','Long-term peace durability (variable)','Justice for victims (variable)','International monitoring deployed (variable)'],explain:'Students apply the PIN model to discover that successful negotiation moves parties from stated positions to underlying interests and then to fundamental human needs. Ceasefires are relatively easy but durable peace is hard. Core P&C thematic study content.',real:'Oslo Accords 1993, Minsk agreements Ukraine, Colombia FARC peace agreement 2016, Northern Ireland Good Friday Agreement 1998'},
//     {label:'Truth and reconciliation commission simulation',concept:'Justice',related:'Peace, Human rights, Memory',lp:'Caring, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Social skills',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Peace and Conflict thematic study; transitional justice',scene:'A public hearing room. Students play commission members, victim testimony givers, perpetrators seeking amnesty, civil society observers, and international advisors. A justice-peace trade-off meter displayed. Truth and reparations panels alternate.',sliders:['Amnesty offered (0=No amnesty \u2014 prosecution only \u2192 4=Full amnesty \u2014 truth exchange)','Victim voice in design (0=Excluded \u2014 top-down \u2192 4=Victim-led \u2014 co-designed)','Political leadership support (0=Leaders obstructing \u2192 4=Full cooperation)','Reparations fund (0=No resources \u2192 4=Substantial reparations programme)'],resources:['Truth revealed publicly (variable)','Perpetrators held accountable (variable)','Victim healing (variable)','Social reconciliation (variable)','Impunity prevented (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the core tension in transitional justice: criminal prosecution maximises accountability but may deter peace. The TRC simulation models the South Africa model and reveals its successes and failures. Directly addresses the P&C thematic study.',real:'South Africa TRC 1996-1998 Mandela and Tutu model, Rwanda Gacaca courts, Cambodia ECCC hybrid tribunal, Colombia Jurisdiccion Especial para la Paz'},
//     {label:'Arctic governance summit borders and environment',concept:'Sovereignty',related:'Environment, Development, Power',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: borders and environment',scene:'An Arctic Council session. Eight Arctic states plus observer states and indigenous peoples representatives negotiate shipping routes, resource extraction rights, and environmental protection. A melting sea ice counter runs.',sliders:['Resource extraction vs environmental protection (0=Moratorium \u2014 protection first \u2192 4=Maximum extraction)','Indigenous communities rights (0=Token consultation \u2192 4=Free prior informed consent \u2014 veto power)','Military presence in Arctic (0=Demilitarised \u2014 cooperative \u2192 4=Active militarisation)','UNCLOS extension claims (0=No claims \u2192 4=Overlapping claims \u2014 legal dispute)'],resources:['Environmental protection level (variable)','Indigenous communities benefit (variable)','Interstate tensions (variable)','Economic gains (variable)','International legal framework (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the melting Arctic creates new geopolitical opportunities and tensions. Models how climate change is a geopolitical driver and why Arctic governance (Arctic Council) lacks binding legal authority. Models the HL borders and environment global challenge.',real:'Russia Arctic militarisation and continental shelf claim, Canada-US Northwest Passage dispute, Norway-Russia Svalbard, Greenland strategic importance to US'},
//     {label:'Cyberattack attribution and response council',concept:'Power',related:'Technology, Security, Sovereignty',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: technology and security',scene:'An emergency national security council. A major cyberattack has disrupted critical infrastructure. Intelligence agencies present attribution evidence. Students decide: retaliate, sanction, refer to international law, or absorb.',sliders:['Attribution confidence % (0=Low 30% \u2014 could be false flag \u2192 4=High 95% \u2014 state actor confirmed)','Proportionality of response (0=Disproportionate \u2014 escalation risk \u2192 4=Proportionate \u2014 calibrated)','International coalition support (0=None \u2014 unilateral \u2192 4=Allied consensus \u2014 multilateral)','Diplomatic channel available (0=None \u2014 crisis \u2192 4=Back-channel open \u2014 negotiated exit)'],resources:['Correct attribution (yes/no)','Escalation risk (variable)','International law compliance (variable)','Deterrence signal sent (variable)','Diplomatic relationship preserved (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why attribution is the central problem in cyber conflict \u2014 technically difficult and politically contested. The simulation reveals the fog of cyber war and why international norms for cyber are still in early development. Models the HL technology and security challenge.',real:'SolarWinds hack attributed to Russia 2020, NotPetya attributed to Russia 2017, Stuxnet attributed to US and Israel, Sony hack attributed to North Korea'},
//     {label:'Big Tech antitrust hearing data power and market equality',concept:'Power',related:'Technology, Equality, Governance',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: technology and equality',scene:'A congressional or parliamentary antitrust hearing. A major platform company faces legislators and regulators. Students play tech executives, antitrust economists, consumer rights advocates, data privacy experts, and small business complainants.',sliders:['Market dominance evidence (0=Contested \u2014 multiple players \u2192 4=Clear monopoly \u2014 90%+ market share)','Data privacy violations (0=Minor technical breach \u2192 4=Systematic \u2014 fundamental rights violated)','Regulator independence (0=Captured \u2014 revolving door \u2192 4=Independent \u2014 strong authority)','Global regulatory coordination (0=Fragmented \u2014 company exploits gaps \u2192 4=Coordinated \u2014 G7 common standard)'],resources:['Antitrust action taken (yes/no)','Consumer data rights protected (variable)','Market competition restored (variable)','Innovation chilling effect (variable)','Global regulatory precedent set (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why regulating global platform companies is structurally difficult \u2014 they operate across jurisdictions making national regulation partial. Models the political economy of Big Tech and the contrast between EU and US regulatory approaches. HL technology and equality challenge.',real:'EU Digital Markets Act, Google antitrust ruling EU 2017 and US 2024, Meta Cambridge Analytica and GDPR, Amazon market self-preferencing'},
//     {label:'Migration policy summit borders and identity',concept:'Justice',related:'Rights, Sovereignty, Development',lp:'Open-minded, Caring, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: borders and identity',scene:'A ministerial summit on migration governance. States negotiate asylum policy, legal migration pathways, and border management. Students play origin states, transit states, destination states, UNHCR, and migrant community organisations.',sliders:['Legal migration pathway breadth (0=Closed \u2014 no pathways \u2192 4=Open \u2014 skills and humanitarian)','Asylum processing quality (0=Arbitrary \u2014 rapid refoulement \u2192 4=Fair \u2014 UNHCR standard compliant)','Border enforcement intensity (0=Open borders \u2192 4=Militarised \u2014 pushbacks)','Integration policy investment (0=None \u2014 hostile environment \u2192 4=Comprehensive)'],resources:['Refugees legally protected % (variable)','Migration governance coherence (variable)','Host community cohesion (variable)','Origin country remittances (variable)','Human smuggling scale (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that border closures do not stop migration \u2014 they make it more dangerous and enrich criminal smuggling networks. Models the tension between state sovereignty over borders and the right to seek asylum. Directly addresses the HL borders and identity global challenge.',real:'EU-Turkey migration deal 2016, UK Rwanda deportation scheme, US Title 42, Mediterranean deaths UNHCR data, Australia offshore processing'},
//     {label:'LGBTQ+ rights summit identity and cultural sovereignty',concept:'Justice',related:'Rights, Identity, Sovereignty',lp:'Principled, Open-minded, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: identity and equality',scene:'A UN human rights forum. States with different legal frameworks debate decriminalisation of same-sex relations. Students play Western European liberal states, African states citing cultural sovereignty, LGBTQ+ civil society groups, and the Office of the High Commissioner.',sliders:['Universality argument strength (0=Cultural relativism \u2014 no universal standard \u2192 4=Universalism \u2014 rights indivisible)','Civil society access (0=Excluded \u2014 states only \u2192 4=Full participation)','Economic leverage from donors (0=No conditions \u2192 4=Aid conditionality on decriminalisation)','Domestic political backlash risk (0=None \u2014 stable context \u2192 4=High \u2014 religious political parties)'],resources:['Decriminalisation progress (variable)','Cultural sovereignty argument upheld (variable)','Civil society empowerment (variable)','International pressure effectiveness (variable)','Trust between blocs (variable)'],explain:'Students directly encounter the universality-relativity debate at the heart of IB Global Politics Rights and Justice. The simulation models how rights claims are simultaneously moral, political, and geopolitical and why the same cultural sovereignty argument is used across different contexts.',real:'Uganda Anti-Homosexuality Act 2023 and aid suspension, EU suspension of Uganda funding, Ghana LGBTQ+ bill 2021, Saudi Arabia and Iran at UN Human Rights Council'},
//     {label:'Reparations for colonialism and slavery debate',concept:'Justice',related:'Equality, Development, History',lp:'Principled, Open-minded, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: equality',scene:'A commission hearing on reparations. Students play representatives of Caribbean nations (CARICOM), UK and European governments, historians, economists, and diaspora community organisations. Arguments for and against in different forms: financial, institutional, educational.',sliders:['Form of reparations (0=Refusal \u2014 responsibility denied \u2192 4=Full financial reparations \u2014 calculated damage)','Moral vs legal responsibility (0=No legal obligation recognised \u2192 4=Legal and moral liability accepted)','Recipient community agency (0=Donor-decided \u2192 4=Community-designed \u2014 full participation)','Political feasibility (0=Impossible \u2014 electoral backlash \u2192 4=Feasible \u2014 consensus building)'],resources:['Justice and recognition achieved (variable)','Economic repair to affected states (variable)','Historical record acknowledged (variable)','Public trust in institutions (variable)','Precedent set for other claims (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that the reparations debate involves legal liability, moral responsibility, practical form, and political feasibility. Models structural historical injustice and directly addresses the HL equality global challenge and prepares students for Paper 2 analysis.',real:'CARICOM reparations 10-point programme, Barbados removal of Charles III as head of state, Germany Herero and Nama reparations, US debate on H.R. 40 commission'},
//     {label:'Deforestation accountability summit environment and development',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Environment, Justice, Development',lp:'Caring, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: environment',scene:'An international environmental summit. Amazon deforestation is accelerating. Students play Brazil government, indigenous communities, environmental NGOs, European Union trade partners, and commodity companies.',sliders:['Deforestation rate (0=Near-zero \u2014 commitment \u2192 4=Record rates \u2014 economic priority)','Indigenous land rights (0=Unrecognised \u2014 encroachment \u2192 4=Legally protected \u2014 demarcation enforced)','EU trade conditionality (0=No conditions \u2014 business as usual \u2192 4=Strong \u2014 deforestation-free supply chain law)','Domestic political will (0=Hostile to environmentalists \u2192 4=Green government \u2014 proactive)'],resources:['Forest coverage maintained % (variable)','Indigenous territory protected % (variable)','Biodiversity loss rate (variable)','Carbon sink function (variable)','Trade relationship preserved (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the political economy of deforestation \u2014 economic interests face weak enforcement while indigenous communities bear the greatest cost. The simulation models how EU trade conditionality represents new environmental governance through market power. HL environment global challenge.',real:'EU Deforestation Regulation 2023, Amazon tipping point research, Bolsonaro vs Lula deforestation rates, REDD+ ecosystem payments, Norway-Brazil Amazon Fund'},
//     {label:'Artificial intelligence governance committee technology and security',concept:'Power',related:'Technology, Justice, Security',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: technology and security',scene:'An international AI governance committee drafting binding rules. Students play US tech companies, EU regulators, China government, civil society researchers, and military representatives. Three rule domains: autonomous weapons, facial recognition, and algorithmic decision-making.',sliders:['Binding vs voluntary commitments (0=Voluntary guidelines only \u2192 4=Binding treaty with enforcement)','Autonomous weapons allowed (0=Full ban \u2014 human control required \u2192 4=Fully autonomous lethal systems)','Algorithmic transparency required (0=No transparency \u2014 trade secret \u2192 4=Full explainability \u2014 audit rights)','AI development equality (0=Winner-takes-all \u2014 US China dominate \u2192 4=Technology transfer to developing world)'],resources:['Human rights protected in AI (variable)','Military escalation risk from autonomous weapons (variable)','Innovation maintained (variable)','Global equity in AI benefits (variable)','Democratic accountability (variable)'],explain:'Students discover why AI governance is both urgent and structurally difficult \u2014 the states with most to gain from AI are also most resistant to binding constraints. Models the contest between values-based (EU) and strategic (US/China) approaches. HL technology and security global challenge.',real:'EU AI Act 2024, UN General Assembly resolution on AI 2024, Lethal autonomous weapons debate Geneva, US AI Executive Order, China AI governance regulations'},
//     {label:'Poverty eradication strategy council',concept:'Development',related:'Justice, Sustainability, Power',lp:'Caring, Principled, Balanced',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Extension \u2014 Global political challenges: poverty',scene:'An international development policy council. States, the World Bank, IMF, NGOs, and affected community representatives debate poverty reduction strategies. Three models: conditional cash transfers, universal basic income, and structural reform.',sliders:['Transfer programme conditionality (0=Unconditional \u2014 no requirements \u2192 4=Conditional \u2014 school job search)','Structural root cause addressed (0=Symptoms only \u2014 cash transfers \u2192 4=Structural reform \u2014 land tax trade)','Community agency in design (0=Top-down donor-designed \u2192 4=Community-led \u2014 participatory)','Long-term financing sustainability (0=Aid-dependent \u2192 4=Domestic revenue mobilisation \u2014 sovereign)'],resources:['Poverty headcount reduction % (variable)','Recipient dignity and agency (variable)','Long-term dependency risk (variable)','Political sustainability (variable)','SDG 1 progress score (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the core debate in development economics: do cash transfers treat symptoms while leaving structural causes intact? Models the Sachs-Easterly debate and the shift from conditionality to community ownership in development practice. Directly addresses the HL poverty global challenge.',real:'Mexico PROGRESA conditional cash transfer, GiveDirectly unconditional cash Kenya, Bolsa Familia Brazil, Basic income pilots Finland and Kenya'},
//     {label:'Non-violence vs armed resistance policy debate',concept:'Peace',related:'Justice, Power, Rights',lp:'Principled, Thinkers, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'Paper 2 \u2014 Peace and Conflict thematic study; resistance and liberation movements',scene:'A structured academic debate. Two teams argue: non-violent resistance vs armed struggle. Evidence panels draw on historical case studies. A third team adjudicates selecting the most persuasive evidence-based argument.',sliders:['Non-violent movement mass base (0=Small educated elite only \u2192 4=Broad \u2014 working class poor women)','State repression severity (0=Tolerant \u2014 allows protest \u2192 4=Extreme \u2014 mass killings of protesters)','International solidarity and media (0=Ignored \u2192 4=Global attention \u2014 solidarity movements)','Armed resistance operational success (0=Militarily defeated \u2192 4=Controls territory)'],resources:['Movement goal achieved (yes/no)','Civilian casualties (variable)','International legitimacy (variable)','Regime change achieved (variable)','Long-term democratisation (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that non-violent civil resistance is on average more effective than armed struggle \u2014 but context matters enormously. The simulation models the conditions that favour each approach and directly prepares students for Paper 2 comparative analysis of peace and conflict.',real:'Gandhi Indian independence \u2014 non-violent, Mandela and ANC armed struggle then negotiation, PLO \u2014 combination, Myanmar \u2014 armed resistance after coup 2021, Ukrainian resistance 2022'},
//     {label:'Model UN engagement project simulation',concept:'Interdependence',related:'Diplomacy, Rights, Power',lp:'Communicators, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Communication, Research, Social skills',aoCrit:'Engagement Project \u2014 active participatory citizenship in political contexts',scene:'A full Model UN simulation cycle. Students research a real country position on a contested resolution, write position papers, caucus informally, formally debate, and negotiate amendments. Parliamentary language coach embedded.',sliders:['Country position alignment with own values (0=Very different \u2014 challenging \u2192 4=Similar \u2014 natural advocacy)','Coalition-building skill (0=No allies found \u2192 4=Strong bloc \u2014 leading the coalition)','Resolution amendment quality (0=Weak \u2014 easily defeated \u2192 4=Strong \u2014 broad support)','Public speaking confidence (0=Struggling \u2014 reading verbatim \u2192 4=Confident \u2014 impromptu)'],resources:['Resolution passed (yes/no)','Personal learning about country (variable)','Diplomatic skill development (variable)','Understanding of multilateralism (variable)','Engagement project documentation quality (variable)'],explain:'Students experience the full arc of multilateral diplomacy \u2014 research, preparation, caucusing, formal debate, and compromise \u2014 developing precisely the skills the IB Global Politics Engagement Project requires.',real:'UN General Assembly third committee human rights debates, Security Council simulation on sanctions, WHO Assembly on pandemic preparedness, UNESCO cultural heritage resolutions'}
//   ]},
//   {icon:'📝',name:'English A',sub:'12 simulations · SL & HL',topics:[
//     {label:'Authorial choices — narrative voice, structure and reader positioning',concept:'Perspective',related:'Representation, Communication, Transformation',lp:'Thinkers, Open-minded, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Guided literary analysis; Individual Oral (IO)',scene:'An animated manuscript where narrative choices visually shift the text. POV spotlight moves between characters. Chronological structure shown as a reorderable timeline. Imagery density shown as colour saturation.',sliders:['Narrative point of view (0=Third-person omniscient → 4=First-person unreliable)','Chronological structure (0=Linear → 4=Non-linear fragmented)','Figurative language density (0=Plain prose → 4=Highly figurative — extended metaphor)','Tone and register (0=Detached ironic → 4=Intimate confessional)'],resources:['Reader engagement (55)','Thematic clarity (65)','Interpretive openness (40)','Character depth (60)','Stylistic distinctiveness (45)'],explain:"Students make author choices and observe how each repositions the reader. Directly models the close reading and authorial intention analysis required in DP Language A Paper 1. Connects technique to effect to purpose.",real:"Ishiguro's unreliable narrator in The Remains of the Day, Morrison's fragmented structure in Beloved, Camus' detached register in The Stranger, Pamuk's multi-narrator structure in My Name is Red"},
//     {label:'Language and power — representation, ideology and media discourse',concept:'Power',related:'Identity, Representation, Communication',lp:'Principled, Open-minded, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Language in cultural context; Individual Oral (IO)',scene:'A media broadcast showing the same event framed differently by two news sources. Word choice and framing differences highlighted. Audience response meters show how framing affects perception. Ideological positioning compass.',sliders:['Institutional authority of speaker (0=Marginalised voice → 4=State authority — maximum reach)','Euphemism/dysphemism degree (0=Neutral language → 4=Politically loaded framing)','Visual and design rhetoric (0=Neutral imagery → 4=Emotionally charged photography)','Counter-narrative space (0=Suppressed → 4=Amplified — plurality of voices)'],resources:['Dominant narrative strength (70)','Marginalised voice visibility (25)','Critical thinking in audience (50)','Factual accuracy maintained (60)','Long-term public trust (55)'],explain:"Students discover how the same event can produce radically different audience responses depending on language choice, visual framing, and whose voice is amplified. Directly develops DP Language A Individual Oral critical analysis skills.",real:"Orwell's Politics and the English Language, Colonial renaming (Mumbai/Bombay), Indigenous language reclamation, COVID-19 media framing across different countries"},
//     {label:'Paper 1 unseen text analysis — decoding an unfamiliar non-literary text',concept:'Communication',related:'Representation, Perspective, Creativity',lp:'Thinkers, Communicators, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Guided textual analysis; 1h30 exam unseen text',scene:'An exam desk where an unseen non-literary text appears — a political speech, advertisement or news editorial. Annotation hotspots glow as techniques are identified. A guiding question banner sits at the top. A clock counts down 90 minutes.',sliders:['Text type familiarity (0=Completely unfamiliar genre → 4=Well-practised genre)','Guiding question focus (0=Ignored — general waffle → 4=Precisely answered throughout)','Evidence integration (0=No quotations — assertion only → 4=Every claim supported with close reference)','Effect-to-purpose link (0=Identifies technique only → 4=Explains effect AND authorial purpose)'],resources:['Analytical depth score (40)','Guiding question relevance (50)','Evidence density (35)','Technique identification (60)','Purpose evaluation (30)'],explain:"Students practice the Paper 1 close reading process — identifying the guiding question, selecting techniques, explaining their effect on the audience, and evaluating the author's overall purpose. Repeated rounds model the exam 90-minute process.",real:"Barack Obama 2008 election speech — anaphora and pathos, Amnesty International print ad — visual rhetoric, The Guardian editorial on climate — argument structure, Nike 'Just Do It' — brand ideology in three words"},
//     {label:'Individual Oral — selecting a global issue and building the comparative argument',concept:'Identity',related:'Culture, Representation, Perspective',lp:'Communicators, Open-minded, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Individual Oral — 10 min + 5 min Q&A; 40 marks; 30% of SL grade',scene:'A preparation desk split into two panels — one literary text extract, one non-literary text. A global issue selector wheel spins showing themes: displacement, gender inequality, power, climate, technology. A 10-minute countdown clock. Argument strength meter builds as links are drawn.',sliders:['Global issue clarity (0=Too broad — topic not issue → 4=Specific pervasive cross-cultural issue)','Literary text connection (0=Surface plot mention → 4=Deep formal analysis — how form expresses issue)','Non-literary text connection (0=Thin media reference → 4=Close textual analysis of language choices)','Comparative insight (0=Two separate analyses → 4=Genuine comparison — shared and contrasting approaches)'],resources:['Global issue validity (50)','Literary analysis depth (45)','Non-literary analysis depth (40)','Comparative synthesis (35)','Personal voice and interpretation (55)'],explain:"Students rehearse the Individual Oral structure — moving from issue identification through literary analysis through non-literary analysis to comparative synthesis. Teaches the crucial difference between a topic and a global issue, and between description and analysis.",real:"Margaret Atwood's The Handmaid's Tale IO on gender and power, Chinua Achebe's Things Fall Apart IO on colonial identity, A UN refugee report paired with a poem on displacement, Malala Yousafzai speech paired with a novel on girls' education"},
//     {label:'Rhetoric and persuasion — analysing speeches, manifestos and campaigns',concept:'Communication',related:'Power, Representation, Perspective',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Non-literary text; Areas of Exploration: Readers Writers Texts',scene:'A speaker at a podium — audience reaction meter on the left, rhetorical device detector on the right. Aristotle\'s rhetorical triangle (ethos, pathos, logos) glows as each technique activates. Standing ovation-o-meter rises.',sliders:['Ethos — speaker credibility (0=Unknown outsider → 4=Revered authority figure)','Pathos — emotional appeal intensity (0=Purely factual → 4=Highly charged emotional narrative)','Logos — evidence quality (0=Anecdote only → 4=Peer-reviewed data and statistics)','Repetition and anaphora (0=No repetition → 4=Powerful three-beat anaphoric structure)'],resources:['Audience persuaded % (40)','Critical thinking triggered (55)','Emotional impact score (50)','Logical coherence (60)','Long-term credibility (65)'],explain:"Students apply Aristotle's rhetorical triangle to political and social speeches — discovering why ethos + pathos is more immediately persuasive than logos alone, but logos + ethos sustains trust. Directly models Paper 1 non-literary text analysis of speeches.",real:"Martin Luther King 'I Have a Dream' — anaphora and metaphor, Greta Thunberg 'How Dare You' — ethos through vulnerability, Churchill 'We Shall Fight' — antithesis and climax, Malala UN speech — personal narrative as logos"},
//     {label:'Identity and culture — how literature constructs and challenges the self',concept:'Identity',related:'Culture, Transformation, Representation',lp:'Open-minded, Thinkers, Caring',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Areas of Exploration: Time and Space; Individual Oral global issue — identity',scene:'A character silhouette on a stage, gradually filled with cultural markers — language, clothing, heritage, religion, social class. As sliders shift, the silhouette changes. A tension meter shows conflict between inherited and chosen identity.',sliders:['Cultural heritage weight (0=Fully assimilated — no heritage → 4=Tradition maintained intact)','Social class influence (0=No class consciousness → 4=Class determines all choices)','Migrant displacement factor (0=Settled at home → 4=First-generation diaspora)','Gender and identity norms (0=Fully conforms to gender role → 4=Radically subverts expectations)'],resources:['Identity coherence (65)','Cultural belonging (55)','Personal agency (50)','Social acceptance (60)','Self-expression (45)'],explain:"Students explore how literary characters construct identity in tension with cultural expectations — essential preparation for the Individual Oral global issue framework. Connects the IB concept of identity to specific textual techniques authors use to show internal conflict.",real:"Jhumpa Lahiri's The Namesake — second-generation Indian-American identity, Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's Americanah — race and identity construction, Amy Tan's The Joy Luck Club — mother-daughter cultural tension, Mohsin Hamid's Exit West — identity and migration"},
//     {label:'Intertextuality — allusion, echo and dialogue between texts',concept:'Transformation',related:'Creativity, Communication, Culture',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Areas of Exploration: Intertextuality; HL Essay line of inquiry — influence and echo',scene:'A library of glowing books. Arrows of light connect titles across shelves — direct allusion (bright), thematic echo (softer), structural homage (dotted). A genealogy of influence builds as connections are identified. A new text is placed in the web.',sliders:['Directness of allusion (0=Subtle echo → 4=Direct quotation and attribution)','Cross-cultural reach (0=Same tradition only → 4=Across languages and cultures)','Subversive intent (0=Respectful homage → 4=Counter-narrative — rewrites the original)','Historical distance (0=Contemporary — same era → 4=Centuries apart)'],resources:['Intertextual richness (40)','Reader recognition (55)','Meaning deepened by reference (50)','Originality maintained (65)','Critical lens opened (45)'],explain:"Students discover how texts are never written in isolation — every text echoes, responds to, or subverts earlier texts. Models the IB intertextuality area of exploration and helps students find comparative angles for Paper 2 and HL Essay line of inquiry.",real:"Jean Rhys Wide Sargasso Sea — postcolonial rewriting of Jane Eyre, Stoppard's Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead — Hamlet retold from margins, Walcott's Omeros — Caribbean Homer, Margaret Atwood's Penelopiad — feminist Odyssey revision"},
//     {label:'Representation and transformation — how literature reshapes worldview',concept:'Representation',related:'Identity, Transformation, Culture',lp:'Caring, Open-minded, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — comparative essay; key concept: transformation',scene:'A reader seated in a chair. Their worldview shown as a globe of assumptions — coloured blocks representing prior beliefs. As they read each text (books appear), blocks shift, crack, or rebuild. A transformation index measures change across rounds.',sliders:['Text\'s challenge to dominant narrative (0=Confirms status quo → 4=Radically subverts dominant view)','Marginalised voice amplification (0=Absent → 4=Central — marginalised narrator claims full authority)','Empathy demanded of reader (0=Distant third person → 4=First-person intimate address)','Historical moment critiqued (0=Timeless universal → 4=Specific historical injustice exposed)'],resources:['Worldview challenge score (60)','Empathy generated (55)','Political awareness raised (45)','Aesthetic transformation (50)','Long-term reader impact (40)'],explain:"Students experience how literary texts transform the reader's understanding — the IB concept of transformation in practice. Discovers why representation matters: whose story is told determines what we believe is real or normal.",real:"Toni Morrison Beloved — trauma and the unspeakable, Chimamanda Adichie 'The Danger of a Single Story' TED talk, Arundhati Roy The God of Small Things — caste and colonialism, Chinua Achebe Things Fall Apart — colonial narrative reversed"},
//     {label:'Paper 2 comparative essay — building a thematic argument across two texts',concept:'Creativity',related:'Perspective, Communication, Transformation',lp:'Thinkers, Communicators, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — Comparative literary essay; 2 hours; 30 marks',scene:'A writer\'s desk with two open books side by side. Argument threads weave between them — theme threads (pink), technique threads (blue), context threads (gold). An essay structure scaffold builds visually. A balance scale ensures equal treatment of both texts.',sliders:['Thematic argument strength (0=Plot summary → 4=Original analytical thesis across both texts)','Balance between texts (0=One text dominates → 4=Equal analytical depth on both)','Technique-to-theme link (0=Techniques listed → 4=Every technique directly evidences theme)','Comparative connectives (0=Two separate analyses side by side → 4=Integrated comparison throughout)'],resources:['Thesis originality (40)','Textual balance (50)','Evidence integration (55)','Comparative depth (35)','Essay coherence (60)'],explain:"Students practice the Paper 2 comparative essay process — from question selection through thesis formation to integrated comparison. Discovers the difference between juxtaposition (listing) and comparison (genuine analytical dialogue between texts).",real:"Kafka Metamorphosis vs Camus The Stranger — alienation compared, 1984 vs Brave New World — dystopian control mechanisms, The Handmaid's Tale vs The Power — gender and power inversion, Hamlet vs Death of a Salesman — fathers and sons across eras"},
//     {label:'HL Essay — developing a line of inquiry on a single literary work',concept:'Creativity',related:'Perspective, Transformation, Communication',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Research, Self-management',aoCrit:'HL Essay — 1200-1500 words; single literary work; student-developed line of inquiry; 20 marks',scene:'A scholar\'s study where a single book sits illuminated at the centre. Research threads branch outward — each thread is a possible angle of inquiry. An essay word counter ticks. Four assessment criterion gauges (Knowledge, Analysis, Focus, Language) animate.',sliders:['Line of inquiry specificity (0=Vague topic → 4=Precise researchable question with clear scope)','Close reading depth (0=General paraphrase → 4=Word-level analysis of specific passages)','Argument development (0=Descriptive summary of techniques → 4=Evaluative argument sustained throughout)','Integration of evidence (0=Block quotations → 4=Quotations woven into argument sentences)'],resources:['Inquiry precision (35)','Analytical depth (50)','Argument coherence (45)','Language precision (60)','Word count discipline (70)'],explain:"Students learn that the HL Essay is not a standard essay but a focused inquiry — the line of inquiry frames everything. The simulation shows how vague inquiries produce descriptive essays while specific inquiries unlock analytical depth. Directly prepares for the HL-only internal assessment.",real:"Ishiguro — how unreliable narration in Never Let Me Go conceals grief, Plath — how extended body metaphor in The Bell Jar externalises psychological fragmentation, Achebe — how proverb structure in Things Fall Apart performs Igbo cultural authority"},
//     {label:'Visual and multimodal texts — reading image, layout and design as language',concept:'Communication',related:'Representation, Creativity, Perspective',lp:'Thinkers, Open-minded, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Non-literary texts; multimodal and visual text types',scene:'A design studio with a large canvas showing a magazine cover, infographic and social media post side by side. Annotation tools highlight: typography choices, colour psychology, gaze direction of subjects, white space, layout hierarchy, caption positioning.',sliders:['Typography expressiveness (0=Neutral sans-serif body text → 4=Bold display typography as meaning)','Image-text relationship (0=Image merely illustrates text → 4=Image and text in productive tension)','Colour symbolism deployment (0=Neutral palette → 4=Deliberate cultural colour coding)','Layout hierarchy intentionality (0=Random arrangement → 4=Deliberate Z-path or F-pattern reading flow)'],resources:['Visual rhetoric effectiveness (50)','Audience positioning success (55)','Multimodal coherence (60)','Analytical vocabulary applied (40)','Meaning beyond words (45)'],explain:"Students learn to read non-verbal meaning — the language of visual design. Covers the specific vocabulary needed for Paper 1 analysis of multimodal texts: typography, colour, gaze, salience, framing, layout hierarchy. Equips students for any non-literary unseen text.",real:"Vogue cover — race and body politics in visual framing, Greenpeace campaign poster — visual metaphor for deforestation, Instagram influencer post — authenticity construction, Wartime propaganda poster — Rosie the Riveter and gender ideology"},
//     {label:'Genre conventions and subversion — how authors manipulate form for meaning',concept:'Creativity',related:'Transformation, Communication, Perspective',lp:'Risk-takers, Thinkers, Communicators',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 2 — essay question on form and genre; HL Essay line of inquiry',scene:'A bookshelf of genre labels — Gothic, tragedy, dystopia, bildungsroman, satire. A new text slides in and genre expectations light up as conventions are met or broken. A convention-subversion meter shows the creative tension. Reader expectation vs actual experience gap displays.',sliders:['Genre convention adherence (0=Every convention subverted → 4=Every convention met — pure genre)','Satirical intent (0=No satire → 4=Full satirical inversion — genre used as critique)','Tragic structure fidelity (0=No catharsis → 4=Classical Aristotelian arc with hamartia)','Metafictional self-awareness (0=Invisible narrator — realist → 4=Text comments on its own fictionality)'],resources:['Reader orientation (60)','Genre knowledge activated (50)','Subversion impact (40)','Meaning from form (45)','Critical appreciation (55)'],explain:"Students discover that genre is a contract between author and reader — and breaking that contract is itself a technique. Connects to Paper 2 questions on form and structure, and HL Essay inquiries into how unconventional form expresses meaning.",real:"Kazuo Ishiguro The Unconsoled — stream of consciousness deconstructs linear narrative, Muriel Spark The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie — omniscient narrator that contradicts itself, Salman Rushdie Midnight's Children — magic realism as political commentary, Samuel Beckett Waiting for Godot — anti-drama as existential statement"}
//   ]},
//   {icon:'🙏',name:'Hindi A/B',sub:'10 simulations · SL & HL',topics:[
//     {label:'Hindi acquisition — immersion, input & identity',concept:'Communication',related:'Context, Identity, Culture',lp:'Communicators, Open-minded, Risk-takers',atl:'Communication, Self-management',scene:'An animated Hindi-language town (शहर) where a learner character walks through markets, schools, and homes. Devanagari script appears on signs as immersion rises.',sliders:['Immersion depth (0=No Hindi exposure → 4=Full immersion)','Listening input quality (0=Simplified only → 4=Authentic native speed)','Reading practice level (0=None → 4=Daily newspaper reading)','Speaking output practice (0=Silent → 4=Daily conversation)','Script fluency (0=Roman transliteration → 4=Full Devanagari)'],resources:['Speaking fluency (10)','Reading comprehension (15)','Listening accuracy (20)','Cultural competence (25)','Confidence level (30)'],explain:"Students experience how Hindi acquisition works through the relationship between input and output. Connects to Krashen's input hypothesis applied to Hindi specifically — comprehensible input must slightly exceed current level (i+1) to drive acquisition.",real:"Mumbai's multilingual code-switching, Bollywood as language learning tool, Hindi Belt vs South India language politics, Sanskrit influence on Hindi vocabulary"},
//     {label:'Hindi साहित्य — text, social context and the author-society relationship',concept:'Perspective',related:'Identity, Culture, Representation',lp:'Open-minded, Knowledgeable, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Communication, Research',aoCrit:'DP Hindi A Paper 1 — Guided Literary Analysis; Paper 2 Comparative Essay',scene:'An animated literary timeline from Bhakti period through Chhayavaad to contemporary prose. Author portraits glow by era. Social conditions (caste hierarchy, colonialism, independence) appear as background illustrations.',sliders:['Historical period (0=Bhakti 15th century → 4=Digital age 21st century)','Author social positionality (0=Upper-caste male voice → 4=Dalit or female authorial voice)','Genre and form (0=Classical doha/pad poetry → 4=Contemporary prose and digital poetry)','Censorship and creative freedom (0=Heavy restriction → 4=Full expression)'],resources:['Social commentary depth (60)','Literary innovation (55)','Marginalised representation (40)','Accessibility (65)','Cultural heritage preservation (70)'],explain:"Students explore how Hindi literary texts reflect and challenge their social context — from Kabir's caste-challenging dohas to Premchand's rural realism to Omprakash Valmiki's Dalit autobiography. Aligned to DP Hindi A Paper 2 comparative analysis.",real:"Premchand's Godan and agrarian crisis, Kabir's egalitarian Bhakti dohas, Mahadevi Varma's feminist Chhayavaad poetry, Valmiki's Joothan and Dalit literary canon challenge"},
//     {label:'Bhakti poetry — Kabir, Mirabai and the spiritual challenge to caste',concept:'Identity',related:'Culture, Transformation, Representation',lp:'Open-minded, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 1 — Poetry commentary; Paper 2 — Bhakti vs Chhayavaad comparative essay',scene:'A medieval village scene. Kabir sits at a loom weaving cloth — doha verses float as woven threads. A caste hierarchy pyramid stands in the background; as his verses gain acceptance, its blocks crack. Mirabai dances in a temple courtyard. Audience reception meter tracks upper-caste hostility vs lower-caste embrace.',sliders:['Nirguna devotion intensity (0=Ritual and idol worship → 4=Formless God — abstract pure devotion)','Caste critique explicitness (0=Implicit metaphor only → 4=Direct naming of caste injustice)','Accessibility of language (0=Sanskrit elite register → 4=Vernacular Braj Bhasha / Awadhi)','Social reach of poet (0=Court patronage only → 4=Masses — oral street tradition)'],resources:['Spiritual authority (60)','Social challenge power (45)','Literary innovation (55)','Accessibility to masses (70)','Establishment resistance (50 — rises with critique)'],explain:"Students discover how Bhakti poets used devotional verse as radical social commentary — Kabir's dohas attacked both Hindu caste hierarchy and Muslim orthodoxy simultaneously. Mirabai's devotion to Krishna subverted brahminical patriarchy. Connects to Hindi A Paper 1 poetry commentary skills and Paper 2 literary periods comparison.",real:"Kabir Granthawali — first hundred sakhis, Mirabai's bhajans still sung at Rajasthani weddings, Dalit activists citing Kabir as proto-Ambedkarite, Bollywood Mirabai biopics and their sanitisation of her radicalism"},
//     {label:'Chhayavaad — Nirala, Mahadevi Varma and Indian Romanticism',concept:'Creativity',related:'Identity, Transformation, Culture',lp:'Risk-takers, Thinkers, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 1 — Poetry analysis; Paper 2 — Chhayavaad comparative essay',scene:'A misty forest landscape bathed in soft light — the Chhayavaad aesthetic. Mahadevi Varma writes at a desk; her lines appear as glowing strands of nature imagery. Nirala composes a free-verse revolution. A meter shows movement away from classical rhyme schemes. A feminist consciousness indicator rises as Mahadevi\'s female subjectivity enters.',sliders:['Nature imagery density (0=Urban industrial → 4=Deep immersive natural metaphor)','Free verse experimentation (0=Classical metre — Braj tradition → 4=Chhand-mukt — completely free)','Female subjectivity (0=Absent — male gaze only → 4=Full female interior consciousness)','Nationalist undercurrent (0=Pure aesthetic — no politics → 4=Independence struggle subtext throughout)'],resources:['Lyrical beauty (75)','Feminist voice strength (40)','Formal innovation (55)','Emotional depth (70)','Social relevance (50)'],explain:"Students explore Chhayavaad — Hindi Romanticism 1918-1936 — as both aesthetic revolution and ideological statement. Nirala's free verse broke classical constraints; Mahadevi Varma's poetry gave Hindi literature its first sustained female interior voice. Critical for Paper 1 poetry commentary and Paper 2 cross-period comparison.",real:"Mahadevi Varma's Yama collection — Jnanpith Award 1982, Nirala's Kukurmutta — political satire through flower imagery, Jaishankar Prasad's Kamayani — epic of consciousness, Sumitranandan Pant's Pallav — nature and soul"},
//     {label:'Premchand\'s realism — Godan, the agrarian crisis and rural-urban divide',concept:'Representation',related:'Culture, Identity, Transformation',lp:'Caring, Principled, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 1 — Prose commentary; Paper 2 — Social realism essay; Individual Oral',scene:'An animated rural landscape divided from a city skyline. Hori the farmer (from Godan) stands in his field — crops wither as debt rises. Money-lender character hovers. In the city, a parallel middle-class drawing room shows the other half of the novel. A socioeconomic inequality meter divides the screen.',sliders:['Agrarian debt burden (0=Debt-free smallholder → 4=Crushed by zamindari and moneylender debt)','Rural-to-urban migration pressure (0=None → 4=Entire family forced to city)','Landlord exploitation level (0=Benevolent → 4=Extractive zamindari maximum pressure)','Social mobility possibility (0=Some escape routes → 4=Caste and class lock all exits)'],resources:['Farmer wellbeing (75)','Debt level (20 — rises each round)','Crop yield (70)','Family dignity (65)','Social justice (30)'],explain:"Students simulate the world of Godan (1936) — Premchand's masterwork of Indian realism. Hori's tragedy of aspiring to own a cow (go-dan = gift of cow) becomes a lens on debt bondage, caste, and colonial land policy. Critical for Paper 2 prose analysis and IO global issue on inequality.",real:"Vidarbha farmer suicides — modern Godan echoes, B.R. Ambedkar on agrarian caste economy, Land Acquisition Act 1894 and its consequences, Mahatma Gandhi's village economy vs Nehru's industrialisation debate"},
//     {label:'Dalit literature — Omprakash Valmiki\'s Joothan and identity assertion',concept:'Identity',related:'Representation, Transformation, Power',lp:'Principled, Caring, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 1 — Autobiography and non-fiction commentary; Paper 2 — Dalit literature essay',scene:'A school courtyard split in two — upper-caste children in seats, young Valmiki forced to sweep outside. As the memoir\'s testimony builds, the sweeping boy steps inside the classroom — barriers crumbling. A dignity meter rises against a shame meter. The Dalit Panther banner appears in later rounds.',sliders:['Caste discrimination visibility (0=Hidden — polite silence → 4=Explicit — named school humiliation)','Testimonial voice authority (0=Apologetic tone → 4=Assertive witness — narrator claims full dignity)','Ambedkarite consciousness (0=Pre-political — accepts fate → 4=Fully mobilised — systemic critique)','Literary canon challenge (0=Requests inclusion → 4=Demands canon rewriting on its own terms)'],resources:['Witness authenticity (70)','Political consciousness (45)','Emotional impact (75)','Canon disruption (40)','Reader empathy (65)'],explain:"Students explore how Joothan (1997) functions simultaneously as personal testimony, historical document, and political intervention. Valmiki's autobiography challenges the Hindi literary canon dominated by upper-caste voices. Connects to the Hindi A concept of how social positionality shapes both what is written and what is published.",real:"B.R. Ambedkar's Annihilation of Caste — intellectual foundation, Dalit Panther movement 1972 — political mobilisation, Joothan translated into 10 languages — global Dalit diaspora reach, Namdeo Dhasal's poetry — Marathi parallel"},
//     {label:'Partition literature — displacement, memory and communal violence in Hindi prose',concept:'Transformation',related:'Identity, Culture, Perspective',lp:'Open-minded, Caring, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 2 — Comparative essay on historical context and literature; Individual Oral global issue: displacement',scene:'A train at a station in 1947 — both platforms show families leaving in opposite directions. Religious symbols shift on either side of a dissolving border. A grief meter fills. Flashback panels show the village before and after. A collective trauma index and individual resilience meter compete.',sliders:['Communal violence intensity (0=Peaceful transfer → 4=Maximum brutality — riots and massacres)','Memory reliability (0=Clear factual → 4=Fragmented — trauma distorts recall)','Nostalgia vs bitter truth tension (0=Pure nostalgia — idealised homeland → 4=Unflinching violence)','Recovery and reconciliation (0=Permanent rupture → 4=Community rebuilding across border)'],resources:['Community cohesion (80)','Trauma depth (20 — rises with violence)','Cultural memory preserved (65)','Hope for reconciliation (50)','Narrative justice for victims (40)'],explain:"Students explore how Hindi Partition literature processes collective trauma. Writers like Yashpal (Jhootha Sach) and Bhisham Sahni (Tamas) depict 1947 not as liberation but as catastrophic rupture. Connects to the Hindi A IO global issue of displacement and to Paper 2 comparative essays on how different writers handle the same historical event.",real:"Yashpal's Jhootha Sach — two-volume Partition epic, Bhisham Sahni's Tamas — BBC adaptation, Saadat Hasan Manto's Urdu Partition stories — comparison across languages, 1947 Partition Archive — oral testimonies"},
//     {label:'Nayi Kavita — experimental form, urban alienation and modern Hindi poetry',concept:'Creativity',related:'Identity, Transformation, Culture',lp:'Risk-takers, Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 1 — Modern poetry commentary; Paper 2 — Poetry across periods',scene:'A 1950s Delhi cityscape at night. Agyeya types in a bare room — verse fragments appear as incomplete neon signs. The city drowns out nature imagery from the previous Chhayavaad era. An alienation meter rises as industrialisation grows. Experimental form indicator shows traditional metre dissolving.',sliders:['Urban alienation depth (0=City as opportunity → 4=City as dehumanising maze)','Formal experimentation (0=Residual Chhayavaad romanticism → 4=Prose poem — anti-lyrical','Existential questioning (0=Social optimism → 4=Existential uncertainty — no answers given)','Collective vs individual voice (0=National we — nationalist poetry → 4=Isolated I — private modern subject)'],resources:['Formal innovation (60)','Emotional authenticity (65)','Accessibility (45)','Critical recognition (55)','Connection to prior tradition (40)'],explain:"Students explore Nayi Kavita (New Poetry) — the post-1947 reaction against Chhayavaad romanticism. Agyeya's Tar Saptak (1943) launched experimentalism; poets rejected nationalist uplift for personal alienation and existential doubt. Directly prepares Paper 1 modern Hindi poetry commentary and Paper 2 cross-period comparison.",real:"Agyeya's Ashadha Ka Ek Din — consciousness over plot, Muktibodh's Andhere Mein — epic of intellectual crisis, Tar Saptak 1943 anthology — seven poets manifesto, Dharamvir Bharati's Andha Yug — Partition and moral collapse"},
//     {label:'Hindi B themes — Identity, Social Organisation and Sharing the Planet',concept:'Communication',related:'Culture, Identity, Perspective',lp:'Communicators, Open-minded, Caring',atl:'Communication, Research, Self-management',aoCrit:'Hindi B Paper 1 — Productive writing; Paper 2 — Receptive listening and reading; Internal Oral',scene:'A Hindi B classroom where five theme globes float: Identities (blue), Experiences (green), Human Ingenuity (gold), Social Organisation (purple), Sharing the Planet (teal). A student picks a theme and an authentic Hindi text appears. Listening comprehension audio plays. A writing task timer begins.',sliders:['Theme complexity (0=Basic vocabulary — Experiences → 4=Abstract concepts — Social Organisation)','Text authenticity (0=Graded simplified text → 4=Unedited native-speaker newspaper)','Cultural context depth (0=Tourist surface — food and festivals → 4=Socio-political nuance)','Productive output ambition (0=Formulaic letter → 4=Analytical article with opinion)'],resources:['Receptive comprehension (40)','Productive accuracy (35)','Cultural competence (30)','Register flexibility (45)','Theme vocabulary range (50)'],explain:"Students navigate the five Hindi B prescribed themes through authentic texts — preparing for Paper 2 listening and reading comprehension and Paper 1 productive writing tasks. Discovers that cultural competence (knowing what a text assumes the reader knows) is as important as linguistic accuracy.",real:"Dainik Bhaskar front page — news reading task, All India Radio broadcast excerpt — listening comprehension, Hindi social media posts on climate (#ShareThePlanet), Bollywood song lyrics as cultural text analysis"},
//     {label:'Contemporary Hindi voices — Geetanjali Shree, globalisation and gender',concept:'Transformation',related:'Identity, Representation, Culture',lp:'Open-minded, Knowledgeable, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'Hindi A Paper 2 — Contemporary prose; Individual Oral — global issue: gender and identity',scene:'A modern Delhi apartment and a village in Uttar Pradesh connected by a phone screen. Geetanjali Shree\'s Ret Samadhi (Tomb of Sand) pages appear — grandmother character crosses the Partition border in old age. Gender constraints shown as softening walls. A Booker Prize announcement flashes. Global literary map shows Hindi\'s new international reach.',sliders:['Narrative structure innovation (0=Linear chronology → 4=Layered — multiple time periods interwoven)','Female agency (0=Confined to domestic sphere → 4=Radical transgression — crossing borders)','Language play and wordsmithery (0=Standard literary Hindi → 4=Experimental — Sanskrit, dialect, English woven in)','Global-local tension (0=Pure local Indian → 4=Globally circulating — translated world literature)'],resources:['Narrative originality (70)','Female voice authority (65)','Literary recognition (55)','Cultural specificity (75)','Global reach (40)'],explain:"Students explore how Geetanjali Shree's Ret Samadhi (2018) — Booker International Prize 2022 as Tomb of Sand — represents a new era for Hindi literature: experimental, feminist, globally recognised yet deeply rooted in Indian partition memory. Connects to IO global issue on gender and border-crossing identity.",real:"Ret Samadhi Booker Prize 2022 — first Hindi novel to win, Daisy Rockwell's translation challenges — cultural untranslatability, Chitra Mudgal's Avaidh on migrant labour identity, Mridula Garg's Chitcobra — female desire in Hindi fiction"}
//   ]},
