//     {label:'Memory models & cognitive load — how we learn and forget',concept:'Cognitive processes',related:'Memory, Learning, Attention',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Self-management',scene:'A stylised brain cross-section — sensory store shown as flickering lights at ears/eyes, short-term memory as a spinning workspace with 7 slots, long-term memory as a vast filing cabinet.',sliders:['Chunking strategy (0=None → 4=Expert chunking)','Rehearsal frequency (0=Zero → 4=Spaced repetition optimal)','Emotional significance (0=None → 4=High emotional valence)','Distraction level (0=Silent environment → 4=High noise/notifications)','Sleep quality after learning (0=None → 4=8 hours optimal)'],resources:['STM retention % (70)','LTM consolidation % (40)','Recall accuracy % (55)','Cognitive load (50 — lower is better)','Retrieval ease (60)'],explain:'Students encode information through the Multi-Store Model and Working Memory Model across 5 learning scenarios.',real:'Ebbinghaus forgetting curve, HM patient anterograde amnesia, Elizabeth Loftus false memory research, Spaced repetition apps, Sleep consolidation neuroscience'}
