//     {label:'Sociocultural approach — conformity, obedience and group behaviour',concept:'Social and cultural factors',related:'Behaviour, Identity, Norms',lp:'Thinkers, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Sociocultural Approach; SAQ and ERQ',scene:'An animated social psychology laboratory. Confederates sit around a table. The naive participant (the student) sees clearly wrong answers being given unanimously. A compliance meter rises. Social norms arrows push the figure toward conformity.',sliders:['Group unanimity pressure (0=No group — alone → 4=Unanimous wrong confederates)','Authority figure presence (0=Peer only → 4=White coat authority figure)','Task ambiguity (0=Clear correct answer → 4=Ambiguous — no clear right answer)','Cultural collectivism vs individualism (0=High individualism — resist → 4=High collectivism — conform)'],resources:['Conformity rate % (variable)','Obedience rate % (variable)','Cognitive dissonance level (variable)','Minority influence exerted (variable)','Ethical concern level (variable)'],explain:"Students experience Asch conformity and Milgram obedience dynamics through the simulation, discovering how situational factors override individual ethics — the core insight of the sociocultural approach in IB Psychology.",real:'Asch line judgment conformity study 1951, Milgram electric shock obedience study 1963, Abu Ghraib Stanford Prison Experiment parallel, Bystander effect Kitty Genovese case study'},
//     {label:'Biological approach — hormones, neurotransmitters and behaviour',concept:'Biological correlates',related:'Neurochemistry, Behaviour, Health',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Self-management',aoCrit:'SL/HL Paper 1 — Biological Approach; SAQ and ERQ',scene:'A brain cross-section with neurotransmitter pathways highlighted. Dopamine pathway lights up during reward. Serotonin pathway shown affecting mood regulation. Hormone level meters for cortisol and adrenaline. PET scan image overlays update.',sliders:['Dopamine activity level (0=Very low — anhedonia → 4=Very high — mania/addiction)','Cortisol stress hormone (0=Low — relaxed → 4=Chronic high — immune suppression)','Serotonin availability (0=Low — depression link → 4=Optimal — mood regulation)','Sleep quality on neurochemistry (0=Sleep deprived → 4=Optimal 8 hours REM)'],resources:['Mood and wellbeing index (65)','Reward motivation level (70)','Stress response intensity (40)','Cognitive performance (60)','Emotional regulation ability (65)'],explain:"Students discover how neurochemistry underpins behaviour and mental health — why dopamine is not just a 'happiness chemical' but a prediction-error signal, and why chronic cortisol disrupts immune function and memory.",real:'SSRI antidepressant mechanism and serotonin hypothesis, Dopamine and addiction — slot machine variable reward, Cortisol stress and working memory impairment research, Exercise neurogenesis and BDNF research'},
//     {label:'Abnormal psychology — diagnosis, culture and mental health stigma',concept:'Health and wellbeing',related:'Norms, Culture, Behaviour',lp:'Caring, Principled, Open-minded',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'HL Paper 2 — Abnormal Psychology option',scene:'A diagnostic process animation. DSM-5 criteria checklist fills in as symptoms are selected. Cultural context slider shifts what counts as abnormal. Stigma barrier rises between patient and treatment. Treatment effectiveness comparison bar chart.',sliders:['Symptom severity (0=Subclinical → 4=Severe — diagnostic criteria met)','Cultural context of behaviour (0=Behaviour is culturally normal → 4=Clearly abnormal across cultures)','Stigma level in community (0=No stigma — open discussion → 4=High stigma — help-seeking avoided)','Treatment access (0=No access → 4=Full multi-modal treatment available)'],resources:['Diagnostic accuracy % (variable)','Help-seeking behaviour probability (variable)','Recovery likelihood (variable)','Social functioning maintained (variable)','Cultural validity of diagnosis (variable)'],explain:"Students discover how mental health diagnosis is both biological (symptom criteria) and sociocultural (what is considered abnormal depends on cultural context) — preparing for HL Abnormal Psychology option evaluation questions.",real:'Drapetomania — historical false diagnosis, PTSD cross-cultural manifestation differences, Japan hikikomori cultural syndrome, WHO Atlas global mental health treatment gap data'}]}
