//     {icon:'🏛️',name:'Design Technology',sub:'7 simulations · SL & HL',topics:[
//     {label:'CAD virtual prototyping — surface solid models and generative design',concept:'Models',related:'Innovation, Form, Technology',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Risk-takers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'A2.2.5 — CAD virtual prototypes; B2.2.3 — Construct and interpret CAD models',scene:'An animated CAD environment showing three modelling approaches side by side. Surface modelling shows a car body built from NURBS patches. Solid modelling shows a mechanical bracket built from extrusions and Boolean operations. Generative design panel shows multiple optimised bracket geometries produced by the algorithm from load conditions and material constraints.',sliders:['Modelling approach (0=Surface — exterior form and aesthetics → 4=Solid — functional engineering parts)','Generative design constraint (0=Minimum weight objective → 4=Maximum stiffness to weight ratio)','Material specified (0=Aluminium — light → 4=Steel — strong but heavy)','Manufacturing method constraint (0=Traditional machining → 4=Additive — complex geometries allowed)'],resources:['Part mass grams (variable — generative design minimises this)','Structural integrity score (variable)','Manufacturing complexity index (variable)','Design iterations generated (variable — generative produces hundreds)','Material utilisation efficiency % (variable)'],explain:'Students discover that surface and solid CAD models serve different purposes — surface modelling captures aesthetic form for products like car bodies while solid modelling creates functional parts for engineering analysis. Generative design uses algorithms to explore thousands of possible geometries simultaneously, finding shapes no human designer would conceive. Models A2.2.5 and B2.2.3.',real:'Airbus partition bracket — generative design reduced weight 45%, Autodesk generative design for NASA lander, Nike shoe sole generative design, Apple Mac Pro chassis CNC-machined from solid model'},

//     {label:'Finite element analysis — simulating structural performance under load',concept:'Models',related:'Structure, Evidence, Change',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Principled',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'A2.2.5 — FEA virtual simulation; B2.2.4 — Interpret FEA output; B3.2.3 and A3.2.5 — Structural failure and stress-strain',scene:'A mechanical part shown in a 3D FEA environment. The part is meshed into thousands of small elements shown as a coloured grid. A load is applied — force arrows appear at attachment points. The stress distribution colour map updates — red zones show maximum stress near yield strength blue zones show safe low-stress regions. Deformation shown (exaggerated for visibility).',sliders:['Applied load magnitude Newtons (0=Low — well within safe range → 4=High — approaches failure)','Mesh refinement (0=Coarse — fast but less accurate → 4=Fine — slow but accurate stress peaks)','Material yield strength MPa (0=Weak polymer 30MPa → 4=High-strength steel 800MPa)','Boundary conditions (0=Fixed at one end — cantilever → 4=Fixed both ends — beam)'],resources:['Maximum von Mises stress MPa (variable)','Safety factor = yield strength / max stress (variable)','Deformation at load point mm (variable)','Stress concentration factor at fillet (variable)','Failure risk assessment (safe/caution/fail)'],explain:'Students read FEA output colour maps and identify stress concentrations — the red zones where failure is most likely. They discover that safety factor = yield strength divided by maximum stress must exceed 1 for safety and typically needs to be 2-4 for real products. Sharp internal corners create stress concentrations that FEA makes visible. Models A2.2.5, B2.2.4, B3.2.3, A3.2.5.',real:'Boeing 787 wing FEA — millions of elements, bicycle frame stress analysis before manufacture, Bridge load testing simulation replacing physical testing, Formula 1 aerodynamic components FEA before each race'},

//     {label:'VR AR and digital humans — immersive virtual prototyping',concept:'Models',related:'Innovation, Interaction, Form',lp:'Thinkers, Inquirers, Risk-takers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'A2.2.5 — VR AR digital humans motion capture haptic technology in design',scene:'A split-screen immersive design environment. Left: VR headset perspective shows a designer walking through a full-scale virtual prototype of a hospital ward — moving furniture repositioning medical equipment. Right: A digital human mannequin in different anthropometric percentiles tests reach zones and sight lines. Motion capture data overlaid on ergonomic task analysis.',sliders:['Prototype fidelity (0=Low fidelity wireframe — fast to produce → 4=Photorealistic — immersive evaluation)','User population represented (0=50th percentile only → 4=5th to 95th percentile range — inclusive design)','Interaction mode (0=Passive viewing → 4=Haptic feedback — physical force sensation)','AR overlay opacity (0=Physical prototype only → 4=Full AR digital overlay on physical space)'],resources:['Ergonomic reach zone compliance % (variable)','User evaluation realism score (variable)','Design iterations completed before physical prototype (variable)','Accessibility compliance for user range (variable)','Development cost saving vs physical prototype (variable)'],explain:'Students discover how VR allows evaluation of full-scale spatial designs before any physical prototype exists — catching layout and ergonomic problems at the cheapest possible stage. Digital human simulation tests whether the design accommodates the full range of human body sizes. Haptic technology adds force feedback making interactions realistic. Models A2.2.5 design process digital tools.',real:'Airbus cabin design evaluated in VR before manufacture, Ford vehicle interior ergonomics using digital human RAMSIS, IKEA AR app — furniture placement before purchase, NHS hospital ward layout evaluated in VR with clinical staff'},

//     {label:'Rapid prototyping — SLA FDM SLS from digital model to physical test',concept:'Models',related:'Innovation, Change, Technology',lp:'Thinkers, Risk-takers, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'A2.2.6 — Rapid prototyping techniques; B2.2.5 — Complex physical prototypes from CAD',scene:'Three animated 3D printing process panels side by side. SLA: UV laser traces liquid resin layer by layer — smooth high-detail parts shown. FDM: heated nozzle deposits thermoplastic filament layer by layer — visible layer lines. SLS: laser sinters nylon powder — no support structures needed complex geometries possible. Part quality surface finish and material properties compared.',sliders:['Rapid prototyping process (0=FDM — cheapest most accessible → 4=SLS — strongest most complex)','Layer thickness mm (0=Thick 0.3mm — fast but rough → 4=Thin 0.05mm — slow but smooth)','Prototype purpose (0=Concept model — appearance only → 4=Functional prototype — mechanical testing)','Design complexity (0=Simple geometry — injection moulding could do this → 4=Complex internal channels — RP only)'],resources:['Build time hours (variable — increases with layer thinness)','Material cost estimate (variable)','Surface finish roughness Ra (variable)','Dimensional accuracy mm (variable)','Suitable for user testing? (variable)'],explain:'Students discover the trade-offs between rapid prototyping methods — FDM is accessible and cheap but produces visible layer lines and anisotropic strength; SLA gives beautiful smooth surfaces for form evaluation; SLS produces functional parts with complex internal geometry impossible by traditional machining. The critical insight is that RP allows iteration — cheap early failure leads to better final products.',real:'GE fuel nozzle — SLS production part not prototype, Invisalign dental aligners — SLA prototyped then thermoformed, COVID-19 face shields — FDM distributed local production, Bugatti titanium brake calliper — SLS from single CAD file'},

//     {label:'Structural systems — forces stress strain and safety factors',concept:'Systems',related:'Structure, Evidence, Technology',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'A3.2.5 — Stress-strain and Young Modulus; A3.2.7 — Equilibrium; B3.2.4 — Force diagrams; B3.2.5 — Safety factors',scene:'An interactive structural analysis environment. A beam with applied loads shown. Free body diagram (FBD) drawn automatically as loads are placed. Stress calculated as force divided by cross-sectional area. Strain as extension divided by original length. Stress-strain graph plots with elastic limit yield point and fracture shown. Safety factor calculates from material properties.',sliders:['Applied load Newtons (0=Low — well within elastic limit → 4=Beyond yield — permanent deformation)','Cross-sectional area mm2 (0=Small — high stress → 4=Large — low stress)','Material type (0=Ductile steel — large plastic region → 4=Brittle ceramic — fracture at yield)','Safety factor required (0=Safety factor 1 — no margin → 4=Safety factor 5 — very conservative)'],resources:['Stress = Force / Area MPa (variable)','Strain = deltaL / L (variable — dimensionless)','Young Modulus = Stress / Strain GPa (variable — material property)','Safety factor achieved (variable)','Failure mode predicted (elastic/plastic/fracture)'],explain:'Students discover that stress and strain are material-independent measures of load and deformation — stress depends on force and area, strain on deformation and length. Young Modulus is the material stiffness property linking them. Safety factor must always exceed 1 and is typically 2-5 in engineering depending on consequence of failure. FEA uses these relationships at every mesh element. Models A3.2.5, B3.2.4, B3.2.5.',real:'Eiffel Tower girder safety factor calculation, Bicycle chain designed to fail before frame — deliberate safety factor hierarchy, Aircraft wing designed for 3.5g manoeuvre load with safety factor 1.5, Golden Gate Bridge structural steel stress at design load'},

//     {label:'Electronic systems — logic gates flow diagrams and circuit simulation',concept:'Systems',related:'Logic, Technology, Interaction',lp:'Thinkers, Knowledgeable, Inquirers',atl:'Thinking, Research',aoCrit:'A3.4.5 — Digital systems binary and logic; B3.4.5 — Flow diagrams for programmable systems; B3.4.6 — Circuit diagrams; B3.4.8 — Microcontroller circuits',scene:'A dual panel environment. Left: logic gate simulator with AND OR NOT NAND NOR XOR gates. Students build combinational logic circuits and see truth table populate automatically. Right: flow diagram builder for a microcontroller system — inputs (sensors switches) decision diamonds outputs (LED motor speaker). Boolean algebra simplification shown.',sliders:['Circuit type (0=Simple single gate → 4=Complex combinational logic — multiple gates)','Input state A (0=Logic 0 → 4=Logic 1)','Input state B (0=Logic 0 → 4=Logic 1)','Microcontroller complexity (0=Simple input-output → 4=Multi-state system with loops and decisions)'],resources:['Logic gate output Q (0 or 1) (variable)','Truth table complete (variable)','Boolean expression derived (variable)','Flow diagram correctness (variable)','Circuit simulation state (variable — all input combinations tested)'],explain:'Students build logic circuits and discover that any digital function can be constructed from NAND gates alone — NAND is functionally complete. The flow diagram translation shows how sequential logic (if-then-else loops) maps directly to microcontroller code structure. FEA and circuit simulation use the same computational principle — breaking complex behaviour into simple element interactions. Models A3.4.5, B3.4.5, B3.4.6.',real:'Traffic light controller — NOR gate memory latch circuit, Arduino microcontroller flow diagram for automatic plant watering, Touch screen capacitive sensor logic, Anti-lock brake system ABS logic — sensor input processing output'},

//     {label:'Life cycle analysis — simulating environmental impact from cradle to grave',concept:'Sustainability',related:'Change, Systems, Evidence',lp:'Caring, Principled, Thinkers',atl:'Thinking, Research, Communication',aoCrit:'C3.2 — Life-cycle analysis as environmental simulation; A2.2.5 — Sustainability in virtual prototyping',scene:'An animated cradle-to-grave product lifecycle for a smartphone. Raw material extraction (mining rare earths) flows into materials processing manufacturing distribution use phase and end-of-life disposal or recycling. Carbon footprint CO2e allocated to each phase. Students adjust design decisions and see which phase dominates impact.',sliders:['Material choice (0=Recycled aluminium — low extraction impact → 4=Rare earth primary — high impact)','Manufacturing location and transport (0=Local renewable powered → 4=Distant coal powered — high logistics footprint)','Product use phase energy (0=Very low power device → 4=High energy use — long use phase dominates)','End of life strategy (0=Landfill — no material recovery → 4=Full takeback and remanufacture)'],resources:['Carbon footprint kg CO2e per product (variable)','Phase with highest impact identified (variable)','Material efficiency % recovered at end of life (variable)','Energy use over product lifetime kWh (variable)','LCA hotspot for design improvement (variable)'],explain:'Students discover through LCA simulation that environmental impact is rarely dominated by manufacturing alone — use phase often dominates for energy-using products. Material extraction can be the hotspot for electronics due to rare earth mining. LCA reveals counterintuitive results: an electric car produces more CO2 in manufacturing than a petrol car but lower lifetime total. Models C3.2 and connects to A2.2.5 sustainable design.',real:'iPhone LCA — Apple publishes product carbon footprint showing use phase 80% of impact, Bamboo toothbrush vs plastic — full LCA comparison, Cotton t-shirt water footprint LCA — growing cotton dominates, Tesla Model 3 LCA vs Toyota Camry — manufacturing vs fuel phase trade-off'}
